   Pager: (800) 946-4645 (PIN 599-4539).
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: triggp(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CLINTON-STARR PACKAGE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TEXT (Washington) _ Complete text of a response by
President Clinton's lawyers to the report submitted by Kenneth
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel, to the House of
Representatives. The references to ``narrative at'' a given number
are to specific points in Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SCHOLARS (Washington) _ Experts on constitutional law
said Saturday that some of the scathing allegations in report by
the Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr could
appropriately be defined as impeachable offenses within the meaning
of the Constitution. But in interviews after they had read the
report, several of them said that because impeachment is defined as
a political process by the Constitution, the question of whether
Clinton's actions merited removal from office depends not on legal
analysis but on the public reaction to the details of 445-page
report. By William Glaberson.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STRATEGY (Washington) _ President Clinton's closest
advisers waited nervously Saturday to see if the most audacious
political gamble of his career _declaring last month that he told
the truth when he swore he did not have a sexual relationship with
Monica Lewinsky _ would cause the public to turn on his inquisitors
rather than on him.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ASSESS (Washington) _ As President Clinton starts down a
fateful road with many forks, he will want to walk as slowly as he
can. It would be surprising if he made definitive decisions
quickly. Public opinion coalesces only slowly, and public opinion
will ultimately prove sovereign. It will guide Congress in its
deliberations, as well as the president, but its shape may not be
completely clear for a week or more. By R.W. Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-RDP (Washington) _ The White House prepared a second
wave of rebuttal Saturday to defend President Clinton from the
threat of impeachment, pressing to regain the initiative as House
members made critical soundings of how the scathing charges of
illicit sex and abuse of office were being received by America at
large. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-STARR (Washington) _ Kenneth Starr, a deeply religious
man, whose father, a fundamentalist minister, used to deliver
sermons back home in Texas on the perils of women dressed in
bermuda shorts, has sent an impeachment report to Congress chock
full of explicit sex. And Wanda Cates of Crowell, Texas, is not
surprised. By Michael Winerip.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REPUBS (Washington) _ Political memo. In a partisan
call-to-arms last April, Speaker Newt Gingrich vowed to lead a
drumbeat of attacks about scandal at the White House. So after
Kenneth Starr's report reached the House on Thursday, it marked
quite a transformation when Gingrich sternly lectured members about
decorum. That reticence, and that of several other party leaders,
reflects a carefully drawn strategy to say nothing that could
tarnish an image of impartiality, at least until the elections. By
Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 2NDLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-DAY (Washington) _ The president's day, with expected
additional rebuttal. By James Bennet.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HILLARY (Washington) _ A look at Hillary Clinton in the
wake of the report's release. By Melinda Henneberger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-INSIDERS (Washington) _ The people around Clinton who
knew of his escapades: Betty Currie, Harold Ickes, formerly of his
staff, and Lou Fox of Secret Service. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-COMPARE (Washington) _ Comparing Starr's report and
Clinton's rebuttal. By David E. Rosenbaum.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-BLACKS (Washington) _ Unwavering support for Clinton
among members of the Congressional Black Caucus. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-HYDE (Washington) _ On Henry J. Hyde's ``power wall'' in
his Capitol Hill office are photographs of him with Dwight D.
Eisenhower, Richard M. Nixon, Gerald R. Ford, Jimmy Carter, Ronald
Reagan, George Bush, Mother Theresa, the Pope _ and Bill Clinton.
``To Mr. Hyde _ with respect,'' Clinton signed the photo taken
during their first encounter in 1993, just before he made his first
address to Congress as President. Nobody, it seems, doesn't respect
Henry Hyde. By Elaine Sciolino.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONYERS (Washington) _ A look at John Conyers, the
ranking Democrat on Judiciary Committee. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MEDIA _ How newspapers handled the salacious nature of
the report. By Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LIBRARY (Little Rock, Ark.) _ What's going on at Clinton
library. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-GORE (Seattle) _ With the vice president, who travels to
the West Coast on Saturday. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT (Paris) _ The Starr report on President
Clinton dominated news reports in Europe on Friday night and
Saturday. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   (Subbed with 1STLD)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-REACT _ Voices from across the country. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-NY-POLS (New ork) _ New York-area politicians' comments
on Clinton are guarded. Speaking off the record, some of the
candidates and their aides expressed mounting frustration that, at
a time when they would like all eyes on their races, they were
being swamped by the news from Washington. By Richard Perez-Pena.
</P>
<P>
   And see related (filed in `k' category):
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ COMMENTARY: PULP NONFICTION. (The
president must not lose his job. Not over this. Certainly, Bill
Clinton should be deeply ashamed of himself. He has given a bad
name to adultery and lying. He has made wickedness seem pathetic,
and that's truly a sin. Kenneth Starr, all these years and all
these millions later, has not delivered impeachable offenses. He
has delivered a 445-page Harold Robbins novel.) By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (Undated) _ COMMENTARY: STILL DOESN'T GET IT.
(There is nothing new in Kenneth Starr's report, just confirmation
in extreme and at times lurid detail of the type of person Clinton
has always been. The president is not sorry. He's apologizing
because there's a gun at his head. He's not changing what he now
describes as his sinful ways. He's trying to manipulate public
opinion so he can survive to sin again. The psychodrama remains as
long as he remains.) By Bob Herbert.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK TIMES PARTNERS: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Please note that your New York Times News Service report
includes news and features from The Arizona Republic, Bloomberg
News, The Boston Globe, Cox News Service, The Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Hearst Newspapers, The Houston Chronicle, The Kansas
City Star, The Los Angeles Daily News, The San Francisco Chronicle,
The Seattle Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New
York Times Regional Newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
