<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-DEVILRAYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARK INJURED IN RANGERS' 8-2 VICTORY AGAINST DEVIL RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The Rangers gained ground on the American
League West-leading Anaheim Angels, but ground might be an
essential that their first baseman no longer can cover at a time
when it matters most.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers moved within one game of the Angels with last
night's 8-2 victory against the expansion Devil Rays at Tropicana
Field. First baseman Will Clark, however, sustained an injury that
leaves his availability in question and jeopardizes a contending
team's prospects with 15 games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be anything from a couple of days,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said, ``to the rest of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark fractured the big toe on his right foot after being hit
with a third-inning slider thrown by former Rangers right-hander
Julio Santana. Clark remained in the game after being hit by the
pitch, but he departed during the fourth inning for X-rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be the ultimate day-to-day, but I'm going to
strap it on one way or another,'' Clark said. ``I will be
available.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's injury served as the proverbial dark cloud on an
otherwise shining evening.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve outfielder/first baseman Mike Simms _ who replaced Clark
in the lineup _ and catcher Ivan Rodriguez hit consecutive home
runs in a span of six pitches during the Rangers' three-run fifth
inning, and right-hander Rick Helling (19-7) battled through eight
innings and joined Yankees right-hander David Cone as the league's
19-game winners.
</P>
<P>
   Simms, who entered the game mired in a 1-for-31 slump, gave the
Rangers their second lead with his two-out, two-run homer off
Santana (5-4). Rodriguez followed suit with a solo home run that
gave the Rangers a 4-1 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The opposite-field home run ``tells me I'm getting close,'' said
Simms, who snapped a streak of 29 hitless at-bats with his
sixth-inning double Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's important right now,'' said Oates, who indicated that
designated hitter Lee Stevens and Simms will form a platoon at
first base should Clark not be able to play.
</P>
<P>
   Clark can play as pain allows, but it remains to be seen how the
fracture will affect his playing time and ability to hit. Clark
strides toward the mound with his injured right foot, but the left
foot remains more instrumental in his swing. A left-handed batter
supports his weight and rotates his hips through his left foot.
</P>
<P>
   The reduction of swelling and pain in the toe remains Clark's
chief priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see how good modern medicine is,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Helling surrendered two runs on eight hits and issued three
walks, but the right-hander escaped second-inning trouble and
minimized the damage during the Devil Rays' one-run third and fifth
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't nearly as sharp as I have been the past four or five
starts, but I battled through the first five innings,'' Helling
said. ``It wasn't easy those first five innings, but I was able to
make the pitches when I needed it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore ensured the Rangers' victory with
his two-run, sixth-inning double against right-hander Esteban Yan,
and third baseman Todd Zeile later provided another two-run double
during the Rangers' final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers learned of the Angels' 3-2 loss to the Orioles in
Baltimore before last night's first pitch and took advantage of
their opportunity to gain ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're one game closer to them than we were today,'' Oates
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, might be one first baseman shy, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
