<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-REDS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS VICTIMIZE DAAL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Pitchers like to be appreciated by their manager
and teammates, but they like a more tangible form of support even
more. Omar Daal is getting plenty of the former, very little of the
latter.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks left-hander was terrific against the Cincinnati
Reds on Saturday, giving up an unearned run and four hits in seven
innings. But again, Daal had nothing to show for it except a
diminished ERA and lots of kind words after the Reds' 3-0 victory
at Cinergy Field. Bret Boone drove in all the runs as the
Diamondbacks lost their fourth straight and sixth in seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Omar was outstanding again,'' Manager Buck Showalter said.
``I've sat here quite a few times and said the same thing. He
deserved a better fate.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop-turned-second baseman Jay Bell said, ``Omar pitched
wonderfully. When a pitcher gives you a chance to win, you've got
to take advantage of that. We didn't take advantage of a tremendous
outing like we should have.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller, who had two of the Diamondbacks' three
hits, was only half-kidding when he said, ``We're pretty much
guaranteed zero or one run when Omar pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal was coming off a bad start against Houston (four innings,
seven runs), but before that he had a 1.65 ERA over 54 innings. His
record during that stretch is 3-3. All three losses were shutouts,
2-0, 3-0 and 1-0. In his past six losses, the Diamondbacks have
scored four runs.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching with a sore throat because of tonsillitis, Daal lowered
his ERA to 2.78. But here's how his luck is running: He fell
one-third of an inning short of qualifying for listing among the
league leaders. Daal was lifted for pinch-hitter Brent Brede in the
eighth with two outs and Miller on first. And remember, this is the
guy who missed nearly three weeks after injuring his hamstring
running the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks, who lost, 13-1, on Friday, still were in the
game at that point, trailing, 1-0. Brede walked, moving the tying
run to second base. But the next hitter, Andy Fox, grounded out
weakly to second.
</P>
<P>
   With Daal out of the game in the bottom of the inning, Boone's
single off Aaron Small scored a pair of runs after pinch-hitter
Sean Casey was intentionally walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, it's a little bit frustrating,'' Daal said. ``In the
last month when I pitch, sometimes we don't get runs. But that's
the game. And the other pitchers? They've pitched very well. Parris
was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Reds right-hander Steve Parris, who worked 7
innings and retired 17 straight between Miller's leadoff double in
the third and Miller's single in the eighth. After Brede walked,
Gabe White came in to get Fox and finished up.
</P>
<P>
   Daal's only real mistake was walking Reggie Sanders to lead off
the Reds first. Chris Stynes then hit a double play ball to Bell,
but shortstop Tony Batista dropped the relay throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just missed it,'' said Batista, back at his old position as
part of the experiment of trying Bell at second. ``That's one error
for me. It was a good flip.''
</P>
<P>
   Dmitri Young then lofted a pop fly that fell among Bell, Batista
and deep-playing center fielder Devon White for a single. The
consensus was that it was a catchable ball. Catchable by whom
wasn't totally clear, although Bell took responsibility. With the
bases loaded and none out, Paul Konerko popped out, but Boone's
sacrifice fly to left was deep enough to score Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   That was plenty for the Reds. The Diamondbacks were ``anemic,''
in Showalter's word, against Parris and White.
</P>
<P>
   It was hot on the AstroTurf, a day game after a night game, but
Showalter expected more and carefully noted what he saw. Or didn't
see.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today's one of those days when you can separate yourself
out,'' he said. ``A hot day and the standings are tough for you.
When I played, I looked at it as an opportunity to shine.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you've got to take the initiative, especially
at this time of year. First impressions and last impressions are
very important.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
