r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-A     09-13 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-TKACHUK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SMITH: WE CAN WIN WITHOUT TKA CHUK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - As he waits and ponders his next move from
his home near Boston, Keith Tkachuk can't help but wonder what life
without him might be like for the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   The star left wing will have plenty of time to think about it,
too, as he settles in for what figures to be a drawn-out and bitter
holdout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want it to come down to this. I wanted to be there
right from the start and not even have to think about that,'' said
Tkachuk, who was suspended by General Manager Bobby Smith on
Saturday for failing to report. Every day he sits will cost Tkachuk
more than $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they made a promise they couldn't keep, and that's why I'm
(in Boston) and not there,'' Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   ``How is the team going to do without me? Why don't you ask
Bobby Smith? He's the one who said the Coyotes can make the
playoffs without me. Apparently, they'll do fine without Keith
Tkachuk. They don't need me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk was being sarcastic, but Smith wasn't when he said last
month the Coyotes can succeed without their best player. They'll
begin to find out for certain today, when veterans open daily,
on-ice workouts at the Cellular One Ice Den in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keith's agent (Bob Murray) took real issue when I made that
statement, too, saying it's nothing but conjecture,'' Smith said.
``Well, I know it's conjecture, but I honestly believe we can make
the playoffs without Keith Tkachuk. I know we'd do better with him
in the lineup, but just look around at what we've got on this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Smith right? Let's look: &QL; 
The defense rests
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it seems this franchise has shaken itself from the
image of never having a top-notch NHL defense. Of the top five
D-men they plan to roll out for the season opener Oct. 11 against
Ottawa, only Teppo Numminen and Gerald Diduck were with the Coyotes
at the start of last season.
</P>
<P>
   But they managed to re-sign All-Star Oleg Tverdovsky, traded for
U.S. Olympian Keith Carney (from Chicago) and then locked up
perhaps the best blue-liner on the free-agent market for the next
four years by landing Jyrki Lumme (from Vancouver).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so good, you wouldn't believe it,'' said Coyotes center
Cliff Ronning, a teammate of Lumme's for in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Lumme is expected to team with Numminen on Phoenix's No. 1
defensive unit, which should be one of the strongest pairings in
the Western Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times, you never know how certain combinations are
going to work out,'' Coach Jim Schoenfeld said. ``Sometimes, what
you think makes perfect sense on paper doesn't always translate to
perfection on the ice. I don't know, but when I look at teaming
Teppo Numminen with a guy like Jyrki Lumme, I feel pretty safe it's
the right way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Carney and Tverdovsky should form the perfect one-two punch
behind the two Finns. Carney is a proven, stay-at-home defenseman
who looks after his own end, and Tverdovsky is a huge offensive
threat, having finished fourth in the league among defensemen in
scoring two seasons ago with 55 points as a 20-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   Diduck, a 14-year pro, brings stability to the third unit, where
he will be joined by any one of a handful of capable linemates. &QL; 
Center of attention &QL; 
Tkachuk was furious to see his good friend and favorite center,
Craig Janney, get dealt to Tampa Bay this summer. But by sheer
reduction _ including to the team payroll (Janney made $1.5
million) _ the Coyotes actually strengthened the center position.
</P>
<P>
   Janney's departure means fan favorite Jeremy Roenick can vault
to the No. 1 line, where he was so successful as a Chicago
Blackhawk for seven seasons. He's capable of cracking the 100-point
mark again but probably won't if he can't pass the puck to the
goal-happy Tkachuk, who has averaged 41 goals a year since 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy had a great second half and a real good playoffs. He's
the kind of guy who builds on something like that,'' Schoenfeld
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronning also seems poised for a rejuvenation. When his ice time
picked up, he took off, finishing 14th in the league with 44
assists, one more than Janney. Expect that total to climb with a
full season centering the likes of Greg Adams and Rick Tocchet, who
love to crash the net and camp outside the crease.
</P>
<P>
   Depth is no problem, either. The Coyotes have four
interchangeable skaters who will battle for the regular, final two
spots _ Bob Corkum, Daniel Briere, Juha Ylonen and Mike Stapleton.
Briere, 20, is an offensive machine, and the other three are among
the best penalty-killers on the squad. &QL; 
Left wing lock &QL; 
They might not have Tkachuk, but the Coyotes finally found a second
left wing who can step in and supply some offense. Adams, the
former standout from Northern Arizona University who spent the past
three seasons with the Dallas Stars, gives Phoenix instant
credibility at the position.
</P>
<P>
   If he can stay healthy, he's a 20- to 25-goal scorer. The
Coyotes haven't received more than 11 goals from any other left
wing besides Tkachuk since relocating from Winnipeg. Adams is 35,
but he should flourish here. He also might be asked to step up to
the top line alongside Roenick and right wing Dallas Drake and fill
Tkachuk's skates as long as the captain continues to sit. &QL; 
Leadership &QL; 
Tkachuk will tell you he still views himself as the leader of the
Coyotes _ whether some fans agree with him or not _ but there will
be no lack of leadership without him. Tocchet will see to that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not long after he got here, I think more guys were listening
to (Tocchet) than anybody, maybe even more than the coaches,'' one
player said. ``He helped keep the team together. He knows exactly
what buttons to push.''
</P>
<P>
   If Smith and Schoenfeld decide to strip Tkachuk of his
captaincy. Tocchet is the safe bet to wear the ``C.'' Numminen and
Roenick, assistant captains last season, are also possibilities. &QL; 
The puck stops here
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Nikolai Khabibulin is back to form after enduring a
couple of shaky slumps last season, there is little to worry about
in the goaltending department. He still posted 30 wins for the
second straight year and continues to be on the doorstep of moving
into NHL elite status.
</P>
<P>
   With veteran Jimmy Waite back for a full season, and improving
rookie Scott Langkow, the AHL's goalie of the year, Khabibulin will
get adequate rest and relief. Remember, he started 60 straight
games at one point, the second-longest streak in modern NHL
history. &QL; 
The verdict
</P>
<P>
   Are the Coyotes a better team without Keith Tkachuk? Yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   They'd be better with him. But after a busy summer of free
agency and trades, which also brought in J.F. Jomphe, Louie
DeBrusk, Mike Sullivan and Joe Dziedzic, and the expected
improvement within from Roenick, goalie Nikolai Khabibulin and
youngsters such as Brad Isbister and Shane Doan, they're better
than they were.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at what happened in Detroit during (Sergei) Fedorov's
holdout,'' Smith said. ``All the other guys stepped up and got the
job done. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be very disappointed if Keith Tkachuk isn't in our
lineup, but if you look at this objectively, we'll still have a
better team on opening night 1998 than we had in 1997. I don't see
how you can dispute that.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
