<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2514 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-MARIS-HAL     09-13 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-MARIS-HALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOMEZ: MCGWIRE'S A LOCK, BUT HALL SHOULD GIVE MARIS 2ND LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Not only did Mark McGwire almost single-handedly bring
baseball back this summer, he could wind up carrying Roger Maris
into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire's assault on the single-season home run record returned
Maris' name to the forefront of the baseball world.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire probably has cemented his placement in the Hall of Fame,
especially considering he has hit more than 50 home runs in each of
the the past three years, a feat that never had been accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   But don't forget, it wasn't that long ago that McGwire was
anything but a lock for the hallowed Hall.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire missed most of two seasons because of foot ailments,
hitting a combined 18 home runs in 1993 and '94. Even after
back-to-back 50 home run seasons, McGwire easily could have slipped
back in the pack with another injury-filled season in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But after breaking the single-season home run record and
fattening his career total to 449, McGwire basically has secured
his placement in Cooperstown. A more amazing feat on McGwire's part
would be dragging Maris in with him.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime followers of the game believe more was written and
spoken about Maris over the past two weeks than when the reluctant
record breaker set the single-season standard with 61 home runs in
1961.
</P>
<P>
   The forgotten hero, one who fought personal and public demons
much of his career, actually may find himself boomeranging into
Cooperstown's hallowed halls, albeit posthumously.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he does so while holding onto McGwire's coattail? Is
there really any shame in that? Well, at least one member of the
veterans committee believes there is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should he be in now?'' one of the members who will control
Maris' fate said. ``He wasn't a Hall of Famer two years ago. What
makes him one now?''
</P>
<P>
   And so, the argument rages on.
</P>
<P>
   While Maris, who died of cancer in 1985, no longer is eligible
on the regular ballot (a qualified player remains on Hall of Fame
ballot a maximum of 15 years), he still can be elected through the
veterans committee, where a panel of 15 distinguished members act
as a safety net for players who may get overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   Maris' name already has come up with the veterans committee,
which failed to induct him in previous attempts. But with the
massive amount of attention toward Maris this season, maybe it's
time to try one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been hopeful all along,'' Roger Maris Jr. said. ``I
think with the wave of energy that has been pushed behind him and
his name this year, I think if he doesn't get in the Hall of Fame
this year, after all the attention drawn to his name and what he
did, then he is just not meant to be in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   The case for Maris is compelling but far from a slam dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Maris played from 1957 to 1968, hitting 275 home runs and
driving in 851 runs while batting .260 in 1,463 games for the
Cleveland Indians, Kansas City Athletics, New York Yankees and St.
Louis Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, his most famous 61 home runs came during the 1961
season, when he broke the record previously held by Babe Ruth. It
was such a bittersweet time for Maris that he never could enjoy
what took place.
</P>
<P>
   The love fest that engulfed McGwire the past two weeks was
non-existent for Maris. Ruth's widow, who attended the final game
of the '61 season at Yankee Stadium when Maris set the record,
never acknowledged him. Those who covered the story say she openly
rooted against Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is pulling for Mark McGwire and they want to see him
do this, and I think that would be just an outstanding feeling for
my dad,'' Maris Jr., said. ``I wished that would have happened for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   While Maris' numbers might not stack up against the greatest
players in the Hall of Fame, they do measure up quite nicely
against some others who are enshrined.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 54 outfielders in the Hall of Fame, 36 have fewer career
home runs, including hitters such as Roberto Clemente, Goose
Goslin, Joe Medwick and Hack Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Another argument for placing Maris in the Hall is that he is the
only eligible player ever to win two Most Valuable Player awards
not inducted into Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   Almost lost when Maris hit his 61 home runs and in subsequent
years was his having won the American League MVP award the year
before, his first with the Yankees. Maris hit 39 home runs with 112
RBIs in 136 games for the Yankees in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   There is absolutely no clear-cut criteria for voting a player
into the Hall of Fame. Ballots are distributed to Baseball Writers
Association of America members who have covered baseball a minimum
of 10 consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for induction, a player must have played at least
10 major league seasons. A BBWAA screening committee then places
all those players who warrant consideration on the annual ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Each voter is then left to choose his own criteria for
inclusion. A common requirement is for a player to have been the
best at his position for at least a five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Maris comes awfully close using that requirement. He averaged 36
home runs from 1960 to '64. Despite playing in only 90 games in
1963, Maris averaged 95 RBIs during the same span.
</P>
<P>
   To be eligible for the veterans committee, a player must have
received at least 60 percent of the votes during one of his 15
eligible years on the regular ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Maris came close at least one of those years. It's
not like putting Maris into Cooperstown would be a stretch or put a
black eye on the integrity of the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   All things considered, Maris probably is straddling the fence
for inclusion into the Hall. However, taking into account what
Maris meant and did for the game, then any ties should go in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope the veterans committee sees it that way and at the
very least offers Maris' name up for consideration in January.
Inducting Maris into the Hall of Fame would not slight anyone
already there or those standing on the same fence as Maris.
</P>
<P>
   The veterans committee could make a wonderful gesture this
winter, one that would truly cap off a year filled with nothing but
celebration.
</P>
<P>
   What a sight it would be to see the Maris children accepting
Maris' spot in Cooperstown next summer. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at 602-444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
