<SLUG> BC-BBO-MCGWIRE-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEEK HAS BEEN A BALL FOR NEW INDUCTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first one-on-one interview with home run ball No. 62, which
now resides at the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   First, congratulations''.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, Sept. 8, 1998, you flew into baseball history
and became an instant celebrity. But you turned down every
interview'' request until now. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``Doctor's orders. I sustained a concussion.''
</P>
<P>
   You look fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the swelling has gone down.''
</P>
<P>
   Any stitches?
</P>
<P>
   (Ball rolls eyes and smiles.)
</P>
<P>
   All of America was watching when Mark McGwire came to bat. What
do you remember after you left pitcher Steve Trachsel's hand?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not much. The neurologist says the details may come back to me
in time. But it could be weeks, months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just remember shutting my eyes and thinking, `You can kiss
THIS baby goodbye.' I must have passed out.''
</P>
<P>
   You didn't hear the bat crack?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd roar?
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Did you see the flashbulbs? It was magical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the replay. They said it was McGwire's shortest home
run of the season. It also had to be one of the ``fastest.'' Next
thing I remember, I was behind the wall and a ballpark employee had
me in his hand. I heard him say he was going to give the ball to
McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy. And relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   How's that?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, for one thing, I could have ended up in the bleachers
and had people diving and piling on me, fighting over me like I was
a fumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's demeaning, and dangerous. Every home run ball's worst
fear. Plus, I could have been taken hostage.''
</P>
<P>
   A fan demanding a ransom. . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly.''
</P>
<P>
   That worried you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Look what happened to Patty Hearst.''
</P>
<P>
   But here you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still don't think it's sunk in. Pete Rose isn't in the Hall
of Fame and I am. A $9 baseball. It's unbelievable, really.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire talked about fate. Did you ever dream you might be the
ball he hit to break Roger Maris' record?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was aware of his home run pace. Everybody was. At the
Rawlings factory in Costa Rica I remember a ball _ we were packed
in the same box like eggs in a crate _ saying something like,
``Wouldn't it be great if we ended up in St. Louis in September.
One of us could become famous.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just kidding around, you know, joking the way people
do about winning the lottery.''
</P>
<P>
   Do you agree that McGwire's record-setting summer has revived
interest in baseball?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely. It's all the country talks about. McGwire and
Sosa. Fans complain about salaries. McGwire gets $8 million, more
than the president makes. But Mac has had a better year.''
</P>
<P>
   We know about Mark McGwire. He is divorced. His 10-year-old son
is the Cardinals batboy. Tell me about yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a SWM. Cushioned cork center. 5\ ounces. I like outdoors,
movies, sports, travel, dining out, quiet evenings. Seek special
lady for friendship, possible long-term relationship. Guess there's
not much chance of that now.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in here for life, man.''
</P>
<P>
   What's the Hall of Fame like?
</P>
<P>
   ``Musty.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but what a place. It's the Smithsonian of baseball. The
story of our national pastime is told here. There's Babe Ruth's bat
from 1927. Ty Cobb's cleats. DiMaggio's locker.
</P>
<P>
   `` What's a typical day for you like''?
</P>
<P>
   Truthfully? It's so boring. Doors open at 9. They close at 5. I
sit in this glass case. People walk by. They say `Look . . .' or
`Wow!' Most just stare. I feel like a moon rock.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ball looks around, lowers his voice.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mantle's bat and I are bustin' out at midnight a week from
Thursday. Keep it quiet.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
