<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-SUSPENSION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TKACHUK SUSPENDED, TO BE FINED $10,181 DAILY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - If  &UR; Keith Tkachuk plans to stick it to the
Coyotes by refusing to report to training camp, the Coyotes plan to
stick it him _ and his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what they did Saturday to the holdout left wing,
announcing that they have suspended Tkachuk and that he immediately
will begin losing a portion of his $2.8 million salary this season
every day he continues to sit out.
</P>
<P>
   After one day, it already has cost him $10,181 _ his average
daily salary based on the 275 days of the NHL season, including
training camp and the preseason.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said rules in the NHL's collective
bargaining agreement allow teams to forfeit a day's pay from any
player with a contract who refuses to report to his team. He
notified Tkachuk's agent,  &UR; Bob Murray, of the team's decision by
fax Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murray nor Tkachuk, the team's captain and leading
scorer each of the past three seasons, could be reached for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk, 26, has two years left on his contract, but he is
demanding a multiyear extension that would pay him at least $8
million annually and make him one of the NHL's highest-paid
players.
</P>
<P>
   Although the suspension figures to be a significant financial
hit for Tkachuk, Smith wasn't prepared to speculate whether it
could convince Tkachuk to abruptly end his holdout, which
officially enters Day 2 today, when veterans skate for the first
time in Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Smith said. ``I just know we're doing what the
rules say we do. We play by the rules, and this is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tkachuk sits out the entire preseason and then decides to
report for the season opener Oct. 11 against Ottawa, he will have
forfeited $295,272.72.
</P>
<P>
   Smith suspended Tkachuk last season on the eve of the Coyotes'
final preseason game for refusing to play in any exhibition games.
He reported to camp and worked out with the club every day, but
staged a boycott of the preseason games because he wanted his
contract restructured.
</P>
<P>
   Tkachuk didn't forfeit any money then because he had reported to
camp and was practicing.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rejected two last-ditch contract proposals from Murray on
Friday, calling them ``outlandish and offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   An NHL source close to both parties said the latest offers were
not less than the $40 million-plus package Murray and Tkachuk
originally presented in May. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
