A2518 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     09-13 1674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE STILL DELIVERING AT GATE _ AND AS PERSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Mark McGwire became the single-season home run record holder.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire and the St. Louis Cardinals watched more than 100,000
fans file into Cinergy Field for a two-game set between the
Cardinals and Reds. On Friday night it was more of the same as more
than 51,000 showed up at the Houston Astrodome, giving McGwire a
standing ovation when he came to the plate in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he felt in the middle of the game (Tuesday), he was so
exhausted he talked about scratching the day altogether,''
Cardinals Manager  &UR; Tony La Russa. ``I said, `Let's talk about it on
the plane and see how you feel (Wednesday).' He didn't sleep very
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he was aware that there was a big crowd (nearly 52,000),
and he thought he had the responsibility to do something. I want to
apologize to the fans, but they got two at-bats and I was proud of
Mark for making himself available, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The following is a sampling of some lesser-known facts about
McGwire's week:
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference at Cinergy Field the day after McGwire
hit the record-setting 62nd home run, Cincinnati rookie first
baseman  &UR; Sean Casey hid behind a curtain and photographed him.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 51,969 showed up at Cinergy Field to see McGwire, who
was prepared to take a day off but decided to play half the game
upon learning of the size of the crowd, which was the largest
non-opening day crowd since the stadium opened in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The Milwaukee Brewers were on a charter flight from Pittsburgh
to Houston when the pilot told the club over the cabin's speakers
of McGwire's historic home run. ``When we got to the hotel, I
stayed up all night watching (the coverage),'' Brewers Manager
 &UR; Phil
 &UR; Garner said.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has hit 50 home runs against right-handed pitchers and
12 against lefties. He has hit 32 at Busch Stadium and 30 on the
road. Tuesday seems to be his favorite day, having hit 15 on that
day.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire hit home runs against 19 of the Cardinals' 20 opponents
this season. Detroit, which only played St. Louis twice, is the
only club not to give up a home run to McGwire this season.
</P>
<P>
   A clause in McGwire's contract kicked in during Tuesday's
memorable game, one in which he receives $1 for every ticket sold
over 2.8 million. So far, McGwire has earned $7,599. The Cardinals
are expected to draw somewhere around 3.2 million fans, which would
translate into about $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   In 189 games with St. Louis, McGwire has 86 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, McGwire has been the story of the 1998 season. Hands
down. &QL; 
A Mickey Mouse decision &QL; 
The Anaheim Angels finally acknowledged the deal they turned down
last year with Oakland, the one that could have landed the Angels
the game's current icon, McGwire.
</P>
<P>
   It's now known the Angels could have had McGwire and third
baseman
 &UR; Scott Brosius, who was an American League All-Star for the Yankees
this season, in exchange for center fielder  &UR; Jim Edmonds and third
baseman  &UR; Dave Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives, however, decided to nix the deal, which
Oakland had agreed to complete. The biggest problem for the Disney
executives was their uneasiness with what it would take to sign
McGwire in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, McGwire, who grew up in Los Angeles, would have
probably done anything to make a deal work with the Angels,
especially since his 10-year old son,  &UR; Matthew, lives in Orange
County.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; John McGwire, Mark's father, recently told  &UR; Ross Newhan of the
``Los Angeles Times'' that the Angels ``obviously missed the boat''
and that he was ``terribly disappointed with the Disney
organization'' for failing to recognize what McGwire would mean at
the gate and on the field for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The senior McGwire also was upset that the Angels passed on
McGwire, an All-American at Southern California at the time, in the
1984 draft after a scout ``sat in our living room and led us to
believe they were going to pick him.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter  &UR; Chuck Finley couldn't help but wonder what might
have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over here, there's no telling what he might have done,''
Finley said, ``with all the smaller yards and the protection in our
lineup. He might be pushing 80 right now.'' &QL; 
Eating at Raul &QL; 
 &UR; Raul Mondesi, who returned to his familiar spot in right field
recently after  &UR; Gary Sheffield's season ended because of a severely
sprained ankle, is talking like a man who wants to return
permanently to a position where he won two Gold Gloves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right field, that's my best position,'' Mondesi said. ``I
should be in right field to help my team. If the team wants to win
a lot of games, I can help do that in right field. When they asked
me to (switch positions), I wanted to help the team, you know? But
that's enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi played 94 games in center field after the Dodgers made
their blockbuster deal with Florida, acquiring Sheffield along with
three others for  &UR; Mike Piazza and  &UR; Todd Zeile. Still, Mondesi
leaves open the possibility of remaining in center field next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, maybe I can do this (play center),'' Mondesi
said. ``Maybe I'll just stay there because my team needs me
there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Tommy Lasorda, who turned over the duties of general manager to
 &UR; Kevin Malone on Friday, believes Mondesi is just being Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' Lasorda said after hearing Mondesi's quotes. ``He
doesn't want to play center field? Well that's where we need him to
play. I've known Raul for a long time, and that's just talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Just another day in Dodgerland. &QL; 
THE HIT LIST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gee, what a wonderful endorsement: Milwaukee's  &UR; Phil Garner,
who has managed the Brewers since 1992, suddenly has gone from
rock-solid to very iffy for next season. General Manager  &UR; Sal Bando
said, ``I think it's in the best interests of the club to wait
until after the season is over to re-evaluate everything.'' Ouch!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; C'mon, this is a joke, right?: Cleveland Manager
 &UR; Mike Hargrove had Toronto's  &UR; Jose Canseco intentionally walked in
the eighth inning during Monday's game. The catch? The Indians
trailed, 15-1, at the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback (specially selected for you St. Louis
 &UR; fans): Tom Niedenfuer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; What a very cool gesture: Seattle outfielder  &UR; Ken
 &UR; Griffey Jr. paid to fly a banner over Cincinnati's Cinergy Field on
Wednesday night when the St. Louis Cardinals were in town. It was a
salute to  &UR; Mark McGwire and his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trivia for the buffs: Five pitchers faced both
 &UR; McGwire and  &UR; Roger Maris in a regular season game, with none having
allowed a home run to both players. The five:  &UR; Tommy John,  &UR; Joe
Niekro,
 &UR; Phil Niekro,  &UR; Nolan Ryan and  &UR; Don Sutton. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's  &UR; Jay Buhner underwent ligament replacement (`` &UR; Tommy
 &UR; John'') surgery last week. The full recovery time is 6 to 8 months.
The Mariners are talking about possibly starting the season with
Buhner at first base and potential Gold Glove first baseman  &UR; David
 &UR; Segui in right field.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hideo Nomo is 1-4 with an 8.29 ERA in his past six starts. The
New York Mets, who have used a six-man rotation the past few weeks,
have dropped Nomo into their bullpen. Allowing him to continue
starting could have hurt their playoff chances. Willie Blair, are
you ready?
</P>
<P>
   Former American League Rookie of the Year  &UR; Marty
 &UR; Cordova is falling out of favor with Minnesota Manager  &UR; Tom Kelly,
who benched Cordova for two games last weekend. Opposing managers
have started walking Todd Walker to get to Cordova, who has only 10
home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh's  &UR; Jason Kendall entered the weekend with 20 stolen
bases, five short of tying the National League record for stolen
bases by a catcher, set in 1978 by  &UR; John Stearns of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's  &UR; Marlon Anderson hit a home run in his first
major league appearance Tuesday. The last Phillies player to do so
was  &UR; Ed Sanicki, who accomplished the feat on Sept. 14, 1949, in a
game at Pittsburgh's Forbes Field.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago White Sox GM  &UR; Ron Schueler gave first-round draft choice
 &UR; Kip Wells until Monday to decide whether he wants to accept the
White Sox's $1.2 million signing bonus. Wells, a right-handed
pitcher from Baylor, is seeking $1.7 million. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though Pittsburgh's attendance will not match last season's
of 1,657,022, Pirates GM  &UR; Cam Bonifay expects his club's payroll to
jump from $13.4 million to around $22 million. The Pirates had a
payroll of $9 million last season. Expect a power hitter to be
added via free agency.
</P>
<P>
   Texas appears on the verge of dropping opening day starter  &UR; John
Burkett from the rotation. Rangers Manager  &UR; Johnny Oates has so
little faith in Burkett that he pulled him from Tuesday's game
against Kansas City after 4 innings. Burkett had not allowed a run
at that point.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Giants officials are worried that  &UR; Kirk
 &UR; Rueter's pitching elbow is bothering him. Rueter insists nothing is
wrong, but the Giants will baby the left-hander the rest of the
season. Rueter was removed after five innings in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Kevin Malone took over as Los Angeles' GM on Friday afternoon.
The final boost for Malone may have come when  &UR; Dave
 &UR; Dombrowski, the Dodgers' top choice, gave a glowing recommendation
for Malone, who used to work with Dombrowski in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Just because  &UR; Dombrowski has agreed to return to Florida for the
next five years, courtesy of a $5 million contract that will make
him the highest-paid GM in the game, don't expect Manager  &UR; Jim
Leyland to follow suit. Leyland will have two weeks at season's end
to get out of the remaining three years of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fred Claire, unceremoniously ousted as Dodgers GM this summer,
could be in line to take over as Kansas City Royals president. They
could do worse than hiring Claire, who put together a solid Dodgers
club before it imploded. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Pedro Gomez can be
reached at 602-444-2364 or at pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
