<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEAM HITTING ROCK BOTTOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ The Diamondbacks are hitting so poorly as a team
that they can manage only three hits against the Reds and not lower
their batting average.
</P>
<P>
   Batting .245 before losing, 3-0, at Cinergy Field on Saturday,
the Diamondbacks are still hitting .245. That's dead last in the
majors.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has lost four straight. In their past three games, the
Diamondbacks have scored only three runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been a thorn for us all year,'' Manager  &UR; Buck
 &UR; Showalter said of the lack of offense. ``Statistics don't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a statistic: Until  &UR; Brent Brede walked in the eighth
inning, the Diamondbacks had sent up 98 hitters dating to Tuesday
without drawing a base on balls. Reds starter  &UR; Steve Parris had a
four-pitch inning in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never anticipate walks being part of your attack, but they
should be,'' Showalter said. ``Everybody's trying to bridge the gap
between being aggressive and being selective. Obviously, they
haven't done too good of a job with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach  &UR; Jim Presley said, ``When you only get three hits,
you'd better throw in some walks. Last week, we hit the ball really
well, but the past four or five days, we've struggled. . . . We've
got to swing at balls in the zone and we're not doing that right
now. When it goes bad, it goes.'' &QL; 
Going for it &QL; 
 &UR; Andy Benes, who starts for the Diamondbacks today, has a chance to
tie the record for pitching victories on an expansion team.
</P>
<P>
   Benes has 12 wins. The record is 13, held by  &UR; Gene Brabender of
the Seattle Pilots (1969),  &UR; Dave Lemanczyk of the Toronto Blue Jays
(1977) and Tampa Bay's  &UR; Rolando Arrojo, who will get a few more
starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Brian Anderson also has a shot. Anderson, who pitches Monday
against the San Francisco Giants, has 11 victories. &QL; 
Undecided &QL; 
Short of holding open tryouts, Showalter has an open mind about who
will pitch Wednesday against the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   It's  &UR; Clint Sodowsky's turn, but the right-hander has been
roughed up since joining the rotation Aug. 1. Sodowsky, the losing
pitcher in Friday's 13-1 loss to the Reds, has given up 18 earned
runs and 31 hits in 28 innings over six starts. He is 1-2 with
three no-decisions during that stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter and pitching coach  &UR; Mark Connor have discussed using
relievers  &UR; Willie Banks, Alan Embree and rookie  &UR; Vladimir Nunez.
And Sodowsky remains a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about everybody,'' Showalter said. &QL; 
Doing better &QL; 
The wife of Reds pitcher  &UR; Dennis Reyes has regained consciousness
and their premature newborn baby is healthy, the team reported.
</P>
<P>
   Because of complications and the condition of his wife,
 &UR; Clauvia, Reyes missed a start Thursday and returned home to
Higuera de Zaragoza in Mexico to be with his family. Reyes is
expected to rejoin the team Monday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
