<HEADLINE>
SAN CARLOS LAKE NEEDS HELP TO AVOID GOING DRY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - San Carlos Lake on the San Carlos Apache Reservation
is in danger of drying up again.
</P>
<P>
   The lake is at 9 percent of capacity and falling rather rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The lake has a history of going dry. But when it has water, it
may be the best fishing lake in the state. It also sustains
populations of eagles and other wildlife.
</P>
<P>
   It appeared it would go dry a year ago, but Congressman J.D.
Hayworth led a drive that included money from private interests to
purchase water from the Central Arizona Project. That water saved
the lake for another year.
</P>
<P>
   But it's in trouble again. How many times can it be saved?
Here's where it stands: Its prime feeder stream is the Gila River.
Above Safford, the river is running at 113 cubic feet per second.
But after irrigation water is pulled for agricultural purposes, the
flow into San Carlos is 32 cfs.
</P>
<P>
   Since most of the water in the lake is owned by water users
downstream, the current release from the lake is 460 cfs. That
means it's dropping at a steady rate, about 430 cfs.
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to be able to address the problems of this huge
recreational and wildlife resource.
</P>
<P>
   Water both above and below the lake is dedicated to irrigation.
The Apaches can't afford to buy back water. Private concerns and
governmental agencies can't continue to do it under current
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   If the lake is to reach any stability, it'll take governmental
action that will provide a constant flow of water.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't one of those easy problems to fix. &QL; 
Bad for hunters &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you haven't already read it, eight California men were cited
in the Yuma area for possession of 163 doves and are suspected of
shooting as many as 500.
</P>
<P>
   Seven plainclothes officers, four from the Arizona Game and Fish
Department and three from the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service,
observed the shooters killing doves and not attempting to retrieve
them.
</P>
<P>
   Doves are migratory birds and are subject to federal regulations
besides those of the state.
</P>
<P>
   One of the shooters had a sack of doves he intended to give
away, officers said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, officers used a dog to gather another 75 birds left
in the field. The remains of 50 more birds the men had killed the
day before also were recovered. The total number of birds found was
estimated at 200.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 shotgun shell casings were recovered.
</P>
<P>
   The bag limit for doves is 10.
</P>
<P>
   Officers said that overall compliance to laws was good by
hunters in the Yuma area and that the eight California shooters
were not a sign of a larger problem.
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes and no.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has been famous for its dove shoots. I say ``shoots''
instead of ``hunts'' because, unless a person has scouted the
territory for doves, that person knows where they are from past
experience and just goes to shoot. There is no hunt involved.
</P>
<P>
   Movie stars and other celebrities in addition to corporate
executives traditionally have come to Arizona to shoot doves.
</P>
<P>
   In the ``old days,'' shooters would take a limit of doves in the
morning, rest, then return to the field in the evening to shoot
another limit. We're not talking about common criminals here but
people who usually adhere to game laws.
</P>
<P>
   On my hunts this year, I have observed people shooting from
roads, which is illegal, and other offenses. They also left their
shell casings, which is littering. Most, I believe, are doing it
out of ignorance.
</P>
<P>
   But that's the problem with dove shooting in this state. In
other hunting sports, there truly is a hunt. It's a game. The
hunter surveys the territory, stalks the prey and tries to kill it.
</P>
<P>
   There are no apologies here. Hunting is both an ethically and
biologically sound outdoor pursuit _ unless it's abused.
</P>
<P>
   That's what bothers me. When shooting becomes an event instead
of a hunt, there's something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I think most dove shooters are ethical and law-abiding. But when
shooters kill doves just to see them fall, there's something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   I hope the Californians are prosecuted strictly. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
