<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONA-STANFORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 PLUS 2 EQUALS SCORE FOR WILDCATS' OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ It's a team with a lot of couples.
</P>
<P>
   Two and too.
</P>
<P>
   Call it Arizona math.
</P>
<P>
   Two quarterbacks in two games added up to two Arizona victories
Saturday with a 31-14 win at Stanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The whipping of Stanford 10 days after the season-opening win
over Hawaii are a couple of reasons to think that maybe, just
maybe, the Wildcats are better than expectations and
prognostications.
</P>
<P>
   But a couple of unknown factors have to be added to Arizona's
evolving equation.
</P>
<P>
   Too early?
</P>
<P>
   Too easy?
</P>
<P>
   Neither the NCAA Division I-A outpost at Hawaii nor the Pac-10
Conference's sadly-declining Cardinal resembles the projected
contenders that loom on Arizona's calender. So blame the schedule
maker. Or, if you're Arizona Coach Dick Tomey, put him on your
Christmas card list.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Tomey's Wildcats are gaining momentum for the
midseason and confidence in the evident talents they'll need for
tougher tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tickled to death,'' said Tomey, whose 1995 Wildcats
jumped out 2-0 only to lose four of their next five for a 6-5
finish. ``That was a hard-fought battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The battle in front of a tiny crowd on a warm day actually was
over early in the fourth quarter when Arizona quarterback Keith
Smith and receiver Dennis Northcutt noticed that the Cardinal had
just sent in an untested cornerback, freshman Brian Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   Smith and Northcutt delivered a 33-yard lesson to Stanford's
first-year student. Northcutt displayed some brilliant foot work
along one side of the end zone for a touchdown and one of his five
receptions for 160 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown was decisive. The Cardinal, now 0-2 after a
season-opening loss to San Jose State, had just scored by going 75
yards in six plays within 1:48. The quick strike killed any notion
of a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't just sit back and run the ball,'' said Smith, who
started, struggled and returned with the key play after Ortege
Jenkins led the Wildcats to three touchdowns and Mark McDonald
field goals in the second and third quarters. ``We couldn't play
conservative. About 12 minutes were left. We still had to play the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't play baby football.''
</P>
<P>
   No babies allowed.
</P>
<P>
   That, at least, has been the mature approach taken by Smith and
Jenkins through two games. On this day, Jenkins was more effective
after starting and struggling at Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford, crippled in the opening quarter by the loss of
receiver Troy Walters to an ankle sprain, represented Smith's turn
to start and struggle. The Wildcats muffed three scoring
opportunities and found themselves trailing, 7-0, 19 minutes after
the opening kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Jenkins.
</P>
<P>
   He went 8 of 14 with 158 yards, including a 22-yard touchdown
strike to Jeremy McDaniel, whose moves along the sidelines and
through defenders would dazzle an skilled dance partner.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins also scrambled 20 yards for a key first down, tossed a
44-yarder to Northcutt and handed off to Kelvin Eafon for
touchdowns on runs of 10 and 4 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got two great quarterbacks,'' said Jenkins, whose
day was helped immeasurably by the return of running back Trung
Canidate, a former Central High star who rushed for 110 yards in
his first game since recovering from a stress fracture. ``I was
excited all week after I struggled at Hawaii. I wanted to compete
and help the team win. I didn't get the chance at Hawaii, because
Keith was so hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't how you can keep me off the field. I don't how you can
keep Keith off the field. I'm glad I don't have to make the
decision. That's a tough one.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, it's also been a good one. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
