<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2524 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PANEL-COX     09-13 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PANEL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party circles wagons
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Since independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
on President Clinton was made public Friday, Washington has been
running full tilt.
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions of the president's sexual encounters with
Lewinsky _ broadcast on television and reprinted in major
newspapers across the country _ were truly the talk of the town
Saturday. Outside a downtown Starbucks, where tourists chatted as
they ordered their double lattes, a homeless man closely read a
tattered copy of the Washington Post's reprint of the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   As the White House braced for reaction to the lurid descriptions
in Starr's report, leaders in the Democratic Party attempted to
pull their membership together.
</P>
<P>
   In an hourlong phone conversation Saturday, House Democratic
leaders talked about ways to overcome Starr's report and what to
expect as the Judiciary Committee ponders whether there is enough
evidence to warrant an impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   The strategists included Majority Whip David Bonior of Michigan,
Rep. Rosa DeLauro (D-Conn.), Robert Menendez (D-N.J.), Vic Fazio
(D-Calif.), Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.) and Martin Frost (D-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   Their hope: The American people will see it as a report about
the president lying about a sexual affair to protect his family
from the hardship of discovering the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is disgusting,'' said John Lewis, who, like DeLauro
and Menendez, is one of the party's chief deputy whips. ``But this
is not a Watergate, it is not what Nixon did. To me, the president
had an affair with a girl and lied about it.''
</P>
<P>
   And as the Democrats conferred on the phone, work on the report
continued. In a plain, government-issue room of the Gerald R. Ford
Office Building, Republican and Democratic staffers from the House
Judiciary Committee labored into the night, poring over some 2,000
pages of supporting material sent by Starr to back up his
allegation that Clinton has committed impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Pressure is building in both parties to make this next batch of
material public because it contains evidence Starr believes backs
up the 445-page report alleging that Clinton committed perjury and
then obstructed justice by concealing an adulterous affair with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Abbe Lowell,chief counsel to the Democrats on the Judiciary
Committee, and David Schippers, his Republican counterpart, started
reviewing files as soon as the sergeant-at-arms unsealed the boxes
Friday. Lowell stayed until midnight when one of the three
permanent guards stationed in front of the room asked him to leave.
</P>
<P>
   The guards are stationed to protect the 2,000 pages and 17 boxes
of evidence that have not been made public and to keep the media
from entering the building. Lowell and Schippers must approve any
slip of paper going into the room. No recording devices are
permitted and security codes must be punched in before anyone is
allowed in the room. There is also a motion detector inside, which
requires a special code to shut it off.
</P>
<P>
   These elaborate security precautions did little to stop TV crews
from lining up in front of the nondescript outpost on Capitol Hill.
They came as early as 8 a.m. to wait for a comment from a member of
the House Judiciary Committee, the panel charged with overseeing
any possible impeachment hearings, and the only group allowed to
enter the room other than the investigatory staffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has been going on for a long time; we are new meat
in a den of hungry animals,'' said Lowell, referring to the
mediaoutside as he walked back into the room.
</P>
<P>
   The documents could be made public as early as midweek, as
Democrats want to get the evidence out as quickly as possible. This
was a strategy used during last summer's hearings into whether the
Democratic National Committee and the White House violated campaign
fund-raising laws. The idea is to get the bad news out as quickly
as possible to lessen the long-term damage.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the Democratic National Committee adopted another
strategy, sending an analysis of Starr's report to decision-makers
throughout the country, including a chart with a headline asking:
``Where's Whitewater?'' The text pointed out that Starr's report
mentioned sex 548 times and Whitewater, the failed land deal Starr
was hired to investigate four years ago, only twice.
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis sees it, Starr's report fails to make a case for
impeachment, and Clinton has been punished enough by the pain his
behavior has caused his family and the public humiliation he has
been forced to endure.
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats have not been as supportive. The real test will
come after the nation has had time to digest the massive Starr
report, which lists 11 grounds for the possible impeachment of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde (R-Ill.), who has made
numerous assurances that any inquiry will be bipartisan, said
Saturday that he is unhappy with the ``salacious material.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think one of the downsides, or fallouts, from this whole
process has been giving too much currency to salacious activities
and talk,'' Hyde said. ``I don't think that's helpful to the
country, but there's a tremendous demand for the whole story to be
put out on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the panel fear politics will play a role in putting
that story on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people deserve an analysis of Ken Starr's
evidence and a determination of the future course of Congress
(that) is fair and objective,'' said Jim Jordan, spokesperson for
the Democratic side.
</P>
<P>
   California Democratic Rep. Zoe Lofgren, a member of the
Judiciary panel, said she sees her job as applying the law to
facts. And the facts, she notes, do not rise to the level of facts
laid out in the Watergate impeachment inquiry of former President
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the behavior; obviously, it's tawdry,'' Lofgren
said of Clinton. ``But the question is not how I feel about his
behavior, which is obviously immoral and wrong. The question for me
as a member of the Judiciary Committee is to use my head and apply
facts to law, and that's what I will do.''
</P>
<P>
   When she does apply facts to law, she is skeptical that, at this
point, the Starr report allegations rise to the level of
impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't really address the issue of the Constitution at
all, which I think is kind of shocking, and the one area where he
addresses it in a hasty fashion, it is legally deficient,'' said
Lofgren, a lawyer and former low-level Democratic aide during the
Watergate inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
