<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-SIDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENS SHRUGS OFF BRUSHBACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Thirteen seasons as a professional
baseball player advised Rangers designated hitter Lee Stevens of
what to expect.
</P>
<P>
   Major-league pitchers often don't surrender consecutive home
runs within a span of six pitches and not send a message to the
next batter who steps to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays right-hander Julio Santana, a former Rangers player
and Stevens teammate, delivered his message with a first-pitch,
head-high fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had some good swings against him, and he tried to throw
the ball up and in,'' Devil Rays manager Larry Rothschild said.
``He didn't hit him, and he didn't try to hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, who came to the plate after consecutive third-inning
home runs by first baseman Mike Simms and catcher Ivan Rodriguez,
displayed no emotion after the pitch sailed past his head and to
the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have hit me if he wanted,'' Stevens said. ``He throws
95 mph.''
</P>
<P>
   Plate umpire Larry McCoy intervened immediately and issued a
warning to both benches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me he didn't want anything to get started, and that's
why he warned Santana,'' Rothschild said.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens understood why Santana responded in the manner he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was just something he felt had to be done,''
Stevens said. ``He didn't let it go. He didn't throw it as hard as
he could have.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers right-hander Rick Helling planned to deliver a similar
message to a player in the Devil Rays' lineup, but several in the
visitors' dugout urged their starting pitcher not to retaliate and
risk being ejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't care less if I go four innings and we win the
game,'' Helling said. ``The guys know that I'm going to do whatever
it takes to protect our hitters.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens no doubt appreciated Helling's sentiments, but he
downplayed the incident and the situation never escalated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things happen,'' Stevens said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0044EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
