<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-ALLEN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICKING UP THE TAB  
 ALLEN'S DEEP POCKETS HOLD KEY TO SEATTLE HOPES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE Let's see. . . What has Paul Allen bought lately?
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, it's been a few more companies, a ton of land
in and around Seattle, an election and another pro sports
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a new week, and this fun-loving multibillionaire
techno-wizard knows no bounds. If he can think it, he can do it.
And he has.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, who founded Microsoft with high school buddy Bill Gates,
is the nation's third-wealthiest person. Only Gates, at $48
billion, and investor Warren Buffett, at $33 billion, rank ahead of
Allen and his $21 billion net worth, according to ``Forbes''
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   So, coughing up $6 million for lobbying, public relations and
campaign ads and picking up the tab for the June 1997 special
election in which the people of Washington narrowly agreed to pitch
in $300 million to help him build a new $425 million football
stadium and exhibition center in downtown Seattle was pocket change
to Allen.
</P>
<P>
   He told the people of the state that if they helped pay for the
complex, he would buy the NFL's Seattle Seahawks for $200 million
and keep them in the Emerald City. They did, and he has.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are the Seahawks staying, but Allen has begun building
them into something special, as swiftly and proactively as he did
with his personal empire.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a salary cap in place in the NFL to keep someone from
just buying players,'' said Cardinals Coach Vince Tobin, whose team
visits Allen's Seahawks this afternoon at 1. ``There are parameters
that we all are required to operate within. But at the same time,
there are things that the wealthiest owners can do with signing
bonuses that has diluted the purpose of the cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure even the wealthiest owner can go out and buy a
Super Bowl winner, but but there are ways he can make his team much
more competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen has figured that out.
</P>
<P>
   With huge signing bonuses, Allen has landed free agents and
reached quick agreement with high draft picks. He also has rewarded
those already on the roster with extensions or renegotiations that
include whopping bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   The most striking example to Cardinals fans was Allen's victory
in the Ricky Watters sweepstakes in March. Watters, a Pro Bowl
running back whose contract had expired at Philadelphia, visited
the Cardinals the final week of February and came away impressed,
calling them an exciting, young, up-and-coming team.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals thought they had him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Allen swooped in, offered up the Seahawks as an example of
a young team reloaded for a playoff run, and reinforced his
argument with an offer of a $5 million signing bonus in a $13.5
million deal over five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Always the money is important,'' said Watters, whose only
question to Allen was, ``Where do I sign?''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals couldn't match that signing bonus _ guaranteed
upfront money; yearly salaries in the NFL generally are make-good
only _ and Watters quickly became a Seahawk on March 4.
</P>
<P>
   Feagles signed &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Allen took another bite out of the Cardinals when he offered
their punter, Jeff Feagles, an unprecedented $1.06 million signing
bonus. Feagles is a Valley native who'd had four productive seasons
with the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   But Cardinals owner Bill Bidwill couldn't compete with such a
huge guarantee, so the free-agent Feagles packed up and headed to
the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Allen has shelled out slightly more than $47 million in
guaranteed signing bonuses to 12 key players since he took control
of the team in June 1997 from the Behring family.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Paul, obviously we've gone out and been more active in
free agency,'' said Seahawks Coach Dennis Erickson, whose future
with the team has been enhanced by improved personnel. ``He has
enabled us to do things with upfront money to get players in here.
That's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen describes himself as an idea man, a visionary. His
interests are broad, and he is anything but stingy with his wealth.
</P>
<P>
   He bought the Seahawks not only to keep them in his native
Seattle but also because he and his nephews like football. One
night while visiting the kids, he asked his sister if she liked
football. When the answer was yes, his decision was made _ if the
public would help him replace the aging Kingdome, a structure that
has been deemed not to be earthquake proof.
</P>
<P>
   Vote of confidence &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So he took his case to the public. His purchase was contingent
upon passage of Referendum 48 in 1997. Allen said he would be
personally responsible for any cost overruns, which already have
topped $30 million before ground has been broken. Opponents brought
consumer crusader Ralph Nader to town. Nader was no match for
Allen, who made a rare public appearance in a TV ad for the
project.
</P>
<P>
   When the state's voters agreed to spend $300 million for their
portion, Allen, celebrated at Seattle's historic Union Station,
which Allen is spending millions to restore, by cranking up his own
electric guitar and jamming.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really stepped to the plate on the stadium issue,''
Erickson said. ``It's great for the team and great for the city of
Seattle.''
</P>
<P>
   Groundbreaking is scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Seahawks, the Cardinals are a rebuilding team trying to
get a better facility.
</P>
<P>
   Allen certainly has been more proactive in the community on his
stadium issue than Bill Bidwill, owner of the Cardinals, has been
on his, although Bidwill's son, Michael, has been a key mover and
shaker in the proposed Rio Salado Crossing project.
</P>
<P>
   And while Bidwill couldn't match the signing bonuses that Allen
offered down the line, it might be surprising to know that Bidwill
has paid two signing bonuses higher than any Allen has ever paid,
$7.5 million to defensive tackle Eric Swann in February, and $10.49
million to rookie Andre Wadsworth last week.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bidwill &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill and Allen are more alike than people might imagine.
</P>
<P>
   They're both perceived as reclusive, although neither really is.
Both guard their privacy. Among acquaintances, though, they're
gregarious and fun-loving. Allen recently cut his trademark long
hair and shaved his beard because he said too many people had begun
to recognize him. Now clean-cut with dark-rimmed glasses, he
resembles the computer nerd most incorrectly believed him to be.
Yet Allen, 45, annually pops up on the list of most eligible
bachelors in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to comparing wallets, neither Bidwill nor any
other NFL owner can keep up with Allen, who also owns the NBA
Portland Trail Blazers and the new facility in which they play, the
Rose Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Allen, driven by his love of the music of Jimi Hendrix, is
building a rock and roll museum at Seattle Center, best known for
the Space Needle. Allen has his own garage rock band and built a
recording studio for him and his pals.
</P>
<P>
   He throws big-time parties for big-time celebrities _ everywhere
from Cannes, France, to the world's ritziest cruise ship off the
coast of Alaska. The cruise guest list included Bill and Melinda
Gates; actresses Debbie Reynolds, Candace Bergen, Carrie Fisher and
Penny Marshall; actors Robin Williams, Dan Aykroyd and Jeff
Goldblum; moviemakers Francis Ford Coppola and ``Titanic'' director
James Cameron; former NBA star Clyde Drexler, who played for Allen
in Portland; and musician Quincy Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Allen organized a masked ball in Venice for 300 friends last
year.
</P>
<P>
   He is altruistic as well as hedonistic. Last year, Allen donated
$32.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   He clearly is a man who loves life, driven by the scare of
losing it when he was diagnosed in 1983 with Hodgkin's disease.
That's why he left Microsoft. The disease is in remission.
</P>
<P>
   But Allen is rich because he is visionary. He sees the next wave
of technology being tied to fiber optics, something he calls
``Wired World.'' He explains his ``Wired World'' philosophy, and
his projects that have touched every aspect of Northwest life _
from the arts to environment, recreation, medical research,
education and the economy _ on his own Web site ( &UR; www &QL; 
 &UR; .paulallen.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always thinking about the future as a kid,'' Allen told
the ``Seattle Times'' in a rare interview last year. ``When you're
a kid, you think anything is possible. You don't know about
constraints.''
</P>
<P>
   He still doesn't. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
