</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASTECH-NORTHTEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVENGE-SEEKING TEXAS TECH ROUTS NORTH TEXAS, 30-0
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Fred Pertile spent the summer back in Midland,
preparing for this upcoming season and talking a little trash to
his friends playing for Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Pertile, a sophomore linebacker at North Texas, relished in
reminding them of Tech's surprising loss to a 30-point underdog UNT
team last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We beat them,'' Pertile said, ``but tonight they ``really''
beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech exacted a measure of revenge, handing UNT a 30-0 loss last
night at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   UNT upset and embarrassed Tech with a 30-27 victory in Week 4
last season in Lubbock. Tech looked anything but upset and
embarrassed last night.
</P>
<P>
   The offense was decent. The defense was salty. The results were
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Tech held UNT to 125 yards in total offense while racking up 531
yards for themselves. The Eagles managed just five first downs
while the Red Raiders had 30. Tech scored. UNT didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we are horrendous on offense, and that's nobody's
fault but mine,'' Eagles coach Darrell Dickey said. ``We don't have
a running play that we can hang our hat on, that we can execute
real well and make a few yards, and that's something we're going to
have to address _ very quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Tech coach Spike Dykes: ``The defense controlled the game
to a point where we didn't have a chance to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech nailed down the necessary points for winning with a single
play, a perfectly delivered pass from Matt Tittle to Donnie Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Tittle, a Marcus High School graduate, delivered a perfectly
placed ball to Hart for a 44-yard touchdown on Tech's opening play
from scrimmage. Two touchdowns and a barrage of field goals
followed as UNT struggled to slow Tech.
</P>
<P>
   Tittle finished 16-of-27 for 257 yards with a touchdown and
three interceptions while Red Raiders tailback Ricky Williams added
170 yards on 28 rushes with two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   UNT had 68 yards rushing in all, and failed to convert four Tech
turnovers into any points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out and were talking a little trash about last year,
and they were getting hot,'' Eagles offensive lineman Phillip
Armour said. ``You could tell that last year was their prime
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Dykes said the loss had sat with his players all year. ``The
only way to do something about it is to shut up and play,'' Dykes
said. ``I thought our guys did a nice job of shutting up and
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   And now this summer, they will be able to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Pertile knows it is coming, the payback for a summer of popping
last season's game into the VCR when Tech's Antwan Alexander and
John Norman were visiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll try to forget it, but I know that John and Antwan won't
let me,'' Pertile said. ``I know they will not let me live it
down.'' &QL; 
EXTRA POINTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Waxahachie's Montae Reagor recorded two tackle for a loss,
passing Zach Thomas for Tech's all-time lead with 30. ... Tech
hadn't gone 2-0 to open a season since 1989. ... UNT's Lawrence
Ellis, Heath Moody and Jeff Rodgers all snagged their first career
interceptions against Tech. ... UNT quarterback Chase Corley took
his first collegiate snap last night in relief of Jason Attaway.
His first completion was a 33-yard pass to Broderick McGrew. He was
3-of-8 for 47 yards. ... Tech kicker Jaret Greaser strained a groin
muscle in the third quarter, and was replaced by Chris Birkholz,
who made his first career field goals (43 and 45 yards). ... UNT
finished with eight offsides penalties on defense. ... UNT punter
and All-America candidate John Baker averaged 45.3 yards in eight
attempts yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
