</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-SCHOENFELD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDSKINS' QB SWAP SHOWS SIGNS OF PANIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were the popular pick to win the NFC East, the team that
spent about $58 million on twin defensive tackles  &UR; Dana
Stubblefield and  &UR; Dan
 &UR; Wilkinson.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Washington Redskins should have found themselves a
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Coach  &UR; Norv Turner benched starter  &UR; Gus Frerotte in the second
half of last week's loss at the New York Giants and has replaced
him for Monday night's game against San Francisco with a guy who
has thrown one pass in five years in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Going to  &UR; Trent Green one game into the season isn't just
bizarre, it's a panic move.
</P>
<P>
   Even Green, the team's third-string quarterback as of two weeks
ago, was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always prepare myself like it could happen, but to think
this was going to happen in the second week . . .'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Why shouldn't Green be surprised?
</P>
<P>
   He was the 222nd of 224 players taken in the 1993 draft out of
Indiana, then was cut by the San Diego Chargers after his rookie
year. He was unemployed in '94 until he took a job selling
furniture in Bloomington, Ind.
</P>
<P>
   Green didn't give up his dream to start in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd basically bug everybody,'' he said. ``I'd say, `Hey, I'm
still out there, still working. Keep me in mind.'''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Green played for the British Columbia Lions of the
Canadian League before signing with the Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, the Redskins spent the third pick overall in the
draft on Tennessee quarterback  &UR; Heath Shuler and a seventh-round
choice on Frerotte. Shuler was cut after the '96 season, and
Frerotte's job now is in trouble, especially because he also has a
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help Frerotte any that after throwing his second
interception in the third quarter a week ago, linebacker  &UR; Marvcus
 &UR; Patton got in Frerotte's face on the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm emotional on the field,'' Patton said. ``Football's an
emotional game. Things just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner had to break up the teammates. Amazingly, Turner defended
Patton's actions, saying, ``He's trying to keep Gus going. He's
trying to keep him focused and in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Those statements sound as if they are coming from a coach who
has lost control of his team and could be on the hot seat.
</P>
<P>
   Turner is 26-38-1 in four years and hasn't taken the Redskins to
the playoffs. Now, the team is up for sale, which won't help
Turner's security.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I was pretty upset,'' Frerotte said of Patton's
sideline display. ``I was in a lot of pain. I had a couple of bad
plays, but you don't have to tell me when I made a bad play. If
anybody knows it, I do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marvcus and I talked. He apologized. He's an emotional guy.
We've all been through two rough years.'' &QL; 
Dirty pool &QL; 
Stubblefield never thought he would leave the San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a time when I just knew they cannot get rid of me or
B.Y. (defensive tackle Bryant Young),'' Stubblefield said.
``They're not going to separate us. I just knew for sure that they
had lost their mind if they got rid of one of us. It was a definite
surprise when things didn't work out between me and the Niners
because I just knew it would. I took it at first like, `OK, they
don't want me, forget them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   He'll be lined up against 14-year veteran  &UR; Ray Brown but also is
expected to face right guard  &UR; Kevin Gogan on some plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing about Ray, I know he's not going to try to cut me or
cheap-shot me or doing anything illegal like that,'' Stubblefield
said. ``I know Gogan (will), but Ray won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Gogan has the reputation as a cheap-shot artist. In fact, he was
thrown out of last year's Pro Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Stubby,'' Gogan said. ``I wouldn't like to do it to him,
but if I have to, I will. I might get my hands on him a few
times.'' &QL; 
Rough ride &QL; 
Former Detroit Lions Coach  &UR; Wayne Fontes has made a workers'
compensation claim against the team because of a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Fontes claims he suffered on-the-job injuries during his eight
years with the team that have resulted in permanent disability.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, he said he had to ride around in a golf cart his
final few seasons because standing on the sidelines was too hard on
his back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special man to claim incapacitation and then go out
and play in numerous charity golf outings,'' Lions Vice President
 &UR; Tom
 &UR; Lewand said. &QL; 
Right choice &QL; 
When the Pittsburgh Steelers had a coaching opening in 1992,
 &UR; Bill &UR; Cowher was picked over  &UR; Dave Wannstedt, &UR; who wound up with the
Chicago Bears.
</P>
<P>
   Cowher goes into today's game against the Chicago Bears with a
70-38 record, six playoff appearances, five AFC Central titles and
one Super Bowl berth.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt is 36-45 and led the Bears to playoffs only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our three highest-paid players last year were
( &UR; Alonzo) &UR; Spellman, &UR; ( &UR; Bryan) &UR; Cox and  &UR; Rick Mirer,'' Wannstedt said.
``And none of them is on the team (this year). That kind of sums it
up why we're backed into a corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed on way too many draft picks. But the reason we're
backed into a corner is because we've missed on and made mistakes
in the personnel area and free agency that a lot of teams haven't
made, primarily the Steelers.'' &QL; 
Spectacular debut &QL; 
Minnesota Vikings rookie wide receiver  &UR; Randy Moss was so
impressive in his first pro game that teammate  &UR; Robert Smith
already is predicting Moss will make the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm serious,'' he said. ``You could see it after the first day
of practice. There is nothing he can't do. Anybody who said they
knew he was going to be this good, they're just not telling the
truth. If NFL teams thought he was going to be this good, you think
he would have dropped all the way to 21 (in the draft)?''
</P>
<P>
   Moss scored on his first two receptions against Tampa Bay a week
ago, one from 48 yards and the other from 31.
</P>
<P>
   Reunited &QL; 
Buffalo Bills quarterback  &UR; Doug Flutie and Miami Dolphins Coach
 &UR; Jimmy &UR; Johnson will be on the same field today for the first time
since Flutie's 48-yard pass on the final play gave Boston College a
47-45 victory over Johnson's Miami Hurricanes in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Flutie said he is asked about the play nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's someone who recognizes you and wants to approach
you but doesn't know what to say, they'll bring that up as an
icebreaker,'' Flutie said. ``A lot of times people want to tell you
the story of where they were when they saw it. They'll say they
were in a bar, or they were having Thanksgiving dinner, or they
turned the TV set off after Miami scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather be remembered for the skillful things I did rather
than a prayer of a pass I threw. But at least there's a signature
play people do remember you by.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 602-444-8334 or at steve.schoenfeld(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
