<HEADER>
A2530 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     09-13 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS EARN RIGHT TO BOAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ In college football, there are two ways, one
new and one old, to be a national-championship contender.
</P>
<P>
   The new way, introduced this season, is to earn a spot in the
Jan. 4 Fiesta Bowl between No.1 and No.2 through a rating formula
that multiplies your team's AP ranking, its Nielsen share, its
mortgage interest deduction, its coach's mother's birth month and
the square of the hypotenuse.
</P>
<P>
   The old way is to simply declare yourself a candidate, early and
loudly, on the field and in the locker room. Which UCLA did
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' right guard Andy Meyers said after the Bruins
defeated Texas 49-31, ``this proves we're a contender for the
national championship.''
</P>
<P>
   And so they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make those statements,'' said do-it-all freshman
Freddie Mitchell, ``when you've worked hard in the summer
(practice).''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike recent UCLA teams, who said goodbye to perfect seasons in
September, this one overpowered its first opponent, and a ranked
opponent at that, doing it with a shocking array of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike recent UCLA teams, comprised of polite young men who let
the results do the talking, this one will demand attention from the
championship voters.
</P>
<P>
   Not that brash talk comes naturally to them. A couple of school
records were set at the Rose Bowl, and one was for repetition of
the phrase, ``one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   And for a while there, listening to quarterback Cade McNown and
head coach Bob Toledo during his postgame press conference, you
might have thought Texas had won.
</P>
<P>
   ``My hat is off to Texas,'' McNown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to give credit to Texas,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   They were being nice to a team they defeated 66-3 in 1997 and
were thrashing no less convincingly Saturday _ 35-3 in a first half
without turnovers _ before boredom set in.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo doesn't want his team tripping over its tongue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of our goals,'' he said of the national
championship, which would be the Bruins' second, UCLA having shared
the title with Ohio State in 1954. ``But I want them talking about
one game at a time. We're not there yet. We're not a finished
product.''
</P>
<P>
   But the message from this one game is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who thought a Heisman Trophy for McNown is all the
Bruins had to fight for this year can dream a little higher.
</P>
<P>
   The players have known it all along. This season, the first in
which a Pacific-10 champion can bypass the Rose Bowl for a 1 vs. 2
showdown, the Bruins used that as an incentive to start fast after
failing to go 3-0 since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   One thing everybody understands about the weird new rating
formula is the best strategy is: don't lose.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, fired up over last year's embarrassment and primed by a
season-opening rout of New Mexico State, was a big bullet to dodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought they were good going in, so I wasn't surprised,''
Texas coach Mack Brown said, calling UCLA's first-half performance
``a perfect game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made more good plays in the first half than we did against
New Mexico State, but it wasn't obvious because UCLA was so good.''
</P>
<P>
   Are the Bruins national title material?
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you start in the top 10, you're as talented as they
and you've got a quarterback as skilled as McNown is, you've got
what it takes to be a national champion,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA is ranked sixth. (Texas is No. 23.)
</P>
<P>
   UCLA completed passes to nine receivers, including Mitchell (who
had a 79-yard touchdown catch and run) and sophomore Brian
Poli-Dixon (who had two touchdowns). It found a reasonable
facsimile of Skip Hicks in sophomore Jermaine Lewis (who rushed for
115 yards and two touchdowns in his first college start) and a
future star in freshman DeShaun Foster (who averaged 6.3 a carry).
</P>
<P>
   McNown was everything the campaign posters promised.
</P>
<P>
   And the defense was a revelation, though it remains to be seen
how much its first-half showing was helped by the big lead, which
blunted the rushing influence of Texas Heisman hopeful Ricky
Williams, and the weak playmaking of Texas quarterback Richard
Walton.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule gets tougher. The Bruins go to Miami, Arizona and
Washington, and face Oregon and USC at home. Any of those could
shut them up.
</P>
<P>
   But for a week at least, they have national-title potential and
a perfect right to talk the talk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
