<HEADLINE>
OKLAHOMA RALLIES PAST TCU, 10-9
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By TERRANCE HARRIS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ The TCU Horned Frogs found themselves on the
verge of upsetting Oklahoma last night.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the final 2:26 minutes of the game.
</P>
<P>
   And just about anything that could have gone wrong did for TCU
in its home opener at Amon Carter Stadium. Missed offensive
opportunities. A defensive secondary letdown. An onside kick. An
interception-turned fumble. The waning seconds field-goal
conversion. And then the postgame brawl.
</P>
<P>
   When it was all clear, the Sooners had stolen one from TCU,
10-9.
</P>
<P>
   In the final analysis, a stellar defensive performance by the
Frogs became a victim of circumstance when Oklahoma kicker Jeff
Ferguson converted a 40-yard field goal with 10 seconds remaining
to cap a 10-0 rally by the Sooners in the final 2:26.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one was a hard one to lose,'' said TCU coach Dennis
Franchione, whose team moved to 1-1. ``One play makes the
difference in college football. And there were a lot of them that
could have made a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs had held their ground and a 9-0 lead (three Chris
Kaylakie field goals) for nearly the entire second half before
things came unglued. Their lack of offensive production and the
Sooners' athletic ability finally caught up to them.
</P>
<P>
   But even with teary eyes and solemn facial expressions, the
players talked more about rebounding than about what went wrong in
their second consecutive matchup with a Big 12 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``A loss like this is certainly disappointing, but it's not the
end of the world for us,'' senior defensive end Kam Hunt said.
``You hate to ever lose, but this was a nonconference game, and we
have to keep on going.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are brighter days ahead for this football team.''
</P>
<P>
   And after an impressive outing against Iowa State, first-year
quarterback Patrick Batteaux often seemed uncertain and impatient
against an athletic Oklahoma defensive front.
</P>
<P>
   Batteaux gained just 24 yards on 16 carries, while completing
two of 12 pass attempts for 17 yards. And senior tailback Basil
Mitchell had eclipsed 100 yards rushing only to have losses late in
the game reduce him to 89 yards on 12 carries for the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs have a week off before opening the Western Athletic
Conference season on Sept. 26 at home against Air Force.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get better on offense, there's no doubt about
that,'' Franchione said. ``There's not an aspect of the offense
that we can't improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, you can't take anything away from the
Oklahoma defense. They are a stout group.''
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma (2-0) began its improbable rally when quarterback
Patrick Fletcher placed a perfectly thrown pass over defensive back
Greg Walls and into the outreached hands of receiver Chris Blocker
in the left corner of the end zone for a 21-yard touchdown
reception. Then came a mishandled onside kick that ended up in the
grasp of Oklahoma's Chris Hammons at the Frogs' 47.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, TCU linebacker Joseph Phipps appeared to
salvage the Frogs when he snared his third interception of the
evening only to fumble it away at the TCU 23. Four plays later, the
Sooners' comeback was complete.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
