<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLDOG HELLING RANGERS' BEST BET TO WIN A BIG GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By GIL LeBRETON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Ever the bulldog, Rick Helling won his
19th game of the season last night.
</P>
<P>
   Ever the Doberman, Helling was ready to launch the missiles in
the fifth inning, just to make a point.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, it does appear, will not skip merrily to any
division title this season. On the contrary, if they get there,
they will likely have to do it growling and clawing.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Helling.
</P>
<P>
   He snarls. He battles. He wins games.
</P>
<P>
   Last night at Tropicana Field, with the added parlay of an
Anaheim defeat already in the bank, Helling delivered again.
Growling and clawing, he weathered an inconsistent first five
innings, but ended up pitching eight.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old right-hander's 19th victory fueled the Rangers'
8-2 triumph against the Tampa Bay Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   And as the bottom of the fifth inning began last night, Helling,
citing the law of the jungle, was ready to chunk it all.
</P>
<P>
   In the top half, his pitching counterpart and former teammate,
Julio Santana, had responded to back-to-back Rangers home runs by
sailing a smoke-alarm fastball past Lee Stevens' chin. Umpire Larry
McCoy promptly walked from behind the plate and issued both teams a
warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, at that point, that four innings were going to be
my max tonight,'' Helling related.
</P>
<P>
   This is the same Rick Helling who, as a 21-year-old Olympian,
didn't think twice about brushing back the blustery Cubans. This is
the same Helling who, on Rafael Palmeiro's ``homecoming'' to The
Ballpark, launched one behind Raffy's ear.
</P>
<P>
   His response last night, after hearing umpire McCoy's
no-headhunting warning, was vintage Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get the 'pen ready,'' he told pitching coach Dick Bosman as he
prepared to take the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never like to see your hitters get thrown at,'' Helling
explained, with no visible semblance of remorse. ``I feel like it's
my job to protect them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, a vanguard of cooler heads promptly intervened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I guess three or four guys must have heard me,'' Helling
said, ``because they jumped up and said, `No, no. Don't do that.
We'll get them some other time. We need you out there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, Helling accepted the leash and behaved himself.
</P>
<P>
   He's not bad, you see. He just pitches that way.
</P>
<P>
   And on a team of kindly all-for-one musketeers, isn't a genuine
chippy character like Helling an intriguing change?
</P>
<P>
   If you had any doubts, last night again should have resolved
them. The Rangers have no better starting pitcher with a ``must''
game on the line. And this is a ``must'' road trip, especially
after launching the itinerary Friday by stumbling, 3-2, to the
last-place Devil Rays.
</P>
<P>
   A poignant scene had started the night. A knot of Rangers had
gathered in Danny Wheat's training room and, huddled around a
laptop computer, tracked the end of the Angels' game at Baltimore.
When word spread that the Orioles had come back from a 2-0 deficit
to win with three runs in the bottom of the ninth, a ripple of
light, but noticeable, approval ran through the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now it's our turn,'' a voice shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Helling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five innings were really a grind,'' the pitcher
recounted. ``But the last three, I felt like I was in a groove.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling teetered in the second inning and then let a run in and
left the bases loaded in the third. He had two outs and a Devil Ray
on third in the fifth inning when he allowed back-to-back singles
by Fred McGriff and Bubba Trammell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sent Bosman out there to chew him out,'' manager Johnny
Oates said. ``He had two strikes on both of those guys, and rather
than challenge them, he threw two get-me-over curveballs. Bos had
to go out there and remind him, `Let's go and get after it.'''
</P>
<P>
   That's not the usual Helling, of course. The usual Helling is
the one who, between innings, walked over to home-plate ump McCoy
and wanted to _ how shall we put this? _ waive responsibility for
anything that was about to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure he had warned us,'' Helling said.
``I told the umpire, `Well, I'm still going to throw inside.' He
just answered, `I know. But I know the difference.'''
</P>
<P>
   On this night, however, Helling heeded his manager's caution.
Order prevailed. Teeth were bared, but that's Rick Helling.
</P>
<P>
   He growls. He battles. He wins games.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
