<HEADLINE>
CANIDATE STARTS HIS RUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   STANFORD, Calif. _  &UR; Trung Canidate went from casualty candidate
to game ball contender.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation took a couple of seconds.
</P>
<P>
   On Arizona's fifth play from scrimmage Saturday at Stanford
Stadium, Canidate did what had had not done for more than nine
months.
</P>
<P>
   He carried the football.
</P>
<P>
   For 11 yards.
</P>
<P>
   For the rest of the day, there would be 20 more carries and 99
more yards.
</P>
<P>
   Goodbye, stress fracture. Hello, season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little rusty out there,'' Canidate said after his
first game since recovery from a stress fracture to his right foot.
``But the offensive line made it easy for me. I can't complain.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Stanford, neither can anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats gained a mediocre 133 yards rushing in a
season-opening victory at Hawaii 10 days ago. In the 31-14 victory
at Stanford, it was an effective, Canidate-to-contender 223.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trung runs so hard,'' said  &UR; Keith Smith, who continued to
share quarterback duties with  &UR; Ortege Jenkins. ``He just blows
through the hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trung makes such a difference. He kind of levels out the whole
offense. He allows you to do other things.''
</P>
<P>
   Canidate didn't start. Those duties fell to reliable  &UR; Kelvin
Eafon, who scored two touchdowns. But it's clear that Canidate is a
key to the Wildcats' hopes. He promised better days.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I wanted to do was run the ball,'' said Canidate, who has
speed, power and instincts that propel him through imperceptible
cracks in the defense. ``The offensive line gave me some big holes.
They deserve the credit.'' &QL; 
Briefly . . . &QL; 
All-purpose cornerback  &UR; Chris McAlister struggled early but
recovered for one knockdown of a pass attempt and an interception,
the 11th of his career. ``With concentration, I could have had four
picks,'' said McAlister, his own worst critic.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was announced at 30,096, Stanford's smallest since
1991. In the 85,000-seat stadium, it looked more like 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe everybody was hiding in the shade. UA's sweat-soaked
coach,  &UR; Dick Tomey, sounded as though he was seeking some. ``Today
was hotter than any day I've experienced in Tucson,'' said Tomey,
who blamed the humidity for all that hot air.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinal has an 11-game schedule and virtually no bowl
hopes. Still, quarterback  &UR; Todd Husak said ``the 12th game is still
a possibility.'' Yeah, if you're counting next year's season
opener.
</P>
<P>
   UA has won six straight games dating to last season. The past
three have been on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Keep 'em down on The Farm and on the UA schedule. UA has won six
straight over Stanford. The Cardinal's last victory was in 1990 in
Tucson. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
