<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LATECH-TEXASA&AMP;M-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO. 18 TEXAS A&AMP;M DOWNS LOUISIANA TECH, 28-7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ The Texas A&AMP;M Aggies took a step down
in competition last night, but their performance reinforced the
lessons learned in a season-opening loss to Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, their defense has a chance to be very, very good. And
their offense has, to be charitable, room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
   The 18th-ranked Aggies defeated Louisiana Tech, 28-7, at Kyle
Field, evening their record at 1-1. The Bulldogs fell to 0-3.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies did it by dousing the high-octane Bulldogs offense
and by doing just enough when they had the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The defense, which shows signs of earning the ``Wrecking Crew''
moniker given to past attacking, destroying A&AMP;M units, held
Louisiana Tech to 323 yards. That's 201 fewer than the Bulldogs
averaged in their first two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pleased with our defensive effort in controlling a very
good offensive team,'' Aggies coach R.C. Slocum said.
</P>
<P>
   The offense was more methodical than spectacular. It gained 349
yards, including 83 by Dante Hall, 79 and three touchdowns by
D'Andre Hardeman and 134 passing yards by Branndon Stewart. But
that's 162 fewer than the Bulldogs averaged giving up in their
first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum said the conditions were a factor. More than six inches
of rain had fallen since Thursday, and a steady drizzle persisted
throughout the game.
</P>
<P>
   However, the conditions had little to do with A&AMP;M's offensive
line struggling to open holes for the second consecutive game.
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom going in said this would be a shootout, with
the Aggies winning a wild one. The A&AMP;M attack didn't do what it was
supposed to do, but then the defense kept the Bulldogs from running
up and down the field.
</P>
<P>
   Make that passing up and down the field.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldogs quarterback Tim Rattay had carved up the first two
defenses he faced this season, including that of fourth-ranked
Nebraska. He passed for 590 yards against the Cornhuskers in the
Bulldogs' season opener, and 524 last week against Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Troy Edwards ran up and down the field in the first two
games after catching Rattay's passes. He had an NCAA-record 405
yards against Nebraska, and 206 yards against Central Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Aggies, Rattay was held to 239 yards. Edwards caught
11 balls for 67 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran a great scheme and had great speed at every
position,'' Louisiana Tech coach Gary Crowton said. ``They are good
at causing turnovers, and hit you in the mouth every time.''
</P>
<P>
   Safety Rich Coady intercepted two passes, including one on the
end zone in the fourth quarter to stop a Bulldogs drive, and
cornerback Jason Webster recovered a fumble to set up a touchdown
drive just before halftime. &QL; 
EXTRA POINTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A reminder that the ``A'' in A&AMP;M stands for ``Agricultural:'' A
little more than six inches fell on the Kyle Field grass since
Thursday, but there were no visible mud spots and relatively few
slips. ... Edwards was held to less than 100 yards for the first
time since Oct. 11 against Auburn. He had a streak of seven
consecutive games of hitting the century mark. ... The Bulldogs had
239 passing yards, their lowest total since 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
