<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARK HAS BEEN INVALUABLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ It's unofficial. Chan Ho Park is the Los Angeles
Dodgers' MVP for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There is no voting, but manager Glenn Hoffman said Park's
durability after starters Ramon Martinez and Ismael Valdes went
down with injuries kept the season from being far worse.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman also cited Park's 12-game winning streak at Dodger
Stadium that stretched back to last season and eclipsed the mark
set by Hall-of-Famer Sandy Koufax. Overall this year, Park is 13-8
with a 3.87 ERA and is one victory away from matching last year's
total.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the way he stepped up all season when we needed
him,'' Hoffman said. ``When starters were out and the bullpen was
down, he took the ball. Those pitch counts really say something.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who was 14-8 last year with a 3.38 ERA, has won his past
two starts. Each time he threw 136 pitches, about 25 to 30 more
than normal.
</P>
<P>
   Alou for manager?: Felipe Alou has one year left on his contract
with Montreal, but many believe he is the front-runner to replace
Hoffman as Dodgers manager.
</P>
<P>
   Alou was the manager when new Dodgers GM Kevin Malone was the
general manager of Montreal, and the two had an excellent
relationship. In the strike-shortened 1994 season, the Expos had a
74-40 record, the best in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was forced to trade some of his top players as part of
the Expos' annual salary purge, but Alou has kept his team in
contention until this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't think he doesn't want to win,'' said Dodgers shortstop
Mark Grudzielanek, who played four seasons for Alou. ``He is very
nurturing, but he is also very competitive. He doesn't show it, but
I really think it hurts him deeply every time he has to let an
established player go.''
</P>
<P>
   Another candidate with Malone ties is Davey Johnson, who was
fired last season by Baltimore after winning the AL East. He also
won the National League Central with Cincinnati in 1995 before
getting fired. Johnson reportedly irritates upper management, but
has a good relationship with Malone.
</P>
<P>
   The job is expected to go to someone with major-league
managerial experience. But former Dodger Davey Lopes, a coach in
San Diego, served as a bench coach in Baltimore when Malone was
assistant GM.
</P>
<P>
   Padres notes: Trevor Hoffman's 48th save Friday night was part
of an even bigger record. Since July 24, 1996, San Diego is 169-0
when leading after eight innings.... Joey Hamilton's 1-0 victory
Friday raised his record to 8-1 lifetime against the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0055EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS &LR;      09-13 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Even at less than 100 percent, Randy Johnson is still light-years
ahead of the competition.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Johnson overcame stomach-flu symptoms and a rocky first inning
Saturday to strike out 11 as the Astros tied a club record with
their 96th victory, beating the St. Louis Cardinals 3-2 in the
Astrodome.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won their eighth consecutive game _ before a
regular-season-record crowd of 52,493 _ as Craig Biggio hit a
two-run, bases-loaded double off the left-field wall to erase a 2-1
deficit in the seventh inning. With the early-afternoon victory,
the Astros clinched at least a tie for the National League Central
title and reduced to one their magic number for winning the
division outright.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, the Astros gathered in the clubhouse, with
champagne on ice, to watch the Chicago Cubs-Milwaukee Brewers
contest. The Cubs could have clinched the division for the Astros
but rallied from an eight-run deficit to stun the Milwaukee Brewers
15-12.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros did clinch a playoff spot when the New York Mets
lost. The Astros can win their fourth division title (the others
were in 1980, 1986 and 1997) before they take the field tonight if
the Cubs lose to Milwaukee this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're probably better off winning on the field. It
will be a better celebration,'' Astros left fielder Moises Alou
said after the Cubs won.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros clinch the title today, it will be the earliest an
Astros team has wrapped up its division. ``It's kind of early. I
think we can win one more game,'' Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis took a two-run first-inning lead off Johnson, who
became ill late Friday. Astros manager Larry Dierker was
considering a pitching switch until two hours before the first
pitch.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up his first runs in the Astrodome this season, the
6-10 lefthander, stomach empty, starved the St. Louis batters over
the next six innings. He struck out the side in the first, fifth
and seventh innings and retired the final 15 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, whose fastball was clocked in the low 90s, somewhat
slower than normal, had enough zip to record his sixth double-digit
strikeout total since he joined the Astros on Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Among his victims was Mark McGwire, who finished 0-for-3 with
three strikeouts, two coming against Johnson. Johnson allowed two
runs and four hits and walked two in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a testament right there that you don't have to throw 95
mph and blow everybody away,'' Johnson (8-1) said. ``The way the
first inning started, I thought it was going to be a short day for
me. Basically, all I was doing was letting them put the ball in
play. I didn't really feel like I had a whole lot behind any of my
pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis scored when Joe McEwing led off with a single and
scored on a double to right by Fernando Tatis, snapping Johnson's
scoreless-innings streak in the Dome at 36.
</P>
<P>
   After a pair of strikeouts, including a called strike to
McGwire, native Ron Gant delivered a run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros answered in the bottom half when Biggio walked, stole
two bases and scored on Derek Bell's grounder to third base off
Darren Oliver (3-3).
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who pitched shutouts in his first four Astrodome
starts, allowed one hit the rest of the day before being relieved
by Scott Elarton to begin the eighth. Billy Wagner pitched a
scoreless ninth for his 29th save.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros were silent after the first inning until Richard
Hidalgo led off the seventh with a double. He advanced on Sean
Berry's sacrifice before a tiring Oliver walked Brad Ausmus and
pinch hitter Pete Incaviglia and Biggio followed with a two-run
double.
</P>
<P>
   The hit was also his club-record 196th. The previous record was
195 by Enos Cabell in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked a little lackluster,'' Dierker said. ``He (Oliver)
kept the ball out of the middle of the strike zone and kept us a
little frustrated. We might have been a little tired from last
night, and they might have been too.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to get back after an emotional night game. But we
got it done.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis had the tying run on base in the eighth (Ray Lankford)
with one out when McGwire stepped to the plate to face Elarton, a
22-year-old rookie. Elarton, who gave up home run No. 40 to McGwire
on July 12 at Busch Stadium, caught McGwire looking with a 2-2
curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be something I remember forever, coming in my rookie
season and striking out Mark McGwire in his home-run-record year,''
said Elarton. ``He's already got me once this year, so I guess once
is enough. I think it did freeze him a little bit. He hadn't seen
my curve. I was just going to pitch him tough. I wasn't thinking,
`It's Mark McGwire up there.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
