<HEADER>
A2537 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-13 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
RANDY Johnson's fastballs can be sickening. This we know. This we
expect.
</P>
<P>
   They are 98-mph lasers that pop into the mitt and send even the
greatest big-league batters back to the dugout, dragging their
bats, tripping over their bottom lips, begging for mercy or a pinch
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect me to strike out 15 every time,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Saturday's Astros-St. Louis Cardinals game was
supposed to be a show like no other _ the Cards' Mark McGwire
standing there swinging away at Johnson's heat.
</P>
<P>
   Biceps against Big Unit. McGwire against McCheese.
</P>
<P>
   Try to find the ball if McGwire got a hold of one. Try to find a
radar gun capable of clocking Johnson's fastball when he really
rared back and let one fly, Texas-style, against his former USC
Trojans teammate.
</P>
<P>
   It was a marquee match with a matinee start, everything a
baseball fan could want _ McGwire vs. Johnson and home in time for
dinner, which is why it was hard to find a ticket or anyone not
holding their breath when Johnson strode to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Little did we know that while everyone was holding their breath,
Johnson was trying to hold down the last remnants of breakfast. He
was sick, the victim of some sort of bug that gripped him Friday
evening and well, let's just say nothing Johnson ate agreed with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have anything in his stomach today,'' Astros manager
Larry Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   Except guts.
</P>
<P>
   Before the bug zapped him, Johnson said he would try to pitch
McGwire as if Johnson were blindfolded _ in other words, ignoring
the 62 home runs and the mighty McGwire aura and simply firing his
heat as usual. Why not? Johnson entered 4-0 in the Dome with an ERA
not even Kenneth Starr could find _ 0.00.
</P>
<P>
   Little did Johnson know he also would be trying to pitch with,
in essence, his hands tied behind his back, the butt of a cigarette
gripped between his teeth and McGwire's gun-barrel biceps cocked
and ready to fire.
</P>
<P>
   This looked like an uncharacteristic firing squad with Johnson
the guest of honor, a rare loss brewing for the Astros in this
record-setting season. Johnson gave up a pair of hits to open the
game and two runs by the time he got out of the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   His fastball clocked a mere 93 mph in the first inning _ ``Like
a changeup,'' Johnson said, a comment that might be like Tiger
Woods saying he won with his ``C'' game if it weren't true.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's usually intimidating stare at batters over the webbing
of his glove was a bit glassy-eyed. He shook his head as if to
clear the cobwebs. He sighed a lot and took deep breaths.
</P>
<P>
   He was sick, not sickening. And things looked good only for the
ball-hawks in the bleachers hoping to catch a McGwire bomb.
</P>
<P>
   But little did we know Johnson's sickness and queasiness merely
served as a symptom for something else that became clear in the 3-2
Astros victory.
</P>
<P>
   He is a pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   We had seen a bit of craftiness from Johnson before, and heard
Dierker and others talk about how impressed they were with the way
Johnson can nibble, confuse and tease batters just like Atlanta's
Greg Maddux but without the bookworm motif.
</P>
<P>
   But never has Johnson shown the full arsenal of his craft like
he did Saturday. He struck out McGwire twice, hitting corners with
sliders and placing his fastball in good spots. Unlike his meals,
he kept the ball down. He threw changeups, for gosh sakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to throw those pitches,'' Johnson said. ``My bag of
tricks was running out.''
</P>
<P>
   After one inning, Johnson brought the baseball back to the
Astros' dugout with him. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to resort to scuffing the ball, and I didn't want the
umpire to find out,'' Johnson joked.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was a superstition. But there were many parts of
Johnson's game on display Saturday that he hadn't shown a lot of
before. He hadn't had to. He had never felt the way he felt
Saturday, at least not as an Astro.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, Johnson said he had a similar bug grip
him before a start against the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember throwing up in the back of a taxi,'' Johnson said.
``I tipped the guy pretty good. When things like that happen, you
just try to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did we know the marquee show would turn into a clinic.
Little did we know this guy could be finesse. Next thing you know,
Johnson will unveil a knuckleball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
