</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-SWTEXAS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAU GETS HEAVENLY HELP IN WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM GINTONIO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ It was a slip of the tongue, but when Francis
St. Paul was introduced at a post-game gathering as ``St.
Francis,'' it was an accurate description. He made some miraculous
catches and moves, and he helped rescue teammates in need Saturday
night in the Lumberjacks' 38-16 victory over Southwest Texas.
</P>
<P>
   St. Paul, a sophomore wide receiver who was converted from
running back, caught touchdown pases of 60, 23 and 50 yards in the
second half to ignite an NAU offense that floundered in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lumberjacks (2-0) rebounded from a 13-10 halftime deficit
when Travis Brown, considered one of the top two or three
quarterbacks in Division I-AA, began to show the form that was kept
under wraps in the season opener. When that happened, Southwest
Texas (0-1) began to fall apart.
</P>
<P>
   The win had a dark side, however. Brown, a junior from Moon
Valley High School, sustained an injury to his left elbow after
throwing the 23-yard strike to St. Paul on the first play of the
fourth quarter. He spent the rest of the game with his arm wrapped
and in a sling. He will continue to be evaluated, and his status
for next week's home game against Cal State-Northridge is
uncertain. But before he exited, Brown went over the 7,000-yard
mark in career passing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This hurts a lot,'' said Brown, who seemed to cheer up when
the conversation turned to St. Paul. ``Francis really turned it up
in the second half. We knew it would happen. You can't conceal a
player like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive fireworks, 411 total yards, might be just the
tonic NAU needs to make Coach Jerome Souers' first season a blast.
It was a reversal from last week's 9-0 defensive struggle against
Cal Poly-San Luis Obispo.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have a strategy in the first half, but you have to
credit Southwest Texas,'' Souers said. ``Our assistant coaches and
players made the adjustment at halftime.''
</P>
<P>
   Souers also said that Clay Brown, who replaced Travis Brown and
hit St. Paul with the 50-yard strike, did an outstanding job. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0201EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
