<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL WORLD CRASHING AROUND SUN DEVILS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVO, Utah _ Drop the illusions. Lose the fantasy. Forget about
a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, the Arizona State Sun Devils aren't even the best
football team in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   They are overrated. Paper tigers. A frustrated group that ran
out of bad things to do on a frightful night in Mormon country.
</P>
<P>
   A football team _ in case you've forgotten _ that has lost its
past three regular season games.
</P>
<P>
   A team that has been outscored, 47-16, in the past six quarters.
</P>
<P>
   A team that is 0-2 with an anchor.
</P>
<P>
   The reality: In Tucson, there is reason to brag. In Tempe, there
is reason to sulk.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's too early to panic, especially with a schedule that
softens considerably and a strong whiff of zany parity invading
college football. But a little concern is in order.
</P>
<P>
   How does a passing program such as Brigham Young chew up 214
yards on the ground, pile-driving its way to a 26-6 victory? How
does an offense loaded with weapons get shut out for 49 minutes
against a mediocre, somewhat plodding defense? And how many movies
do they show on that flight to Honolulu for the Jeep Aloha Bowl?
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the defense took a few baby steps. In Week 1, the
Sun Devils made Brock Huard look like a combination of Ken Stabler
and John Elway. Which he probably is. On Saturday, a jitterbug
named Ronney Jenkins gained a mere 171 yards. But the Sun Devils
blitzed with success. They got after the quarterback. They did some
positive things, keeping their team in the game before exhaustion
set in.
</P>
<P>
   The offense, which looked so good against the Huskies, again
took giant strides. Backward.
</P>
<P>
   Which means it probably will get it right by next week against
North Dallas Forty.
</P>
<P>
   Oh boy.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the opening play of the debacle _ a BYU interception
that was ruled an ASU completion by a napping side judge _ the Sun
Devils lived 60 minutes of Murphy's Law. Dropped passes that
could've been touchdowns. Shanked field goals. Fumbles that
should've been recovered. Late hits on the quarterback and punter.
Tempers that flared out of control.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the frequent false-start penalty _ perfect for a
team going nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Kealy, a quarterback who is still learning on the job,
didn't get much help. But he was clearly overzealous, caught up in
the moment. He was throwing rockets when a little finesse was
necessary. He needs to develop some touch on his pass. He needs to
take it easy on his receivers, who began treating the football like
a hand grenade.
</P>
<P>
   J.R. Redmond, on the other hand, never had a chance. BYU refused
to kick the ball in his direction, refused to let him win the game
with his legs. In a chance to captivate a national audience and put
some steam behind the publicity drive, he gained 28 yards in 16
carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Trophy _ yes, the bronze statue _ might have had
more success.
</P>
<P>
   It was ugly stuff, really. After three quarters of choreographed
chaos, the only ``O'' to be found was up on the scoreboard. When
the clock expired, the Sun Devils had salvaged a touchdown, but any
chance at dignity dissolved with a muffed extra point.
</P>
<P>
   So the Sun Devils are scratching their heads. A confused bunch
searching for answers and confidence. A team that is 0-2 for the
first time since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem with college football: Preseason rankings are
not only useless, they are counterproductive. Notre Dame beats
Michigan, then soars in the polls. Except we find out that Michigan
isn't so good, after all. And judging by Saturday's results,
neither is Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   It is all an exercise in nothing. And with the Sun Devils, it
may have hurt the cause. The generous rankings only increased the
pressure. Talk of a national championship made the loss to
Washington sting even more, undoubtedly interfering with the focus
for BYU.
</P>
<P>
   The reality: ASU is a team with eight new starters on defense. A
team with a sophomore quarterback. A team playing in a conference
loaded with talent.
</P>
<P>
   Like the undefeated rival down in Tucson. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 0204EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
