<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-TIGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANDA, TIGERS SINK RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ You know all the carpe diem optimism generated at
Fenway Park by the arrival of the most futile team in the American
League? Forget about it. From now until the moment the Red Sox fate
is decided, assume nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the Red Sox won't. They lost to the lowly Detroit Tigers,
3-2, Saturday, and, coupled with Toronto's 5-3 defeat of the
Yankees, are only four games ahead of the Blue Jays in the
wild-card race _ just where they stood before Detroit came to town
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The loss dropped the locals to 2-3 on the six-game homestand
that concludes Sunday. The Sox then embark on seven-day road stint
to New York, Baltimore, and Chicago. The trip could move the Sox
closer to wrapping up the wild card or handing it to the Blue Jays,
Rangers, or Angels.
</P>
<P>
   That's why losing to a team with the third worst road record in
baseball (28-46), one that entered the game having lost seven of
their last 10 games, is so costly. But it serves to show that, as
slugger Mo Vaughn put it, no victory should be considered a sure
thing no matter the opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just have to come back (Sunday) with the attitude to win.
No team is just going to come in and lay down for the Red Sox,''
Vaughn said. ``This is really no time to worry about losses. The
thing is we just have to win as many games as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Winning, of course, is no easy task if you can't score runs.
Detroit, beaten by the Sox, 6-2, Friday night, was held scoreless
by starter Pete Schourek through six innings Saturday, but tied the
game, 1-1, when Joe Wood smoked his first major league home run
into the left-field screen in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The score remained tied until the ninth, when Joe Randa smacked
a two-run homer into the left field screen off Red Sox ace reliever
Tom Gordon (7-4). It was Gordon's first loss since a 3-1 decision
to Detroit July 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hit the ball pretty hard,'' said Gordon. ``He got the pitch
he wanted to hit and he swung and made good contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Pinch hitter Midre Cummings homered in the ninth _ his second
pinch hit home run of the season _ to cut the lead to 3-2, but that
was it. The Red Sox are now 5-4 against the Tigers this season, 2-2
at Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get into games like this, it's a matter of little
things here and there,'' said Schourek, who remained winless in a
Red Sox uniform after five starts. ``I regret the (home run) pitch
a little bit, obviously because he hit it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was that terrible a pitch. It was that that
particular one cost us the lead. But when it gets down to crunch
time, everything has to be almost perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek was solid at the start, allowing just Damion Easley's
single through the first three innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is he pitched good,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy
Williams. ``He kept us in the game. You just have to tip your hat
to the other side, they pitched a little bit better.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Detroit starter Bryce Florie didn't get the decision, but he
managed to hold the Red Sox to a single run on three hits through
six innings. Reliever Matt Anderson got the win (4-1), pitching two
scoreless innings, walking one and striking out a pair. Todd Jones
picked up his 24th save of the season, despite allowing Cummings's
blast.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't steal first,'' said Williams. ``We didn't get too
many hits today, so we just have to come back (Sunday) and do it
again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox left seven on base and blew their biggest
opportunity in the fifth. Lewis stole second as Donnie Sadler
struck out. Vaughn was walked intentionally to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Before Nomar Garciaparra reached the plate, pitching coach Rick
Adair went to the mound for a conference with Florie and catcher
Joe Siddall. Adair's advice worked. Florie got Garciaparra to
ground to short to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Boston went hitless until Cummings's home run.
</P>
<P>
   There was no talk of squandering a good opportunity to reduce
the magic number Saturday. ``You just have to go out and win as
many games as you can,'' said John Valentin, who left the game with
a contusion of the right elbow, courtesy of Florie pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are going to be the numbers, whether whoever wins
(Saturday) or not. (Sunday), we just have to go out and win. If
not, obviously the race gets closer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
