<SLUG> BC-SOC-REVOLUTION-CREW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVOLUTION KEEP PLAYOFF HOPES AFLOAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH _ Goalkeepers are not directly involved in most of
the action in soccer, especially on successful teams. And coaches
are even more peripheral to events, once the match begins.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter Zenga has displayed a winning touch with the
Revolution in both roles. He rallied the team into the MLS playoffs
on the field last year, and he has guided them to within 3 points
of Miami for the final playoff spot in the Eastern Conference this
year after a 2-0 win over Columbus Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Revolution's second successive two-goal victory in
three games since Zenga replaced Thomas Rongen as coach. They had
been the league's worst defensive team, but they have undergone a
transformation, surrendering only one goal in the last five halves
of play.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has organized the defense, and Saturday night played
tactician with an effective 3-5-2 alignment and strategic
substitutes to counter Columbus's second-half rally.
</P>
<P>
   Joe-Max Moore curled in a 20-yard free kick in the 31st minute
as the Revolution capitalized on a generous foul call by referee
Jose Manuel Garcia-Aranda. The Revolution retained their poise
after Columbus substitute Jeff Cunningham hit the post midway
through the second half. And Jair, who replaced Carlos Rocha,
clinched the win, converting after Moore went down in the penalty
area in the 84th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``My players played a hard game against a very strong team,''
Zenga said. ``I did nothing special. I asked something of the
players in midfield and defense and they did it. But there is a
long way to go before we are a great team.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his sort of modifield catenaccio style, referring to
the Italian version of defensive soccer, Zenga said:
</P>
<P>
   ``If catenaccio means playing good defense and with a good
mentality, not giving space to the other team, then I like it. We
didn't give space, we were compact, made them play wide, and we
tried to score goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Columbus has been a much more explosive offensive team, but the
Revolution stymied striker Stern John and midfielder Andy Williams
with some rough play and luck. Williams was twice taken down in the
penalty area, but did not gain the benefit of the doubt from Garcia
Aranda, to the delight of the 35,462 who attended a doubleheader
that included the US's 9-0 win over Mexico in a US Women's Cup
game.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution have gained composure under Zenga. The
galvanization process began in the second half of Zenga's first
game as coach, when they rallied to tie from a two-goal deficit but
lost to Miami, 3-2. They took a 2-0 victory against the MetroStars
in East Rutherford, N.J., then Saturday won at home for the second
time since May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga has mostly fine-tuned the team. He placed Paul Keegan in
defensive midfield, started Rocha at striker, and went with a
three-man defense of Richard Goulooze flanked by Brian Dunseth and
Manny Motajo.
</P>
<P>
   The Crew, which is chasing D.C. United for first place in the
Eastern Conference, threatened at the end of the first half as
Brian McBride headed off the side of the net. Garcia Aranda
cautioned three Revolution players in the first 15 minutes of the
second half. And as the Revolution tired, Zenga pulled Rocha for
Jair to keep possession. But Jair provided a bonus, his third goal
of the year and first since returning from an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``For my team I always want progress and for them not to lose
concentration,'' Zenga said. ``I don't like to compare now and
before. Every game is different, every season is a different
situation. I am sad because of the second half against Miami. I
would like to see if we had tied that game, 2-2, what it would be
like in Miami now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
