<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-BYU-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUGARS DROP SUN DEVILS TO 0-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVO, Utah _ OK. Ha, ha. Very funny. Where is it? Who hid
Arizona State's offense?
</P>
<P>
   Because the group that showed up at Cougar Stadium Saturday
night ``certainly'' couldn't have been the one that looked so
dangerous a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about total meltdown. The No. 14 Sun Devils mustered just
22 rushing yards against Brigham Young and were humiliated, 26-6,
in front of 65,096 and a national television audience.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the loss that hurts,'' tailback J.R. Redmond said.
``It's that we know we're a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for a national title, a Heisman Trophy and maybe a major
bowl. ASU struggled so much that North Texas, next week's opponent,
is suddenly looking a lot more formidable.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils start 0-2 for the first time since 1979, Frank
Kush's last season.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, a Heisman hopeful, was held to 28 yards. Quarterback
Ryan Kealy completed 16 of 34 pass attempts. ASU receivers dropped
numerous passes. The Sun Devils committed 11 penalties for 105
yards. Mike Gauthier missed field goal attempts of 44 and 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Other than that . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``We struggled to get J.R. the ball,'' ASU Coach Bruce Snyder
said. ``We dropped some balls. We misread some defenses, in terms
of where to go with the ball. They just outplayed us.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was BYU's second straight over ASU.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Sun Devils made a star of BYU tailback Ronney
Jenkins, who rushed for 171 yards and one touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ASU returned home Saturday night with several significant
questions to answer:
</P>
<P>
   How can an offense with so many weapons be so ineffective?
</P>
<P>
   While Kealy was sharp at times, he also appeared to lack the
touch that has been his forte.
</P>
<P>
   Too many receivers dropped passes. The group has been called one
of the deepest in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Redmond's longest run was seven yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``The front four they've got is big,'' center Grey Ruegamer
said. ``They played very well and we played like (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   What's the next move for the kicking game?
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier missed two field goals after making one of two in last
week's opener against Washington. The Sun Devils may have to take a
closer look at punter Stephen Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Can the team overcome this emotional hurdle?
</P>
<P>
   Snyder said it took his team nearly four days to get over the
season-opening loss to Washington. How long will it take the
players to get over this? Two of ASU's next four games are against
Southern California and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say this,'' Snyder said. ``I still believe in this team
and I told them that at the half and at the end of the game. . . .
We can still have an awfully good season.''
</P>
<P>
   Is the defense good enough to allow for offensive lapses?
</P>
<P>
   Snyder already has this answer. No. While the unit played better
than it did against the Huskies, this is still a young group that
needs more game experience.
</P>
<P>
   Why do the Sun Devils continue to commit so many penalties?
</P>
<P>
   While many of the later flags were products of frustration, they
added up. ASU has been one of the Pac-10's most penalized teams in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Credit must go to BYU, who rebounded from a season-opening loss
to Alabama to put an impressive defense on the field. ASU's only
score was a 15-yard pass from Kealy to Lenzie Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were going to play well tonight because we had such
a great practice,'' Cougars Coach LaVell Edwards said. ``It was one
of the best weeks we've had around here. I didn't know tonight's
game would go quite like it did, but we were very pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   ASU's offense appeared out of sync early.
</P>
<P>
   Kealy overthrew Tariq McDonald. Several receivers dropped
catchable passes. Redmond couldn't find a hole if his life depended
on it. Fortunately, it didn't.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars were a bit more effective, and scored the only
points of the first quarter on a 34-yard field goal by Owen Pochman
with 10:19 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Pochman made all four field goals he tried.
</P>
<P>
   BYU came out in a variety of formations to try to keep the Sun
Devils off balance. ASU substituted freely, and by early in the
second quarter, had played eight defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Cougars increased their lead to 10-0 on a 74-yard scoring
play from Kevin Feterik to Ben Horton. Feterik's pass was tipped by
cornerback J'Juan Cherry before Horton grabbed it, juked several
ASU defenders and ran into the end zone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
