<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2605 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     09-13 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV20-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release on Sunday, Sept. 20.)  
 (HLW)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; ALL OVER BUT THE SHOUTIN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Rick Bragg. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   A child of ``white trash'' America tells of how he escaped his
dirt-poor Alabama upbringing to become a Pulitzer Prize-winning
correspondent for The New York Times, a journey made possible in
large part by the sacrifice and suffering of his formidable mother.
Last year our reviewer, Anthony Walton, called this a ``sad,
beautiful, funny and moving memoir.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LARRY'S PARTY &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Shields. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing in minute detail on the inner life of Larry Weller, a
thoughtful Canadian landscape designer whose passion is building
garden mazes, this affectionate novel seeks to define what it's
like being a man in the '90s. The labyrinth of Larry's existence is
revealed gradually: his childhood, his elusive and complicated
romantic entanglements, his friends and family, above all his
unflinching dialogue with his ``self's silver mirror.'' By the end,
``the reader could not feel closer to Larry Weller or more
benevolently disposed toward him, a measure of his creator's
generosity,'' Verlyn Klinkenborg wrote in the Book Review in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE DARK SIDE OF CAMELOT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Seymour M. Hersh. Back Bay/Little, Brown, $15.
</P>
<P>
   A renowned investigative reporter trots out nearly every report,
claim or rumor of nasty goings-on by John F. Kennedy and his
coterie. Even if the author's scattershot approach has mixed
results, ``he makes life difficult for historians by digging up
just enough about distressing matters so they can't honestly be
ignored,'' Thomas Powers said here last year. In  &UR; THE KENNEDY
TAPES: INSIDE THE WHITE HOUSE DURING THE CUBAN MISSILE CRISIS &LR; ,
edited by Ernest R. May and Philip D. Zelikow (Belknap/Harvard
University, $16.95), the president emerges as a highly skeptical
dove when the world was on the brink of nuclear war, and seems
Lincolnesque in his grim resolve. In 1997 our reviewer, Barry
Gewen, called this scholarly transcription, which includes
connecting text and explanatory passages, ``a splendid
achievement.'' The Cuban missile crisis is also the subject of  &UR; ONE
HELL OF A GAMBLE: KHRUSHCHEV, CASTRO, AND KENNEDY, 1958-1964 &LR; , by
Aleksandr Fursenko and Timothy Naftali (Norton, $14.95), in which
two historians, one Russian and one American, draw on archival
material from official Soviet sources to provide a fresh
perspective on the drama. ``The story takes on the elements of
great theater as it moves to its denouement,'' John Newhouse wrote
in these pages last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE FORTUNATE PILGRIM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Mario Puzo. Fawcett Columbine, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Before Don Corleone there was Lucia Santa, a cunning,
tough-as-nails matriarch who raises six children by herself in
Hell's Kitchen. This fictional chronicle of immigrant life by the
author of  &UR; THE GODFATHER &LR;  is ``lifted into literature by ... its
penetrating insights and its mixture of tenderness and rage,''
David Boroff said here in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEGINNING OF SPRING &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Penelope Fitzgerald. Mariner/Houghton Mifflin, $12.
</P>
<P>
   This comedy of manners, set in Russia in 1913, revolves around a
self-effacing British printer who scrambles to find someone to care
for his three children after his wife bails out and returns home.
``It is a lovely novel,'' Robert Plunket wrote here in 1989, with a
colorful cast of flaky expats and exuberant locals. The same
publisher has reissued an earlier novel by the author,  &UR; INNOCENCE &LR; 
($12), in which a guileless woman from an aristocratic Florentine
family summons an English girlfriend to help her win the heart of a
neurologist. ``Fitzgerald casts a wry, forgiving eye on her
characters and charms us,'' our reviewer, Emily Leider, said in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A COMMOTION IN THE BLOOD: LIFE, DEATH, AND THE IMMUNE SYSTEM &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen S. Hall. Owl/Holt, $16.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author, a contributing writer and editor at The New York
Times Magazine, argues that the history of immunotherapy in the war
against cancer has been a messy, up-and-down affair that is
fascinating even if there isn't a ``magic bullet'' in sight. The
result is a ``masterly study,'' Roy Porter wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOCKEY SUR GLACE: STORIES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Peter LaSalle. Breakaway/Lyons Press, $13.
</P>
<P>
   These seven stories and four poems are marked by a deep
affection for the hockey of mill towns and pickup games played on
pond ice by older skaters with young hearts. The tales ``all take
weight from a powerful retrospect, from lost times that were both
troubled and blessed,'' Ron Carlson wrote in these pages last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RACHEL CARSON: WITNESS FOR NATURE  &LR;  By Linda Lear. Owl/Holt,
$17.95.
</P>
<P>
   This biography reveals how the largely self-taught author of
 &UR; SILENT SPRING &LR;  contributed so much to the postwar environmental
movement and had such a strong influence on American sensibilities.
This is ``the most exhaustive account so far of Carson's private,
professional and public lives,'' Robert B. Semple Jr. said here in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BACON FANCIER: FOUR TALES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Alan Isler. Penguin, $11.95.
</P>
<P>
   Each of these novellas is set in a different century and locale,
from 17th-century Venice to latter-day Manhattan, but they are
linked by mistrustful Jewish protagonists struggling with pride in
a gentile world. Last year our reviewer, James Saynor, called this
a ``clever and radiant work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
