<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PUBLIC14-COX     09-13 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PUBLIC14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLLS MAY INFLUENCE _ BUT WON'T DECIDE _ CLINTON'S FATE
 &HT;    600&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Public opinion will weigh heavily as Congress
decides whether President Clinton should remain in office, but
polls won't matter much for a while and may not be the key factor,
politicians and campaign consultants said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Polling conducted since Friday, when Independent Counsel Kenneth
Starr released his report, is statistically suspect, the experts
agreed. And opinions could shift dramatically in the weeks or
months before the House Judiciary Committee may hold hearings on
the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flabbergasted listening to people on television talking
about how America has responded and what America has concluded''
about the Starr report, said Harrison Hickman, a Democratic
campaign consultant. ``That process has only just begun.''
</P>
<P>
   Several surveys released Sunday showed that most Americans still
think Clinton is doing a good job and want him censured by Congress
rather than removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   The polls showed a majority of Americans _ ranging from 59
percent to 67 percent _ approved of the way Clinton was performing
his duties as president.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, a majority in three polls taken over the weekend and
released Sunday _ for ABC News, CBS News and CNN/USA Today/Gallup _
said they thought the president should remain in office, the
Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   But more people had an unfavorable opinion of Clinton personally
than had a favorable one, and a majorities said they wanted
Congress to punish the president in some way. A majority in the CBS
News poll, 56 percent, and in the CNN poll, 59 percent, said they
favored censure by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, these initial findings may not hold up, polling experts
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If instant polls showed a plummet in Clinton's support, it
would be significant,'' said Andrew Kohut, director of the
nonpartisan Pew Research Center. ``But if they show no change, that
does not mean there won't be change.''
</P>
<P>
   Americans ``certainly shouldn't be looking at any of the polls
coming out over the weekend,'' cautioned Hickman, the Democratic
consultant. ``The weekend is a terrible time to poll under any
circumstances. There is not a representative sample of Americans at
home on weekends. And the overwhelming majority of interviews of
this unrepresentative sample'' have not learned enough about report
and the president's response to form a lasting opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Even when Americans have considered the evidence and made up
their minds, there is a limit to how important public opinion will
be in the final judgment of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we need polls,'' Rep. John Conyers of Michigan,
the ranking Democrat on the House Judiciary Committee, said Sunday
on CNN's ``Late Edition'' program. ``I don't think we need to
measure how people feel. We have a constitutional duty that should
rise above that. And I think that we'll be able to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Poll figures won't tip the balance for most members, agreed Rep.
John Boehner, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Republican Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that from a member's perspective, that's a
consideration at all,'' said Boehner. ``Members are going to vote
how they believe their constitutional responsibilities require and
not by what their constituents think of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Harrison Hickman, a pollster for Democratic candidates, agreed,
noting that the majority of House incumbents in both political
parties have safe seats and he expects they will use their own
judgment in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those times where being slavish to polls is
especially ill-advised,'' he said. ``'Frankly, I'd be shocked if
one of my clients even asks me to poll on that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the polls are being closely followed on Capitol Hill and
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   With Congress preparing to decide whether to formally begin an
impeachment proceeding, ``where we go from here is not legalistic
but political,'' said Kohut. ``The opinions of normal Americans''
will be considered in the actions of their elected representatives.
</P>
<P>
   In this public arena, the questions will focus on broader
grounds than the legal definitions of perjury or obstruction of
justice, political observers predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The case for the American public, since the impeachment is a
political matter, has to do with their view of the leader of this
country. Is he the person who should lead the country? Is he the
person who should deal with other nations? Is he the person who
should show an example to the children of this country?'' said
White House correspondent Sam Donaldson on ABC's ``This Week'' news
program. ``I think the people will make that judgment and their
elected representatives will reflect it, whatever it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   Kohut said poll readers should watch several indicators for
change in public opinion:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The president's job approval rating.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether people think he should resign.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether they think the charges are serious enough that the
president should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Whether Clinton has the moral authority and respect of the
public and of other leaders to continue in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``In most polls, it will take a while for the impact'' of the
Starr report to be accurately gauged on these key questions, Kohut
said. ``And look for signs of a backlash, that respondents are
angry with Starr'' for the graphic depictions of sex in the report.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Another poll that could have bearing on what happens to Clinton
is the generic survey of voting intentions _ whether respondents
intend to vote for a Democrat or Republican in the upcoming
congressional elections, said Kohut. ``Now it's very close, with
the Republicans having a small lead,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If this gap widens in favor of the GOP, he said, Democrats in
swing districts ``will want to distance themselves further from the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress will have weeks, if not months, to study
these polls before having to cast any risky votes on the issue,
however. Even Democratic supporters of the president say that
Starr's report will probably lead to an impeachment inquiry by the
Judiciary Committee _ which would liely mean hearings beginning
after the November congressional elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be very likely that the next Congress will
ultimately be the body that will consider most of the evidence that
the Judiciary Committee may, in the interim, be looking at in much
greater detail,'' Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., said in a television
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
