<SLUG> BC-GROUCHO-FBI-FILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILES SHOW GROUCHO MARX WAS INVESTIGATED BY FBI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (Eds: Spelling of ``Graucho'' in quote in 3rd graf is cq.) 
(lb) 
 By DINITIA SMITH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the Cold War, while the FBI was investigating the
followers of Karl Marx, it was also focusing its attention on
another Marx, Groucho, an article by a professor at the University
of California says in this week's issue of The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   To write the article, the professor, Jon Wiener, obtained 186
pages of Marx's FBI file, which spans 27 years, under the Freedom
of Information Act. Most of the file, which frequently misspells
``Groucho,'' concerns a copyright lawsuit unrelated to politics,
the article says, and 14 of its pages have been blacked out. But
parts give details of the comedian's activities in left-wing causes
in Hollywood during the 1930s and '40s.
</P>
<P>
   One memorandum to J. Edgar Hoover, the FBI's director, written
in 1953, notes that a member of the Communist Party in San Diego
``recently remarked to a confidential informant that Graucho Marx
contributes heavily to CP.'' But the memorandum also says that a
Los Angeles informant states that ``Marx was never affiliated with
CP.''
</P>
<P>
   Marx's son, Arthur, said his father, who died in 1977 at the age
of 87, had never been a communist. ``He was all his life a
Democrat,'' Marx said. ``He was one of the founders of the Screen
Actors Guild, which was probably one of the reasons for them
looking into his activities.''
</P>
<P>
   The comedian, whose career spanned vaudeville, movies and
television, and who once sang, ``Whatever it is, I'm against it,''
almost never spoke seriously about politics after the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the FBI's own criteria, it was not surprising that Leonard
Bernstein had a file, because he had a party for the Black
Panthers,'' said Victor Navasky, the author of ``Naming Names,'' a
book about the McCarthy period, and The Nation's publisher and
editorial director. ``But a file on Groucho symbolizes the ultimate
absurdity and wastefulness of the FBI's manic pursuit of
communists. One is only sorry that Groucho isn't around to
comment.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the FBI said she could not comment, because
she had not seen the file with blacked-out material provided to
Wiener.
</P>
<P>
   A document in the FBI report quotes remarks it says Marx made to
The Daily Worker, defending the Scottsboro Boys, black men wrongly
convicted of rape in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   The file also notes that Marx attended a benefit in 1942 for
Russian War Relief, opposed recognition of fascist Spain by the
United Nations and belonged to the Committee for the First
Amendment, a Hollywood group that condemned investigations of the
film industry by the House Un-American Activities Committee.
</P>
<P>
   There are also letters from viewers and memorandums from unnamed
FBI officials to Hoover about Marx's hit television show ``You Bet
Your Life,'' which appeared in the 1950s. One viewer complained
that Marx had called the United States ``the United Snakes.''
Hoover's secretary replied that she would call it to the director's
attention.
</P>
<P>
   When another viewer complained that ``You Bet Your Life'' was
``full of communist propaganda'' because Marx was making fun of the
automobile industry, Hoover wrote back that the FBI did not have
the authority to furnish evaluations ``concerning the character or
integrity of any individual.'' Hoover enclosed with his letter a
copy of ``What You Can Do to Fight Communism and Preserve
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiener, who wrote a book about John Lennon's FBI files,
suggested that the FBI investigated Marx because the columnist
Walter Winchell had called Marx's band leader, Jerry Fielding, a
communist sympathizer. Wiener said that Fielding had been
subpoenaed as a witness by the House committee and believed that
the committee was pressuring him to name Marx as a communist.
</P>
<P>
   Wiener said, ``Fielding refused to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Marx dismissed Fielding at a sponsor's behest, but said
he regretted it.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mention of Fielding in the file.
</P>
<P>
   Marx, Wiener writes in The Nation, ``seems to have been a man of
the left, and later, of liberal principles _ for which posterity
may thank him.'' Still, Wiener wrote, ``As he once said: `Why
should I care about posterity? What's posterity ever done for
me?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
