u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-795     09-13 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-795(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT TORONTO FESTIVAL, ELITE TAKE BACK SEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Only half a dozen years ago Toronto was a backwater on
the film-festival map. Cannes, Venice, Berlin, Sundance and New
York were among the higher-profile festivals that lured movie
stars, top directors and distributors seeking to promote films and,
in some cases, discover them.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happened to us is phenomenal,'' said the Toronto Film
Festival director, Piers Handling, a 49-year-old film academic and
author. He was seated in his busy office on Bloor Street, in the
heart of Toronto, which has essentially been taken over by the 23rd
annual festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically,'' he said, ``the structure of the festival has
always been the same. The films have a wide diversity, from the
most esoteric to the most mainstream, from studio films to movies
from Kazakhstan and Kyrgyzstan.''
</P>
<P>
   More than a dozen movie stars _ including Tom Cruise, Meryl
Streep, Billy Bob Thornton and Cameron Diaz _ as well as scores of
Hollywood studio executives, American, Asian and European
distributors, 600 journalists and, perhaps most important, 250,000
Canadian filmgoers have turned this year's Toronto festival into
one that rivals any of the more noted ones.
</P>
<P>
   The eclectic festival, now the largest in North America, ranges
from glitzy premieres of films like Dreamworks' animated ``Antz,''
with the voices of Woody Allen, Sharon Stone, Sylvester Stallone
and others, to ``The City,'' a wrenching neorealistic series of
dramatic vignettes about impoverished Latin American immigrants
exploited in the New York garment district, with mostly
nonprofessional actors starring in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a world we haven't seen before in films,'' said David
Riker, who began the project as a New York University graduate
student.
</P>
<P>
   What sets the Toronto festival apart from many of the others is
not only its sheer size _ more than 300 films, including 144 world
premieres, are being shown _ but the fact that Toronto has a
decidedly nonelitist air.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult, if not impossible, for an average moviegoer to
attend the other festivals, which are crammed with agents, studio
executives, filmmakers, VIPs, hangers-on and anyone with
connections. By contrast, the Toronto festival is available to
typical filmgoers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audiences, the actual civilian audiences, here are
amazing,'' said Mark Ordesky, the president of Fine Line Films.
``They're film literate. They're very enthusiastic. Is there any
other festival where people line up around the block in the early
morning to watch films from Morocco?''
</P>
<P>
   What transformed the festival was, essentially, Hollywood's
realization that Toronto was an extremely friendly, and fairly
close, launching pad for upscale studio films. (A funny, if
low-grade, comedy like ``There's Something About Mary'' wouldn't
open in Toronto.) This year, for example, Paramount unveiled ``A
Simple Plan,'' a bleak and funny drama about greed, directed by Sam
Raimi and starring Thornton, Bill Paxton and Bridget Fonda.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here are kind of receptive and laid back about
movies,'' said Thornton, seated in a hotel room on Saturday
afternoon, hours before the opening of his film. ``They're not
cynical like other places where they go wanting to think of clever,
horrible things to say about a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Friedman, vice chairman of Paramount Motion Picture
Group, was even blunter. ``It's the highest-profile North American
festival, and it's great for generating publicity, generating
excitement. That's why studios come.''
</P>
<P>
   The nine-day festival was opened on Thursday night with a
Canadian drama, ``The Red Violin.'' The film, about the travels of
a violin over three centuries, stars, among others, Samuel L.
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   The more noted films (made by either studios or
quasi-independent companies owned by studios) include ``Pecker,''
directed by John Waters; ``Dancing at Lughnasa,'' with Ms. Streep,
directed by Pat O'Connor; Kirk Jones' ``Waking Ned Devine'';
Richard LaGravanese's ``Living Out Loud''; Roberto Benigni's ``Life
Is Beautiful'' (which was shown at Cannes), and Gary Ross'
``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   But these larger films were more or less dwarfed by the flood of
smaller movies from Europe and Asia as well as the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the common themes in many of the films, Handling,
the festival director, said: ``There seem to be two widely
divergent trends. There are a lot of dark, unsettling films. Films
about dysfunctional families, films about substance abuse. At the
same time we see a lot of more prominent films that are romantic
feel-good comedies. It's just so surprising that the trends are so
far apart. There seem to be two different realities out there, one
where people are trying to put their relationships back together
and the other where people feel hopeless.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   One vivid reality was evident in ``The City,'' Riker's film,
which was first shown early Saturday night. By Sunday morning Riker
was set to meet several distributors, although his film's
commercial prospects are uncertain. The black-and-white film,
almost entirely in Spanish with English subtitles, is reminiscent
of the postwar Italian neorealistic work of Roberto Rossellini.
</P>
<P>
   Riker, who is 35 and lives in New York, won an Academy Award and
a Director's Guild Award in 1995 for his modest student film ``The
City'' (``La Ciudad''), which was the basis for the expanded movie
shown in Toronto. He said the current film cost about $1 million,
the bulk of it from the Independent Television Service, a division
of PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The film deals, in a series of generally bleak and sometimes
harrowing episodes, with Mexican and Central American families in
New York, many of them illegal immigrants, many of them exploited
as workers in sweatshops or pick-up jobs on streets.
</P>
<P>
   The episodes are simple and often heartbreaking. A homeless
father, seeking a better life for his daughter, cannot enroll her
in school because he has no proof of residency. A seamstress,
working in a sweatshop, struggles desperately for money owed to her
to help her sick child in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very, very closely based on the true experiences of
immigrants I spoke with,'' said Riker. One episode, about a young
day laborer who is killed scavenging for bricks in a derelict
building, was based loosely on a newspaper article.
</P>
<P>
   Riker said that most of the actors were nonprofessional and were
found in churches and small grocery stores and on street corners.
He said they went through months of workshops and improvisations
before facing the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I wanted to do, from the very beginning, was make a film
about uprootedness,'' said Riker.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the festival's extremes from Riker, who
is sharing a room at a local Howard Johnson's, are stars like
Cruise, who is here promoting ``Without Limits,'' the film he
produced about the runner Steve Prefontaine, and Cameron Diaz,
arguably the fastest-rising actress in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Diaz, who stars in ``There's Something About Mary,'' one of
the most successful films of the summer, came to Toronto to promote
the film ``Very Bad Things,'' a bleak movie about a bachelor party
that goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   Seated in a conference room at the Four Seasons, Ms. Diaz
shrugged. ``I still don't actually think I'm at a film festival,''
she said. ``I can be anywhere right now. I hear Toronto's a great
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, Don McKellar, a top actor, writer and director in
Canada, sought to put some perspective on the festival. McKellar,
who is 34, is connected to no fewer than six films being shown
here, and The Globe and Mail of Toronto recently called him ``the
most ubiquitous presence at this year's festival.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheerfully unpretentious, McKellar said: ``The whole star issue
is very complicated in Canada. It's slightly unbecoming. People
have a very ambivalent attitude toward promotion, celebritydom, the
star system. Very unlike the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar said the film festival itself was, of course,
peculiarly Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see a lot of movies here, they're very informed and
very serious about movies, and it has to do with that whole thing
of observing culture, which is a very Canadian thing,'' he said.
``We have a kind of observer status looking all the time at
America, this big machine, sort of disinterested but fascinated at
the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   McKellar laughed. ``I'm not supposed to admit this, but most of
the time we define ourselves in reaction to America, on how
different we are from America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
