<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: PRIVACY IN CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Advertisers and agencies involved in aiming online
sales pitches at children are being exhorted to toughen their
policies for protecting privacy or suffer the consequences of
growing demands from parents and government officials for
restrictive regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Those stern warnings were heard on Friday at a daylong
conference at the World Trade Center in lower Manhattan that was
described by its organizers as a ``guide to safe harbors and sound
practices online.'' The conference, the third of its kind, was
sponsored by the Children's Advertising Review Unit, an
organization that is a crucial part of Madison Avenue's longtime
efforts to resolve disputes about advertising without outside
intervention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done a pretty good job so far,'' Elizabeth Lascoutx,
vice president and director for the children's unit, said in her
opening remarks to the 85 people at the conference. ``But we have a
long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Concerns about privacy in cyberspace are intensifying as sites
for children proliferate on the World Wide Web. There are
increasing consumer perceptions that many marketers are reluctant
to address problems like the overzealous collection of personally
identifiable information from young computer users and the porous
handling of such data.
</P>
<P>
   ``One site is asking kids for their Social Security numbers,''
Parry Aftab, a lawyer who specializes in interactive issues, said
in her keynote speech. ``How frustrating is that?''
</P>
<P>
   Those involved in the children's Internet market ought to be
``joining forces and writing a privacy page so kids know what to
give out and not give out,'' said Ms. Aftab, the author of ``A
Parents' Guide to the Internet ... And How to Protect Your
Children'' (SC Press, 1997).
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find a workable solution,'' she added, ``or we'll
lose the wonderful wealth of creativity and content that sites can
offer.''
</P>
<P>
   The advocacy of self-regulation by the children's unit had been
echoed enthusiastically by the Clinton administration, which sent
Ira Magaziner, the president's Internet adviser, to the 1997
conference to applaud efforts to establish voluntary guidelines to
police online peddling to youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   But in June, a report from the Federal Trade Commission said
legislation might be required because violations of children's
privacy online were discouragingly frequent and safeguards were
woefully absent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not suggesting the advertising industry attracts none but
the truly altruistic,'' said Walter O'Brien, president of the
National Advertising Review Council, which administers the
children's unit along with the Council of Better Business Bureaus
and three industry organizations. ``But it's enlightened
self-interest to make a commitment to ethical advertising,
particularly to children under 12.''
</P>
<P>
   And last month, the FTC accused Geocities, a company known for
offering members access to so-called virtual neighborhoods, of
ignoring the privacy policy posted on its site and engaging in
misleading practices that included disseminating information
gathered from children.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to look very far to see a fundamental mistake
there, a mistake we cannot make anymore,'' said John Kamp, senior
vice president at the American Association of Advertising Agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In legal terms, it's called fraud,'' he added with a smile.
``In general terms, it's called `Do you know what you're doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more our customers trust us, the more we succeed in
developing the relationships with them that make our Web sites
work,'' Kamp said. ``Privacy is the great opportunity to
distinguish ourselves from our competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamp's organization is one of the three involved with the
children's unit; the others are the American Advertising Federation
and the Association of National Advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC ``has been very supportive of self-regulation in
children's advertising,'' said Toby Milgrom Levin, a lawyer with
the commission who worked on the Geocities case. ``We recognize
that the advertising industry did rise to the occasion and develop
conventions to protect children from deceptive and overreaching
ads.''
</P>
<P>
   But the belief that advertisers are dawdling about the Internet
is likely to lead Congress to act, she said, and ``there may well
be hearings by the end of the month'' on a bill that ``authorizes
the FTC to prescribe regulations to protect the privacy of children
under 16.''
</P>
<P>
   To forestall legislation, ``you can make privacy a front-burner
concern,'' Ms. Levin advised, especially among top management.
``The Webmasters are not in a position to make privacy happen,''
she added.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, more of those involved in putting up Web sites are
becoming sensitized to privacy matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Privacy is in the forefront of all our programming
decisions,'' said Tina Sharkey, vice president and general manager
of the CTW Online unit of the Children's Television Workshop in New
York, which plans to introduce Monday a redesigned site called the
CTW Family Workshop (www.ctw.org).
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't collect information from children under 13,'' she
added, at areas on the site that are sponsored by marketers like
Ford Motor Co. and Kellogg Co. ``And parents are told everywhere
they can sign up that they can opt out with a `click here.'''
</P>
<P>
   More than one speaker referred to the timing of the conference,
coming as it did while computer users caused some Internet gridlock
in searching for the report on President Clinton by the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``If any group in this country understands the danger of private
information going public and having an impact on their lives,''
said Dan Jaffe, executive vice president at the Association of
National Advertisers, ``it's our politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
