<HEADLINE>
MARTHA THROWS THE PRESIDENT OVERBOARD
</HEADLINE>
  
     By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Clinton &LR;  was to have been the honored guest on `` &UR; Martha &LR; 
 &UR; Stewart &LR;  Living'' on Friday, in a segment taped in June but
Stewart, no ``Stand By Your Man'' kind of woman, dumped him.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton appearance was to have been the highlight of
Stewart's season kick-off week, but pre-program publicity on her
Web site and also in her magazine drew complaints from devotees of
the household goddess.
</P>
<P>
   ``After reflection on subsequent events and information and
feedback from our audiences,'' one of the show's executives told
the Washington Post, ``we feel that airing the program would be
inappropriate at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   The program not seen featured Stewart preparing a meal for the
president and presenting him with a monogrammed pillow, which she
said he was sure to enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   (Not everyone's career is wrecked by scandal:  &UR; Gennifer Flowers &LR; 
is scheduled to sing at the 1998 Electronic Retailing Association
Convention in Las Vegas on Tuesday.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - As if members of Congress weren't titillated enough by the
 &UR; Starr &LR;  report, a decidedly adult coloring book created in 1975 by
 &UR; Tee Corinne &LR;  is being distributed to all.
</P>
<P>
   The book is one of many in the San Francisco Library's Gay and
Lesbian Center, which is named after  &UR; James Hormel &LR; ; its
circulation is an attempt to further damage his chances of
confirmation as ambassador to Luxembourg.
</P>
<P>
   Queer Arts Resource opens an online exhibit of Corinne's work on
October 24.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Laurie Roberts &LR;  thinks the combination of `` &UR; Joe McCarthy &LR; 
was right!'' and ``I'd rather be juggling!'' a pair of bumper
stickers she saw on one vehicle on Highway 17, could give rise to a
whole new Personals category: Unlikely Bumperfellows.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; AND FURTHERMORE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - At the request of  &UR; Paul Hartmann &LR; ((CQ)) brother of the late
comedian  &UR; Phil Hartman &LR; ,  &UR; Gene &LR;   &UR; Schoenfeld &LR;  will scatter some of
Hartman's ashes out beyond the Golden Gate on September 26, in
conjunction with the scattering of other Hartman ashes in his
favorite places, off Catalina Island, and in Mendocino, Big Sur and
Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Cardinal O'Connor &LR; 's boasts about Catholic home-run hitters
did not upset Rector &UR; Robert Cromey  &LR; of Trinity Episcopal Church.
``No Episcopalian would be caught dead hitting little balls great
distances unless they are golf balls,'' says Cromey.
</P>
<P>
   - Eye-witness  &UR; Bob Oberg &LR; , inspecting the Burning Man before he
was torched, looked up and noticed ``in the Man's crotch was a
smoke detector.''
</P>
<P>
   - And finally, reading about Icelandic death threats to Keiko
the whale,  &UR; R.L.  &LR; wonders if they began ``Call me Ishmael.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KERRY FOR 2000? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Windsurfing Senator  &UR; John F. Kerry &LR; , D-Mass., has picked up the
2000 presidential endorsement from American Windsurfer magazine.
</P>
<P>
   A 27-page profile of Kerry in the magazine includes his profound
thoughts about education (``the most critical concern'') and the
spirituality of the  &UR; Dalai Lama &LR;  (``who I've spent time with and
who is absolutely intriguing'').
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's press secretary said he was going to ``work on the
roller-bladers next.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GETTING A MAKE-UNDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Playwright  &UR; Paul Rudnick &LR;  decries the popularity of the beauty
makeover, ``a last ditch assault on feminist progress,'' in the big
fat fall issue of Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   While makeovers humanize public figures, ``reducing  &UR; Janet &LR; 
 &UR; Reno &LR;  and  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR;  to career gals experimenting with
lip gloss at Kmart,'' Rudnick calls them ``the opposite of style --
they are personality kits. ... At best, they are a form of playing
rainy-day attic dress-up; at worst they are  &UR; Michael &LR; 
 &UR; Jackson  &LR; attempting a racial revamp.''
</P>
<P>
   As to televised talk show makeovers, Rudnick proposes a show
called ``The Hose.'' ``On this show, people previously made over on
 &UR; Leeza Gibbons &LR;  or  &UR; Ricki Lake  &LR; would be led center stage and
blasted with fire hoses. Eventually, we would see what they really
look like without the Crayola lipliner and evening-drama cheekbone
glitter. Then each contestant would be given the option of either
facing the world as some semblance of their actual self or suicide,
perhaps by liposuction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
