<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MTV VIDEO MUSIC AWARDS: SALUTE TO TASTELESSNESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NEIL STRAUSS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What is happening in music today? MTV certainly
doesn't know. That's why it has been replacing program directors
and staff every few months. Recently, the channel told the
thrash-rock band Korn not to bother making any videos for its new
album. But last month, when Korn had a hit on the radio and it
became clear that the band's album was going to be No. 1 on the pop
charts, MTV called back. It wanted a video after all.
</P>
<P>
   MTV is not alone in its confusion. Music television, commercial
radio stations and mainstream magazine covers have become
increasingly reliant on market research, primarily because ratings
and circulation are so important to their advertisers. As a result,
the era of the individual with an ear to the ground _ a popular
disk jockey or magazine whose role is to find good artists and
expose them to a mass audience _ is over. The mall rules. Just look
at all the poll-takers walking around the food court with
clipboards. One result is events like the MTV Video Music Awards, a
three-hour salute to tastelessness that took place on Thursday
night at the Universal Amphitheater here.
</P>
<P>
   The big winners were Aerosmith, the Beastie Boys, Will Smith and
Madonna (the formerly controversial singer who used to speak in an
American accent and who walked away with the Best Video Award among
five others). Rewind 10 years, and the winners could have been the
same.
</P>
<P>
   Two things are happening: On the popular front, music is in a
lull (maybe a quiet before the storm), and to fill the gap, it's
back to the '80s. ``The Wedding Singer'' may have catered to the
growing market for '80s nostalgia, but the Video Music Awards were
the decade's coming out party.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the finale featuring the former Stray Cat Brian Setzer,
Beck wearing new-wave sunglasses and a muscle shirt as he
breakdanced onstage, the return of New Kids on the Block in the
form of the Backstreet Boys, and the predominance of old-school
hip-hop scratching throughout the night.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the after-show party at Universal Studios, an airplane
flew overhead advertising a concert by the '80s electronic pop band
Depeche Mode, and executives chattered about the return of '80s
arena metal.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most atypical performance at the ceremony was by
Master P, the Louisiana entrepreneur resurrecting gangsta rap on
his No Limit label. Recently, Master P has become an MTV fixture
not because the cable channel likes something about his music, but
because it has been forced to bow to his phenomenal record sales.
The most powerful arbiter of musical taste in the '90s is not MTV
or radio, but Soundscan, the upstate New York company that every
Wednesday releases regional and national statistics on exactly how
many records are being sold by various acts and genres. These
reports are scrupulously pored over by executives at MTV, record
labels and radio stations, who then make their decisions. They are
analyzing the water but ignoring the wave, and a result is a rerun
culture, where today's pop music is doomed to repeat yesterday's
successes.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, the awards show touched on larger topics than the
return of the '80s and MTV self-promotion. During their acceptance
speeches, Adam Yauch of the Beastie Boys spoke out against the U.S.
missile attacks on sites in Sudan and Afghanistan, and Wyclef Jean
of the Fugees criticized a line in ``How Stella Got Her Groove
Back'' that associated Haiti with AIDS. But Master P's street-style
performance of ``Make 'Em Say Uhh'' _ a melee of people playing
basketball, tumbling and dancing onstage _ was the best evidence
that music was connected to something more real in the outside
world than Versace and Prada.
</P>
<P>
   The awards themselves have never really mattered. Over the
years, MTV and its sister station VH1 have lost their faith in the
music video, first as a block of programming to hold the viewers'
attention for half an hour (thus the rise of programs like ``Real
World'') and then as a medium capable of holding someone's
attention for even a few minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with ``Beavis and Butt-head'' and increasingly with
shows like ``12 Angry Viewers,'' ``Pop-Up Video'' and ``Say What,''
it has become plain that MTV and VH1 don't like to show videos
alone. They put animated characters, words of explanation and faces
of viewers on the screen at the same time, in case people get bored
with just the video. If you factor in the heavy hand MTV censors
have in the videos, it doesn't add up to much respect for the video
as an art form.
</P>
<P>
   What the awards show has always been about is mixing a bunch of
celebrities in a room and waiting to see what unpredictable
shenanigans arise. This year, there were hardly any, a definite
reflection of the current stasis in American pop culture. Like
``Godzilla,'' the awards show became an event because it kept
saying it was, with MTV promoting the show literally 24 hours a
day.
</P>
<P>
   And like ``Godzilla,'' the marketing was more exciting than the
product.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
