<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASCAR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite thrilling finish, tire talk still wags tongues in
Richmond
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ They couldn't beat Jeff Gordon in the tire test
last week, so they beat him on the track at Richmond International
Raceway on Saturday night. Jeff Burton's margin of victory over
Gordon was a hood length, .015 seconds and the closest Winston Cup
finish of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roush, owner of Burton's winning No. 99 Ford, felt
confident that he had scored a victory for fair play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all the competitors feel better about the new policy
NASCAR has, which limits the teams from bringing tires from home
that are of unknown pedigree and putting them on pit road to go on
the cars,'' Roush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every competitor had the same tires off the Goodyear truck
(Saturday night). It, for sure, was a fair race. There is no
question that could be raised by me or anybody else about whether
or not somebody had special tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Roush insinuated that Gordon's crew might be
doing something illegal, like using chemicals on tires to create an
unfair advantage. Roush said that was enabling Gordon's No. 24
Chevrolet to win with two new tires late in the race while other
teams were racing with four.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR allows teams to bring back tires purchased at a track in
the season's second race, but all teams must start and finish races
with tires dispensed on race weekend.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR said its independent lab tests revealed that Gordon's
tires were clean, and Roush was criticized for his allegations. But
Burton stood up for his boss after holding off Gordon during the
last three laps of Saturday's Exide 400.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Roush had the confidence in himself to bring up an issue
that 85 percent of the car owners behind closed doors were talking
about,'' Burton said. ``And Jack Roush was the only one that had
enough guts to say it and try to do something about it. So as other
car owners have stayed quiet, Jack has been part of making a policy
that will guarantee fairness in racing, and what's wrong with
that?''
</P>
<P>
   Roush claimed the Saturday night victory wasn't particularly
vindicating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever you can beat the 24 team you've really done
something,'' Roush said. ``They've got a great program. I had
exactly one problem with the way the program had been going, and
that was the fact that in two of the last three races, including
the Loudon race, they put on two tires and outran cars with four
tires, and you just can't do that on anything but maybe Darlington
and Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday night) the tires were a factor,'' he said. ``Of
course, I'm looking for closure on the tire thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams took four tires on their last pit stop, contrary to
what Gordon said about Burton's two tire swap at the end of the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been so much controversy about to tires,'' Burton
said, ``I wouldn't dare do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton had the dominant car all night, leading for 203 of the
400 laps, including the last 40. But he pointed to a caution with
35 laps to go as the key to his second victory of the season. ``We
were in trouble with a long run,'' he said. ``We had gotten by him,
but he was going to come back and getting that caution was a key.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton was asked early last week if he and Gordon were the next
great stock car racing rivalry. Not even the Exide victory could
make him buy into that odd concept.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won 10 races; we've won two,'' Burton said. ``I've got to
get off my butt and win some more races.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
