<SLUG> BC-BRAVES-NOTEBOOK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miracles of modern medicine make Neagle confident
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Idle since Sept. 1 while his left shoulder cooled off,
Denny Neagle insists he will make his next start, scheduled in
three days when the Braves open a four-game series in Arizona.
Better living through cortisone.
</P>
<P>
   ''It got to the point where I was just playing catch,'' he said,
''and unless I threw (side-arm) like Brad Clontz, as soon as I'd
reach a little bit, it was grabbing me. That's what bursitis is,
though. You get all that inflammation and it doesn't let you
extend.''
</P>
<P>
   Neagle has had two throwing sessions since Tuesday's cortisone
injection and surely wants to return to the mound. Having solved a
1-4 slump that dated back to mid-July, the left-hander is on a
three-game win streak and one more win would give him 15.
</P>
<P>
   Significant because he has reached 15 victories only once before
in his career, Neagle could also make history by becoming the the
team's fifth 15-game winner. Not since the 1930 Washington Senators
has a staff had five pitchers reach 15. The last National League
club to do so was the 1925 Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my own personal goals, I always try to get 15 wins,'' said
Neagle, who turned 30 on Sunday. ''I think that's a good number to
shoot for at the start of the season. Even more important, it has
more significance. That's something you should be proud of. The
first time since 1930? That's incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, I'm going to down-play it and say I'm not going to
be thinking about it when I'm pitching. It's only natural to say
you want to get this so I can compliment everybody else. It's
obviously not comparable to McGwire's year but there are only so
many times that a season like this rolls around.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching plans
</P>
<P>
   Neagle's return has little bearing on the future use of rookie
of Bruce Chen, who went 1-0 in the two starts he made in Neagle's
absence. Manager Bobby Cox will soon be moving Kevin Millwood to
the bullpen, to re-acclimate him for relief work he will be doing
in the postseason. As well, the team is still considering passing
over John Smoltz, if not just giving him an abbreviated start, in
the last two weeks to give some relief to his right elbow. Chen
would find service in either scenario.
</P>
<P>
   Wounded knee
</P>
<P>
   Danny Bautista's right knee will still not allow him back into
action, 21 days after the club placed him on the disabled list.
Though the team believes the slight tear found in his medial
colateral ligament is the result of an old injury, Bautista's knee
has become too loose to allow him to maneuver in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ''He isn't ready yet,'' said Cox. ''He can't turn. We'd hoped to
have him on the (postseason) roster. He's not 100 percent yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bautista's absence makes an October opportunity for Curtis
Pride, who has started in both left and right field and provides
some speed for the bench. He also gives Cox three left-handed
hitting outfielders of out five, but right-handed pinch-hitter Greg
Colbrunn evens out the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Hola, Raffy
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Walt Weiss made his second start in three days without
incident, a development which just about eliminates any chance of
Rafael Belliard appearing in a Braves uniform again this year, if
ever. On the 60-day disabled list after tearing his quadriceps in
the second week of the season, Belliard rejoined the club this
weekend after completing a three-week injury re-hab assignment in
Richmond, which he capped off with his fourth career minor-league
home run off Norfolk's Josias Manzanillo.
</P>
<P>
   But a healthy Weiss, with a healthy Ozzie Guillen sharing time
with him, spells an end to Belliard's career with the Braves. Since
he is on the 60-day disabled list, which would require dropping
someone from the 40-man roster to activate him, only an emergency
would get him back on the team this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''The last two weeks, I was playing all nine innings and it felt
very good,'' said Belliard, 36. ''I wasn't feeling anything wrong
with my leg.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
