u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DICKEY-Q-AND-A-COX     09-13 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DICKEY-Q-AND-A-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Poet's son back with memoir, memories
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta that Christopher Dickey returns to this
week is vastly different from the city he grew up in during the
1950s. Back then, he and other students at Brandon-Morris
Elementary School huddled under their desks during nuclear attack
drills, and parents talked nervously of impending integration.
</P>
<P>
   And Dickey's father, James Dickey, was still more famous for his
Coca-Cola jingles than for his poetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``No city in the South was a more suitable home for an
advertising man,'' Dickey says in his memoir, ``Summer of
Deliverance: A Memoir of Father and Son'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster,
$24.95). ``Slogans and jingles, with a little chicanery and a lot
of chutzpah, were as natural to Atlanta as the rhetoric of fire and
brimstone was to the rural parishes just beyond its horizons.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of his return to the city of his youth, Dickey, 46,
the Paris bureau chief for Newsweek, talked about what it feels
like to come home again.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q: In your book, you talk about the years of estrangement from
your father. Was your childhood in Atlanta a happy one?
</P>
<P>
   _ A: Yes, it was. We lived a quintessentially suburban life at
2930 Westminster Circle, which was a dead end in those days. That
was when I was 8 or 9, and we would go hunting and canoeing in
North Georgia. And there was a little creek and a lot of weeds and
a few trees near the house. In the summer you'd come across snakes
down there. The dangers of nature were a little closer to our
suburbs than anybody really wanted to admit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q: Have you visited the house where you grew up ?
</P>
<P>
   _ A: I did when I was working on the book a couple of years ago.
I didn't go in, because somebody's living there. It's a very small
ranch house, and it was a very nice place to live when I was little
boy. It doesn't look as big as I remember it. I also went to my
grandmother's house at 166 W. Wesley. It seemed like a huge
distance to her house then, but I drove it the last time I was
here, and I was amazed it was so close. I've often thought of going
and knocking on the door and introducing myself, but I know it
wouldn't look the same. And it wouldn't smell the same.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q: Do you remember your neighbors?
</P>
<P>
   _ A: Across the street from us lived a salesman. One summer he
had a Fourth of July party. There was a street parade with
crepe-paper streamers on our bicycles, and we ran three-legged
races and ate Waldorf salad and fried chicken and watermelon. Dad,
I remember, won the husbands' beautiful-legs contest. Farther up
the street, toward Howell Mill, was a woman who'd survived a
concentration camp and had a number tattooed on her arm. She also
had rows of little red-and-white pins on the visor of her car to
show how many times she'd given blood to the Atlanta Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q: What kind of feelings do you have about the city?
</P>
<P>
   _ A: Atlanta was a town I lived in when I was a little boy and
it's been a long time since I was a little boy. Most of my visits
have been quick hits on business or for funerals, so I never had
much sense of the town, and certainly not as my town. I'm looking
forward to going back now. It always had a lot more texture and
complexity than most of the cities in the South. And since my
father and I started talking to each other before his death, I find
myself identifying more with Atlanta as his town.
</P>
<P>
   _ Q: In ``Summer of Deliverance,'' you were very hard on your
father about his drinking and abusive behavior. What would he have
thought of the book?
</P>
<P>
   _ A: I think my father would be very happy with the book. I have
gotten a little tired of reading that line where it says I hated
him, but a lot of reviewers recognize the book is about how much I
loved him.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
