<HEADER>
A2729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-WEEK14-COX     09-13 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-WEEK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designers buck tradition with early-bird showings
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Helmut Lang wouldn't be considered one of America's
most influential fashion designers if he didn't produce such nice
white blouses.
</P>
<P>
   Donna Karan's claim to fame is the fact that her stretchy,
solid-colored clothes look good on average women's physiques.
</P>
<P>
   And Calvin Klein's underwear, jeans and fragrances have adorned
millions who might never have worn his couture designs.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Lang, Karan, and Klein decided to preview their
spring/summer 1999 womenswear collections this week _ rather than
wait to show their clothes in November with the majority of
America's top designers _ it filled the fashion world with the sort
of frightful uncertainty best reserved for armed conflict between
nations, weather disasters or outbreaks of disease. The irony of
the situation is that Lang, Karan and Klein are famous for the
simplicity of their designs, and yet they're the reason everything
is suddenly so complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar de la Renta, the (BEGIN ITAL) eminence grise (END ITAL)
among New York designers, said he was sticking with the November
schedule because ``It's too tramatic and impossible for me to
switch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was naughty of Calvin Klein to do this (plan an earlier
show in September) without talking to the Council of Fashion
Designers (a governing body of fashion designers). I have always
wanted to accommodate retailers and the press. I never did a show
at 9 p.m. in the evening or in a place that's difficult to get to
in New York. I think when you are in a position of power, like many
designers are, you use this power in a nice way, not in a way to
inconvenience retailers and the press.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, New York's top designers have always waited for
their counterparts in England, Italy and France to unveil their
womenswear collections on a biannual basis before sending their own
seasonal styles out onto the runway. That tradition ended when Lang
_ an Austrian who moved his operation from Paris to New York last
year _ announced that the time-honored schedule didn't work for him
and that he would be staging his spring/summer '99 preview on Sept.
17, six weeks before anyone else in New York had planned to show.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein _ who's customarily afforded the honor of being the
last American to stage a preview during the citywide expo known as
Fashion Week _ followed Lang's lead. Things snowballed from there:
Nicole Miller, Vivienne Tam, Karan, and others jumped aboard the
beat-Europe-to-the-punch bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his few explanatory statements to the press, Lang
said, ``One thing I don't understand is why New York wants to be
last (in fashion) when it wants to be first in everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Karan told reporters that she opted to show early because ``It
makes more sense for the retailer to see the collection first and
then (order) the collection. It also helps us for organization and
delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   The perceived benefits of being a New Yorker who shows before
the Europeans do are more conceptual than tangible. Perhaps showing
first will gain the American designers a greater share of retail
sales space if their collections are the first, rather than the
last, that the buyers see. And perhaps fashion editors will stop
accusing American designers of borrowing ideas from the Europeans
if they see what New York has to offer first.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, perhaps not.
</P>
<P>
   The facts are these: Designers don't usually stage runway shows
until weeks after they've already shown their collections to the
stores and magazine editors who really determine what'll be
considered stylish six months hence; and most of the world's top
designers now rely on the same manufacturers, so victory goes to
those who contract to have their clothes made the most swiftly.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Klein issued a statement saying, ``The advantage is
that we will be able to go into production much earlier. I as a
designer who now has a global business had to have collections
ready earlier. It's from the business point of view that this
really makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Kalinsky, who owns the Bob Ellis Shoes, Jil Sander and
Jeffrey boutiques at Phipps Plaza in Atlanta, concurs with Klein's
assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The earlier they show the better,'' he said. ``It's great for
the Americans to be first; they are just as valid as European
designers. I love American design, and now I'll see the collections
before I've been to Europe and spent all my dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Invitations to this week's major runway shows wouldn't be nearly
as sought after as tickets to the Yankees or ``Rent'' if not for
fashion arbiters' hunger to be among the first to see and say what
the best-dressed people should be wearing. By causing this
confusion _ being the commercial masterminds that they are _ Lang,
Klein and Karan are merely throwing fat onto the fire of (BEGIN
ITAL)fashionistas' (END ITAL) ascination.
</P>
<P>
   It's really that simple.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
