<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love her or hate her, `Ally McBeal's' back
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her hair has gotten a little lanker, the eyes seem a bit bigger,
the skirts, if possible, a little shorter. She's Ally-er than ever,
and she's back tonight for the start of season two.
</P>
<P>
   For the blissfully unaware, ``Ally McBeal'' (9 tonight on Fox )
was more than just a breakout hit last season. It was the McBuzz _
endlessly chattered about, obsessed over, dissed and dissected. A
dithery, klutzy attorney in her late 20s, Ally (Calista Flockhart)
had minis that were too minimal, neuroses that were too ridiculous,
hallucinations that were too weird, and a dewy romanticism that
made her seem oh so huggable or relatable, depending on your
gender. Or, for other viewers, the exact opposite of all that.
</P>
<P>
   Whimsy is perhaps the toughest act to maintain _ just ask the
writers of ``Northern Exposure'' and ``Moonlighting,'' both of
which set their bars very high and then kept settling for
cutesiness or quirkiness. ``Ally'' may have it tougher than either
of those shows, not least because at this point, David E. Kelley
has written every single script, and he just can't keep that up.
And even Kelley has trouble living up to his own reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Take tonight's premiere. It's not bad, it's just not the
knockout fans of the show are hoping for after a summer of re-runs.
We're back in the unisex bathroom for a round of mistaken
identities. Ally's back with her sarcastic shrink (Tracey Ullman).
There's a kinky court case, about a 39-year-old woman who had an
affair with a 16-year-old boy. Cage (Peter MacNicol) is wistfully
recalling ``Summer of '42,'' while Richard Fish (Greg Germann) is
adding to our too-much-information list of his turn-ons (Shari
Lewis and his stock portfolio tonight, though not the two
together). It's kinda nice to dip back into their dippy lives, but
there's also a feeling that the show is verging on self-caricature
at times.
</P>
<P>
   New to the mix tonight is blond ice queen Portia de Rossi as
Nelle Porter, an attorney whose nickname is ``Sub-Zero.'' She's
beautiful and brainy, so the guys are all groveling and the women
are all catty. Nelle isn't showing much of her hand yet, but she
gives the impression she could spank them all soundly and send them
to bed. Which may _ who knows? _ be next week's episode. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
