<HEADLINE>
STRONG SHOWING BY BAVARIAN CONSERVATIVES BOOSTS KOHL'S CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUNICH, Germany _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl's prospects for
re-election got a significant lift Sunday, when Bavaria's
conservative Christian Social Union won a decisive victory over the
Social Democratic Party in state-wide elections.
</P>
<P>
   Based on exit polls Sunday evening, the Christian Social Union _
the Bavarian sister-party to Kohl's Christian Democrats _ received
more than 52 percent of the vote. The opposition Social Democrats
received about 29.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks before Germans vote for chancellor in national
elections, the results Sunday were a surprising setback for Gerhard
Schroeder, Kohl's Social Democratic challenger for chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who had been barnstorming across this bastion of
conservatism in the last two weeks, had set a goal of improving on
the 30-percent share that Social Democrats received here in 1994.
The Christian Social Union had been fighting to hold on to at least
50 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts and politicians alike were cautious about
reading too much into Sunday's results. Bavaria has the strongest
economy and lowest unemployment rate of any German state, and
political leaders have carefully distanced themselves from Kohl in
their campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the vote was considerably better for the
conservatives and considerably worse for the Social Democrats than
most people here had expected. Schroeder and other party leaders
had campaigned hard in order to use the Bavarian vote as a solid
sign of their growing strength. Conversely, the Bavarian Premier,
Edmund Stoiber, had campaigned heavily on the theme of villainizing
Schroeder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a clear drubbing for the Social Democrats,'' gloated
Stoiber at the majestic Bavarian statehouse Sunday night. ``This
showed a clear shift among voters to the benefit of the ruling
coalition'' in Bonn.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian Social Union, which is only active in Bavaria, is
a member of the center-right coalition led by Kohl's Christian
Democratic Union. The other party in the coalition is the much
smaller Free Democratic Party, which represents the most reliable
pro-business voters in Germany. Although Stoiber and his party
remain popular and were not expected to lose control of the state
government, they had been struggling to retain an outright majority
of votes and therefore of seats in the state parliament. Recent
polls indicated their support had fallen to almost exactly 50
percent, down from 52.8 percent in the previous election, and the
Social Democrats appeared to be attracting about 33 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, Schroeder continues to lead Kohl in all polls and
the Christian Democrats are still considered the underdogs. But
Sunday's news was the first solid indication that Schroeder's
momentum may be weakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will definitely have an effect on the national
election,'' said Theo Waigel, who is both chairman of the Christian
Social Union in Bavaria and Kohl's Finance Minister in Bonn. ``I
had begun to sense the change in sentiment for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   But Social Democrats argued that Sunday's results had no
significance for the election for chancellor later this month,
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a Stoiber election, but on Sept. 27 the choice will
be between Schroeder and Kohl, and people will choose Schroeder,''
said Renate Schmidt, the party's candidate for premier of Bavaria.
</P>
<P>
   In Bonn, Schroeder and other national party leaders said they
would still prevail. ``Despite the results in Bavaria, the SDP will
still win the national election,'' Schroeder insisted.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There is still no doubt that voters here are far more loyal to
the Christian Social Union that to the broader ruling coalition in
Bonn. This is, after all, a state that still likes to think of
itself as a separate country from the rest of Germany and where
people sing what amounts to a national anthem at major public
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign battles of the last few weeks, Stoiber has
carefully avoided appearing on the same stage as Kohl or even
mentioning Kohl's name in his speeches. Stoiber has also been a
vociferous critic of Kohl's most passionate project, the creation
of a single European currency that will eventually replace the
German mark, and he has also infuriated other members of the ruling
coalition by proposing that wealthy states like Bavaria be freed
from having to underwrite social security costs for poorer states.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the incumbent conservatives here have a strong
tailwind that their counterparts in other parts of Germany do not
have. Unemployment is far lower here, at 6.1 percent, than in any
other state in Germany. The economy is growing faster, with local
companies like BMW and Porsche booming and a new generation of
technology companies settling here to take advantage of a skilled
work force and generous support from the state government.
</P>
<P>
   Under Stoiber, the state has privatized more than $3 billion
worth of state-owned businesses and used that money to invest in
new infrastructure and provide venture capital for new companies.
The loquacious and combative premier routinely boasts about
``Lebkuchen und Lasers'' _ gingerbread and lasers _ and remains far
more popular than Kohl.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, recent surveys by the Enmid polling organization have
shown that more than 70 percent of voters feel positively toward
Stoiber, but less than 45 percent feel that way about either Kohl
or Waigel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
