<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2738 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-LEGISLATION14     09-13 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LEGISLATION14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AMID CRISIS, BOTH PARTIES MUST DEAL WITH LEGISLATION
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and congressional leaders will
try this week to set aside his woes and get back to grappling with
national and global priorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're focusing on the job we have to do,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss. Describing a Republican
strategy session of Senate and House leaders Thursday, he said,
``We talked about the appropriation bills, tax cuts, agriculture
issues, higher education, financial services modernization,
bankruptcy reform. We didn't talk at all about this other matter.''
</P>
<P>
   The president echoed those sentiments Saturday in his radio
address. ``The most important thing to do now is to stay focused on
the issues the American people sent us here to deal with _ from
health care to the economy to terrorism,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the ``critical issues'' pending before Congress
include fiscal discipline, support for the International Monetary
Fund, and support for education, patients' rights, the environment
and campaign finance reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may think they mean it,'' said John Hibbing, a University
of Nebraska political scientist who has studied Congress
extensively. ``But my hunch is, they're going to be preoccupied
(and) it's going to be difficult to have a productive legislative
period before the mid-term election.''
</P>
<P>
   Routine spending bills _ either individually or bundled into an
all-encompassing ``continuing resolution'' _ are likely to pass. So
are minor tax cuts, said Michigan State University political
scientist David W. Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he doesn't anticipate agreement on non-monetary
matters such as patients' rights or environmental and educational
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I don't think anything much would have been done on
them this year anyway, even if we'd never heard of Monica
Lewinsky,'' Rohde said. Unlike arguments over money, philosophical
differences over issues like regulation and provision of health
care cannot be resolved by splitting the difference, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gridlock on such issues hasn't seemed to hurt either Clinton or
Congress this year. Both have seen their poll ratings rise and stay
high.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's been a feeling in Congress of 'let's not do so
much that we screw that up,' `` Hibbing said.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Congress will have to push hard to meet its goal of
finishing the routine appropriations process within the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 13 annual spending bills, only one has become law. Two
bills are stalled in the House, another is stalled in the Senate,
and eight have yet to emerge from Senate-House conference
committees. In fact, the leaders still haven't gotten around to
naming the members of several conference committees.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., said the GOP leaders
``agreed that we're going to work very hard to get all the
appropriations bills done to ensure that the government stays open
and to have no excuse for the president to try to distract
attention by shutting the government.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans have absolutely no other choice,'' Rohde said.
It is they, not Clinton, who will face the voters in November, he
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake for them to think the president is going
to automatically cave in to them because of the problems he's
having,'' Rohde said. ``It's exactly the opposite: They'll be
dealing with a president who will be very wary that Republicans
might try to take advantage of him.''
</P>
<P>
   One potential battleground will be income tax cuts, a longtime
GOP priority.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, chairman of the tax-writing House
Ways and Means Committee, said the Republicans want to use 10
percent of the expected budget surplus to pay for a five-year
package of $80 billion in tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But Gingrich said the other 90 percent must be set aside as a
contingency fund for next year's Social Security reforms, rather
than used to fund Clinton's request for about $20 billion above the
amounts that Republicans want to spend. The extra money would be
used for readying government computers for the year 2000, enhancing
security of U.S. embassies, providing emergency aid to farmers and
maintaining peacekeeping troops in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Finance Committee Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., last
week floated a compromise proposal. ``We have a very large surplus.
I have concluded that if we are going to do spending increases
which break the (spending) caps, then we ought to do tax cuts right
alongside it,'' Domenici said.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting down that trial balloon, Senate Democratic Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., on Friday said, ``There is no way Democratic
senators will support raiding Social Security for an $80 billion
tax cut.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle's statement, as Rohde pointed out, left room for
Democratic approval of a smaller tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
