<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALTIMORE-BOOK-REVIEW     09-13 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOK REVIEW: FOR A SCIENTIFIC TEAM, A CASE GOES TERRIBLY AWRY
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Scientific truths, of whatever order, are reached by
eliminating perturbing or conflicting factors, and recognizing only
fundamental factors,'' wrote Herbert Spencer cogently in ``The Data
of Ethics'' in 1879.
</P>
<P>
   But what if for some reason ``eliminating perturbing or
conflicting factors'' is perceived as deliberately skewing
experimental evidence? This is at the heart of the drama described
so meticulously by the science writer Daniel J. Kevles in his
weighty new book, ``The Baltimore Case: A Trial of Politics,
Science and Character.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Margot O'Toole, a post-doctoral fellow working in a
laboratory at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, was asked
to do experiments that would extend the work described in a paper
on an immunological experiment. The paper was written by her
employer, Thereza Imanishi-Kari, along with, among others, David
Baltimore, the Nobel laureate MIT biologist who conceived the
experiment. When O'Toole could not reproduce the results described
in Imanishi-Kari's contribution to the paper, Kevles writes, she
became convinced that her employer had fudged her own results, and
she eventually complained to an acquaintance, who in turn alerted
authorities at the National Institutes of Health that Imanishi-Kari
might have committed scientific fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Occurring at a time when the United States government was
growing highly sensitive to misconduct in the scientific community
and the possible misuse of public funds, what became known as the
Baltimore Case (Baltimore was the paper's senior writer) led to an
investigation by both Rep. John Dingell's House Subcommittee on
Oversight and Investigations and the National Institutes' Office of
Scientific Integrity, and an eventual judgment of fraud on
Imanishi-Kari's part.
</P>
<P>
   Although she was finally exonerated on appeal in 1996, the
decadelong case damaged Imanishi-Kari's career and that of
Baltimore, who, because he defended his colleague so vociferously,
was maligned by many of his peers in the scientific community and
forced to resign from the presidency of Rockefeller University 18
months after assuming it in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The wonder of Kevles' book is the coherence with which he
describes a case so complex that any attempt at summary does it
violence. You read it with a rising sense of despair and outrage,
and you finish it as if awakening from a nightmare that only Kafka
could have conceived.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Kevles _ whose previous books include ``The Physicists'' and
``In the Name of Eugenics'' _ remains meticulous about presenting
every arcane detail raised by both Imanishi-Kari's attackers and
defenders, including, not incidentally, the considerable number of
unintentional errors she made. And his analysis of what happened is
so painstaking that you find it difficult to point any finger of
blame, except possibly at the Dingell subcommittee, which Kevles
accuses of having ``emulated Senator Joe McCarthy in ways that it
perhaps did not realize,'' and at the majority of the media, which
tended to report uncritically what Imanishi-Kari's accusers said of
her.
</P>
<P>
   As for her chief detractor, O'Toole, Kevles characterizes her as
combative, overzealous, hyperpolitical and inclined to see the
world in black and white. But he leaves you with the sense that
O'Toole's primary motive in attacking Imanishi-Kari so doggedly was
her determination to rescue her own career as a scientist, which,
Kevles writes, she saw as having suffered because of her
accusations.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Kevles pays a certain price for his meticulous
attention to the details of the case. He explains that he wrote his
book ``to make its scientific content accessible to nonbiologists
as well as to biologists, keeping discussions of the technical
issues as concise as possible and relegating elaborative material
to the notes.''
</P>
<P>
   But he gives nonbiologists few breaks. He makes no attempt to
create a simplifying metaphor for the experiment, which involved
stimulating the formation of antibodies in mice and which was so
``technically intricate,'' Kevles writes, that even some biologists
``find it difficult to comprehend.'' Nor does he explain the
broader implications, if any, of the experiment's results; he
merely writes that ``taken together, its findings were
remarkable.'' As a result, much of the reasoning in the arguments
over Imanishi-Kari's work simply passes the nonexpert reader by.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the human drama is what matters most in ``The Baltimore
Case,'' the collision of scientists, bureaucrats and politicians in
an arena where money and power are at stake. As Kevles himself
points out, ``At its core, this book is the story of how a great
injustice was perpetrated in the name of scientific integrity and
the public trust and how it then came to be remedied, or remedied
as much as it could be after its weight had been endured for a
decade.'' Today, Imanishi-Kari is a tenured associate professor at
Tufts University and Baltimore is the president of the California
Institute of Technology, in Pasadena, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   And Kevles demonstrates effectively the disastrous consequences
when political agendas are imposed on the process of scientific
inquiry. ``Baltimore may not have appreciated that John Dingell did
not intend to attack American science as such,'' Kevles concludes,
but ``he was justified in thinking that the way Dingell pursued the
misconduct issue in effect threatened the flexibility and freedom
with which scientists approached the understanding of their data.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanislaus Leszcynski, an 18th-century King of Poland, said,
``Science is nothing but good sense and sound reason.'' In ``The
Baltimore Case,'' Kevles shows us at length and with great
eloquence that, alas, this isn't always the case.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BALTIMORE CASE: A Trial of Politics, Science and
Character.'
</P>
<P>
   By Daniel J. Kevles.
</P>
<P>
   Illustrated. 509 pages. W.W. Norton &AMP; Co. $29.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
