<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FCC GRANTS EXTENSION FOR WIRETAP MODERNIZATION
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has given the
telecommunications industry until June 30, 2000, to install the
software and hardware necessary for court-authorized wiretaps of
modern digital and wireless communications networks.
</P>
<P>
   The extension, which grants a reprieve of an additional 20
months, leaves unresolved some questions raised by industry
executives and privacy experts who had argued that the FBI was
using the law both to expand its wiretapping power and add new
capabilities like the ability to track the location of cellular
telephone users and intercept Internet traffic.
</P>
<P>
   A Preview of the Microsoft Case
</P>
<P>
   The arguments in Microsoft's trial on antitrust charges, now set
to begin Oct. 15, are becoming clear. The Justice Department and
the 20 state attorneys general who filed the lawsuit against the
software giant contend that Microsoft's leaders will prove the
government's case. But Microsoft contends that its business
practices are the same as those of other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gartner Is Counting Down Till 2000
</P>
<P>
   Gartner Group, the computer consultant that moves to the New
York Stock Exchange on Tuesday, will display a custom-made Bolivian
rosewood case that combines an hourglass with a digital clock set
to count down to Jan. 1, 2000 _ a date that some experts predict
will live in infamy for all the mayhem it may cause computers
unable to recognize dates ending in ``00.'' Gartner is advising
many corporations on how to gird their computers for the
millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Technology Outlook Seems Brighter
</P>
<P>
   Intel said Friday that third-quarter sales would be 8 percent to
10 percent higher than the $5.9 billion reported in the second
quarter, rather than flat, as it had suggested earlier. And other
technology companies are expected to announce similar positive
results for the third and fourth quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Marketing of a Phone Company
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Clayton, the executive who is widely believed to have
been hired by Frontier phone company to get it into shape for a
sale, faces a shorter list of potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Critics Challenge Internet Findings
</P>
<P>
   A study that links Internet use with increases in depression and
loneliness has been severely criticized.
</P>
<P>
   Rates for Photographs Unchanged
</P>
<P>
   An article in Photo District News, a publication for
professional photographers, contends that rates paid for editorial
photography have barely changed since 1988 when a majority of the
major magazines paid a so-called day rate of $350. Moreover,
publishers now generally receive the right to re-use pictures for
``minimal additional compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Battle of Online City Guides
</P>
<P>
   Online city guides offering everything from concert listings and
restaurant reviews to traffic reports have been one of the
Internet's fiercest battlegrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Argentina Maintains Exchange Rate
</P>
<P>
   Argentina and its economic advisers continue to promise that
they will keep the government's fixed exchange rate that pegs the
value of the Argentine peso to the American dollar one to one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
