<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MARYLAND-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME IN MARYLAND'S 8TH CD, THE STARR REPORT SEEMS LIKE OLD
NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERAL; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(ART ADV: A graphic of Maryland's 8th CD is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(hlw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   POOLESVILLE, Md. _ By the time the food stalls and souvenir
stands were up and running here this weekend for the annual
Poolesville street fair, the contents of the Starr report were old
news to residents of this little suburban village 25 miles
northwest of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   To hear most fairgoers talk, after learning what was in the
report on Friday, they concluded there was more lewdness than news
_ and little they could do about the report, anyway. And so, they
said, they turned the issue off late that night, along with the 10
o'clock news.
</P>
<P>
   No, many insisted, it really didn't come up the next morning
over breakfast or later down at the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should it?'' asked Alex Viessmann, a retired Navy captain,
as he waited for the big Main Street parade to begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's really nothing new to say after all these endless
months of Clinton-Starr, Clinton-Starr, Clinton-Starr,'' he went
on. ``We're all just more disgusted, more disappointed and more
frustrated than ever. Besides, it's out of our hands now, up to
Congress from here on out.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the issue isn't entirely up to Congress, given
the way Congress reacts to public opinion. And, try as they might,
the people of Poolesville did not turn Clinton-Starr off on Friday
night with the flick of a button.
</P>
<P>
   They still have plenty of opinions about what should be done,
almost as many opinions as there are people in Poolesville, it
sometimes seems. Beneath all the chatter at the street fair about
snow cones, pony rides and McGwire-Sosa, Clinton-Starr still nagged
_ still nags _ the people of Poolesville, stubborn as a summer cold
and a lot more painful.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many other Americans, they are bone weary of
Clinton-Starr and many, if not most, are talked out on the issue or
find it just too uncomfortable to talk about, even in the turbulent
wake of the Starr report. But once they start talking. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I want him out of there, just can't stand the man,''
Viessmann, an independent who mostly votes Republican, said a few
moments after insisting the fate of President Clinton had shifted
away from places like Poolesville and now rested solely in the
hands of Congress. ``He can resign, which I don't anticipate, or he
can be impeached. But he's hurt and embarrassed this country and
he's got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cooper, a Cub Scout leader and a Democrat who voted for
Clinton, had a more benign take on the issue, though he was no less
concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true that the country has been terribly hurt by all
this,'' he said as he struggled to get his squirming blue-clad pack
assembled for the parade. ``Even these little guys I've got here
know something terrible has gone wrong. But it won't help the
country any if Clinton resigns or is impeached. That is a struggle
that will only make things worse. What he's done is inexcusable,
but it isn't resignation or impeachable stuff. What I say is that,
now that it's all been aired, let's push on.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Trusilo, a school teacher who votes Republican, said that
Clinton should resign because he had failed as a leader, not
politically but morally.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way I can teach kids to be good citizens when the
biggest example-setter of all does things that have grammar
schoolchildren making jokes about cigars,'' she said, with hurt in
her voice.
</P>
<P>
   And if Clinton did not resign?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, Lord,'' she replied, frustration replacing hurt. ``I don't
know. Impeachment? I don't know. That's mighty hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in the middle of all of this was Pat Michaels, a
travel company operator.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Rep. Constance Morella, a Republican whose
congressional district includes Poolesville, working the fair
crowd, he rushed to her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to ask one thing,'' he said, frustration in his
voice. ``For God's sake, get us out of this mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Morella, seeking votes for reelection to a seventh term in
a district that is more Democratic than Republican, said she would
do all she could. But she was otherwise non-commital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be very careful about this,'' she explained. ``I'm
not going to commit to anything until we've studied all aspects.
But I will say this: I don't want any of my grandchildren reading
Mr. Starr's report.''
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Vanwerthoven, a computer service company owner, said she
was disgusted with both the President and Kenneth Starr, the
independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Abuse of power,'' she mused. ``If you ask me, they're both
guilty of abuse of power. This whole mess has whirled out of
control. It should never have gone this far. I can't believe our
country has become a world stage for a multimillion-dollar sex
probe.''
</P>
<P>
   She turned to look for her husband, Philip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enough of all this,'' she said, heading off in his direction.
``Gotta catch up with the parade.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
