<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-EDITORIALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATION'S EDITORIAL WRITERS SOUND OFF ON CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-SERMONS;
CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT; CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT;
CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A roundup of editorial comment about President Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   From The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Saturday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   A president more concerned with the national interest than his
own self-preservation would realize that resignation is his only
responsible option.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, Bill Clinton has shown himself incapable of such
sacrifice. He is a complex man with many attractive qualities, but
in the end his character has been defined by his crass selfishness.
It is that trait _ perjury and adultery are merely its symptoms _
that has rendered him unfit to continue as president.
</P>
<P>
   From The Charlotte Observer, Saturday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   The nation is not endangered by having Bill Clinton in the White
House. Our economy is not collapsing, we're not under attack,
there's no threat of a coup. Surely the worst that can be said of
him has been said. He continues to exercise the powers of office,
and did so rather well in Ireland and Russia. There is ample time
for Congress to consider Starr's report and to receive a detailed
reply from Clinton, then decide what course to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Removal of a president from office, by the impeachment process
or by forced resignation, is a grave action. The notion that
presidents should be removed or resign because of public outrage or
unpopularity is foreign to our system.
</P>
<P>
   From The Boston Herald, Saturday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   During ordinary times, in an ordinary election year, Congress
would recess in early October, and that has been the plan this
year. But this is no ordinary time. This report cannot and must not
be allowed to fester away at the conscience of a nation. It must be
dealt with promptly and thoroughly until there is a resolution of
the issues now before Congress.
</P>
<P>
   From The Philadelphia Inquirer, Saturday, Sept. 12:
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton should resign. He should resign because his
repeated, reckless deceits have dishonored his presidency beyond
repair. He should resign because the impeachment anguish that his
lies have invited will paralyze his administration at a time when
an anxious world looks to the White House for sure-footed
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   He should resign because, if he does not, his once-glittering
agenda of centrist change faces a devastating setback in November's
congressional elections, And those results will reflect not the
view of the American majority of the issues _ they are with him
there _ but only a weary, tragic turning away from a politics
turned sordid.
</P>
<P>
   From The Washington Post, Sunday, Sept. 13:
</P>
<P>
   The question that Congress now faces is whether the president's
public conduct warrants impeachment and removal. It is not an easy
question, and it goes to the heart of what does and does not
constitute ``high crimes and misdemeanors.'' On the one hand, the
crimes alleged are serious ones and the evidence on some is quite
strong; on the other hand, this misconduct took place in the
context of a subsequently dismissed civil case and would probably
not, in other circumstances, have been deemed worthy of
investigation or prosecution. Clinton's behavior is at the margins
of impeachability _ straddling the line that separates
disqualifying crimes from conduct that merely mars indelibly the
presidential office and the man who holds it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
