<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TEXAS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S CASE ADDS A GRIM TONE TO DEMOCRATIC CONGRESSMAN'S
`FUNDAY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on the 17th District is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By RICK LYMAN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ERICKSDAHL, Texas _ Chub Richards, whose cotton farm is not far
from the Beth El Lutheran Church picnic grounds where he waited in
line for his shot at the barbecue, fried chicken and football-sized
hunks of watermelon, held out his hand with a wide grin when his
congressman, Charles Stenholm, passed by.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all been having a fun week in Washington?'' Richards
asked.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-term Democratic congressman grimaced. ``Let me put it
this way,'' Stenholm said. ``I'm planning to have fun for the next
two hours.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first Saturday after Labor Day, which, in the 17th
Congressional District of Texas, means that it is time for Funday,
the bash for constituents that Stenholm has been holding every year
since he was elected to Congress in 1978. About 1,000 people turned
up, despite glowering skies.
</P>
<P>
   Coming this year the day after the report by the independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, was made public, it was inevitable that the
trials of Washington would find their way into this shady elm grove
40 miles north of Abilene.
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm said he had heard from a lot of ``frustrated and
irritated'' constituents since he arrived back in the district this
weekend, both at Funday and earlier, at a parade in Abilene. But he
said he had detected little enthusiasm for impeachment, and still
felt that those who wanted the president to resign were in the
minority. The overwhelming sentiment, he said, was for Washington
to find some way to get the mess over with.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are three elements to this,'' Stenholm said. ``The
moral, the political and the legal. On the moral side, there is no
question. What the president has already admitted to is repulsive,
disgusting, all the words that have been used to describe it. That
kind of behavior should not be tolerated.''
</P>
<P>
   But it would be wrong to overlook the political side of the
scandal, he said, because some elements of the Republican Party
hope to use it to cripple the remainder of the president's term,
defeat Democrats in November and spur the election of a Republican
president in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political side of this is going to get meaner and uglier
by the day,'' Stenholm said.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the legal side of the crisis, he said, and that is
where the answer lies. Stenholm said he was convinced by what he
read in the Starr report that there were grounds for asking the
House Judiciary Committee to open investigations this week into the
possible impeachment of the president. He said he would vote for
that but intended to keep an open mind about whether to eventually
vote a bill of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have sworn to uphold the Constitution of the United
States,'' Stenholm said. ``And I believe that no president, no
county judge, no congressman, nobody is above the law. I think most
people just want the legal side to work itself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Richards was sitting on a hay bale, working his way through a
chicken breast, while the Cooper Fiddlers were giving ``Yellow Rose
of Texas'' a pretty good ride from the makeshift stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sad day for the United States,'' Richards said.
``Personally, I think the president should dismiss himself from his
position. I mean he should resign. There is no way he can be
effective anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Norris Lineweaver, a retired postman from Abilene, could not
disagree more.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing is the worst example of negative politics
that I have ever seen, the way the Republicans are handling it,''
Lineweaver said. ``And that report, I couldn't even read it. You
can go to the pornographic place over in Merckel and pick up all of
that stuff you want. You can't defend what Clinton did, but this
whole thing is just a political lynching.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Wills, a financial planner from San Angelo, laughed when
asked whether she had read the Starr report. ``Like, hello?'' she
said. ``Of course, I read every sordid and steamy little detail.''
</P>
<P>
   And? Ms. Wills shrugged. ``It didn't bother me that much,'' she
said. ``I guess I'm just a child of the '60s.''
</P>
<P>
   Stenholm, a fiscal conservative, did not even face Republican
opposition in six elections, from 1980 to 1990. But recent
elections have grown more competitive, and this year, he faces a
rematch with an Abilene dentist and businessman, Rudy Izzard, who
held Stenholm to 52 percent of the vote in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure they're going to try to use the Clinton scandal
against me,'' Stenholm said. ``They'll try to tie me to the
president. That's OK. We'll tie my opponent to Newt Gingrich. Newt
is about as unpopular here as the president is.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
