u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS     09-13 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MOST DEMOCRATS FLEE CLINTON, ONE CONGRESSMAN STAYS PUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on Massachusetts' Third District is being sent to
NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(nk) 
 By SARE RIMER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER, Mass. _ Most Democratic candidates can't do enough to
distance themselves from President Clinton. But not Jim McGovern.
Last month the freshman congressman from Massachusetts made
national headlines _ and took what pundits and his Republican
opponent called a big political risk _ when he welcomed the
president to his hometown just days after his grudging and
ill-received admission of his involvement with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   And out on the campaign trail here Sunday, McGovern was making
no secret of where he had been on Friday night. ``I was at the
White House last night with the president and first lady,'' he told
the small group of voters gathered in a living room in Paxton, a
suburb of this working-class, Democratic stronghold. McGovern said
he had been attending an event honoring the president's efforts in
bringing peace to Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, from a pancake breakfast in Sterling to a
clambake at the East Side Improvement Club here to a barbecue given
by the fire department in suburban Grafton _ home of McGovern's
opponent, state Sen. Matthew Amorello _ McGovern made it clear that
he was disappointed with the president's behavior in the Lewinsky
matter. But that was not what he _ or his constituents, for the
most part _ wanted most to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Notwithstanding the fact that you can't pick up a newspaper
and not read about scandals, there's a lot more to the government
than scandal,'' McGovern, 38, told voters in the living room of
Denis Crowley, a retired soft drink executive. ``Republicans in the
Senate the other day killed campaign finance reform, and yet you'd
need a magnifying glass to find that out. If people want to be
outraged about something, morally indignant about something, they
should be outraged about that.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern got his start in politics 20 years as an intern in the
Washington office of George McGovern (no relation), whose
presidential candidacy carried only one state, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   But not surprisingly, on a day when the Worcester Telegram and
Gazette, like newspapers across the country, had published the
Starr report, the first question for the candidate was not about
Social Security, or Medicare, or home health care, or public
education, or the environment, or any of the other issues McGovern
said he wanted to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   The first question was this: ``Do you think they're going to
impeach him?'' But it was asked with real concern, not the
political speculation and odds-making that fill the television
airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   McGovern answered that he hoped not, but that he would be
surprised if there were not hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Weinstein, a retired social worker and Democrat, wanted
to know what impact the Starr report would have on Democrats in the
coming elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the impact the news media makes you think,'' McGovern
replied. ``If I hear Sam and Cokie tell me one more time, `You're
done,' I'll scream.''
</P>
<P>
   McGovern was referring to Sam Donaldson and Cokie Roberts, the
ABC television commentators, who have been forecasting gloomy odds
for Democrats in the upcoming elections.
</P>
<P>
   The voters along McGovern's route Sunday indicated that they,
too, are fed up with the media. ``The media are definitely blowing
this thing up,'' said Dave Urella, 44, a field engineer for Wang
Laboratories, referring to the Starr report. ``If they decide to
impeach, it's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to follow McGovern around was to experience a disconnect
between the media that is saturated with news of the Starr report,
as well as impeachment, and the citizens. While they expressed
concern about what might happen next, and disappointment, and even
outrage, over Clinton's conduct, most of the voters were hardly
obsessed with the report, or even very focused on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue in America isn't Bill Clinton's sex life,'' said
Chet Jakubiak, 53, a social worker and Democrat. ``It's Social
Security reform, health insurance for the uninsured, job security,
education reform.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Over barbecued chicken in Grafton, Judy Read, 32, a nurse and
registered Independent, expressed similar concerns. ``We have
bombings,'' she said. ``We have terrorism, kids killing each other
in schools, so many other problems. To spend this amount of time on
this is just deplorable.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mrs. Read added: ``I've had it with Bill
Clinton. I'm starting to think he's a pretty sneaky guy.''
</P>
<P>
   No one in the national press paid much attention to McGovern's
race until last month, when Clinton unexpectedly telephoned to ask
if his earlier invitation to visit Worcester still stood, and
McGovern said that it did. The visit was a success, with the
president addressing a packed hall of cheering supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was proud that he came here,'' McGovern said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 1952EDT &QL; 
