</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-WASHINGTON-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SEATTLE`S SUBURBS, FEW CALLS FOR PRESIDENT'S IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs to add art note and reefer note) (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ Perhaps Rep. Rick White's constituents were in
a forgiving mood this weekend because the Seattle area was bathed
in sparkling late-summer sunshine. Maybe it was because much of the
congressman's flesh-pressing on Sunday was done amid jovial fans
assembled at a park-and-ride station for a trip to the Kingdome to
watch the Seahawks, the pro football team whom many Seattleites
believe may actually make the playoffs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reasons, there were strikingly few calls for the
impeachment of President Clinton as White, a Republican running for
re-election, made the rounds of his district, which takes in many
of the northern and eastern suburbs curling around Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's kind of sad what he's done, but it's really none
of our business,'' said Dennis Pappas as he climbed aboard a bus
with his wife, Janice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrong but not impeachable,'' was how Pappas, a 55-year-old
inventory planner for the Boeing Co., summarized the president's
behavior. Added Mrs. Pappas: ``Yes, it's between him and Hillary. I
think the rest of us should get on and get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were far more adamant in their defense of the president.
``The man's done a great job in the office that we elected him
to,'' said Lynann Bradbury, 35, who works for a local
public-relations firm and who said she was angry at Kenneth Starr,
the independent counsel, for releasing such a sexually graphic
report about what she saw as a private encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``My question,'' said Ms. Bradbury, ``is, are we really better
off as a country knowing all this?''
</P>
<P>
   Many people, to be sure, used words like ``sickening,''
``disgusting,'' and ``pathetic'' to describe the president's
relationship with a White House intern, and a few said the proper
moral response was for him to resign. Others said the Congress
should censure the president to register its disapproval, and one
man suggested the president be made to pay a fine since, in his
view, Clinton was unlikely to be swayed by condemnatory words
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's got to be some sanction in some way,'' said the
proponent of the monetary penalty, Randy Harlow, 36, of Seattle.
``If you just allow him to get away scot-free, you're setting a
precedent for years and years to come.''
</P>
<P>
   But pressed on whether the president should be impeached for
what Starr depicts as his perjury over the affair, very few of the
people White encountered on his campaign rounds said yes.
</P>
<P>
   No such crowd is scientifically representative of the population
at large. Still, at the park-and-ride station this morning, a
reporter conducting random interviews for an hour could not find
anyone favoring impeachment until, at last, he called out to the
crowd, specifically seeking those who favored the action. Then
there were takers, but not a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely, impeach him,'' volunteered Michael Wallace, 41, a
mail clerk for a Seattle bank, weighted down with Seahawks
paraphernalia. ``For what he did, for how he lied about, for how
he's really not at all contrite, and for a lot of other things too.
I say get rid of him.''
</P>
<P>
   White, one of six Republicans elected to Congress from
Washington state in the party's takeover surge in 1994, said that
few people had specifically brought up the Clinton matter with him
as he approached them to ask for their vote in Tuesday's primary
and to see what was on their minds.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the view of the congressman, who said he had not made up
his mind on whether the House should vote for impeachment, this did
not mean that people weren't deeply bothered by the accusations
against the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people would really prefer it went away, but I think
they know it really can't, and I think we all feel about the same
way,'' said White. ``These are very serious allegations. Even the
president admits his behavior was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   White's district is not viewed as safe for either party _ in
fact, it is chiefly known as a tough one for incumbents to hang
onto. He is in a tough re-election fight against a former
Democratic congressman, Jay Inslee, who lost his seat in another
Washington district in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But while the congressman says he is undergoing a sort of
``osmosis'' to ascertain how people in his district feel about
moves such as censure or impeachment, it seemed clear on Sunday
that many people wished for other options as they mulled over the
president's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should consider resigning, but the thing that
really bother me is that he obviously has no intention of that, it
hasn't even crossed his mind,'' said Richard Jayne, an insurance
broker headed off for the game with his sons, Richie and David.
</P>
<P>
   But even Jayne, a confirmed Clinton critic, said he wasn't sure
about impeachment. He said he was bothered that prosecutors had not
yet assembled a case about ``Whitewater, the China campaign stuff,
Filegate'' and other matters he considered more important than the
president's affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Many people just seemed downright blase about the whole matter.
``Look, it was a stupid thing,'' Janice McCall, who sells
advertising for the local Yellow Pages, said of the president's
trysts. ``But men have been doing it for millions of years. Women,
too for that matter.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
