u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PORTRAIT-2TAK     09-13 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PORTRAIT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR REPORT DEPICTS CLINTON AS COMPLEX AND MANY-SIDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT;
CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN.)  
(js) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the pages of the Starr report, the many faces of Bill
Clinton shine in succession.
</P>
<P>
   There is the mental facility that lets the president finish
crossword puzzles in ink in minutes and, Monica Lewinsky says,
enabled him to recite her telephone numbers from memory after a few
encounters. There is the seductive charm that has melted supporters
for three decades and led him to ply Ms. Lewinsky with ``Leaves of
Grass.'' And there is the casual exploitation of subordinates that
has left his presidency littered with old friends before grand
juries or in jail and turned his loyal secretary, Betty Currie,
into a surreptitious accomplice, spiriting Ms. Lewinsky into
meetings behind the backs of disapproving colleagues and keeping
her phone calls secret.
</P>
<P>
   There is the uncanny blend of self-destructive behavior and
self-preserving instincts that led him to embark on an illicit
affair with Ms. Lewinsky, then an intern, and then custom-tailor
alibis to convince his senior aides that he had not. There is the
needy streak that makes Clinton assume the pose of perpetual victim
of actions by others and made him, Ms. Lewinsky says, bemoan her
transfer from the White House by complaining: ``Why do they have to
take you away from me?''
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, there is Clinton's own propensity for shaving the
English language as fine as a Tuscan truffle. All the president's
past parsings of the truth, from the draft and military service, to
``I didn't inhale,'' at once presage _ and yet pale beside _ his
sworn contention to a grand jury that ``most ordinary Americans''
would subscribe to his view that there can be no sexual
relationship without sexual intercourse, regardless of what other
sexual activities occur.
</P>
<P>
   More than perhaps any sitting president in history, Bill Clinton
has already been psychoanalyzed, fictionalized and vivisected in a
score of serious books and a best-selling novel that chronicled his
outsized talents and his outsized flaws. When even a president's
underwear preferences are known, what else can be left to tell? A
lot, and very little, as it turns out.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, long after the thrill of their relationship had
subsided into mutual recriminations and the fear of disclosure and
discovery, the president telephoned Ms. Lewinsky in the middle of
the night and told her tersely: ``If I'd known what kind of a
person you really were, I wouldn't have gotten involved with you,''
Ms. Lewinsky told investigators, adding that the president ``got so
mad at me, he must have been purple.''
</P>
<P>
   That short passage in Kenneth Starr's voluminous report rings
with unintended overtones, for in all the report's seamy reams of
largely uncontested specifics about sexual encounters, its
unchallenged testimony by senior White House aides and its
unsparing recitation of the president's own sworn struggles with
the truth, it paints a devastating _ but not particularly
surprising _ portrait of Bill Clinton's darker side.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers have dismissed the report as a
``hit-and-run smear campaign,'' arguing that the offenses it lists
are personal, and Congress and the public may well decide that its
selective bill of particulars does not rise to the level of
impeachable offenses. But no one who has much firsthand experience
with Clinton could profess shock at the report's accumulated
detail, because it is replete with all-too-familiar examples of the
character traits and personal failings that have dogged this
president throughout his public life.
</P>
<P>
   In Bill Clinton's first campaign for office, in the Watergate
summer of 1974, and in his last in 1996, his aides had a flip
nickname for him that summed up his unruly, undisciplined ways:
``The Boy.'' In page after page of the Starr report, the president
of the United States is portrayed as the ward of his own worried
aides, from Evelyn Lieberman, the former deputy chief of staff who
moved Ms. Lewinsky out of the White House in 1996 because she was
spending too much time around the president, to the president's own
personal aide, Stephen Goodin, the earnest Generation Xer who
fretted that the president should not be alone with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has always been a man who wants all things, all the
time. At a White House lunch with the network news anchors early in
his first term, guests were offered a choice of chicken, fish or
meat, and the president had a bit of each. In the Starr report, and
his own rebuttals, Clinton at once insists he gravely erred in an
``inappropriate sexual relationship'' with Ms. Lewinsky, and that
his answers were ``legally accurate'' when he denied having any
``sexual relationship'' with Ms. Lewinsky in his deposition in the
Paula Jones lawsuit last January.
</P>
<P>
   The president's contention stems from his assertion that he was
no more than a passive recipient of oral sex from Ms. Lewinsky _ an
assertion that she contradicts in embarrassing detail. But the
Starr report makes clear just how thoroughly Clinton withheld even
this couched admission from his own senior aides when reports of
the relationship became public last January.
</P>
<P>
   And, as he always does, Clinton chose his words to fit his
listeners, a trait often cited in describing a man whose great
strength and weakness has been his powerful and often successful
urge to be all things to all people. His Deputy Chief of Staff John
Podesta, a lawyer with a cool eye for potential loopholes,
testified that Clinton was ``extremely explicit'' in insisting then
that he had never had even oral sex with Ms. Lewinsky. A
presidential aide, Sidney Blumenthal, a former journalist who has
discerned evidence of right-wing conspiracies against the
president, testified that Clinton claimed that he had rebuffed a
``sexual demand'' from Ms. Lewinsky and felt like a character in
the novel, ``Darkness at Noon.''
</P>
<P>
   In his grand jury testimony, Clinton flatly acknowledged being
alone with Ms. Lewinsky, but at another point, he also said,
``There were a lot of times when we were alone, but I never really
thought we were.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been Clinton's nearly unvarying pattern to make missteps
not when he is under fire, but when he is overconfident. He
followed up his 1993 victories on the budget and the North American
Free Trade Agreement with his disastrous overreach on health care
restructuring in 1994. He began his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
not in the depths of his despair after the 1994 midterm elections
but at the beginning of his comeback, in the government shutdown in
November 1995 when he was finally beginning to put the Republicans
on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   And for a president often accused of running the West Wing like
a college pizza party in his first term, the relationship with the
intern began in a poetically appropriate way: Ms. Lewinsky
testified that they had their second sexual encounter when she took
him pizza in the midst of the shutdown, when salaried workers were
told to stay away from the White House and interns took over many
tasks.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
