<SLUG> BC-NORTHWEST-STRIKE-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PILOTS SETTLE BUT NORTHWEST'S LABOR ILLS CONTINUE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Minn., Tenn.)  (mk) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Idled employees at Northwest Airlines began returning to work
Sunday, a day after striking pilots ratified a new four-year
contract that ended the longest walkout against a major airline in
a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the 17-member Master Executive Council of the Air
Line Pilots Association approved the new contract late Saturday,
Northwest began recalling the 31,000 workers laid off during the
two-week strike, which virtually eliminated air traffic in parts of
the Midwest and South.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the airline, which is the country's fourth-largest, said
it would not be ready to resume flights until Wednesday and would
not have all its 1,700 daily flights back in the air until next
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Though the strike is over, Northwest's labor problems are not.
The airline is negotiating contracts with five other unions,
including the International Association of Machinists, which
represents 27,000 Northwest workers, and the International
Brotherhood of Teamsters, which represents the carrier's 11,000
flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual display of unity for the airline industry, all
five unions strongly backed the pilots during the strike, and the
pilots say they plan to return the favor.
</P>
<P>
   After declaring the strike officially ended on Saturday, Steve
Zoller, chairman of the pilots' executive council, said, ``I want
to remind Northwest management that there are five other unions at
Northwest, and the job isn't done until all of us have new
contracts.''
</P>
<P>
   Such unity could prove costly for the airline. Like the pilots,
the other unions believe they are owed a substantial pay increase
to make up for the wage concessions they made in 1993 to help
Northwest avert bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the unions are every bit as passionate as the
pilots are about their pensions, their health benefits and their
job security,'' said Sid Rhinehart, public affairs chairman of
local 543 of the Transport Workers union, which represents 170
Northwest flight dispatchers and operations planners.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots and Northwest had been negotiating for two years
before the walkout on Aug. 29, and there was deep mistrust on both
sides. Virtually no progress was made toward a settlement for 11
days until Bruce Lindsey, one of President Clinton's most trusted
aides, joined the negotiations last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey used the prospect of presidential intervention to
pressure both sides to compromise, said a person involved in the
negotiations who spoke only on the condition of anonymity. When the
talks bogged down early Thursday, Lindsey made it clear to the
pilots that the president would order them back to work that day if
they did not reach a deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides had shaken hands but were still arguing over
whether to call their agreement a tentative contract when Clinton
trumped them by announcing the agreement on national television,
the person involved in negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots were seeking a 14 percent pay increase over three
years, a one-time payment of $86 million to make up for lost wages,
limits on how many regional jets Northwest could add to its fleet
and the phasing out of a two-tier wage scale, which pays junior
pilots a lower salary in their first five years.
</P>
<P>
   In its last offer before the strike, Northwest offered a 9
percent increase over four years, a $57 million payment, profit
sharing and a reduction of the two-tier wage scale to three years.
</P>
<P>
   The final settlement includes a 12 percent pay raise for the
pilots over four years, a lump sum of $57 million, more generous
profit sharing, 2.5 million stock options for the pilots and the
phasing out of the two-tier wage scale. The deal also links the
addition of regional jets in Northwest's fleet directly to the
expansion of the number of larger jets.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts were divided over who got the better deal.
``The kind of pressure that was put on by the White House probably
gave labor slightly more leverage than management,'' said Thomas
Schreier, an airline industry analyst at Credit Suisse First
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But Samuel Buttrick, an analyst with Paine Webber, said in a
note to investors on Friday that management came out on top because
the threat of presidential intervention forced the pilots to relax
their demands.
</P>
<P>
   The strike will take a large financial toll on the airline.
Estimates of its costs range from $275 million to $400 million, not
counting the substantial cost of restarting the carrier. One
Northwest executive put the total at $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   The carrier said on Friday that it expected to lose money this
quarter and next, its first quarterly losses in five years. It also
faces continuing weakness in Asia, which accounts for 30 percent of
its revenues, more than any other domestic carrier.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, experts said that it would not be too
difficult for Northwest to win back its customers because it has a
virtual monopoly at the main airports in Detroit, Minneapolis and
Memphis. Once the airline is back to its full schedule, analysts
said, travelers in those regions will once again have little choice
but to fly Northwest.
</P>
</TEXT>
