<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2788 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-CHANGE-ART-2     09-13 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-CHANGE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRELAND'S `EL PASO' RENOUNCES ITS PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUNDALK, Ireland _ This town 13 miles from the border with
Northern Ireland once harbored so many Irish Republican Army safe
houses, underground weapons networks and gunmen on the run that
police called it ``El Paso.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People here were very resentful of that name,'' said Kevin
Mulligan, 55, editor of the weekly Argus, ``but with time they came
to realize it wasn't too far off the mark.'' Out of a mixture of
sympathy for the plight of Catholics in the North and fear of
reprisals from vengeful local IRA men, Dundalk residents kept any
misgivings to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   When the town of Omagh was bombed on Aug. 15, killing 29 people
in the most deadly single attack of Northern Ireland's three
decades of violence, police suspected guerrillas based here, and
the residents found themselves newly stigmatized. This time they
spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're saying, and saying very strongly, is that there is
no hiding place for terrorists in this town,'' said John Woods, 57,
a Dundalk lawyer who with Mulligan and four downtown businessmen
organized a protest rally in the courthouse square. By police
count, 15,000 people showed up _ half the town's population.
</P>
<P>
   The most overused symbol in the stubbornly confrontational
politics of Northern Ireland is the line in the sand, but Dundalk,
the one-time refuge of the men of violence, may have really drawn
one. ``We are saying that this is not a part of us _ people who do
these things do not represent our community,'' said Brian O'Neill,
55, owner of a century-old family hardware business.
</P>
<P>
   Dundalk's defiant rejection of its past association with
bloodshed is being cited as an emblem of what is happening
throughout the Irish island. ``I'd be an optimistic sort of person
to begin with,'' said Woods, ``but Ireland is now united as never
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Optimism is a sudden newcomer in the North, but it is getting a
warm welcome. People are daring to put their frequently battered
faith in a political solution to the tribal conflict that has cost
more than 3,200 lives. And there are convincing signs of
cooperation in Belfast between leaders of the Catholic and
Protestant communities who have battled and shunned one another for
generations.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams, president of Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing,
and David Trimble, leader of the Ulster Unionist Party and first
minister of the new Northern Ireland Assembly, held a face-to-face
meeting last week, the first time that leaders of the two
traditions had done so in more than 75 years.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday in Belfast, the Northern Ireland Assembly will sit for
the first time, a major step in the fulfillment of the Northern
Ireland peace settlement. Structured under a power-sharing formula,
the legislature was created by the accord negotiated over a
26-month period and concluded on Good Friday, April 10.
</P>
<P>
   Dundalk is a bustling provincial town with storefronts in lively
colors and corner pubs that ring with hearty sounds of blarney.
People driving along congested Clanbrassil Street trade friendly
banter with passers-by. Towns in the North bear legends and murals
celebrating heroes of the sectarian struggle, but the banners here
say only, ``Dundalk celebrates 40 years of tidy towns _ beauty dies
where litter lies.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a center for brewing, shoe manufacturing and building
railway rolling stock, Dundalk has shared in Ireland's new
prosperity with multinational firms like Xerox and Panasonic
locating factories here.
</P>
<P>
   Dundalk was brutally reminded of its old role in the Northern
Ireland struggle by the Omagh killings, though, when responsibility
for the bombing was claimed by renegade republican paramilitaries
called the Real IRA, organized out of here. ``Here we go again,''
O'Neill remembers thinking along with his shock and revulsion.
``Everyone's going to blame Dundalk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Real IRA, made up of former members of the IRA unhappy with
its cease-fire, viewed the peace settlement as a sellout of
republican ideals and set out to undermine it with violence.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials have identified its military leader as Michael
McKevitt, 49, a Dundalk man who once was the quartermaster general
in charge of the IRA's vast arsenal. The vice chairman of the
group's political arm, the 32-County Sovereignty Committee, is his
common-law wife, Bernadette Sands-McKevitt, 40, the sister of Bobby
Sands, a republican martyr who died in a prison hunger strike that
drew international attention.
</P>
<P>
   The McKevitts live in Blackrock, three miles out of town on
Dundalk Bay, and they run The Print Junction, a photocopying,
picture framing and souvenir shop downtown. In the days following
the bombing, people tacked protest notes onto the store door and
stood in vigil outside.
</P>
<P>
   The couple complained to a local priest that they were being
harassed and that they feared for the safety of their three
children. They have not been spotted here for the past three weeks,
and the store is shuttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right after Omagh I was listening to one of these talk
shows,'' Mulligan said, ``and people were calling in and saying,
`We should burn the McKevitts out of their house, ostracize their
children, make a point of getting up and leaving any restaurant
they walk into.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was just that kind of behavior that placed Dundalk in the
center of the struggle with the upsurge in sectarian violence in
1969. Thousands of Catholics fled Belfast to escape Protestant
firebombings and shootings, and Dundalk took them in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were strongly sympathetic; they came down in trainloads and
we literally opened our homes to them,'' recalled Mulligan. Many of
the refugees settled in the Muirhevna Mor housing project, which is
still known as Little Belfast.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then later the IRA started to use Dundalk as a base, and
they spread the violence to the south and over the past 15 years
turned to gangsterism and rackets,'' complained Mulligan.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Eamon Collins, a former IRA gunman and author of ``Killing
Rage,'' a book detailing his disillusionment with the organization,
said that Dundalk was central to the campaign of violence in the
North. ``It was a route for moving a lot of weaponry, and it was
where lots of people could rest up when they were on the run,'' he
said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   Some 300 roads and pathways crisscross the border, which winds
through the woods, pastureland and mist-shrouded hillsides of
County Louth, and there is no way to patrol it effectively. The
farmlands of the nearby Cooley Peninsula became a favorite place
for hiding IRA arms, and the organization's zealousness to protect
its weapons led to a crime that caused widespread revulsion with
the IRA here.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 Tom Oliver, a farmer who lived with his wife and seven
young children outside the town of Carlingford, reported to police
that he had stumbled upon a cache on his property. Calling him an
informer, the IRA abducted him, tortured him and shot him dead.
</P>
<P>
   Intimidation was strongest in the politicized housing projects.
Paul O'Brennan, a 57-year-old London office worker who fled his
home in Dundalk in 1974, said he did so to remove his four sons
from IRA influence. ``It was all around, in every pub and club, and
I didn't want them getting into that stuff,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the middle class, it was less apparent. ``I knew it was
going on, but did someone say, `Joe Bloggs there is a gunman ?'
Never,'' said O'Neill. Mulligan recalled only getting ``the odd
threat'' for something he put in his paper.
</P>
<P>
   Donal Dullaghan, 44, a community worker at the Muirhevna Mor
project, said, ``Before the bombing it was just something we always
accepted. I don't know why we accepted it, but we did. They didn't
wear berets or badges, but we knew who they were.''
</P>
<P>
   The mourners for the dead of Omagh who marched in protest
through the streets of Dundalk a week later filled three condolence
books in the town hall lobby. Many messages spoke to the special
sense of sorrow and responsibility felt here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am ashamed to be living in Dundalk,'' wrote James Miller.
``I do not want a 32-county Ireland. I want a peaceful one for my
children to grow up in.''
</P>
<P>
   In the May referendum on the peace agreement, 95 percent of the
votes in the Little Belfast housing project were for approval, a
telling sign of the community's rejection of violence. ``The whole
republican family is for peace,'' said Liam Adams, 43, chairman of
the community council. Adams, the brother of Gerry Adams, came to
Dundalk 10 years ago, the only one of the ten Adams siblings to
have left Northern Ireland for the south. ``I didn't want my
children to grow up the way I had to grow up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 1, senior members of the IRA visited the homes of
members of the Real IRA and its political committee and told them
to disband or face punishment. A week later, the seven-man military
council of the Real IRA met at an undisclosed spot near Dundalk and
declared its own cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   Collins, the former IRA regular, said it was encouraging to see
the people of Dundalk speaking out and paramilitary groups
forswearing bloodshed, but he added a cautionary note. ``People who
think that physical force republicanism is over don't know their
history,'' he warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
