<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Champagne still on ice in Atlanta as Marlins win 6-5
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ They lost the lead, lost the game, lost the chance to
clinch the division, all of which turned a champagne Sunday
afternoon to vinegar. But the Braves lost Greg Maddux too.
September, in the pain.
</P>
<P>
   The worst team in baseball, Florida's Marlins scored six times
in the last three innings off rookie relievers Odalis Perez and
Adam Butler and then weathered a furious comeback to beat the
Braves 6-5, averting a three-game sweep and leaving Atlanta's magic
number at one. This is miscellany compared to the sixth inning,
when Maddux, guarding a 1-0 lead, went back to the dugout to report
a muscle strain under his right arm pit was beginning to worry him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's important at this time of year to look a little ahead,''
said Maddux, who came out after throwing 83 pitches and extending a
string of scoreless innings to 10. ''It might not have be best
thing (to come out) today but I'd be surprised if it doesn't turn
out to be the best thing two or three weeks from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddux did not think the strain would cost him a start, though
he would not rule it out. His shot at his 18th win immediately fell
apart, after Perez allowed four straight hits to the first four
batters he faced in the seventh, including a two-run double by
Derek Lee and an ensuing two-run homer by Kevin Orie. The Marlins
then went out 6-2 in the eighth with two more runs without
recording a hit after Butler hit Todd Dunwoody, walked Edgar
Renteria and then threw Mark Kotsay's sacrifice bunt down the right
field line.
</P>
<P>
   With New York's 1-0 victory in Montreal, Atlanta cannot clinch
their seventh straight divisional title until tonight, when the
Philadelphia Phillies open a three-game series at Turner Field.
Though the champagne was chilled in a clubhouse back closet, the
Mets' victory was hardly acknowledged after assistant general
manager Dean Taylor confirmed it with a score pager.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you would have seen too much of a celebration,''
said Chipper Jones. ''We're on the verge of going on a nice little
streak here and all of a sudden, you get smacked in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams hit his third homer in three games in the fourth
and Andruw Jones hit his 30th in the seven, making the Braves the
sixth team in major league history with four players reaching 30 or
more. In the eighth, they strung together three hits and a walk to
score three and close to within one. But with the tying run at
third, Tony Graffanino struck out against Vic Darensbourg to end
the comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Mired in a 5-7 September, having just gone 3-3 against the dregs
of the NL East, the Braves seemed to have lost any sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I still believe we got the best team,'' said Andres Galarraga.
''I don't care what anybody thinks. It doesn't matter if we play at
home or on the the road or play against anybody. Let's get this
over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
