</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ONDECK14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves on deck: Philadelphia Phillies
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   _ When: Tonight and Tuesday at 7:40, Wednesday at 1:10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   _ Where: Turner Field
</P>
<P>
   _ TV: TBS will televise tonight and Tuesday. Fox Sports South
will televise Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Probable starting pitchers: Tonight, LHP Tom Glavine (18-6,
2.62; 16-6, 3.42 lifetime vs. Phillies) vs. RHP Curt Schilling
(14-13, 3.25; 5-7, 4.08 lifetime vs. Braves). Tuesday, RHP Kevin
Millwood (15-8, 4.34; 3-0, 2.06 lifetime vs. Phillies) vs. RHP
Tyler Green (6-10, 4.79; 3-1, 3.24 lifetime vs. Braves). Wednesday,
RHP John Smoltz (15-3, 3.10; 10-7, 3.74 lifetime vs. Phillies) vs.
RHP Carlton Loewer (6-7, 6.06; 0-1, 63.00 lifetime vs. Braves).
</P>
<P>
   _ Series history: Atlanta leads the all-time series 224-183 and
is 25-8 against the Phillies the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   _ Past meetings: The Braves are 6-3 with Philadelphia this
season, last seeing the Phillies July 22-23 and sweeping a two-game
series at Veterans Stadium. Andres Galarraga had a two-homer game
July 22 and Kevin Millwood held the Phils to two runs over seven
innings to win the second game 3-2. Atlanta hasn't lost a season
series to the Phils since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phillies leaders: Avg. _ Kevin Sefcik (.319); HR _ Scott Rolen
(28); RBI _ Rolen (104); SB _ Doug Glaville (23). W _ Curt
Schilling (14); ERA _ Paul Byrd (2.84). Saves _ Mark Leiter (23).
Strikeouts _ Schilling (272).
</P>
<P>
   _ Quickly: The Phillies just took two of three from Pittsburgh
over the weekend, winning the first series in their last nine
chances dating back to Arizona Aug. 20-21. Philadelphia has not
taken a series against a winning team since taking three of four
from Boston June 22-25. . . . The Phillies are 4-6 this month and
27-37 in the second half. . . . No team has given up more homers
than the Phillies' 179, 62 more than the Braves staff. Philadelphia
also lead the NL in wild pitches (57) and rank in the bottom three
in four other pitching catagories. . . . The team would be nowhere
without 3B Scott Rolen and CF Doug Glanville. Rolen has scored 106
runs while driving in 104 while Glanville ranks in the league's top
10 in hits and multi-hit games. With both over the 100-run mark,
the Phillies have two right-handed hitters reaching the century
mark for the first time since 1932 (Dick Bartell and George Davis).
. . . Bobby Abreu is hitting .444 with runners in scoring position,
best in the NL with at least 80 at-bats. . . . The Braves saw
enough of Schilling in the first two weeks to last a season. In
back-to-back starts April 5 and 10, Schilling beat the Braves
twice, allowing seven hits and one earned run while striking out 25
in 18 innings. . . . On the DL: RHP Matt Beech (sprained right
elbow ligament), RHP Billy Brewer (right elbow surgery), and RHP
Ron Blazier (elbow surgery).
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's hot: Scott Rolen has 21 RBI in his last 21 games.
Wendell McGee, called up from Class AAA Scranton/Wilkes-Barre on
Aug. 29, has hit .375 since then.
</P>
<P>
   _ Who's not: Through July 10, Desi Relaford was batting .305.
Since then, he is 30-for-194 (.155). Bobby Estalella is batting
.135 with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
