<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Inside college football: Dreams turn into nightmares for FSU,
Michigan, Irish
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So where do we go from here?
</P>
<P>
   That's the question a number of football teams are asking
themselves this morning as they try to pick up the pieces of a
shattered weekend. These are just a few of the top programs that
may have seen national championship hopes end on the second
Saturday in September:
</P>
<P>
   _ Florida State: The Seminoles had the team and the schedule to
go undefeated but inexplicably Chris Weinke threw six interceptions
on Saturday and FSU lost to N.C. State for only its second ACC loss
ever. Suddenly, the Seminoles look human with teams like Southern
California, Virginia, Miami and Florida still on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arizona State: The Sun Devils were a darkhorse national
championship contender because they didn't have to play UCLA in the
Pac-10. After losing in the final seconds to Washington two weeks
ago, Arizona State is now 0-2 after losing to BYU 26-6 late
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michigan: With nine starters returning from the nation's No. 1
defense, the defending AP national champions were primed to make
another run. But the Wolverines looked uninspired and poorly
coached in a 38-28 loss to Syracuse. Now they are 0-2 and the Big
Ten schedule has yet to begin.
</P>
<P>
   _ Notre Dame: The Irish thought they had turned the corner back
to greatness after beating Michigan in the opener. Old coach Lou
Holtz starts talking Fiesta Bowl for the Irish.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   All of those warm and fuzzy feeling were undone late Saturday
night as Notre Dame was embarrassed at Michigan State 45-23.
</P>
<P>
   One unhappy coach
</P>
<P>
   Under Steve Spurrier, Florida has usually made its best
improvement each season from its first game to its second. Spurrier
was less than happy after Saturday night's 42-10 win over Northeast
Louisiana which included five Gator turnovers -- two interceptions,
three fumbles -- all in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Spurrier knows that turnovers have been the difference in the
last five wins over Tennessee, which the Gators play Saturday night
Knoxville (8 p.m., CBS).
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't seem to be very smart right now,'' said
Spurrier. ``What is scary is the teams we are going to start
playing now, we are not all that much better talent-wise. If we
don't get a lot smarter and play within the rules and play like we
know what is going on out there, we could be in dire straits.''
</P>
<P>
   Heisman update
</P>
<P>
   _ Tim Couch, Kentucky: 32 of 41, 372 yards, 5 TDs against
Eastern Kentucky. Through two games, Couch has 870 yards and 12
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Shaun Alexander, Alabama: 206 yards and three touchdowns
against Vanderbilt. In two games, Alexander has 321 yards and eight
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cade McNown, UCLA: 20 of 30 passes for 339 yards and three
touchdowns against Texas. He has passed for more than 200 yards in
16 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   _ Daunte Culpepper, Central Florida: Threw for 406 yards and
four touchdowns in a rout of Eastern Illinois. He also ran for
three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ricky Williams, Texas: 29 carries for 160 yards in the loss to
UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   _ Donovan McNabb, Syracuse: Completed 21 of 27 passes for 233
yards as the Orangemen stunned Michigan. McNabb has completed 43 of
55 passes (78.2 percent) in his first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Widenhofer at TD Club
</P>
<P>
   Vanderbilt coach Woody Widenhofer will be the featured speaker
at today's first meeting of the Atlanta Touchdown Club at the Cobb
Galleria Centre. Lunch will begin at noon. Tickets for the event
may be purchased at the door. For more information, call (770)
953-3200.
</P>
<P>
   SEC climbing polls
</P>
<P>
   Six SEC teams are ranked in the new Associated Press Top 25.
Four (Florida, Tennessee, LSU, Georgia) in the Top 12. Alabama and
Mississippi State cracked the rankings for the first time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
