</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCON14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons come from behind to defeat Eagles 17-12
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There might be a temptation to refer to the Atlanta
Falcons' 17-12 victory against Philadelphia as a wakeup call, a
reminder that this team is not ready to hit the cruise-control
button.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cruise control.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were pushed all over the field for two quarters on
Sunday at the Georgia Dome by a team that lost 38-0 at home last
week to Seattle. Atlanta trailed 9-0 at halftime, and it could have
been worse. Philadelphia missed a 45-yard field goal attempt and
had a touchdown negated by penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was working early for Atlanta. The Eagles outgained the
Falcons 208-63 in the first half, prompting Atlanta coach Dan
Reeves to play shrink in the locker room. That's a nice way of
describing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach chewed us out pretty good,'' defensive end Lester
Archambeau said. ``He said they got on us and were kicking out
butt.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no mistake in the analysis, just shock.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons were varied, ranging from a lack of emotion and
energy on the Falcons' side to perhaps a stale gameplan. Both
fueled the Eagles' fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Falcons record improved to 2-0 for the first
time since 1986 because they scored touchdowns on their first two
drives of the second half. The first score came on a 19-yard pass
pass from Chris Chandler to Brian Kozlowski, marking the 14th
straight game in which Chandler passed for a touchdown and tying
the franchise record with Steve Bartkowski and Chris Miller.
</P>
<P>
   It also helped ease the memory of Chandler's uneven first half,
in which he completed 6-of-15 passes, and threw several errant
passes.
</P>
<P>
   The second touchdown came on a 1-yard run by Jamal Anderson. The
key play in the seven-play, 46-yard drive was a roughing the passer
penalty against Philadelphia's Matt Stevens, who apparently went
for Chandler's head during the sack attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was not in the mood to turn down gifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came out in the first half, and they totally dominated the
football game and the tempo,'' Falcons coach Dan Reeves said. ``You
really worry about (players taking the Eagles too lightly). We
talked about it in every single meeting we had. It's just hard for
them to get the message.''
</P>
<P>
   They got it in time, though, and Reeves wasn't the only one
delivering it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just looked each other in the eye, and we knew we were
giving them too much,'' Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan said. ``Me,
(defensive end) Chuck Smith, we were getting on ourselves, each
other. We were saying . . . let's play like we should. We had so
many missed tackles.''
</P>
<P>
   Missed tackles were tangible evidence. But there also was the
mystery of why Atlanta wasn't challenging rookie Eagles cornerbacks
Allen Rossum and Al Harris. Atlanta wide receivers caught just two
passes in the first half for 22 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were expecting two-deep coverage (zone) in the first half
(to protect the rookie corners), and they didn't (do it),'' said
wide receiver Terance Mathis, who finished with three catches for
24 yards. ``So we made the adjustment at halftime and started
throwing the ball downfield.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case at Carolina last week, the Falcons put this one
away in the second half by cranking up a running game that was
nearly dormant in the first half. Rookie cornerback Elijah
Williams' last-minute conversion to running back didn't help. He
had two carries for minus-two yards. ``The defensive speed is a lot
faster in the NFL, than I remember in college,'' said Williams, who
last played running back at Florida in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But Anderson managed 58 of his 74 yards in the second half, and
Atlanta had a huge time-of-possession edge, 19:03-10:57.
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons enter their bye week before a Sept. 27 game at
San Francisco, there are concerns. Chandler was sacked three more
times by a team that had none last week. Meanwhile, the Falcons had
two sacks in the second half, but the starting defensive line has
one in two games.
</P>
<P>
   Strongside linebacker Henri Crockett dislocated his left wrist
on the second play, and will be out six to eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After the way this one started, though, when the Eagles took the
opening possession 79 yards on 13 plays in 7:14 and after Atlanta
managed just 16 yards in the first quarter, things could have been
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played nearly as well as we're capable,'' said
Reevens, whose team has won eight of 10.
</P>
<P>
   But all is not lost.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The comeback) shows me so much character,'' said Buchanan.
``We didn't play the way we were supposed to, but we ended up
winning. That's what matters. Find a way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
