<HEADER>
A2797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CURRIE-2TAKES     09-13 0886
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CURRIE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR REPORT SAYS PRESIDENT'S SECRETARY FACILITATED TRYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ She was presented to the world by President Clinton
as the family ``role model'' of the White House, the upright,
churchgoing presidential secretary whose fear-stricken appearance
before a grand jury in January generated several days of needed
sympathy for an administration under siege.
</P>
<P>
   But Betty Currie, who has presided at the gate of the Oval
Office for the last five years, played a far less savory role for
the president beginning in 1995, according to the report released
on Friday by Whitewater independent counsel Kenneth Starr. After
Clinton and Monica Lewinsky began their affair, Mrs. Currie
facilitated their clandestine meetings and often helped Ms.
Lewinsky bypass the system designed to note all presidential
visitors, the report says.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie even came into the White House on her days off for
the sole purpose of admitting Ms. Lewinsky to Oval Office meetings
alone with the president, according to sworn testimony from both
Mrs. Currie and Ms. Lewinsky. She allowed herself to be used as the
cover story for visits by Ms. Lewinsky, who would falsely tell
security guards that she was at the White House to see the
president's private secretary.
</P>
<P>
   She even had a code name, Kay, that she would use when sending
messages to and from Ms. Lewinsky, including several occasions when
she frantically paged Ms. Lewinsky to discuss Starr's
investigation, apparently at the president's request.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie told the grand jury that she suspected something
improper was occurring between the president and the former intern.
But the portrait that emerges from Starr's report, based on several
days of testimony from Mrs. Currie and Ms. Lewinsky, is one of a
close aide who almost certainly knew what was happening behind the
slightly open door of the president's private study. She testified
that she knew most of the meetings between the two were personal
rather than business-related, and at one point told Ms. Lewinsky
not to tell her any further details.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't want to hear it,'' she said, after Ms. Lewinsky tried to
persuade her that nothing really happened if no one saw the
encounters. ``Don't say any more. I don't want to hear any more.''
</P>
<P>
   Her thoughts about the relationship, as told to the grand jury,
were a curious mixture of elaborate justification and fear of the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was spending a lot of time with a 24-year-old young lady,''
she said. ``I know he has said that young people keep him involved
in what's happening in the world, so I knew that was one reason,
but there was a concern of mine that she was spending more time
than most.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie's attorney, Lawrence Wechsler, could not be reached
for comment over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It had already been known that Mrs. Currie played an important
role in the drama by retrieving several gifts that Clinton had
given Ms. Lewinsky, an action that prosecutors charge was performed
at the president's behest and constituted obstruction of justice.
(Mrs. Currie testified that it might have been Ms. Lewinsky who
asked her to pick up the gifts, which she hid under her bed until
prosecutors demanded them.) But the degree to which she made the
liaisons possible was one of the most surprising revelations in the
Starr report, shedding a remarkable light on the nature of human
traffic in the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie's stature at the White House was such that with her
permission, Ms. Lewinsky could come and go freely into the Oval
Office, even though Ms. Lewinsky's position would not normally
allow her any access to the famous seat of power that has become an
international symbol of presidential authority. Secret Service
agents noted Ms. Lewinsky's regular presence with annoyance, but
told the grand jury that they were obliged to admit her at Mrs.
Currie's instruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know who it is,'' Mrs. Currie would tell the officer in
the West Wing lobby when Ms. Lewinsky was on her way over. Several
agents also said Mrs. Currie tried to persuade them to admit Ms.
Lewinsky without making a log entry of her visit.
</P>
<P>
   After higher-ranking administration employees grew suspicious of
Ms. Lewinsky's frequent visits, Mrs. Currie testified, she would
often lead Ms. Lewinsky to the Oval Office by a back route. On
weekends and at night, when other employees were not present,
``there would be no need to sneak,'' Mrs. Currie said, and so she
allowed Ms. Lewinsky to wait for the president in her own outer
office.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Ms. Lewinsky said, she asked the president why he
didn't clear her into the White House himself instead of using Mrs.
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said because if someone comes to see him, there's a list
circulated among the staff members and then everyone would be
questioning why I was there to see him,'' she testified.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report says that Mrs. Currie deliberately avoided
writing down or retaining most of the messages that Ms. Lewinsky
left for the president _ a violation of standard procedure at the
White House _ and that she would often place the president's calls
to Ms. Lewinsky directly rather than go through the White House
operators, who keep records of outgoing calls.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie's opinion of Ms. Lewinsky seemed to shift along with
the president's affair. By 1997, after Clinton had ended the
relationship and Ms. Lewinsky was growing increasingly despondent
and desperate to return to a job in the White House, Mrs. Currie
said she began to consider Ms. Lewinsky and her frequent tearful
phone calls ``a pain in the neck, more or less.'' She found Ms.
Lewinsky ``a little bit pushy,'' and resisted the president's
request that she find her a White House job.
</P>
<P>
   But she agreed to ask John Podesta, the deputy White House chief
of staff, to find a job for Ms. Lewinsky in New York, and faxed Ms.
Lewinsky's resume to the United Nations. She also contacted Vernon
Jordan, the president's close friend, to seek his help in finding a
New York job for Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Her testimony on this and other points was far more vague and
thus helpful to the president than prosecutors had hoped. Both
Jordan and Ms. Lewinsky testified that they had reason to believe
the president was behind Mrs. Currie's overture to Jordan, but Ms.
Currie said that she contacted Jordan on her own initiative. She
later testified that while the president probably talked with her
about Ms. Lewinsky's job hunt, she could not recall whether he was
directly involved.
</P>
<P>
   But many of her other, more direct statements provided the
grounds for Starr to accuse the president of impeachable offenses.
The honesty of those statements clashed diametrically with her
earlier intentions to protect her boss.
</P>
<P>
   Under oath, she provided some testimony showing that Clinton was
alone with Ms. Lewinsky, contradicting his statements that he had
not been. (Asked explicitly whether they had been alone, she echoed
the president's statement that he was never truly alone because
other people were in the general area.) A year before she
testified, however, she had waited for 15 or 20 minutes while the
two had a sexual encounter in his study, and then accompanied both
of them out of the Oval Office. Her explanation: ``I didn't want
any perceptions, him being alone with someone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0131 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2799 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN     09-13 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STARR'S UNFINISHED BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The scope of the independent counsel's initial
referral is too narrow: Ken Starr was hired to look into worse
abuses than the cover-up of a sex scandal.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's defense, however, is disappointingly weak:
admit sin but deny crime, and beg forgiveness for lying while
continuing to lie.
</P>
<P>
   The central fact making a mockery of his misty-eyed
``repentance'' is this: He refuses to admit, even now, that he and
Monica Lewinsky had a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   That phrase was precisely defined by a federal judge to include
oral sex and intimate touching. He denied it falsely in his Paula
Jones deposition; he repeated the false denial before a federal
grand jury; and even today he would have the nation believe that he
never once touched Ms. Lewinsky's proffered bosom during their 10
Oval Office assignations.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody believes him because his look-ma-no-hands assertion so
patently defies common sense. Why does he persist in the lie? Two
reasons:
</P>
<P>
   1. If he admits lying in his January Jones deposition, the 8th
Circuit Court of Appeals would likely reinstate Ms. Jones' case. A
jury would surely believe her now, which would cost Clinton a
million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   2. If he admits having repeated to the grand jury in August his
false and misleading testimony, the president would be confessing
to perjury. That would be an undisputed count in an impeachment,
and whenever he left office might result in his arrest and
conviction _ the dread ``Jail to the Chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, his continued lying is not irrational. He runs great
financial and legal risks in telling the whole truth. That's why we
see his legalistic contortions and semantic evasions that turn
truth on its head. Clinton's tactic is to limit potential loss. But
this continued lying will expose his false contrition, erode
popular support and hasten his political demise.
</P>
<P>
   His defense strategy is overly cautious. He should realistically
face up to the likelihood of House impeachment, and if he is to win
Senate acquittal, he must risk all. That means telling the whole
truth now and gutsily facing the consequences later, which would
give credence to his argument that the concealment of adultery is
not the ``high'' crime that justifies removal.
</P>
<P>
   He would win back considerable respect by pledging to reject any
pardon and daring the independent counsel to bring him to trial for
perjury on Jan. 21, 2001. (Not much of a gamble; no D.C. jury would
convict him.) And while he's at it, apologize to Paula and settle
her case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton does not have it in his character to cut out the present
artful dodging and do this, of course; it would be the political
equivalent of all-out, clothes-off intercourse. Someday he may look
back and say, ``If I had only dared . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Now to Starr's unfinished business. His referral completes less
than one-fourth of his assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Starr is duty-bound, after these four years, to come up with
indictments or criminal informations on the Whitewater obstruction,
the Clintons' abuse of Justice Department prosecution to make
places for travel office patronage, and the invasion of 900 FBI
files by White House snoops. Or to report on those investigations
if they exonerate Hillary, Bruce Lindsey, Craig Livingstone et al,
which would force calumniators like me to eat crow and thereby
lessen impeachment heat.
</P>
<P>
   In the sex cover-up, we see direct conflicts of grand jury
testimony. Monica swears that Vernon Jordan told her at a breakfast
to destroy evidence, but the president's friend insists the
breakfast never happened; on another front, Jordan's testimony
conflicts with Clinton's. Is the prosecutor fearful of being
trounced in jury trials, where rules of evidence and presumption of
innocence apply _ as they do not in his House referral?
</P>
<P>
   Surprises may be in store. ``All phases of the investigation are
now nearing completion,'' Starr promises in his report. Do they
show a pattern of deceit and delay, of stonewalling and spinning,
of perjury and abuse of power on heavy political matters _ Clinton
habits so dramatically demonstrated in the cover-up of a sex
scandal?
</P>
<P>
   Many will find poetic justice in Clinton's escaping discovery of
high crimes and being brought down by lower crimes. But poetic
justice, or rough justice, is not real justice. If forthrightly
confessed, perjury about workplace dalliance should not be enough
to force out a president.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
