</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rafter repeats as U.S. Open champ
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK - History says the winner of consecutive U.S. Open
singles championships is an heir to the No. 1 ranking. Patrick
Rafter looked worthy of that title Sunday in a 6-3, 3-6, 6-2, 6-0
victory over Australian countryman Mark Philippoussis in the men's
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I was jumpy and nervous and all over the place,''
said Rafter, the sixth back-to-back U.S. Open champion in the open
era, ``but this year I felt I belonged there. I feel last year
wasn't a fluke then. I've consolidated it. I've done it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The official scorer was generous in the definition, but Rafter
was called for only five unforced errors, none in the third set,
and 24 fewer than Philippoussis for the match. Rafter also allowed
Philippoussis just three break-point chances while earning 20 of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five errors for the whole match, that's impressive,''
Philippoussis said. ``At the moment, he's playing like the best
player in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter moved past Marcelo Rios to No. 2 in the rankings behind
Pete Sampras, but for the past three months, Rafter has clearly
been the best. He's won 23 of his last 24 matches, beating seven
top-10 players and winning four titles. Consider that Sampras has
beaten only one top-10 player, Karol Kucera, all year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the summer, I've probably had the best results out of
everyone,'' Rafter said. ``I wish the next few tournaments were on
this sort of (hardcourt) surface. You can't be on this surface all
the time and be a No. 1 player in the world. I've got to prove
myself again in the indoor season to rival Pete at the top.''
</P>
<P>
   The other players who have won consecutive U.S. Opens in the
open era are arguably the five premier players of the post-Bjorn
Borg era -- Pete Sampras (1995-96), Stefan Edberg (1991-92), Ivan
Lendl (1985-87), Jimmy Connors (1982-83) and John McEnroe
(1979-81). All have been No. 1 in the world.
</P>
<P>
   Philippousis' end came in the third set, serving at 2-3. He
saved three break points and was at deuce when Rafter pushed back
and overhead that Philippoussis smashed at him in the corner rather
than into the open court. Rafter won it on when Philippoussis
netted a volley. Rafter then broke serve and won the final 10 games
of the match.
</P>
<P>
   The Rafter-Philippoussis matchup was the first all-Australian
final since 1970, when Ken Rosewall beat Tony Roche. That was also
the last time Australians had won in consecutive years as Rod Laver
won in 1969 to complete the final Grand Slam in men's tennis.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter is the first Australian to win back-to-back U.S. titles
since Neale Fraser in 1959-60.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
