<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2806 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PORTRAIT-2NDT     09-13 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PORTRAIT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: many tasks.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's very description of that encounter summons images
of Clinton's capacity for playing hearts, watching television,
talking on the telephone and reading a document simultaneously, _
although according to her account, he was eating pizza, receiving
oral sex and talking on the telephone with a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   To veteran Clinton-watchers, the report's accumulated detail
rings true in other trivial but telling ways, from the president's
careful assertion _ seconded by Ms. Lewinsky _ that he always left
the door ajar during his illicit encounters with Ms. Lewinsky in a
hallway off the Oval Office, (presumably so he could argue they
were never alone behind closed doors) to Ms. Lewinsky's assertion
that Clinton told her that accusations that he harassed Kathleen
Willey, a former White House volunteer, were ``ludicrous because he
would never approach a small-breasted woman'' (even in front of
reporters, the president has freely let his eyes fall to a woman's
ample decolletage).
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has long been known for his late-night telephone calls
to aides and friends, and for his capacity to talk a blue streak.
Ms. Lewinsky testified that he frequently called her after
midnight, several times for phone sex, and that after one such
exchange, he fell asleep in midconversation.
</P>
<P>
   In other ways, too, the report tells a familiar tale.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Lewinsky lingered in the Oval Office on Feb. 28, 1997,
the fateful day when she says she and the president resumed their
sexual encounters after 11 months, and when he stained her dress
with his semen, the president's personal aide, Goodin, tried to
shoo Ms. Lewinsky away. Goodin testified that ``I did not know if
that was a good use of his time,'' but the president replied,
``She's a friend of a political supporter.'' Like so many of
Clinton's comments in this case and others, that was literally
true, because Ms. Lewinsky had obtained her internship in the first
place through the efforts of a wealthy Democratic contributor,
Walter Kaye. But it was also, typically, incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Former aides, from Dick Morris to George Stephanopoulos, have
long noted that Clinton never works harder to win someone over than
when he fears he may be in danger of losing their support, while he
saves his harshest treatment for the aides whose loyalty he knows
is unquestioned. In this regard, it is perhaps significant that Ms.
Lewinsky told the grand jury that Clinton was ``the most
affectionate with me he'd ever been'' on July 4, 1997, at a time
when she had implicitly threatened to reveal their relationship and
just moments after Clinton had coldly warned her: ``It's illegal to
threaten the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides also agree that no topic has consumed Clinton more than
his own eventual legacy in office, and he has studied biographies
of his predecessors with care. So it was perhaps no coincidence
that, Ms. Lewinsky said, Clinton first sought to break off their
relationship on the one day reserved by the federal government to
honor great presidents: President's Day, Feb. 19, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, few words in the report are more damning than
Clinton's own in his grand jury testimony. They are full of the
half-confessions and semi-evasions that have marked his handling of
policy questions, from taxes to use of U.S. troops in Bosnia, and
that have suffused his approach to the Lewinsky matter from the
beginning.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Clinton testified that he and Ms. Lewinsky ``might
have talked about what to do in a nonlegal context'' to hide their
relationship, even as he rejected any suggestion that he sought to
influence her testimony in the Jones sexual misconduct suit.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Clinton's words seem simply comic. Asked in his
deposition in the Jones case if he had ever given Ms. Lewinsky any
gifts, the president replied: ``I don't recall. Do you know what
they were?'' In his grand jury testimony, he acknowledged
reciprocating gifts from Ms. Lewinsky on the grounds of etiquette,
saying, ``It was a right thing to do to give her gifts back.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his presidency, Clinton has repeatedly been forced to
apologize for mistakes that even many of his closest allies thought
he could have avoided in the first place, and his vision has
generally been clearest in hindsight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick after it was over,'' Clinton testified of the
resumption of his sexual encounters with Ms. Lewinsky on Feb. 28,
1997. ``And I, I was pleased at that time that it had been nearly a
year since any inappropriate contact had occurred with Ms.
Lewinsky. I promised myself it wasn't going to happen again. The
facts are complicated about what did happen and how it happened.
But, nonetheless, I'm responsible for it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
