NYT-09-13-98 2027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2807 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SERMONS-NYT &LR;      09-13 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SERMONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SERMONS, CLERICS STRUGGLE WITH CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Calif., Colo., Ill., Mass.)  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA) 
(mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In historic Abyssinian Baptist Church in Harlem Sunday, Rev.
Calvin Butts III drew embarrassed titters from his congregation as
he urged the men and women in the pews who may be having
extramarital affairs to sidle up to their paramours on the sidewalk
after services, end the relationship and ask for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we watch the president, we see each other, we see
ourselves,'' Butts told his congregation, to growing applause.
``Each one of us suffers from our own blemishes, our own envy, our
own backbiting, our own meanspiritedness. Have mercy, oh God.''
</P>
<P>
   In sermons explicit or indirect, in tones both angry and
mournful, members of the clergy across the country this weekend
struggled to offer their congregations some guideposts to make
sense of the presidential morality tale unfolding in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   In a broad diversity of churches of many denominations,
conservative and liberal, large and small, ministers emphasized the
theme of forgiveness, saying no one is free of sin, and that only
God has the power to judge, to forgive and to redeem.
</P>
<P>
   ``God loves Bill Clinton,'' said Rev. Darrell Mount, pastor at
Trinity United Methodist Church in downtown Denver. ``And Hillary.
And Monica. And Chelsea. God loves each one of those persons caught
in this lost situation.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few exceptions, clergy members refrained from calling for
the impeachment or the resignation of President Clinton. Most
denounced the president for his adultery and for demeaning his
family, his office and the nation. But some ministers also
chastised the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, for issuing a
sexually salacious report, the public for devouring it, news
organizations for circulating it and politicians who appear to be
rushing to judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pray for the moral discernment of the media that knows
sexual details can increase ratings,'' preached the Rev. Brenda
Stiers, executive minister of the Riverside Church in New York.
``We ask you to restrain us from having an immediate political
reaction and instead take us to the deep recesses of our hearts
where moral decisions are made.''
</P>
<P>
   This past weekend happened to fall at a time when both the
Christian and Jewish liturgies are focused on themes of repentance
and forgiveness. The Roman Catholic lectionary for Sunday took up
the story of the wayward Prodigal Son who spends his inheritance on
prostitutes, and yet is forgiven. Jews on Saturday night celebrated
the Selichot service, a midnight ceremony marking the beginning of
the High Holiday season of introspection, self-examination and
repentance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all familiar with the adage `the leopard can't change
his spots,''' said Rabbi Marc Schneier, president of the New York
Board of Rabbis, and rabbi at The Hampton Synagogue in Westhampton
Beach. ``Selichot brings the reassuring message that we can change.
We are not eternally guilty by past misconduct.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, a significant number of clergy members in many cities
said they had chosen to avoid the Clinton affair entirely in their
sermons. Even the pastors of some of the nation's largest
evangelical ``megachurches'' _ some known as centers of moral and
theological conservatism _ said they were intentionally steering
clear of the topic.
</P>
<P>
   At First African Methodist Episcopal Church in South Central Los
Angeles, the oldest black church in Los Angeles with 16,000
members, the leadership of the church met about a week ago and
decided no longer to talk about the Clinton-Lewinsky scandal from
the pulpit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just felt like it had been addressed enough,'' said the
Rev. Jeanne Beharry. ``It's been discussed and overly discussed in
the newspaper, on television, every Bible study group. There has to
be a point where you say, `How much discussion is necessary?' and
if I had my druthers, I'd druther not discuss it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Gregory Boyle, a Jesuit priest with the Dolores Mission
Church in the Boyle Heights section of East Los Angeles, said,
``There are just too many life and death issues about which we must
preach, and so to preach about Bill Clinton and his situation is
not really relevant to the real issues of folks in a community like
this.'' To do so, Boyle said, would be to risk being labeled
irrelevant by the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Even Cardinal John O'Connor, the Roman Catholic archbishop of
New York, said at St. Patrick's Cathedral Sunday that his silence
on the Clinton matter has caused ``perplexity and has provoked
others to question my courage.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this to be the church's new approach?'' O'Connor said.
``That I point to people in the congregation and say, `I know your
sins, you shouldn't be here. Stand up.'''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said, ``I have no intention of starting such
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did not appear for services at Foundry United Methodist
Church, which he usually attends while in Washington, avoiding both
the media camped on the church's steps and the pastor's sermon
about forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Forgiveness was not the chorus in every house of worship,
however. At the Presbyterian Church of Western Springs, Ill., a
bedroom community of Chicago, the Rev. David Bebb Jones, a
self-described political liberal and moral conservative, preached:
``The president ought to resign immediately. He has violated a
sacred trust, probably a constitutional trust, and surely the
people's trust. I can think of no other position in the country
where such behavior would not result in immediate dismissal,
including the ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   At Trinity Church in downtown Boston, about 150 members of the
Episcopal congregation turned out for an afternoon forum titled
``Immorality in High Places.''
</P>
<P>
   William Barnwell, an associate rector at Trinity, said of
Clinton, ``Even now he will be forgiven by God. Nevertheless,
grievous sin does have grievous consequences. President Clinton has
scarred the institution of the presidency, the Democratic party, of
which I am a proud member, and collective body of the American
people as well of course his own family and Monica Lewinsky. And
those scars will not go away whether he is impeached or not,
whether he resigns or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Intertwined with such chords of despair, some religious leaders
and their congregants said they sensed that Clinton's public
humiliation and confession could be the beginning of ``healing''
for himself, his family and other people wrestling with sin.
</P>
<P>
   As he left a forum on Clinton's transgressions Saturday night at
Wilshire Boulevard Temple in Los Angeles, Bill Steinberg, a temple
member, said, ``I think people are going to synagogues and churches
looking for something different than what they're getting from the
media, looking for forgiveness and looking for healing. I think
that's why people are here tonight. We dont want our nation torn
apart.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
