<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-JUDICIARY-ART     09-13 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUDICIARY-ART-920&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A COMMITTEE KNOWN FOR PARTISANSHIP STRIVES FOR MODERATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS; CLINTON-SERMONS;
CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT; CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT;
CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By LIZETTE ALVAREZ   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The name falls from their lips with
uncharacteristic reverence, like ballplayers conjuring up Joe
DiMaggio in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodino _ he did an extraordinary job,'' said Sheila
Jackson-Lee, a Texas Democrat on the Judiciary Committee,
mentioning the subdued, even-handed chairman of the committee
during Watergate. ``He will be my role model.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Ms. Jackson-Lee, who is known for lengthy attacks on
Republicans and their policies, added, ``I will not venture into
the muddy waters of partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   Conventional wisdom, and recent history, seem to indicate
otherwise. Of all the House committees, the Judiciary Committee is
known as the most polarized and ideologically split on Capitol
Hill. Peter W. Rodino Jr. may have had a core of 10 moderates to
depend on to steer his course, but the current chairman, Rep. Henry
Hyde of Illinois, can count his on one hand.
</P>
<P>
   The polarization is no coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   As Rep. Jerrold Nadler of New York, a New York liberal, said,
the committee's agenda attracts extremes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very bifurcated committee,'' Nadler said. ``You get
people who are interested in abortion and civil rights and due
process. They tend not to be the moderates.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee regularly grapples with an assortment of divisive
issues, including affirmative action, tort overhaul, crime,
terrorism and same-sex marriages. Though the debates are usually
civil, party-line votes are the norm among the 21 Republicans and
16 Democrats; bipartisanship is the exception. What's more, the
panel is stocked with both the president's harshest critics and his
most unswerving supporters.
</P>
<P>
   There is Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga., who asserts that Clinton has so
debased the presidency that last year, even before Monica Lewinsky
became news, he filed a resolution to impeach him.
</P>
<P>
   Barr also introduced a bill to prohibit the federal government
from recognizing same-sex marriages. Barr, who has been divorced
twice, said at the time, ``The flames of hedonism, the flames of
narcissism, the flames of self-centered morality are licking at the
very foundation of our society: the family unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr. of Michigan, the committee's senior
Democrat and its only Watergate veteran, has been almost as severe
a critic of Kenneth Starr as Barr is of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank of Massachusetts, the second-ranking Democrat
on the committee, is a nimble debater who is quick with a quip and
prone to impatience for what he considers poor displays of
intellect. Frank, who is expected to play a forceful role in the
proceedings, is also the brother of Ann Lewis, the White House
communications director.
</P>
<P>
   Another much-talked-about figure on the committee is Rep. Howard
Berman, D-Calif., considered a formidable legal presence by his
peers on the committee. Reserved and politically astute, Berman has
forged a close relationship with Hyde, the committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the aisle, two bookish Florida Republicans
loom as central players: Rep. Bill McCollum, who has said perjury
will constitute an impeachable offense, and Rep. Charles Canady, a
constitutional expert who heads the subcommittee that has proposed
more Constitutional amendments than anyone since James Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans, eager to quell criticism about the panel's
membership, recently appointed their first woman, Rep. Mary Bono of
California, who won the seat held by her late husband, Sonny. The
Republican wing also includes several former judges and federal
prosecutors, who are likely to step back into those roles in any
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Asa Hutchinson, a Republican who expressed ``shock'' at the
Starr report but urged his colleagues to be cautious about not
prejudging the president, was once a U.S. attorney in Arkansas. And
Rep. Ed Bryant, another Republican, was U.S. attorney in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the credentials on both sides _ only three members did
not go to law school _ there is little question that the Democrats
on the committee are considerably flashier and more experienced in
the political arena than their Republican counterparts. The
committee's Republicans, while no less zealous in their views, are
largely a little less quick on their feet, a little more lawyerly
in their demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Having so many lawyers in one room is both fortunate and
unfortunate. ``Lawyers tend to be more contentious and
argumentative, and that can show up,'' said Canady. ``But our legal
background will be helpful in making a judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have hired experienced chief counsels accustomed to
gritty battlegrounds of a separate sort. David Schippers, the
Republican counsel, is a lifelong Chicago Democrat who put the
mobster Sam Giancana in prison. On the Democratic side is Abbe
Lowell, a Washington insider who has defended a roster of
scandal-tainted clients, including former House Speaker Jim Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their ideological gulf, committee members bristle at the
idea that they cannot set aside their differences and behave
judiciously and thoughtfully, just as the committee did during
Watergate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There aren't going to be any food fights,'' Frank said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the gravity of the situation appears to be sinking in.
</P>
<P>
   ``All members feel their constitutional obligation,'' said Hyde,
who is considered fair-minded and gentlemanly and who is expected
to set the tone of the proceedings along with Conyers, despite the
Democrat's antipathy for Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a matter we will relish doing,'' Hyde added.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
