</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-JUDICIARY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: Hyde added.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even such conservative firebrands as Rep. Lindsey Graham,
R-S.C., who last year helped lead an effort to oust Newt Gingrich
as speaker for not being conservative enough, are dutifully
composing themselves for the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to speak out against any Republican who turns this
into `Let me tell you why I don't like Bill Clinton,''' Graham
said. ``I do that every day. But I'm playing a role here that is
big-time serious. The worst thing that can happen is for an
election to be overturned without a heck of a good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that most of the members on the panel are not facing
tough re-election battles this November should help keep those
partisan flare-ups in check.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people are watching us closely'' Canady said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, too, say they want bipartisanship to rule. But a few
have already complained of an inauspicious beginning. Some
Democrats brimmed with outrage when the House voted on Friday to
approve the public release of Starr's report without first giving
the president a chance to inspect it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Melvin Watt, D-N.C., a member of the Judiciary Committee,
criticized the action as unfair and tinged with political motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one looks like it's going to get into a real war,'' Watt
said, referring to a possible impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Hutchinson, R-Ark., acknowledges that there is not much of a
precedent for bipartisanship on the committee. ``But,'' he said,
``hope springs eternal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
