<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-VOTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL OFFICIALS SAY ELECTIONS IN BOSNIA WERE A SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MIKE O'CONNOR    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina _ Despite glitches that may leave
voters in doubt about the legitimacy of elections this weekend,
international officials in charge of the balloting deemed it a
success and a tribute to progress toward democracy.
</P>
<P>
   The chief international official, Carlos Westendorp, said he
thought that moderate leaders might do better than thought by
foreign diplomats worried that the extreme nationalists who led
this country into a 43-month war and won the elections in 1996
would again triumph.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters may have some surprises for the politicians,''
Westendorp said.
</P>
<P>
   At stake were seats in the national legislature, parliaments in
the Serb and Muslim-Croat halves of Bosnia, the Bosnian Serb
presidency and leadership of the 10 Muslim-Croat cantons, as well
as the three seats on the joint presidency, Bosnia's chief
executive body.
</P>
<P>
   The election was crucial to Western hopes of replacing hard-line
nationalist politicians with moderate leaders. Preliminary results
are expected on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The voting was peaceful, in contrast to other elections since
the war ended in 1995, when there was considerable tension. NATO
troops were hardly visible. Voters, often dressed in their best
clothes, lined up calmly at more than 2,000 polling places, each
monitored by an international supervisor and the Bosnian police.
</P>
<P>
   International election officials played down problems that the
losers might use to challenge results.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern seen on visits to 23 polling stations included the
foreign supervisors' saying there were no problems, and the Bosnian
election officials' eagerly reporting difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   In every station an average of 3 percent of the voters were
reported missing from the lists, enough to convince suspicious
inhabitants of the Balkans that something nefarious was afoot.
</P>
<P>
   In the Serb village of Karanovac an observer from a Bosnian Serb
party, Radomir Serdar, said foreign intervention in elections was
accepted, if not liked. ``But when these foreigners give us voting
lists that somehow don't include a lot of voters we suspect they
are setting the groundwork for fraud,'' Serdar said.
</P>
<P>
   In Jajce, three of the 30 people who went to vote in the first
three hours on Saturday were on the list.
</P>
<P>
   In Vogosca one station opened hours late because ballots and
voting lists had not arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Azra Smaijlbegovic searched in vain for her name. ``This could
be nothing more than a mistake,'' Miss Smaijlbegovic said. ``But
you know this is the Balkans, and anything could be happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters not on the lists were allowed to cast ballots sealed with
their names and national identity numbers and sent to Sarajevo for
checking against a master list. If a name is on that list, the vote
will count, foreign election officials said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
