<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD'S PRESS REFLECTS ON CLINTON CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(js) 
 By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a mixture of solemnity, worry and sometimes sheer glee at
the crisis facing President Clinton, newspapers around the world
continued to be dominated by news of how a report about allegations
of sex and lies has threatened to topple the most powerful man in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Several media outlets posted the entire document on their
websites and editorial writers from Munich to Hong Kong ruminated
about its impact on the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The coverage worldwide revealed as much about each country's
relationship with the United States as it did about its own press
traditions and sexual mores.
</P>
<P>
   In China, where Clinton is popular with the government and the
people, the papers offered unadorned reportage, with none of the
lurid narratives or fist-pounding editorials to be found elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Sunday edition of The People's Daily, principal Communist
Party newspaper, ran a short article on page two, with a headline
that read, ``U.S. Congress Publishes Starr's Report, White House
Legal Advisers Rebut on Just Grounds.''
</P>
<P>
   The article reported the number of pages in the Starr report and
listed the 11 allegedly impeachable offenses, but recounted none of
the president's sexual encounters. In fact, the paper offered more
space to the White House rebuttal. ``President Clinton has admitted
his mistake and apologized on many occasions in the past few
days,'' the article concluded, ``and in the meantime, he has
instructed his lawyers to make an effort to defend him.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior editor at a Communist Party paper said that the party's
propaganda department had instructed the country's news outlets to
refrain from commentary. The Beijing Evening News made no mention
of oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, in Iran, where sex is not a matter of public
discourse, the major newspapers did not editorialize about
Clinton's alleged attempts to cover up his relationship with Ms.
Lewinsky. Most reports politely referred to Clinton's
``relationship with the White House intern,'' although one
newspaper, Kayan, broke ranks with a story charging that ``the
report on Clinton's moral case shocked Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hong Kong, the editorial pages generally focused on whether
the investigation by the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, would
affect world financial markets, with Apple Daily, the island's most
popular Chinese-language daily, expressing concern that Clinton's
troubles came at a moment when the world's fragile stock markets
needed strong leadership from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But elsewhere, the Fourth Estate had great fun.
</P>
<P>
   In India, newspapers were not the least bit reluctant to print
the sensational minutiae of Starr's report _ ``Clinton Adrift in a
Sea of Smut,'' screamed a headline in The Indian Express _ and some
leading opinion makers there seemed eager to see him leave office.
</P>
<P>
   The Pioneer, a New Delhi-based paper that has vociferously
defended India's explosion of nuclear devices, wrote in an
editorial Sunday that few would shed tears over the departure of a
president whose administration had ``acted like an outraged bully
over the nuclear tests in Pokhran in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most newspapers depicted the leader of the world's most
powerful nation as a man reduced by his own hubris. ``By his
monumental effort to hide the truth and subvert evidence,''
declared The Hindu, in its lead editorial Saturday, `` Clinton lost
the trust of his people, lost his own moral authority to rule.''
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico City, news of the Starr report led five of the most
important papers in Saturday editions, with several describing an
encounter between Clinton and Monica Lewinsky on the night before
his dinner meeting with Mexican President Ernesto Zedillo.
``Zedillo One of Several World Leaders Present During the Sexual
Adventures,'' read one headline in La Jornada, a leading leftist
daily there.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, the front page of Pagina 12, a leading daily, on
Saturday carried a drawing of Clinton, dressed in nothing but a
tie, polka-dotted with lipstick left by kisses.
</P>
<P>
   If foreign media outlets lampooned Clinton's fate, they also
poked fun at what they regarded as the prudishness of the American
public.
</P>
<P>
   In Germany, for instance, ordinary people and professional
pundits found themselves flummoxed by the prospect that the leader
of the world's most powerful country might be forced out of office
because of sexual improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is harder to say which is more grotesque,'' pondered the
Stuttgarter Zeitung in an editorial. ``Clinton's dumb attempts to
free himself from his liaison and his lies, or the venomous
investigation of special prosecutor Starr, a fevered hunt in the
name of hypocritical morals.''
</P>
<P>
   All weekend long, the Starr report dominated the front page of
every German newspaper and television talk show. Welt am Sonntag,
the nationally distributed Sunday publication, set aside two pages
for a German translation of the report. Only one newspaper called
on the U.S. president to resign. ``Clinton is a president without
his pants on,'' railed a front-page editorial in the conservative
Frankfurter Allgemeine on Saturday. ``A philanderer is not a good
occupant for the White House.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2043EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRADLEY-SOSA-COLU     09-13 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRADLEY-SOSA-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Although McGwire got to 62 first, Sosa was never far behind
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mark McGwire got there first, but McGwire mightn't have made it
without Sammy Sosa. And now Sosa's there, too, but Sosa mightn't
have done it without McGwire. How towering was Roger Maris' record?
So tall that it took two men to surmount it.
</P>
<P>
   Think back to Aug. 19, a day game in Wrigley. McGwire had
managed but two home runs in three weeks. Sosa had drawn even at
47, which is a slew of homers but still miles from 62. On that
Wednesday the Great Chase again took flight, Sosa hitting his 48th
to pull momentarily ahead, McGwire answering with Nos. 48 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   That was the day everything changed, and not just numerically.
McGwire had begun to chafe under the growing scrutiny, grumpily
admonishing the traveling media throng to ''worry about your
families.'' Thirty-seven years ago, in a era not yet cable-ready,
Maris had seen his hair infamously fall out; with 10 times the
exposure and 20 times the number of interrogators, would the
redhead be bald by September?
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, no. This had to do not just with McGwire but
with Sosa. Those around the Cardinals insist that the week that
took McGwire to Chicago was a week of transformation. Said Dave
Parker, once a hitter of renown and now the Cards' batting coach:
''Mac was getting fed up. But then he was around Sammy and his
outgoing personality, and he saw how he was handling things. And
largely because of that, he loosened up.''
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall that Sunday, a conspicuously sunnier McGwire had
hit four more. Even the Androstenedione Affair, which broke that
weekend while he was in New York, couldn't dim the glow. Without
Sosa to serve as an object lesson, would McGwire have reached 62?
Perhaps, but not nearly so soon. For one man assaulting the record
alone, September would have been a long, slow slog.
</P>
<P>
   The flip side: Without McGwire to run interference and draw the
hordes -- on the weekend some 600 writers assembled in St. Louis to
see McGwire hit No. 61, Sosa hit his 58th before an unpacked press
box in Pittsburgh -- Sosa might well have seen his trademark
enthusisiasm diminished. Even as he was slipstreaming behind
McGwire, Sosa kept insisting, only a bit disingenuously, that
''Mark is the man.'' But now, after a week that saw a 62nd homer
launched not once but twice, it seems clear that each man needed
the other.
</P>
<P>
   Maris had company until September, until an ailing Mickey Mantle
left him alone in pursuit. Then it was just one man against Babe
Ruth and history, against Ford Frick and his asterisk. Even as
McGwire smacked 61 and then 62, he was never really alone. Sosa was
in the same ballpark, his at-bats furnishing their own drama, his
presence giving the media something else to chronicle, his
responses to McGwire's blasts serving as slices of sporting grace.
</P>
<P>
   So genuine was Sosa in his esteem for McGwire that you wanted
him to have his moment as well, and his came Sunday. If it was
decidedly lower-key than McGwire's, it was no less momentous. So
what if, in the chronicle of the 1998 season, Sosa gets cast as
Buzz Aldrin to McGwire's Neil Armstrong? Like those lunar
explorers, these cosmic sluggers formed a historic team.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bradley is a columnist for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
