<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S LIES, MORE THAN AFFAIR, BOTHER RESIDENTS IN ONE N.J.
TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(nk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTFIELD, N.J. _ It was a glorious late-summer Sunday in this
prosperous, largely Republican and now fed-up pocket of America.
The soccer teams played at Memorial Park, the Sunday School of the
Congregationalist Church posed for pictures, the line at Starbucks
was long. And when the talk turned to President Clinton, as it
usually did, parents asked their children to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kerry, go over by Daddy, please,'' Christine Foley, 37, told
her 10-year-old daughter at Memorial Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, fine,'' Kerry responded. ``I know what you're up to,
though.''
</P>
<P>
   Out of earshot, Mrs. Foley _ a Republican, stay-at-home mother
of four children and wife of a lawyer _ talked about what she
considered the ``disgusting'' sexual details in the report of the
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr. But in remarks that echoed the
views of many of her neighbors, she also said that Starr's report
never should have been put on the Internet, and that the report
only confirmed the negative opinion she already had of Clinton's
character.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely don't think he should be impeached,'' she added.
``I think I'd like to see him resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why, she paused. ``You're asking a good question, because
I'm still confused about it,'' she said. ``I guess the only way to
get past this is if he removes himself from the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven months ago, shortly after Clinton was accused of having an
affair with Monica Lewinsky, The New York Times asked residents of
Westfield, a predominately white suburb of 29,000 about 25 miles
west of Manhattan, what they thought of the president. Many of the
three dozen people randomly interviewed said then that they didn't
respect Clinton personally but liked the job he was doing as
president _ a view mirrored at the time in national polls, when
Clinton was enjoying record approval ratings. Westfield residents
also said that Clinton's private life, no matter how troubling,
should not be of public concern.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, in two dozen random interviews with other residents of
Westfield, the situation seemed to have changed. Although people
still said they considered Clinton a good president, they seemed
less willing to look past his personal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But they said their disillusionment was rooted in Clinton's lies
about the affair, not in the explicit sexual details they read over
the weekend in Starr's report. ``He's a womanizer, but he always
was,'' said Chris Fraites, 40, a commodities trader and an
independent who voted for Clinton. ``That didn't shock anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   No one interviewed said that Clinton should be impeached because
of Ms. Lewinsky, although many said he ought to resign. A few
others, all Democrats, said that calling for resignation was
premature. Democrats also accused Starr of conducting a ``witch
hunt,'' and said they were angry about the time and money he spent.
</P>
<P>
   The conversations always came back to Clinton's untruthfulness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so disappointed in his having lied in January,'' said
Michelle Ehrich, 38, an independent voter and an investment
banker-turned-author who was selling gift certificates on the
opening day of the religious school at Westfield's Temple Emanu-el.
``I'm having a hard time getting past that. Even though I thought
the investigation was improper, I find it difficult to fathom that
someone could have made such a vehement and emotional denial. He
lied to not only the nation but his closest friends, advisers and
family, standing up there shaking his finger. I'm so upset about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nobody in what Ms. Ehrich called ``a Harold Robbins
novel'' _ from the president to Ms. Lewinsky to Starr _ got much
sympathy in Westfield. Fraites, who gives Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin credit for the good economy, was especially angry at Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out as a Whitewater investigation, and you don't
hear much about that now,'' he said. ``Along the way, he finds out
the president had an affair with an intern. And now the taxpayers
are spending millions of dollars to find out about the president's
sex life. I don't like that. That should be Hillary's problem.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky did not fare well in Westfield, either. If the
report did anything, at least based on the two dozen people
interviewed, it provided a far more unflattering picture of a woman
who people no longer seem to view as a simple victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``She really did come on to him,'' said Amy Margulies, 43, a
Democrat and a former executive of a clothing company, who was at
Starbucks with her daughter, Arielle, nearly 2. ``I do think this
was a hot 22-year-old who forced her way. Yeah, he's the president
of the United States, he should be strong enough. But he's a man.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Margulies paused. ``I guess that is really anti-feminist of
me,'' she said, apologetically.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Moore, 58, a Democrat and a teacher of the handicapped,
agreed that Ms. Lewinsky is no role model. ``What a disservice to
women,'' she said, walking with her 2-year-old grandson, Alec,
outside the Presbyterian Church of Westfield. ``As a woman, I hold
her responsible for her actions. She had every opportunity in life,
and then she made decisions so that she ended up where she ended
up. I have no respect and sympathy for that. I teach kids who come
from places with far less, and they are able to do more for
themselves and society.''
</P>
<P>
   Laing Sisto, 34, a Democrat whose father, Paul Rogers, was a
congressman from Florida, was more tolerant of Ms. Lewinsky _
``you're so naive and the president of the United States is
lavishing attention on you'' _ and thought Clinton should resign.
``He lied to protect his family,'' she said. ``But if you're the
president of the United States, you can't do that under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sisto, the mother of four children, also said that Clinton
will leave a sad legacy. ``Yesterday, I was talking to a
neighbor,'' she said. ``We both have 8-year-olds. And he said, `My
daughter will remember President Clinton as the one who had the
girlfriend.'''
</P>
<P>
   Discussions of Starr's report did create some debate at
Starbucks. ``It was pretty graphic,'' said Richard Geiger, 37, a
Republican who is a lawyer and an engineer at Merck
Pharmaceuticals. ``My first question as a lawyer is, how does she
remember in such detail?''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Margulies was listening at a nearby table. ``What, are you
kidding?'' she said to a reporter a few minutes later, recalling
Geiger's remark. ``I'd remember every single thing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
