<HEADLINE>
REPORT TO CONGRESS WAS NOT LAST WORD FROM STARR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic on the White House rebuttal to the Starr report
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ By the time Richard Nixon faced impeachment
proceedings in Congress a generation ago, many of his closest aides
had already been indicted or convicted of crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In stunning contrast, the independent counsel, Kenneth Starr,
has built an impeachment case against President Clinton over a
series of incidents involving Monica Lewinsky in which no criminal
charges have been filed against anyone. At least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said Sunday that the impeachment report sent to
Congress last week was far from the last step in their examination.
It is not known to what end they are working, but grand juries in
Washington and Virginia are continuing their examinations into
aspects of the Lewinsky inquiry that Starr apparently thought did
not need to be resolved before filing his report with Congress last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the impeachment referral, while painfully detailed about
many intimate aspects of the relationship between Clinton and a
former White House intern, left unresolved several issues that have
emerged in recent months, including these:
</P>
<P>
   _ Did Clinton lie under oath regarding accusations by a White
House volunteer, Kathleen Willey, that Clinton groped her in the
White House in 1993? Did Nathan Landow, a prominent Maryland real
estate developer and Democratic fund-raiser, who talked to Ms.
Willey after the incident, try to influence her testimony? Landow
has denied he violated any laws.
</P>
<P>
   _ What was the role of the deputy White House counsel, Bruce
Lindsey, when he talked to witnesses in the Lewinsky case and the
Paula Corbin Jones case? The White House has appealed to the
Supreme Court a decision in which a federal appeals court said the
president could not invoke lawyer-client privilege to shield
Lindsey from answering questions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Did Linda Tripp alter or duplicate portions of the tapes she
made of her conversations with Ms. Lewinsky, her Pentagon
colleague, despite Ms. Tripp's testimony to the contrary? Did Ms.
Tripp break Maryland law when she surreptitiously recorded
telephone conversations without Ms. Lewinsky's consent? Maryland
authorities are examining that question.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Starr's office said Sunday that the areas not
addressed in the referral were not essential to reaching
conclusions about whether Clinton might have committed impeachable
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   The independent counsel law requires Starr to issue a referral
to the House of Representatives once he has ``substantial and
credible information'' that ``may constitute grounds for
impeachment.'' The law gives no guidance about the timing of such a
referral, although another provision requires that once his inquiry
is over, Starr must give a formal accounting of his entire
investigation to the special court that appointed him.
</P>
<P>
   While its precise timing is still unknown, the report to the
court is certain to provide information about what Starr has
learned throughout his sprawling inquiry. These include the
dismissal of the White House travel office staff in 1993 and the
administration's use of background files compiled by the FBI about
former Republican officials.
</P>
<P>
   Starr has also not provided his conclusions into the four-year
examination of the ties in the 1980s between Clinton, Hillary
Rodham Clinton and a corrupt savings and loan association in
Arkansas that was owned and operated by James and Susan McDougal,
the Clintons' business partners in the Whitewater land venture.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McDougal has been indicted by a federal grand jury in
Arkansas for refusing to answer its questions. She is also a
defendant in a case in California in which she is accused of
embezzling $150,000 from the conductor Zubin Mehta and his wife,
Nancy.
</P>
<P>
   The only other outstanding case brought by the independent
counsel involves Webster Hubbell, the former associate attorney
general. Prosecutors are appealing the dismissal of a tax-evasion
indictment against Hubbell involving income that he received from
friends of the president.
</P>
<P>
   In his impeachment referral, Starr wrote that ``all phases of
the investigation are now nearing completion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This office will soon make final decisions about what steps to
take, if any, with respect to the other information it has
gathered,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   While the impeachment referral inflicted considerable political
damage, it also had the practical effect of clearing a number of
Clinton aides of committing crimes.
</P>
<P>
   By concluding that the president had lied to them, the referral
suggested that they had had no role in any cover-up and that they
did not violate the law when they testified that Clinton did not
have a sexual relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. The crime of perjury
requires as one of its elements that the person testifying know
that the testimony is untruthful.
</P>
<P>
   But the referral may also pose new problems for Clinton outside
of Congress. In particular, it could prompt possible sanctions from
the federal judge in Arkansas who dismissed Mrs. Jones' lawsuit
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, Susan Webber Wright, wrote two weeks ago that she had
concerns about Clinton's January deposition after he acknowledged
that he had had an inappropriate relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Wright indicated that she could find Clinton in contempt of
court for failing to detail his relationship but had not decided
what to do.
</P>
</TEXT>
