<SLUG> BC-GORE-VISIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORGIVE AND MOVE ON, GORE SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ President Clinton has spoken deeply to ``redemption
and repentance, atonement and forgiveness'' and should be allowed
to stay in office and get on with the country's business, Vice
President Al Gore said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who would inherit the White House if Clinton resigns or is
impeached, played the role of loyalist and understanding understudy
Sunday during a closely watched political visit to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Clinton's speech to a White House prayer breakfast
last Friday as showing the depth of the president's contrition. He
argued that the report of special prosecutor Kenneth Starr does not
justify the drastic step of removing a twice-elected president from
office.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his speech (Friday) was perhaps the best of his
presidency,'' said Gore. ``In his manner of responding to this
issue, he has addressed very deep subjects like redemption and
repentance, atonement and forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``In accepting responsibility for doing what he acknowledged was
wrong and indefensible, he has asked both for forgiveness and the
ability to move to problems facing the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I personally believe that even though the
president's lawyers will respond to specifics in the Starr report,
there is nothing in that report that justifies overturning the
judgment of the American people in 1992 and 1996 that Bill Clinton
should be president of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore was interviewed by the Post-Intelligencer after completing
a 5 kilometer ``Race for the Cure'' run against breast cancer at
the University of Washington. The vice president took just over 30
minutes to run just over three miles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore kept up a breakneck pace through the day. He packed in four
fundraisers, a meeting with key local supporters of his anticipated
presidential bid, and a discussion about how to restore imperiled
Northwest salmon runs.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president also challenged GOP Sen. Slade Gorton. Gorton
recently attacked Gore, claiming he favors imposed federal
solutions to Northwest environmental problems. Gorton has hinted
that Gore might support removing some dams from the Columbia River
system to save salmon.
</P>
<P>
   Gore mixed wit and serious argument in a spirited counterattack
yesterday. He suggested attacks from the Republican senator are ``a
case of his hostility toward the environment spilling over toward
me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have been bitten by a squirrel as a child,'' Gore
added, referring to Gorton's often vociferous criticism of the
Endangered Species Act.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was strongly critical of provisions that Gorton has
inserted into a pending spending bill for U.S. Departments of
Interior, Agriculture and Energy. The riders cover everything from
management of Columbia and Snake River dams to prohibiting
completion of a management plan for federal lands in the Columbia
Basin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view is that this policy should not be made in Washington,
D.C., behind closed doors by lawyers and lobbyists for big
polluters, but instead should be made by the people of the region
coming together in a science-based process that fosters harmony and
accommodates all the interests that have to be reconciled,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore met with those interests yesterday. In a broiling sun in
front of Bell Harbor Conference Center, he presided over a lengthy
discussion of salmon involving state, local and tribal leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was ready to be pleased. He promised that ``a single
proposal for salmon recovery for the region'' will be included in
the Clinton administration's proposed fiscal year 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Answers won't come from Washington, D.C., but Washington
state,'' said Gore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
