<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT-10TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S PUBLIC ACTS AND SECRET TRYSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN, JOHN KIFNER and N.R. KLEINFIELD    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Bill Clinton, as for all presidents, the White House has
always been a stage, the symbol of national power and executive
authority, its stately rooms reflecting America's noblest
aspirations. In the Oval Office, presidents have faced questions of
war and peace and the welfare of the people. They have also used
the elegant setting for less lofty purposes, as a political
platform and as a place to charm the rich and powerful for campaign
contributions or votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House has developed a lurid backstage life in
recent years, as investigators have learned, with sexual encounters
between President Clinton and a young intern in rooms just off the
Oval Office, with trysts stolen between the bill signings, the
state dinners and meetings with government officials and foreign
dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   On 10 days between Nov. 15, 1995, and March 29, 1997 _ 10 days
reconstructed in this article _ he wove into his schedule a series
of sexual rendezvous with Monica Lewinsky, according to Kenneth
Starr, the Whitewater independent counsel.
</P>
<P>
   While the Starr report did not tote up the precise amount of
time the president and Ms. Lewinsky spent together, their
encounters apparently occupied less than 10 hours over the span of
16 months, even though Ms. Lewinsky's life appears to have been
dominated by her obsession with the president.
</P>
<P>
   The encounters began, by Starr's account, in the course of the
nation's business: eye-contact at ceremonial functions, a
flirtatious exchange or two, then a meeting one night when the
White House staff was cut drastically by a shutdown of the federal
government in a budget impasse, and interns were brought in to
help.
</P>
<P>
   The first sexual encounter took place in the waning hours of a
day on which Clinton signed a ``Family Week'' proclamation and an
appropriations bill, conferred with aides on negotiations to end
the war in Bosnia and tried to cope with the government shutdown.
He saw Ms. Lewinsky working alone in an aide's office, invited her
into the Oval Office and began with a kiss.
</P>
<P>
   Later on, the encounters were less happenstance, increasingly
orchestrated, the Starr report says. In an often blunt narrative
intended as an argument for Congress to impeach the president, the
report offers passages of seamy details and subterfuges that read
like pulp fiction.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of Secret Service agents, secretaries and assistants
who protect and serve the president in his official role were
clearly aware of the backstage activities, according to the Starr
report, but in many cases chose to avert their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Several encounters were interrupted by phone calls, and one by
the entrance of an aide, Harold Ickes, which sent Ms. Lewinsky into
a panicky flight out a rear door, the report says. Toward the end
of their relationship, it says, Ms. Lewinsky pleaded repeatedly to
see Clinton, but was rebuffed. Finally they met again, but the
report says the president had no time for sex: He had to rush off
for a state dinner with President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NOV. 15, 1995
</P>
<P>
   It was not a routine Wednesday for Clinton, because a budget
impasse with Congress had shut down the federal government, and
800,000 federal workers were staying home for a second day,
including over 80 percent of the White House staff.
</P>
<P>
   The president had no public events scheduled, and he did not
leave the White House. But he had meetings with aides, as well as
with three senators and a group of farmers; an appropriations bill
and several proclamations to sign and an interview with a
television network.
</P>
<P>
   And there were major foreign problems on his mind. In Dayton,
Ohio, negotiations to end the Bosnian war were at a critical stage.
In view of the budget problem and the government shutdown, the
president was grappling with another problem: whether to go through
with a long-planned trip to Tokyo the coming weekend for a
pan-Asian economic conference.
</P>
<P>
   For days, his aides had debated the pros and cons of the trip,
which was intended to ease rising tensions over economic issues.
Foreign policy advisers argued he should go and not risk new
tensions with Japan, or appear to be held hostage by congressional
Republicans over the budget. But domestic advisers had warned him
of congressional mischief in his absence.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton early in the day decided to send Vice President Al Gore
instead. His announcement would say he could not be away from
Washington at such a delicate time. But sensitive to Japanese
feelings, he delayed the public announcement until evening _ that
would be morning in Tokyo _ so he could first inform Prime Minister
Tomiichi Murayama personally in a telephone call.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with the budget matters, Clinton spoke to Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, who averted a national default by taking
$61 billion from two civil service retirement funds (and replacing
the funds with IOUs) to cover interest payments on the national
debt and other bills coming due, including Social Security
payments.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the CBS anchor, Dan Rather, Clinton struck
a defiant note against the Republican budget priorities, saying he
would not give in to their ``huge cuts in Medicare, Medicaid,
education, the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signed three proclamations, for National Family Week,
National Farm-City Week and National Great American Smokeout Day,
which was to be the next day, Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Family Week proclamation cited a ``shared commitment to the
importance of family life,'' in which Americans ``first learn
important lessons about responsibility.'' He called for greater
efforts to prevent substance abuse, domestic violence and teen-age
pregnancy that ``threaten the well-being of our young people.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was unusually quiet throughout the day because
the federal shutdown had furloughed all but essential employees. As
a result, the White House staff of 430 had shrunk to only 90
people. Moreover, some were White House interns, who could continue
working because they were not paid.
</P>
<P>
   Many, including Ms. Lewinsky, who ordinarily worked in the Old
Executive Office Building near the White House, took on a wide
range of added duties that brought them into the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, who had begun her internship in July 1995,
testified before the grand jury that after about a month she began
making eye contact with the president at a number of White House
functions, and both began what she characterized as ``intense
flirting.''
</P>
<P>
   At departure ceremonies and other events, she recalled, she
shook Clinton's hand and introduced herself. Later, when she ran
into the president in the White House West Wing, she introduced
herself again, and, she testified, he responded that he already
knew who she was.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Lewinsky's regular job was to work on correspondence
in the office of the chief of staff, Leon Panetta, in the Old
Executive Office Building, she was assigned during the one-week
federal shutdown to answer phones and run errands in Panetta's
office in the West Wing.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, as on other days during the federal shutdown,
Clinton went frequently to Panetta's office, and sometimes talked
with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   At 1:30 p.m., according to the White House logs, Ms. Lewinsky
entered the White House. The logs do not show the time of her
departure that afternoon, and the Starr report did not say whether
Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton encountered one another during the early
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At about 3:15 p.m., Clinton met with the Senate minority leader,
Tom Daschle, D-S.D., and Sens. Byron Dorgan and Kent Conrad, both
Democrats of North Dakota, and six Dakota farmers. The president
told them he would fight steep cuts in farm subsidies that were
being advanced by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   At 5:07 p.m., according to logs cited by the Starr report, Ms.
Lewinsky re-entered the White House and resumed work in Panetta's
office; her departure from the White House was logged at 12:18 a.m.
During virtually the same time frame _ 5:01 p.m. to 12:35 a.m.,
Clinton was in the Oval Office or in Panetta's office, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, the report said, the president and Ms. Lewinsky
``made eye contact'' when he went to Panetta's office, and again
later at an informal birthday party for Jennifer Palmieri, a
special assistant to Panetta. At one point, they were alone in the
office and, according to the report, ``in the course of flirting
with him, she raised her jacket in the back and showed him the
straps of her thong underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometime before 8 p.m., when the White House spokesman announced
that the president had canceled his trip to Japan, Clinton spent 20
minutes on the phone with Murayama in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   At about 8 p.m., as Ms. Lewinsky walked to a restroom, she
passed the office of a presidential adviser, George Stephanopoulos,
the Starr report said. ``The president was inside alone, and he
beckoned her to enter,'' it went on. ``She told him that she had a
crush on him. He laughed, then asked if she would like to see his
private office.''
</P>
<P>
   He led her through a connecting door into the president's
private dining room and toward his private study off the Oval
Office. Ms. Lewinsky testified: ``We talked briefly and sort of
acknowledged that there had been a chemistry that was there before
and that we were both attracted to each other, and then he asked me
if he could kiss me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the windowless hallway adjacent to the study, they kissed,
the report said, and before returning to her desk she wrote down
her name and telephone number for the president.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, Clinton signed a $36.9 billion appropriations bill
to provide money for the Department of Transportation and related
agencies for the fiscal year that had begun on Oct. 1. The sum was
only $1.4 billion less than the Clinton administration had sought
from Congress, and the White House expressed hearty satisfaction
with the outcome of the bipartisan bill.
</P>
<P>
   The Starr report quoted Ms. Lewinsky as saying she was alone in
Panetta's office at about 10 p.m. when the president walked in. He
invited her to rendezvous again in Stephanopoulos' office in a few
minutes and she agreed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   They again returned to the private study and ``this time the
lights in the study were off,'' the report said. After a kiss, it
said, a sexual encounter ensued. Because the study had uncovered
windows, it took place, as did others later, in the windowless
hallway adjacent to the study, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``During many of their sexual encounters, the president stood
leaning against the doorway of the bathroom across from the study,
which, he told Ms. Lewinsky, eased his sore back,'' the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   During the encounter, the telephone rang; the president answered
it in the study, and, while the sexual encounter continued there,
he talked with a person Ms. Lewinsky took to be a member of
Congress, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   White House records show Clinton talked to Democratic Reps. Jim
Chapman Jr. of Texas from 9:25 to 9:30 p.m., and John Tanner of
Tennessee from 9:31 to 9:35 p.m., but no mention of a call after 10
p.m. was made. Before and after the sexual episode, the report
said, Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton talked.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point during the conversation,'' the report said, ``the
president tugged on the pink intern pass hanging from her neck and
said that it might be a problem. Ms. Lewinsky thought that he was
talking about access _ interns were not supposed to be in the West
Wing without an escort _ and, in addition, that he might have
discerned some `impropriety' in a sexual relationship with a White
House intern.''
</P>
<P>
   The duration of the conversation was unclear from the Starr
report, which noted only that Ms. Lewinsky left the White House
after midnight, and the president was logged out of the Oval Office
a short time later.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   NOV. 17, 1995
</P>
<P>
   The biggest government shutdown in history was in its fourth day
as the sharply diminished White House staff tried to cope with the
heavy flow of presidential pronouncements, correspondence,
meetings, interviews and other activities.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get the federal behemoth moving again, Clinton, as his
first task of the morning, sent Congress a stopgap financing bill
to get 800,000 federal employees back to work, but he gave no
ground in the budget impasse, warning that he would veto the
Republicans' latest spending plan.
</P>
<P>
   Panetta shuttled about Capitol Hill, seeking a deal, but the
Republicans, led by House Speaker Newt Gingrich, refused to
compromise on their plans for huge budget cuts, tax cuts and a
balanced budget in seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Gathering all the support he could muster, the president met at
the White House with a delegation from the Leadership Council of
Aging Organizations, representing 41 consumer, research and trade
groups. They urged him to veto any bill that would cut money for
older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also had a 15-minute Oval Office meeting with Alaska's
Democratic governor, Tony Knowles, who tried without success to
persuade the president that oil drilling would have no long-term
ill effects in an Arctic wildlife refuge in his state.
</P>
<P>
   The president also acted on several foreign-affairs matters. He
rebuked Congress over a Republican-sponsored bill to bar spending
to deploy American troops to Bosnia, saying it could torpedo the
peace talks in Ohio. In a lengthy telephone call, he talked with
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa about a tough multilateral
response to Nigeria's hanging of nine human rights advocates,
including Ken Saro-Wiwa, the writer.
</P>
<P>
   And in an Oval Office interview with Japanese journalists,
Clinton said he would reschedule his state visit to Japan but was
vague about the timing. ``I will come as soon as I can,'' he said.
``This is very, very important to me. I hope the Japanese people
will understand this is no expression of disrespect by me, either
to the government nor the people of Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said the United States' overall military commitment to
Japan (47,000 troops) and the Asia-Pacific rim (100,000 troops)
would not be diminished, despite calls for reductions in the wake
of the rape of a Japanese girl in Okinawa, in which three American
servicemen had been accused.
</P>
<P>
   On this Friday night, two days after what Ms. Lewinsky said had
been their first sexual encounter, both Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky
worked late. White House logs show she checked out at 8:56 p.m. but
returned at 9:38 p.m. for a little over an hour, according to
Starr's report. She was still working in Panetta's West Wing
office.
</P>
<P>
   The report said that at 9:45 p.m., Clinton stepped into
Panetta's office for one minute, and then returned to the Oval
Office. Because they were working late, Betty Currie, the
president's personal secretary, and other staff members had sent
out for pizza, Ms. Lewinsky recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down to let them know that the pizza was there, and it
was at that point when I walked into Mrs. Currie's office that the
president was standing there with some other people discussing
something,'' Ms. Lewinsky testified. ``And they all came back to
the office, and Mr. _ I think it was Mr. Toiv _ somebody
accidentally knocked pizza on my jacket, so I went to go use the
restroom to wash it off, and as I was coming out of the restroom,
the president was standing in Mrs. Currie's doorway and said, `You
can come out this way.''' Barry Toiv was Panetta's chief aide.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky and the president went back to the private study
off the Oval Office, and there she and the president kissed, she
testified. After a few minutes, she said, she told him she had to
return to her desk, but Clinton suggested that she bring him some
pizza.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later, the report said, she returned to the Oval
Office with the pizza and told Mrs. Currie, who was now back in her
office, that Clinton had asked for the pizza. Mrs. Currie opened
the door for her and said, ``Sir, the girl's here with the pizza.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me to come in,'' Ms. Lewinsky testified. ``Mrs. Currie
went back to her office and then we went into the back study area
again.'' A sexual encounter similar to the first ensued in the
windowless hallway, Ms. Lewinsky related.
</P>
<P>
   While it was taking place, Mrs. Currie approached the hallway
door, which was ajar, and said the president had a phone call, the
Starr report said. It quoted Ms. Lewinsky as saying the caller was
a congressman with a nickname. Records show that Clinton spoke to
Rep. Sonny Callahan, R-Ala., for 21 minutes, from 9:53 p.m. to
10:14 p.m. The sexual encounter continued while the president was
on the phone, the Starr report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this visit,'' the report said, ``according to Ms.
Lewinsky, the president told her that he liked her smile and her
energy. He also said: `I'm usually around on weekends, no one else
is around, and you can come and see me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky was logged out of the White House at 10:39 p.m. The
president went back to the chief of staff's office until 10:34
p.m., and then went by the Oval Office and the ground floor
corridors into the president's private residence at 10:40 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition in the Paula Jones case last Jan. 17, the
president said he could not recall most of his encounters with Ms.
Lewinsky, but did remember her ``back there with a pizza'' during
the government shutdown. But he said he did not believe they were
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Testifying before the grand jury on Aug. 17, Clinton said his
first ``real conversation'' with Ms. Lewinsky took place during the
November 1995 furlough. ``One night she brought me some pizza,'' he
testified, according to the Starr report. ``We had some remarks.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   DEC. 31, 1995
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had still not achieved a budget agreement with Congress,
and 280,000 federal workers were on furlough in a second shutdown.
But public opinion polls showed Clinton's approval rating way up,
from a woeful 1994 (as low as 40 percent) to a quite successful
year-end 1995 (in the high 50s).
</P>
<P>
   The reasons were not hard to find: a humming economy, Clinton's
tough stand against unpopular Republican budget cuts, foreign
policy advances in Bosnia, Northern Ireland and the Middle East.
And his longtime political confidant, Dick Morris, was at work
masterminding the 1996 re-election, in which conservative themes
like ``family values'' would play an important role.
</P>
<P>
   It was a quiet Sunday. The president had no scheduled public
appearances, aside from attending early church services. But before
he could leave for a holiday weekend that afternoon with his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, and their daughter, Chelsea, then 15, he
had one meeting on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   At 9:50 a.m., moments before budget talks in the Cabinet Room,
Clinton and congressional leaders spoke to reporters. There was a
light holiday mood to the exchanges. The president said they were
driving hard to settle the budget impasse and would keep at it.
Reminded that thousands of federal employees were still on
furlough, Sen. Bob Dole, the majority leader, said he and his
colleagues would ``try to pass something.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked: ``Are you closer?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' the Kansas senator said to a roar, ``we're about 6 feet
apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Daschle, to more laughter, added, ``We'll be a lot closer in a
couple of hours.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working at it steady,'' Clinton said, adding, ``Happy
New Year, everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The talks ended at midday, amicably but inconclusively.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton retreated to the Oval Office at 12:11 p.m., the logs
show.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, by now a staff member in the White House Office of
Legislative Affairs, testified that she was in the pantry of the
president's private dining room, talking to a White House steward,
Bayani Nelvis, sometime between noon and 1 p.m. She told Nelvis
that she had recently smoked her first cigar, and he offered to
give her one of the president's cigars, the Starr report said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just then, the president came down the hallway from the Oval
Office and saw Ms. Lewinsky,'' the report said. ``The president
dispatched Mr. Nelvis to deliver something to Mr. Panetta.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky, the report said, told Clinton that Nelvis had
promised her a cigar, and the president gave her one.
</P>
<P>
   The report went on: ``She told him her name _ she had the
impression that he had forgotten it in the six weeks since their
furlough encounters because, when passing her in the hallway, he
had called her `Kiddo.' The president replied that he knew her
name; in fact, he added, having lost the phone number she had given
him, he had tried to find her in the phone book.''
</P>
<P>
   By Ms. Lewinsky's account, they moved into the private study and
a sexual encounter took place, their third. It followed the pattern
of the first two: It was halted before climax by the president, the
report quoted Ms. Lewinsky as saying. Apparently in explanation, it
said she testified, ``He didn't know me well enough, or he didn't
trust me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The logs show that Ms. Lewinsky left the White House at 1:16
p.m., and that Clinton went to the White House residence at 1:15
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Later, the president, Mrs. Clinton, and Chelsea flew to Hilton
Head, S.C., for their traditional year-end family retreat called
Renaissance Weekend. It was their 12th straight year at the
gathering, at which the Clintons partied late on New Year's Eve
with 1,000 of their closest friends, then attended a New Year's Day
seminar on personal growth and family values.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JAN. 7, 1996
</P>
<P>
   The blizzard of 1996 had blanketed the East Coast over the
weekend, paralyzing New York, Washington and everything in between.
The president, wearing blue jeans and a red and black checked
shirt, and Mrs. Clinton, in a purple fur-lined hat and a
multicolored winter jacket, were among a few worshippers this
Sunday morning at St. John's Episcopal Church, two blocks from the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ignoring their waiting motorcade, the Clintons trudged home
through calf-high drifts and wind-whipped snowflakes. At one point,
the president playfully scooped up a handful of snow as if to throw
it and cheerfully told reporters that congressional Democrats had
canceled plans to visit him to discuss their continuing budget
confrontation with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had ended a three-week shutdown of federal programs on
Saturday when he bowed to Republican demands and offered a new
seven-year balanced-budget plan. That triggered congressional
action to finance all government programs, but only through Jan.
26. Still, the Republicans were all over the Sunday morning talk
shows, vowing to balance the budget by 2002 and denouncing the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about whether or not there's two snow
jobs going on in Washington,'' Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the
majority whip, said on CBS' ``Face the Nation.'' ``Now we feel like
Charlie Brown, and Lucy has got the football, and every time you
think you're going to get a real budget it gets jerked away from
you.''
</P>
<P>
   On NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Rep. Tom DeLay of Texas, the House
majority whip, was threatening another shutdown, or at least a
cutoff of government services the Republicans did not support.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to fund only those programs we want to fund,''
DeLay said. ``We're in charge. We don't have to negotiate with the
Senate; we don't have to negotiate with the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans were no less bellicose on the subject of Mrs.
Clinton, accusing her of not telling the truth in the Whitewater
investigation or about the dismissal of aides in the White House
travel office.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's answers are ``not the truth,'' Sen. Alfonse
D'Amato, R-N.Y., said on ABC's ``This Week With David Brinkley.''
``We've had this kind of thing over and over again from her people
who have stonewalled us, who have feigned memory loss.''
</P>
<P>
   One poll showed Clinton trailing Dole, the Republican
front-runner for president, 46 percent to 49 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton told reporters he was going to spend the rest of the day
holed up with Panetta and other aides, working on the budget.
</P>
<P>
   But early that afternoon, he telephoned Ms. Lewinsky at her
apartment in the Watergate complex, the first time he had called
her at home, according to the Starr report. He said he was going to
be in his office, she remembered, adding, ``I said, oh, do you want
some company? And he said, oh, that would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   By now, she testified, they had worked out signals for their
encounters. ``I got there kind of saying, `Oh, gee, here are your
letters,' wink, wink, wink, and him saying `OK, that's good,''' she
said. She carried a folder as cover, but her job did not involve
delivering letters.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, Ms. Lewinsky said, they ``made an arrangement that
... he would have the door to his office open, and I would pass by
the office with some papers and then ... he would sort of stop me
and invite me in. So, that was exactly what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   They went to the bathroom of the back study and had a sexual
encounter, she said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   JAN. 21, 1996
</P>
<P>
   Like the rest of the East Coast, Washington was fighting floods.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Jordan, the city's director of the Office of Emergency
Preparedness, had been up all night, watching the rain-swollen
Potomac rise nearly 14 feet, twice its usual height, and flooding
part of Georgetown along K Street near the Tidal Basin and the
waterfront fish market. Jordan worried that the river would rise
another foot before it ebbed.
</P>
<P>
   Swollen streams and rivers in eight states had ravaged homes and
businesses. Some of the flooding was receding, but 10,000 residents
were still being evacuated in West Virginia along the surging Ohio
River. About 1,100 homes on Wheeling Island alone were under 6 feet
of water, their 3,000 occupants refugees. Pennsylvania appeared
hardest hit, with homes and businesses submerged or caked in mud,
power and telephone lines down, and debris littering the streets.
Clinton declared the state a federal disaster area, making
available temporary housing, home repair grants and emergency
loans.
</P>
<P>
   On the television talk shows, his opponents attacked him over
the Whitewater investigation, while the House majority leader, Dick
Armey of Texas, threatened to block the nation's ability to borrow
money to pay its bills unless Clinton yielded to Republicans'
budget-cutting to decrease ``the size and intrusiveness of
government.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same show, NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' Panetta protested
the Republican emphasis on Whitewater, saying: ``There is a fine
line between what is a legitimate continuing inquiry into a
situation and what becomes political harassment. I think they're
getting dangerously close to harassment.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point the first family had a private tour for more than
an hour of the wildly popular Vermeer exhibition at the National
Gallery of Art. Accompanied by several friends, including a former
college roommate of Mrs. Clinton, they gazed at the luminous blues
and yellows, the subtle reflected light and the pearly highlights
of the 21 paintings, which represented much of Vermeer's known
output.
</P>
<P>
   The president logged into the Oval Office at 3:33 p.m. Ms.
Lewinsky's name does not appear on the White House logs, but
according to the Starr report, she ran into Clinton in a hallway
near an elevator in the West Wing and he invited her into the Oval
Office. They had had phone sex for the first time the week before,
the report said, and she was ``feeling a little bit insecure''
about whether he had enjoyed it. Eventually, she testified, they
had phone sex on 10 to 15 occasions.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting this Sunday, Ms. Lewinsky remembered
questioning him about his interest in her, saying, ``I asked him
why he doesn't ask me any questions about myself, and ... is this
just about sex ... or do you have some interest in trying to know
me as a person?'' The president laughed, she said, and replied that
``he cherishes the time that he had with me.'' She thought the
reply was ``a little bit odd,'' because she ``felt like he didn't
really even know me yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As they moved to the hallway by the study, Ms. Lewinsky was in
midsentence when Clinton suddenly kissed her and they had a sexual
encounter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point during the encounter, someone entered the Oval
Office,'' the report said, prompting Clinton to leave her in the
hallway.
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the president was told his next appointment,
a friend from Arkansas, had arrived, and he escorted Ms. Lewinsky
out through a connecting office. She was signed out of the White
House at 3:56 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his daughter ventured through snow to attend Sunday
morning services at Foundry United Methodist Church, where the
senior minister, J. Philip Wogaman, warned the dozens of government
officials among his congregation not to abuse the public trust by
going on what he called ``power trips.''
</P>
<P>
   A deep freeze gripped much of the South that day, after a week
of snow, ice and record cold blamed for 55 deaths across the lower
48 states. Temperatures hovered around zero in parts of
Mississippi, Georgia and Alabama, and Florida's $1.2 billion citrus
industry was in peril.
</P>
<P>
   It was frosty, too, at the annual meeting of the National
Governors' Conference, which took up part of the President's
official day. At a White House dinner, Republicans eyed the mansion
like house hunters on a real estate tour. Fresh from the attack on
that morning's ``Meet the Press,'' Michigan's Republican governor,
John Engler, said he expected a different party to be in residence
in 1997. ``Next year, I'll arrive in a festive mood,'' he said at
the dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the administration put last-minute touches to a budget
statement due the next day, government officials unveiled data that
showed that Medicare's Hospital Insurance Trust Fund had lost money
in 1995 for the first time in 23 years, meaning the Medicare
program was poorer than anybody thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things turned out a little worse than we expected,'' said
Richard Foster, chief actuary of the Federal Health Care Financing
Administration, which runs Medicare for 37 million people who are
elderly or disabled. In Israel, Prime Minister Shimon Peres leaked
word he planned to call for new elections ahead of schedule. The
elections would bring the hard-line Likud leader Benjamin Netanyahu
to power, threatening the Oslo peace accords with the Palestinians
that Clinton hoped would be his enduring foreign policy triumph.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, Mrs. Clinton's book, ``It Takes a Village,''
was on the best-seller lists, having soared to No. 1 within a week
of publication.
</P>
<P>
   In the White House, Ms. Lewinsky was in her office, and that
afternoon, she received a phone call from Clinton. Her sexual
encounters with him were usually on the weekend, she said, when
there were fewer people about.
</P>
<P>
   This time, at her suggestion, they bumped into each other in the
hallway because, she said, ``when it happened accidentally, that
seemed to work really well.'' Clinton was in the Oval Office from
3:36 p.m. to 7:05 p.m., logs show; there is no record of Ms.
Lewinsky. They walked together into the private study, where they
had a sexual encounter.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, they sat and talked awhile, maybe 45 minutes, in the
Oval Office, and Ms. Lewinsky testified that she thought their
friendship was starting to blossom. He said he would call her again
and, perhaps mindful of her previous unease, she remembered saying,
``yeah, well, what's my phone number?'' He recited both her home
and office numbers and, the report said, he called her at her desk
later that afternoon to tell her he had enjoyed their time
together.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MARCH 31, 1996
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was looking forward on this Sunday to throwing the first
ball for opening day of the baseball season on Monday at the
Baltimore Orioles' stadium, Camden Yards. But rain delayed the
all-American photo op.
</P>
<P>
   In Russia, President Boris N. Yeltsin, also facing a tough
re-election battle, said he could not win while the war was still
going on in secessionist Chechnya, and he vowed to halt military
operations against the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   In Bosnia, Defense Secretary William Perry visited U.S. troops
who were part of the NATO peacekeeping force. There was talk of
capturing the Serb leaders indicted by an international tribunal as
war criminals, Gen. Ratko Mladic and Radovan Karadzic, whose
continued freedom was an embarrassment to the administration. It
never happened.
</P>
<P>
   At home, Dole had clinched the Republican presidential
nomination earlier in the month and was assembling a team of
economic advisers. Behind the scenes, the president's political
consultant Dick Morris _ who would be brought down by his own
sexual scandal _ sharpened the Clinton advertising campaign to
focus on Dole. But the expensive advertisements, paid for with
so-called soft money, would later lead to calls for an
investigation into Democratic fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   Things had not been going well in recent weeks for Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   More than a month earlier, on Feb. 19, President's Day, Clinton
telephoned her at her Watergate apartment, Ms. Lewinsky testified,
and she could tell from the tone of his voice that something was
wrong. She asked to see him, but he said he did not know how long
he would be at the office that day.
</P>
<P>
   Worried, she hurried to the White House, the only time she had
gone uninvited to the Oval Office, she said. There, the president
told her he no longer felt right about their relationship and he
had to put a stop to it. She could visit, he said, but only as a
friend. He hugged her, according to the report, but would not kiss
her.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ms. Lewinsky said, in the following days ``there
continued to be this sort of flirtation.'' Clinton called her
apartment, the report said, expressing regret that she had left the
White House early, which she thought ``sort of implied to me that
he was interested in starting up again.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, March 29, while Mrs. Clinton was in Greece, Ms.
Lewinsky ran into the president wearing the first necktie she had
given him. She asked him where he had gotten it. ``Some girl with
style gave it to me,'' she remembered he replied.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested she might want to casually join a group seeing a
movie at the White House theater, but she said she did not want
people to think she was hanging around the West Wing uninvited. She
said that she asked if they could arrange a rendezvous over the
weekend, and that he said he would try.
</P>
<P>
   They did meet that Sunday, March 31, while Mrs. Clinton was
still away. ``According to Ms. Lewinsky, the president telephoned
her at her desk and suggested she come to the Oval Office on the
pretext of delivering papers to him,'' the report said. ``She went
to the Oval Office and was admitted by a plainclothes Secret
Service agent. In her folder was a gift for the president, a Hugo
Boss necktie.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the hallway by the study, the president and Ms. Lewinsky
kissed,'' the report went on, and had a sexual encounter. After
they were finished, the report said, ``Ms. Lewinsky left the Oval
Office and walked through the Rose Garden.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton returned from her trip that evening.
</P>
<P>
   APRIL 7, 1996
</P>
<P>
   It was a bone-chilling Easter Sunday, the exhausting conclusion
of one of the most emotional weeks of the Clinton presidency. Four
days earlier, a military plane carrying Commerce Secretary Ron
Brown and 34 others had slammed into a mountainside near Dubrovnik,
Croatia, killing everyone on board.
</P>
<P>
   And so it had been a week of personal mourning, a black stretch
Clinton spoke of as ``this interminable week.'' Brown had been a
good friend of the president, and in the days following the
tragedy, Clinton postponed or canceled almost all of his scheduled
events to devote himself to propping up the emotions of a grieving
White House and comforting the families and friends of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, though, he did go ahead and visit another somber
destination, traveling to Oklahoma City in advance of the one-year
anniversary of the April 19 bombing of the federal building.
</P>
<P>
   There were other world events to preoccupy the president.
Fighting between rebels and government soldiers was continuing in
the capital of Liberia, and North Korean troops had entered a
buffer zone with South Korea for the third day.
</P>
<P>
   But the president found it hard to focus on much other than the
deaths on the Croatian cliff. He had to blot tears from his eyes on
Saturday, as he watched the coffins bearing the bodies arriving at
Dover Air Force Base in Delaware. ``We were all holding up pretty
well until they started taking the coffins off the plane,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But now it was Easter, and as was the Clinton family custom, the
president, accompanied by his wife and Chelsea, attended the 11
a.m. service at the Foundry Methodist Church, brightly decorated
with lilies, azaleas and balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The president wore a dark suit. Mrs. Clinton chose a white coat
and black hat graced with a white band and pink flower. Chelsea was
dressed in a navy skirt and blazer. Secret Service agents
interrupted the Easter egg hunt on the church lawn so the first
family could enter.
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman, the church's senior minister, praised Brown and the
``practical goodness'' of those who accompanied him on his trip.
``Easter is God's reply to those in heartsick sorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wogaman also singled out Adam Darling, a 29-year-old
confidential assistant at the Commerce Department, who died in the
crash and was a member of the church.
</P>
<P>
   During Clinton's presidential campaign, Darling had endeared
himself to Clinton by offering to ride a bicycle across the country
in support of the candidate. Darling's parents attended the
service, and they requested that his favorite hymn, ``This Is My
Song,'' be sung. It begins: ``This is my song, O God of all the
nations, a song of peace for lands afar and mine.''
</P>
<P>
   The sermon was about resurrection. During it, Wogaman
complimented the president for having ``ministered so well for our
land.''
</P>
<P>
   As the congregation left the church, shafts of sun finally broke
through the clouds. On the way back to the White House, the
Clintons stopped and shared a quiet Sunday brunch at the Four
Seasons Hotel in Georgetown.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent the balance of the afternoon, from 2:21 to 7:48,
in the Oval Office. At one point, the Starr report said, he called
Ms. Lewinsky at her apartment.
</P>
<P>
   According to her grand jury testimony, they spoke of the death
of Brown, and then she told him of a fresh personal trauma of her
own. On the previous Friday, she had been advised by Timothy
Keating, staff director for legislative affairs, that she was being
transferred from her White House job and moved to the Pentagon
because she was ``too sexy'' to be working in the East Wing.
</P>
<P>
   A number of White House aides had become increasingly
uncomfortable about how much time she was spending in the vicinity
of the Oval Office, particularly as the campaign heated up. Ms.
Lewinsky said she later learned from the president that Evelyn
Lieberman, the deputy chief of staff, thought Ms. Lewinsky was
paying too much attention to the president and ``everyone needed to
be careful before the election.''
</P>
<P>
   When she learned she was being transferred, Ms. Lewinsky said,
she was crushed and felt it was because of her relationship with
the president.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton seemed disturbed by the news, the report said. Ms.
Lewinsky was sobbing as she related the details to him. Then she
asked if she could come see him. He agreed.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:56 p.m., according to White House logs, Ms. Lewinsky
arrived at the White House carrying a manila folder and, under the
pretext of delivering documents to the president, was admitted to
the Oval Office. She met with the president in his private study,
where they spoke further about her expulsion from the White House
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do they have to take you away from me?'' she testified
that he asked her. According to her testimony, he looked at her and
said, ``I promise you if I win in November I'll bring you back like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   She said in her testimony that he told her he would find out why
she was transferred, and he said that she could have whatever job
she desired after the election.
</P>
<P>
   Then, according to the Starr report, she began a sexual
encounter with him in the hallway between the private study and the
Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Someone in the Oval Office called out that the president had a
phone call, the report went on. A White House operator had put the
call through to the Oval Office, the report said, but when no one
picked it up, a Secret Service agent was dispatched to locate the
president.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, he knocked on the door to the Oval
Office, got no answer and then entered. Seeing the door to the
study ajar, the report said, he called out, ``Mr. President.''
Getting no answer, he called out again louder. The agent heard
someone say ``Huh?'' from the study and then, after the agent said
that there was a call for the president, Clinton replied that he
would take it.
</P>
<P>
   The report said Clinton picked up the call in the study,
directing Ms. Lewinsky to continue her sexual actions with him
while he spoke on the phone. According to White House records cited
in the report, the call lasted nine minutes and was from Morris,
the political consultant.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes after the president hung up, the report said,
there was a second interruption. The report quoted Ms. Lewinsky as
testifying: ``Harold Ickes has a very distinct voice and ... I
heard him holler, `Mr. President,' and the president looked at me
and I looked at him and he jetted out into the Oval Office and I
panicked.'' She retreated in the other direction, leaving through
the dining room. It was nearly 5:30.
</P>
<P>
   Two minutes after Ms. Lewinsky left, the report said, Clinton
called Ms. Lieberman, though it is unclear whether he reached her.
</P>
<P>
   That evening, the report said, Clinton telephoned Ms. Lewinsky
at home and asked her why she had fled so hastily. He seemed upset
that she had left.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   FEB. 28, 1997
</P>
<P>
   There were big doings for Chelsea in the works. Yesterday, she
had turned 17. To mark the moment, Mr. and Mrs. Clinton had given a
dinner for her and 10 of her friends at the Bombay Club, just a
block's walk from the White House. There was chocolate cheesecake
and a rendition of ``Happy Birthday'' by the pianist, with the
whole restaurant singing along.
</P>
<P>
   While the president and the first lady took the presidential
limousine back, Chelsea insisted on riding in the van with her
giggling friends. But that was just the prelude. The Clintons were
leaving for New York tomorrow to take their daughter to see some
Broadway plays, something she was very much looking forward to.
</P>
<P>
   Before they could set out, though, the president spent a
workaday Friday attending to drug policy and cigarette sales and
Midwestern winter storms. His major announcement was to certify
Mexico as a full ally in the war against illegal drugs, though only
after the Mexican government agreed to commitments demanded by U.S.
law enforcement agencies. For the second year, Clinton did not
certify Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   There was other international and domestic news for him to
ponder. The FBI was frustrated that the Saudis were not doing more
to investigate a truck bombing that had killed 19 American airmen.
The Democratic Party, in one more development in the protracted
campaign finance drama, said it would be returning $1.5 million
more in contributions that it now felt may have been illegal or
improper.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before 11 a.m., Clinton appeared in the Roosevelt Room
and spoke about an initiative to toughen the rules on cigarette
sales to children. Among the new rules was a requirement that
anyone under 21 who bought a tobacco product was to show a photo ID
so that store clerks no longer had to guess the age of customers.
</P>
<P>
   On the legislative front, Clinton signed into law H.J. Res. 36,
which released money for international population assistance
programs. He gave out a statement celebrating the third anniversary
of the ``Brady Act,'' which provided for a waiting period before
someone could buy a handgun, calling the law ``one of the most
effective public safety measures ever.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the day, the president announced plans for
several appointments, including his nomination of Joel Klein as
assistant attorney general in the antitrust division of the
Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   He declared a major disaster in South Dakota, which had been
pummeled by a severe winter storm in November, and ordered federal
aid to supplement state and local recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   He also freed $250 million for a program to teach Americans
about the harmful psychological and physical effects of sex before
marriage. The program was to stress that abstinence from
extramarital sex was the expected standard of the country.
</P>
<P>
   It had been almost 11 months since the president had had
physical contact with Ms. Lewinsky. Her expulsion to the Pentagon
had succeeded in separating them. The only times she encountered
him were at group events. She had seen him at a reception for the
Saxophone Club, a political organization, and went with her family
to one of the tapings of the president's weekly radio addresses.
</P>
<P>
   She got into the president's 50th birthday party at Radio City
Music Hall in New York, as well as a cocktail party for major
donors to the Democratic Party. She testified that she saw him at a
fund-raiser for Senate Democrats. Noticing that he was wearing a
necktie she had given him, she approached him at the event and told
him, ``Hey, handsome, I like your tie.'' She testified that he
called her later that night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was insecure about the relationship at times and thought
that he would come to forget me easily,'' the Starr report said Ms.
Lewinsky testified. ``Usually when I'd see him, it would kind of
prompt him to call me. So I made an effort. I would go early and
stand in the front so I could see him.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said the two continued to talk with some regularity
by phone, especially in the months after she began her job at the
Pentagon. During the fall '96 campaign, the report said, the
president occasionally called while on the road without Mrs.
Clinton. At least seven of those conversations, the report said,
were sexually explicit. But Ms. Lewinsky complained that she had
not seen him privately and, according to her testimony, he told
her, ``Every day can't be sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 14, 1997, Ms. Lewinsky placed a Valentine's Day ad in
The Washington Post intended as a love message to the president. It
was addressed to ``Handsome.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6:29 p.m. on this Friday, Clinton went to the Roosevelt Room
and taped his weekly radio address to the nation. Among those who
attended the taping was Ms. Lewinsky. According to her testimony,
Clinton had extended an invitation to her through Betty Currie, his
personal secretary.
</P>
<P>
   In the address, which was broadcast the next morning, Clinton
spoke of the need to prevent drugs from ruining children's lives.
``First, we must fight drugs before they reach our borders and keep
them out of America,'' he said, and he explained his decision that
day to enlist Mexico in the battle.
</P>
<P>
   At the session, Ms. Lewinsky had her picture taken with the
president. She was nervous, the report said she testified, for she
had not been alone with him since her days working at the White
House. She wore a navy blue dress that she had bought at the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, Clinton told her to see Mrs. Currie
after the photo was taken, since he had something to give her.
Clinton, Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs. Currie together went into the back
office. Stephen Goodin, an aide to the president, had told Clinton
and Mrs. Currie that he did not want him alone with Ms. Lewinsky,
which was why Mrs. Currie chaperoned them, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie, however, said, ``I'll be right back,'' and went on
to the back dining room where, she testified, she waited for 15 to
20 minutes while the president and Ms. Lewinsky were alone in the
study. As belated Christmas presents, Clinton gave Ms. Lewinsky a
hat pin and an edition of Walt Whitman's ``Leaves of Grass.'' He
told her he had seen her Valentine's Day message.
</P>
<P>
   In the hallway near a bathroom, Ms. Lewinsky testified, she
engaged in a sexual encounter with Clinton. He heard something and
they retreated into the bathroom, but no one disturbed them.
According to White House logs cited in the report, Ms. Lewinsky
left the White House at 7:07 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The next time she got out her navy blue Gap dress, according to
the report, she noticed stains near one hip and on the front of the
dress. After seeing the president, she had gone out to dinner. She
thought the stains might be spinach dip. FBI tests, the report
said, later revealed them to be the semen of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   MARCH 29, 1997
</P>
<P>
   It was a lethargic Saturday. The White House was quiet, and the
president was in something of a funk. He had been forced into a
state of unwanted inactivity. It had been only two weeks since
Clinton had tripped on the stairs of the Florida home of the golf
champion Greg Norman and injured his knee, negating the president's
appearance in a member-guest tournament with Norman.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton had gone ahead with a Helsinki summit meeting
with President Boris Yeltsin of Russia a week earlier, at which he
had to be lowered from a catering truck in a wheelchair, his public
schedule had otherwise been sharply curtailed. At most, he attended
one or two brief events a day. Today he had none.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Easter was at hand, and tomorrow the president would be
presiding over the annual Easter Egg Roll on the South Lawn of the
White House. There was a need to prepare for an Oval Office meeting
on Tuesday with King Hussein of Jordan. A whole year had passed
since the death of Ron Brown, and there would be a memorial service
on Thursday that the president would attend.
</P>
<P>
   On sleepy days like this, Clinton usually changed into his
jogging shorts and took to the roadways or, better yet, tuned up a
golf game grown rusty over the winter. Instead, because he was on
crutches, he was reduced to tasting spring by opening the door of
his study or relaxing on the Truman balcony overlooking the Rose
Garden.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, he was home alone. Mrs. Clinton and Chelsea were
on the last leg of a six-nation trip to Africa. On this final day,
they were to tour a women's skills center in Asmara, take in a
tree-planting ceremony and pay a courtesy visit to Isayas Afewerki,
the president of Eritrea.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton put on a white, gauzy cotton dress known as a tilfi
and danced merrily with the leader of Africa's newest democracy.
She was scheduled to return to Washington at 7 the next morning, in
plenty of time to attend the Easter Egg Roll with her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Even the vice president was away, on a diplomatic mission in
Asia. And so Clinton was reading, watching basketball and growing
restless.
</P>
<P>
   In his Easter radio address, broadcast at 10:06 in the morning,
Clinton concentrated on the promise of spring, though there was
still too much of a winter snap in the Washington air. ``Spring is
a season of renewal, not just of the world around us but of the
ideals inside us, those that bind us together as people,'' Clinton
said in the address. ``Millions of families will come together to
celebrate Easter this weekend and Passover in the coming weeks, to
reaffirm their faith in God and their commitment to our sacred
values.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to speak of the need to overcome ``the divide of
race.'' He spoke of a 13-year-old Chicago boy who the previous week
had been riding his bike home from a basketball game and was
attacked and nearly beaten to death. The boy was black and his
accused attackers were white. Clinton finished by saying: ``The
holidays of this season teach us that hope can spring forth from
the darkest of times. Those of us who are Christians celebrate a
risen God who died a painful, very human death to redeem the souls
of all humanity without regard to race or station.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the afternoon, Clinton repaired to the Oval Office. At
one point, the Starr report said, he called Ms. Lewinsky and
invited her over. He said he had something important to tell her.
</P>
<P>
   A little past 2, Ms. Lewinsky showed up. Mrs. Currie greeted her
and took her to the president's study to await Clinton. He hobbled
in.
</P>
<P>
   The president talked at length to Ms. Lewinsky about his
concerns that others might learn of their rendezvous, the Starr
report said. Without specifically identifying it, he told her that
he feared that a foreign embassy was tapping his telephones.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, he recommended cover stories if they
were found out, suggesting that she insist that they were only
friends. Should anyone have tapes of intimate phone conversations,
well, then she should say they knew that someone was eavesdropping
on the calls and thus they simply feigned the exchanges, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Then he kissed her and they had a sexual encounter, she said,
although Clinton later implicitly denied ``inappropriate'' contact
with her that day.
</P>
<P>
   She left at 3:16 p.m. A few minutes later, Clinton left his
office as well. This was, the Starr report says, Monica Lewinsky's
10th and final sexual act with Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   EPILOGUE
</P>
<P>
   In the nine months after the last of the White House sexual
trysts, the Starr report says, the relationship between Clinton and
Ms. Lewinsky crumbled inexorably under the president's fear of
exposure and Ms. Lewinsky's growing frustrations at being shut out
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   They met several more times, and had numerous telephone
conversations. They also exchanged small gifts and expressions of
endearment. But the Starr report details a postsexual deterioration
that spills from argument and recrimination to growing suspicions
and finally mutual distrust and even threats by Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the alternating periods of anger and appeasement, there
were hopeless musings about a possible future together. Letters and
notes were exchanged, and then destroyed in an effort to get rid of
evidence of their affair. Most of their gifts were retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   She had been banished to the Pentagon, but the president
promised to bring her back to the White House, and later to get her
a job in New York, perhaps at the United Nations. He enlisted the
help of aides and friends, including Vernon Jordan, his longtime
friend.
</P>
<P>
   But none of it worked out, and she harangued him about these
failures and her exclusion from his life. In an Oval Office meeting
on July 4, 1997, the report said, Clinton reprimanded her for a
letter in which she had obliquely threatened to disclose their
relationship. ``It's illegal to threaten the president of the
United States,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   The president showed increasing fear as the arm's-length
relationship dragged on, and it expressed itself in his harsher
tones to her. In a face-to-face argument on Dec. 6., Ms. Lewinsky
recalled, he told her he had ``never been treated as poorly by
anyone else as I had treated him.''
</P>
<P>
   When the story of their relationship finally broke on Jan. 21,
the president, in meetings with aides, denied he had ever been
alone with Ms. Lewinsky. He told Sidney Blumenthal, a White House
communications adviser, that she ``came on to me and made a sexual
demand on me,'' and that when he rebuffed her, she had threatened
to say they had had an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal later testified that the president had spoken like a
trapped man.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like a character in a novel,'' he quoted Clinton as
saying. ``I feel like somebody who is surrounded by an oppressive
force that is creating a lie about me and I can't get the truth
out. I feel like the character in the novel `Darkness at Noon.'''
</P>
<P>
   The protagonist in Arthur Koestler's 1941 novel was a man caught
up in the Moscow purges and political trials of the 1930s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2105EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
