</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAFTER KEEPS CROWN WITH DASH AND SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His signature sunscreen mask had already melted away,
and his signature ponytail was flying at half-mast, but Patrick
Rafter, who put his signature on the U.S. Open's trophy for the
second consecutive year Sunday, was simply flying high.
</P>
<P>
   Dashing toward the net on a wing and a prayer, just the way he
had done since he was 9 and used his sprints to beat eight siblings
to the dinner table, the Australian acrobat completed a spirited
and successful defense of his 1997 Open title at the National
Tennis Center.
</P>
<P>
   Pestered only occasionally by the phalanx of jetliners that
mysteriously returned to the shared airspace above Arthur Ashe
Stadium and LaGuardia Airport one match ahead of schedule, the
third-seeded Rafter committed just five unforced errors during the
6-3, 3-6, 6-2, 6-0 pasting of his fellow Australian, Mark
Philippoussis, that secured him a second career Grand Slam crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go into a Grand Slam on adrenaline,'' said the 25-year-old
Rafter. ``Last year was more nerve-racking; nerves never really
played an issue in today's match.''
</P>
<P>
   As the contest wore on for 2 hours and 4 minutes, Philippoussis,
after barreling off to a 5-2 lead in the second set and shaking off
three double faults in the game that leveled the match, began to
doubt his ability to dethrone Rafter. ``Psychologically he never
recovered,'' Rafter said of the final set rout that transpired
after Philippoussis surrendered the third set on a service break.
</P>
<P>
   In that pivotal set, where the 6-foot-4-inch Philippoussis felt
he had been turned into such a big target that he ultimately turned
tail, Rafter made no unforced mistakes at all. The challenger
visibly buckled in the sixth game, after Rafter's frenzied
corner-to-corner scramble ended with a dash toward the net and
retrieval of a drop shot for a break point he converted for a 4-2
edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to hand it to Pat,'' said the loser, who had barely
spoken to Rafter since their springtime rift over Philippoussis'
decision to skip the Davis Cup. ``Five unforced errors in the whole
match, it's extremely impressive. Right now he's playing like the
best player in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The last man to etch his name on back-to-back U.S. Open titles
was Pete Sampras, the four-time champion Rafter ousted in five sets
in the semifinals. The top-seeded Sampras, who last repeated here
as champion in 1996, had hoped to capture a 12th career Grand Slam
at this Open, tying him with the record owned by Australia's Roy
Emerson, but he came up lame and went home empty-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Rafter, who again took home a Grand Slam title at the
expense of an unseeded challenger and now moves up a spot to No. 2
in the rankings. Rafter's victim in the first all-Australian U.S.
Open finale since Ken Rosewall's 1970 downing of Rafter's mentor,
Tony Roche, wore a familiar face: Philippoussis, a first-time Grand
Slam finalist who had never before passed a Grand Slam quarterfinal
and who has been a doubles partner, intramural arch-rival, and
sporadic alter-ego to Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter went the conventional Australian route and drew counsel
from icons ranging from Roche to Rod Laver to John Newcombe. But
Philippoussis took a maverick course and took orders from
outsiders, including his father, Nick, who drove a Melbourne cab to
support his son's tennis habit, and Nick Bollettieri, whose Florida
academy is Philippoussis' current home away from home.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, who hadn't won any of his eight titles until he made his
breakthrough run at the 1997 Open, and Philippoussis, a
late-bloomer with just one title under his belt, didn't receive
their 1998 wake-up calls until the year was half over.
</P>
<P>
   A downcast Rafter was buoyed by some unsolicited motivational
advice from Newcombe just before Wimbledon and went on to win two
hardcourts titles this summer, the first man since Ivan Lendl in
1987 to win a pair of summer titles plus the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   An even more discouraged Philippoussis, who made noise about
temporary retirement after a disappointing Wimbledon tune-up at
Queens, added Pat Cash to his coaching entourage and came into the
Open talking about being a title contender.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter's ability to survive the full seven rounds was all the
more remarkable for the treacherous start he made here. He was down
two-sets-to-none against Morocco's Hicham Arazi and in serious
danger of becoming the first Open champion to receive a first-round
dethroning.
</P>
<P>
   But he rallied, and besides beating Sampras for the second time
in a month, Rafter also defused the ever-dangerous Goran Ivanisevic
in the fourth round. It all proved ample preparation for facing the
service grenades regularly supplied by Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going in with any special voodoo treatments or
chanting or anything,'' Rafter had said of his approach to warding
off his opponent's larger-than-life serves, and it worked.
Philippoussis fired just five aces, one fewer than the winner, and
was so anxious about evading Rafter's well-placed returns that he
hurried into 13 double faults, the last of them at match point.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Philippoussis, Rafter double-faulted just once,
and he lost his cool just once, when he slammed his racquet to the
court during a difficult hold for 3-2 in the third set.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not quite as euphoric as last year, but it's very
satisfying,'' Rafter said after doing the one thing Sampras had
earlier termed the hardest thing to do in his sport: return to the
scene of a seven-round sweep and successfully defend a Grand Slam
title.
</P>
<P>
   For Philippoussis, Rafter predicted a possible trip to the top
if and when he ``gets his game together.'' For himself, he
predicted a Champagne and beer bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``This,'' he said, ``has been a very special day.''
</P>
<P>
   MATCH POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Though a loss to LINDSAY DAVENPORT in the women's final
prevented MARTINA HINGIS from defending her 1997 U.S. Open singles
title, she completed a one-woman sweep of the year's doubles Grand
Slams on Sunday by pairing up with JANA NOVOTNA, her partner at
every 1998 Grand Slam except the Australian Open, to defeat
Davenport and NATASHA ZVEREVA, 6-3, 6-3. Hingis' partner at the
Australian Open was MIRJANA LUCIC.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID NALBANDIAN of Argentina captured the Junior Boys title
Sunday by defeating ROGER FEDERER of Switzerland, 6-3, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   _ JELENA DOKIC of Australia defeated KATARINA SREBOTNIK of
Slovenia, 6-4, 6-2, to win the Girls Junior title. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
