<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2859 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEECEE-PRIMARY-620&AMP;AD     09-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-PRIMARY-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWCOMER FAVORED IN WASHINGTON MAYORAL PRIMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For the first time in 20 years, Marion Barry will
not be a candidate or a looming presence on Tuesday when Democratic
voters in the District of Columbia choose their candidate for
mayor.
</P>
<P>
   His name almost never comes up on the campaign trail, probably
because candidates are reluctant to criticize Barry, who remains
popular despite having to interrupt his third term as mayor to
serve six months in jail on a cocaine-possession conviction and to
suffer the embarrassment of seeing Congress take away most of his
authority in his fourth term when the city listed toward
bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Since Democrats hold a 10-to-1 advantage over enrolled
Republicans, their candidate seems a virtual certainty to be
elected mayor in November. That person is expected to be Anthony A.
Williams, a government technocrat who moved to Washington less than
three years ago when he became chief financial officer and helped
lift the city out of its chronic deficits.
</P>
<P>
   Williams holds a substantial lead over the three other main
contenders, whose roles as City Council members seem to be working
to Williams' advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the odd man out,'' said professor Charles Horner of the
Howard University political science department. ``It becomes a
liability, a disability to be on the council. I think most people
view the council as not effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever effectiveness the Democratic City Council and the mayor
had was taken from them by a Republican Congress, which created a
Control Board last year to oversee the operation of the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Control Board has effective control over things like the
police department, the schools and public works. Barry and his
colleagues have been left with things like promotion of tourism.
</P>
<P>
   At a candidates' forum at the St. Paul's Episcopal Church parish
meeting house the other night, none of the candidates raised the
issue of Williams' brief residence in the city.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview afterward, Williams said the question had not
been raised because ``this isn't a frequent-flyer program'' in
which candidates get credit for the length of residency. ``I've
made a commitment to the city and I've brought its finances back,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in an interview later, Councilman Jack Evans, another
candidate, said he had raised the carpetbagger issue at other
forums.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's a guy who moved here only because he had to,'' Evans
said. ``Can you imagine New York City electing someone who had
lived there only two and a half years?''
</P>
<P>
   But if Williams has a residency problem, Evans has another
hurdle that is even more substantial. He is the only principal
candidate for the Democratic nomination who is white, while the
city's population in the 1990 census was 66 percent black (that
percentage may be lower today).
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps because of this, Evans trailed among the four main
candidates in a poll conducted in late August by The Washington
Post.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was favored by 37 percent of those responding, trailed
by Councilman Kevin Chavous with 20 percent, Councilman Harold
Brazil with 8 percent and Evans with 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he was playing a rather quixotic role, Evans insisted
that he had a chance to win, and he pointed to cities that had
elected mayors who were not members of the predominant racial
group.
</P>
<P>
   Gary, Ind., is 90 percent black and Jersey City, N.J., is 75
percent black but both have white mayors, he said, while Houston,
with a black population of only 15 percent, has a black mayor.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the results of the Democratic primary, there will be a
white mayoral candidate on the ballot in November, Carol Schwartz,
a Republican member of the City Council. Ms. Schwartz is unopposed
in the Republican primary for mayor.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The single most influential factor in elections here is the
endorsement of The Washington Post, and Williams has it, although
The Post's endorsement was hesitant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our enthusiasm for Mr. Williams is not unqualified,'' the
editorial said. While Williams helped ``pull the city back from the
brink of insolvency three years ago,'' the editorial said, it
faulted him for things like engaging in back-channel dealings with
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   When Barry was in jail, The Post's endorsement of Sharon Pratt
Kelly allowed her to leap to the top of a closely bunched group of
candidates. But her mayoralty was not a success, the city's fiscal
crisis worsened, with the deficit rising to $300 million, and
Barry, not long emerged from jail, was re-elected easily in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Through all his travails _ almost a Shakespearean tragedy of a
rise from civil rights leader to a mayor brought down by drugs,
alcohol, corrupt government and misspent public money _ Barry
remains the most popular politician in Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
