<HEADER>
A2861 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-FARMER-815&AMP;AD     09-13 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-FARMER-815&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TOBACCO GROWERS, A CHANGING LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)  (lb) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAVE CITY, Ky. _ Larry Walden doesn't look or sound very much
like a villain.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday afternoon, he stood in his corrugated steel barn
near here, just down the road from Mammoth Cave, and tried
patiently to explain the economics, the emotions and the politics
of growing tobacco, which he has done for a living for the last 30
years, since he was 12 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Above his head, stalks of ocher-colored tobacco, drying in the
late-summer breeze, hung from laths, sticks to those in the trade.
The air inside was as opulently perfumed as a fine Havana cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may be headed for nowhere,'' Walden said. ``I think the
price supports for tobacco may be finished in a year or two, and if
that happens, these little towns around here will just dry up and
blow away. I don't know what I'd do, but I know there's no other
crop that would bring me as much income.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden is the biggest tobacco grower, he thinks, in Barren
County, which produces more tobacco than any other county in the
state. But he is no tycoon, and neither are many of the other
Kentucky growers, most of whom produce flavor- and nicotine-rich
burley tobacco. The state, second in annual production to North
Carolina, has more tobacco-dependent counties than any other, with
60,000 farmers averaging an income from tobacco of about $12,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   A trim, bearded, laconic man in Cat hat and aviator glasses,
Walden clutched a beer, encased in an insulating cylinder called a
``hugger,'' as he talked to a visitor.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that he himself no longer smoked or chewed tobacco.
His wife, he said, had told him, ``If you stop, it might help your
health.'' But that, he insisted, had nothing to do with his
decision to give up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made up my own mind to quit,'' Walden said rather
defensively, like a man determined to defend his picture of himself
as a rugged individualist.
</P>
<P>
   For all the research projects and all the anti-smoking publicity
in the last decade or so, he said he was still not convinced that
smoking is harmful to health. His father, he said, smokes three or
four packs of cigarettes a day. When his father had open heart
surgery not long ago, in his 70s, the surgeon said that half his
patients smoked and half did not, Walden reported.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Baesler, the Kentucky Department of Agriculture's tobacco
expert, said that most growers, like Walden, had grown up in the
business. Families, she said, ``have existed for this for
generations, with tobacco at the center of their lives, so much so
that in the fall, they are drawn to the fields at harvest time,
whatever and wherever their everyday jobs may be.''
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniably a beautiful crop, with the broad leaves turning
green-gold in the fields before the stalks are cut, mounted six to
a stick and hung in old red barns, many of them covered with wild
morning glories, with loose boards to let the air through.
</P>
<P>
   It is undeniably a profitable crop. Mrs. Baesler, whose husband,
Scotty, a Democrat, represents the Lexington area in the House of
Representatives, said that an acre of tobacco produced a gross
income of about $4,000 in good years, while corn or soybeans
produced no more than $500. ``Nothing else, except marijuana,
brings in the kind of money that tobacco does in Tennessee,
Kentucky and the Carolinas,'' Walden said. ``Flat nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Baesler is running for the Senate this fall against Rep. Jim
Bunning, the Hall of Fame pitcher nominated by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, everything from green peppers to wheat has been
proposed as a supplemental or replacement crop for tobacco, without
much success. In July, the University of Kentucky's Center for
Business and Economic Research said that cultivating and processing
hemp, a cousin of marijuana that can be used in paper products and
textiles, could produce $17.6 million a year in worker income, less
than tobacco but a lot more than most other products. But growing
hemp remains illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mr. and Mrs. Baesler are loudly critical of President
Clinton's tobacco policies, particularly his first-term proposal to
finance health-care reform with a tobacco tax. Most Kentucky
politicians feel that way. Rep. Ron Lewis, a Republican whose
district includes Larry Walden's farm, attended a 1994 smokers'
rights rally where Hillary Rodham Clinton was burned in effigy. It
was an ``inappropriate'' act, he said, a ``desperate'' bid to draw
attention to a righteous cause.
</P>
<P>
   Walden said he resented Clinton as well as former President
Ronald Reagan, whom he blamed for driving government-supported
prices down so far that only now, 18 years later, were tobacco
revenues returning to their former levels.
</P>
<P>
   But his deepest scorn was reserved for the four big cigarette
companies, which he accused of profiteering and price manipulation.
It is they, Walden said, ``who give the farmer a real licking, year
in and year out.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He will produce 175,000 pounds of tobacco this year, using
government quotas (the acreage the government allows a farmer to
use to grow tobacco and it can be bought, sold or leased) for his
own land as well as the quotas of other landowners who do not grow
tobacco, which he leases.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard, manual work, from the time the seedlings are
transplanted through the summer harvest and until the leaves are
finally stripped from the stalks at a rotating table, after they
have dried in the barns for eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Walden is optimistic. He sees how much revenue tobacco
produces for the government in taxes, and how many sporting events
it supports, and concludes that ``they'll never put the growers out
of business.'' Other times, he thinks the game is up, and he
wonders about expanding his dairy herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurs to me,'' he said, ``that I'm doing anything
wrong. Nobody forces people to smoke cigarettes. It's their
choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
