<SLUG> BC-IRAN-AFGHANISTAN-ART-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASSASSINATION ATTEMPT IN IRAN ADDS TO TENSION WITH AFGHANS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By DOUGLAS JEHL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ Attackers tried to kill a powerful Iranian
official Sunday, adding to an atmosphere of unease at a time of
growing tension between Iran and neighboring Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Mohsen Rafiqdoust, was reported by the government
press agencies to have been unhurt in the attack, which was carried
out by assailants who opened fire from hills overlooking his
office.
</P>
<P>
   The attempt on his life was the latest in a series of attacks on
prominent Iranians, including the assassination last month of the
former prison director, Assadollah Lajevardi.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, no one had taken responsibility for the attack on
Rafiqdoust, but an Iranian opposition group, the People's
Mujahedeen, has said it carried out the earlier attacks as part of
a campaign against Iran's ruling establishment.
</P>
<P>
   There appeared to be no evidence of any link between the
attempted assassination of Rafiqdoust, who heads a vast
government-affiliated economic foundation, and Iran's increasing
tensions with Afghanistan. Still, the latest attack may well be
cited by some hard-liners here as further reason for Iran to
confront the militant Taliban movement that controls Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   Recent violence in Tehran, including a bombing outside a
downtown courthouse, had already prompted dark suggestions that
saboteurs must have been operating from Taliban-controlled
territory along Iran's eastern border. The main focus of Iranian
concern remained firmly fixed on Afghanistan, where the Taliban on
Sunday captured the last major stronghold held by an Iranian-backed
opposition militia.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine Iranian diplomats were killed by Taliban forces
during an earlier Taliban victory a month ago, and Iran feared that
the Taliban victory Sunday, in Bamiyan, might be followed by
similar reprisals, this time against Shiite Muslim civilians. Most
Iranians are Shiite Muslims; the Taliban are Sunni Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban leader, Mullah Mohammad Omar, sought to dispel
concerns by issuing a statement saying civilians would be free to
leave Bamiyan, the official Afghan press agency reported. But
Iranian television reported Sunday night that the city, whose
population of 300,000 includes about 10,000 Shiites, was in ``blood
and fire,'' and that the dead included many women and children.
</P>
<P>
   Since its diplomats first disappeared from the Iranian Consulate
in the Afghan town of Mazar-i-Sharif last month, Iran has deployed
tens of thousands of troops near the border. Since the diplomats
were found dead last week, Tehran has stepped up its threats of
revenge.
</P>
<P>
   Iran has repeated assertions by international human rights
groups that the Taliban may have already killed large numbers of
Shiite civilians in Mazar-i-Sharif, and President Mohammad Khatami
on Sunday explicitly accused the Taliban of having committed war
crimes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In general, public debate in Iran over what to do about the
Taliban has been divided along familiar lines, even as officials
await an Afghan response to Iranian demands that the Taliban arrest
and hand over those responsible for killing the diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban rejected the demands, with a spokesman saying the
incident was an ``internal affair,'' The Associated Press reported.
</P>
<P>
   In the newspapers known to reflect their views, supporters of
Khatami have usually counseled restraint, while hard-liners
associated with the more conservative religious establishment have
advocated a military strike. The Tehran Times, which usually
straddles a middle ground, said of the Taliban in an editorial
Sunday: ``It would not be surprising if one day Iran decides to
wipe out these irrational fanatics _ a real stigma on the head of
international community _ from the face of humanity in order to
render a great service to mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafiqdoust, the official who escaped assassination Sunday, is a
leading conservative member of Iran's political establishment.
Appointed to his position by Iran's supreme leader, Ayatollah Ali
Khamenei, he heads the Foundation of the Deprived and War Disabled,
which controls most hotels and hundreds of other enterprises. Set
up after the Islamic revolution of 1979, the foundation has assets
estimated in the many billions of dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
