<HEADER>
A2864 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRONTIER-PROSPECTS-AR     09-13 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRONTIER-PROSPECTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOCAL PHONE COMPANY AIMS HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph Clayton, chief executive of the Frontier Corp., wears his
heart on his bumper.
</P>
<P>
   There, on the license plate of one of his three Cadillacs, is
the clearest expression of Clayton's ambitions for the phone
company he has run for a year: ``FRO 50''
</P>
<P>
   That is bold for an executive whose company's shares, under the
ticker symbol FRO, closed Friday at $25.938 _ a long way from $50 _
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   But high expectations are a staple these days at Frontier's
headquarters in Rochester, as the company tries to evolve beyond
its roots as a local phone monopoly. Its 1996 acquisition of part
of the national fiber optic network being built by Qwest
Communications International looks like more of a steal every week.
And it is finally delivering something akin to stable earnings
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Frontier has yet to escape its legacy of
failure. In the 1990s, perhaps no communications carrier has opened
a wider gap between expectation and execution. Its strategic vision
has so often surpassed management's ability to fulfill it that many
industry experts remain unconvinced that Frontier, which changed
its name from Rochester Telephone in 1995, can ever become a
national provider of voice, video and data services.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, normally an effusive salesman, turns a bit coy when
asked the true significance of ``FRO 50.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it would be a good target,'' he said in a
recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   But the prevailing sentiment in the industry is that Clayton,
the former sales and marketing chief for Thomson Consumer
Electronics, was hired last year to whip Frontier into shape and
sell it. And there may be few Frontier stockholders who would not
leap to tender their shares for $50.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock market stays afloat, the communications industry's
takeover tango seems destined to continue at a healthy pace, and
that is good for Frontier. But with every deal _ especially Bell
Atlantic Corp.'s July decision to acquire the GTE Corp. for $52.9
billion _ the list of potential acquirers gets shorter.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Frontier's evolution from clumsy striver to
turnaround (and takeover) prospect reflects the difficulties faced
by old midsize companies in an industry dominated by national
titans and lean niche operators.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Southern New England Telecommunications, sell out to
bigger carriers. Some, like Century Telephone Enterprises, focus on
rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald L. Bittner, Frontier's former chairman, who died last
year, spent decades working his way up the ladder at Rochester
Telephone and had a strategic vision for the company. But he was
unable to enforce the discipline needed to pull it off.
</P>
<P>
   In the early and mid-1990s, Frontier, which is not subject to
the complex federal regulations imposed on the regional Bells,
became the most important local phone company to make a big push
into long distance since GTE and United Telephone (which became
Sprint) did so in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Frontier acquired more than half a dozen long-distance carriers,
including ALC Communications, American Sharecom and WCT
Communications. By 1996, it was one of the nation's top 10
long-distance companies.
</P>
<P>
   But Bittner, whose health was failing, did not properly
integrate the executive teams and financial operations of his
acquisitions. The result was a financial meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   Clayton, 48, has made a difference. Until this year, the company
had not matched a quarterly earnings target in at least two years,
according to First Call, a financial research firm. But in each of
this year's first two quarters, it beat Wall Street's expectations
by a penny a share.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Clayton's agenda has been to clean out the management
team. Among those leaving were Kevin J. Bennis, an executive vice
president; Dale M. Gregory, head of corporate development, and
Louis L. Massaro, the chief financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   To replace Massaro, Clayton hired Rolla Huff, 41, an
up-and-comer in the industry who helped evaluate mergers for the
AT&AMP;T Corp. in the mid-1990s before running AT&AMP;T's wireless
operation in the Midwest. Huff's merger experience will probably
come in handy.
</P>
<P>
   The main reason Frontier is valuable to a bigger company is its
piece of the Qwest network, which will be one of the most advanced
in the world. Bought for $500 million, those fiber optic assets are
now worth billions.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic would have been a natural candidate to acquire
Frontier, with the Rochester operation filling out its New York
territory, but after its deal with GTE, which also owns part of the
Qwest system, it has little reason to buy Frontier's share.
</P>
<P>
   Another Bell, like SBC Communications, could go for Frontier.
But any Bell deal would raise tough regulatory questions because
the Bells are not allowed to offer long-distance service within
their regions, and Frontier sells it all over the country.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Frontier say a foreign carrier could be the most
logical suitor. As British Telecommunications PLC demonstrated with
its attempted takeover of the MCI Communications Corp., foreign
companies can be especially skittish about American acquisitions
diluting earnings. But with a stock that trades at about 23 times
estimated earnings, Frontier is not expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Of the foreign candidates, Cable and Wireless PLC makes perhaps
the most sense. (France Telecom and Deutsche Telekom are still
entangled with Sprint, and Nippon Telegraph and Telephone has not
demonstrated that it is willing to spend big to get into the United
States.) Cable and Wireless is already one of the larger
long-distance carriers in the United States, but it leases its
network capacity. A network of its own could let it cut operating
costs sharply.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Cable and Wireless is about to complete its
acquisition of MCI's Internet business, getting both equipment and
customers. But it still has to lease fiber optic capacity from MCI
to carry Internet data. Frontier's part of the Qwest network would
help solve that problem.
</P>
<P>
   Cable and Wireless' new Internet business could also fit nicely
with Globalcenter, the Web service company run by Douglas T. Hickey
that Frontier acquired this year.
</P>
<P>
   A sticking point in almost any acquisition would be Frontier's
local operations. They generate a lot of cash, but any foreign
carrier interested in Frontier's national network would be a lot
less interested in running (and paying for) a local phone company
in Rochester.
</P>
<P>
   That could require a three-way deal. People close to Frontier
say candidates to acquire Frontier's local operations would include
Bell Atlantic, Citizens and Century.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves one more question: Will Clayton hold out for that
$50?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
