<HEADLINE>
BULLPEN'S LATEST COLLAPSE COSTS CONE 20TH VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The self-tortured David Cone had sidestepped peril
all day as if playing matador on a freeway. But he could only take
an isolated seat on the Yankee bench and chew the flavor out of a
piece of gum as he left his troubles to someone else Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   As his pitch count swelled, Cone was lifted by Manager Joe Torre
with two outs in the sixth inning, the bases loaded and the Yanks
leading the Blue Jays 3-1 at Yankee Stadium. It was up to the
bullpen to pull Cone out of this collision course and preserve the
opportunity for him to become the first pitcher in the major
leagues to win 20 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   But the unsettling struggles of the Yankee bullpen continued as
a parade of relievers _ Graeme Lloyd, Jeff Nelson and Mike Stanton
_ failed to secure the third out in the inning before the Blue Jays
scored three runs and took a lead they would not relinquish.
Toronto sent the Yankees to their third straight defeat, 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Torre continues to play it safe as the post-season
approaches, this was the Yankees' 14th defeat in 25 games and a
sign that the pixie dust has worn off this magical season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think after we clinched the division _ and I hate to say
this _ but there was a letdown,'' said Stanton, who gave up the
go-ahead run after Lloyd had allowed a game-tying, two-run single
two batters before him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Regardless of who we put on the field, if you don't do what
you have to do, you won't win,'' Stanton said. ``As far as I'm
concerned, and I don't care who gets the loss officially, it was my
loss. Right now, I think this team has to guard against waiting
until the last minute to turn it on.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not as if the Yankees (103-44) have grown bored and
uninterested because they have the luxury of playoff security. Paul
O'Neill let that be known when he let his emotion get the best of
him. He represented the go-ahead run with two outs and two on in
the seventh inning when he was caught looking at strike 3.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill slammed down his bat, helmet and batting glove in front
of the home-plate umpire, John Hirschbeck, who ejected him.
O'Neill's volatility would come back into play in the bottom of the
ninth. With two men on, and two outs, the rookie Shane Spencer
batted in O'Neill's place and lined out to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not to take anything from Shane, but you'd rather have O'Neill
up in that situation, yes,'' said Torre, who said he believed what
O'Neill did was wrong but excusable considering the heat of the
moment. ``But you can't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre was concerned by a bullpen that has become more unsteady
as the playoffs near. Even the reliable Lloyd came up empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a concern when you bring guys in and they can't get a
third out,'' Torre said. ``But it's too early to get overly
concerned with it. No question it was frustrating. That elusive
last out wasn't there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cone (19-6) absorbed the loss after battling out of
trouble all day. Typical Cone outing. Just when he would load the
bases _ as he did in the third inning _ he could bear down and
catch Tony Fernandez looking at strike 3. He left the game after
123 pitches and 24 batters in five and two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was flirting with disaster all day,'' said Cone, who gave up
four runs, walked two and struck out 11. ``Everything just caught
up to me. I left a mess out there. It was a struggle for me all
day.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the day he wanted to secure his 20th victory and set
the major league record for most seasons _ nine _ in between
20-victory years. He has two starts left to do it. Two starts to
hit a number that few thought possible after the surgery Cone had
in 1996 to remove an aneurysm from his arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking forward to having this be the day,'' Cone said.
``When you're this close, you want to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, he was helpless to do anything about it as the
bullpen provided another reason to doubt the invincibility of the
once unshakable Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now,'' Stanton said, ``everyone is going to go
home and look in the mirror, and say, let's get back to business,
including me.''
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   The flu has been working its way around the Yankee clubhouse of
late. Neither Tino Martinez nor Tim Raines was in the lineup
because of it, which allowed Mike Lowell to make his major league
debut as a starter Sunday. Manager Joe Torre wanted to see what
Lowell, one of six players called up from Class AAA Columbus on
Tuesday, could do while the Yankees bide their time until the
post-season begins. With Lowell playing third base, Scott Brosius
took over at first. In his first major league at-bat, Lowell hit a
bloop single to center field. ... The Blue Jays, showing much more
desperation than the Yankees did as they took the series, 3-1, are
just three games behind Boston for the wild-card spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
