<HEADLINE>
HUNDLEY'S BLOCK LETS METS HOLD THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ For Todd Hundley, catching is very much like riding a
bicycle. So what if Hundley had not caught a game for the Mets in
nearly a year. The important thing was that he had not forgotten
how to catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm back to my world,'' Hundley had said before his first
major league start behind the plate since Sept. 16. An elbow injury
and surgery kept Hundley from playing at all until July, when the
Mets tried their former catcher in the outfield. That experiment
didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   But Hundley's instincts took over Sunday afternoon. With
Montreal's Shane Andrews racing toward home representing the tying
run with two out in the bottom of the ninth, Hundley thrust his
left leg out to block Andrews' path to the plate as he prepared to
field Brian McRae's perfect one-hop strike from short right center
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had no chance of getting in there,'' said Hundley, who made
the tag for the final out to set off an emotional celebration and
preserve a crucial 1-0 victory for the Mets and Willie Blair. The
Cubs also won, keeping the Mets one game back in the National
League wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Of that final play, Hundley said, ``He was going to have to
break my leg, go through my leg and then go through my shinguard to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   The first person to get to Hundley after the tag was Mets
Manager Bobby Valentine, whose relationship with Hundley has often
been stormy for the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Johnny would be the one picking me up,'' Hundley
said of his close friend, John Franco, who was backing up the play
after he had allowed pinch-hitter Mike Hubbard's line-drive single
over second. ``But it was Bobby. I was thinking, `What are you
doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine said, ``Actually, I was two steps out of the dugout to
argue if he was calling him safe.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no danger of Umpire Jeff Kellogg doing that, not after
Hundley had made sure the play was never in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And by the slimmest of margins, Franco had tied his own
franchise record with his 36th save. McRae _ who had doubled in the
game's only run with two out in the eighth _ began to do a wild
dance in the outfield to celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was about to lay on the ground and start doing a jig,''
McRae said.
</P>
<P>
   Which might sound a little extreme. But the Mets (83-67) came
here Sunday in danger of being swept out of Montreal by the Expos,
and of damaging their chances in the wild-card race with only 12
games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   But the Mets, and Hundley, were able to hold their ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do my talking on the field,'' said Hundley, when he was
asked why he did not celebrate as heartily as Valentine, McRae and
the rest of his teammates after the final out. ``That's what it's
all about. I want to be a part of this, this playoff and wild-card
run. And to do that, I've got to play right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley was only playing because Valentine asked Mike Piazza if
he wanted one last day off before the Mets make their final
post-season push. Piazza accepted, and Hundley proved that he can
still catch and also bolstered his chances of being included on the
post-season roster _ should the Mets qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a nice step in the right direction,'' General Manager
Steve Phillips said of Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can do nothing but help this ball club,'' Piazza said of
Hundley. ``I don't see how there can be any negatives at all. It
gives us two great options to go with.''
</P>
<P>
   In his first real test this season, Hundley, who had caught 18
innings in the minor leagues this season, also threw Andrews out on
a delayed steal attempt in the fourth. At the plate, he walked
three times to give him four walks in five plate appearances since
being activated from the disabled list on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And Hundley's third walk Sunday, off reliever Anthony Telford,
immediately preceded McRae's game-winning double off Rick Dehart.
</P>
<P>
   But it was McRae's online throw and Hundley's instincts that
insured the Mets would prevail in the end.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Both Hundley's and McRae's contributions overshadowed a strong
performance from Blair (5-16), who scattered three hits in seven
and a third innings to win for the first time as a Met. Blair was a
late replacement for Hideo Nomo, who was removed from the rotation.
In two spot starts for the Mets, Blair has allowed just two runs in
14 and a third innings _ and has been given only one run back.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it was enough today,'' said Blair, who was bailed out of
an eighth-inning jam by Dennis Cook, who struck out pinch-hitter
Robert Perez, and then Hundley, who went to the retaining wall to
catch an F.P. Santangelo pop-up, to leave a runner stranded on
third.
</P>
<P>
   And then came Franco, who retired the first two batters he faced
to start the ninth. But Franco walked Andrews on five pitches,
threw a wild pitch and then intentionally walked Vladimir Guerrero
to set the stage for the game-ending play at the plate. ``I didn't
know where he was,'' Hundley said of Andrews, ``but I felt him
coming.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
