<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-POLITICS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CAMBODIA, MORE DEMONSTRATIONS BUT LESS VIOLENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By SETH MYDANS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia _ After a week of chaos in the streets, the
competing rowdy demonstrations and the violence that have paralyzed
the capital began to take on a ritual flavor Sunday as
post-election maneuvers moved toward the bargaining table.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 highly organized pro-government marchers filled
the streets in the morning, chanting obediently at the orders of
men with bullhorns and escorted by armed and helmeted security
forces.
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon the opposition demonstrators, whom the
pro-government marchers have been mimicking, paraded around the
central market, their numbers swelled to more than 5,000 by
bystanders, until police officers fired automatic weapons in the
air to disperse them.
</P>
<P>
   There was a degree of stone throwing, clubbing and shooting, and
at least one man was reported to have been shot in the leg. But by
the standards of the last week, Sunday was not a violent day.
</P>
<P>
   With a round of meetings among political leaders scheduled for
this week, King Norodom Sihanouk issued a statement suffused with
weary pragmatism that supported the victory of the country's
strongman, Hun Sen, in the parliamentary election on July 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a Cambodia that is not a state of law and not a fully
fledged democracy, I have no other choice than to advise the weak
to choose a policy that avoids misfortune for the people, the
motherland and themselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a call to his son Prince Norodom Ranariddh and to the
other opposition leader, Sam Rainsy, to accept the election results
and to reach an accommodation with Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   The new Parliament is to convene on Sept. 24. The two
challengers have vowed to boycott it, contending that fraud and
intimidation skewed the election.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hun Sen's party won the most seats, it needs to form a
coalition with the prince's royalist party to reach the two-thirds
majority needed to form a government.
</P>
<P>
   It appears that Sam Rainsy genuinely hoped to bring down Hun
Sen. But many analysts have seen the prince's alliance with Sam
Rainsy as an attempt to strengthen his own post-election bargaining
position.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Ranariddh signaled his readiness to deal, backing
off from demands for a review of the vote, agreeing to meet the
king and government leaders and saying that it could be possible
for him to participate in a new government even while rejecting the
election results.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Rainsy remained silent. Since Monday, when Hun Sen
threatened to arrest opposition leaders, Sam Rainsy has taken
refuge at a U.N. office in a hotel and abruptly halted his fiery
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend a road map for an end to the impasse has taken
shape, pointing toward an eventual coalition between Hun Sen and
Ranariddh and excluding Sam Rainsy.
</P>
<P>
   Such a coalition, in a new form, would reconstitute the mutually
antagonistic partnership that emerged from the last election, in
1993. It broke apart 14 months ago, when Hun Sen seized full
control in a coup.
</P>
<P>
   That possibility was signaled by the concessions listed by the
prince, by his unilateral statements independent of Sam Rainsy, by
his plan to meet the king on Wednesday without the participation of
Sam Rainsy and by the diverging attitudes shown by the governing
party toward the two men.
</P>
<P>
   The slogans fed to the pro-government demonstrators by Hun Sen's
officials Sunday urged the pri/nce to accept the election results
and participate in the government. But they called Sam Rainsy a
traitor who should be put on trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam Rainsy is out of the picture now,'' a Western diplomat
said. ``He overplayed his hand and he's lost. There isn't much left
for Ranariddh to do but look for the best deal.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For a while Sam Rainsy had seemed to have the initiative. He
organized huge demonstrations and created an encampment of
protesters outside the National Assembly building that lasted for
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But on Tuesday security forces tore down the area. That touched
off street battles that evolved into huge anti-government
demonstrations that seemed to show the strength of popular support
for the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   As if to counter that final bargaining point in the
post-election maneuvering, the government filled the streets this
weekend with its own huge demonstrations. They were largely made up
of farmers trucked in from nearby provinces and provided with food.
</P>
<P>
   It was a familiar spectacle to Rustam Saltiakov, a Russian
member of the U.N. monitoring team in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It reminds me of Red Square in the old Soviet days,''
Saltiakov said. ``A very well-organized spontaneous
demonstration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
