<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2873 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-RAVENS-670&AMP;A     09-13 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-RAVENS-670&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS HOPES AND PLANS UNRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Now the Jets get to see what life is
like when they are expected to win and don't.
</P>
<P>
   In multiple ways that they had not shown during the Bill
Parcells era, they messed up on offense, defense and special teams
Sunday. That was too much of a triple handicap to overcome, and so
the Baltimore Ravens handed them a 24-10 defeat.
</P>
<P>
   It dropped their record to 0-2, a start reminiscent of those
Jets teams from what now seems another era, but was only a few
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Glenn Foley threw three interceptions, one returned
by the old-timer Rod Woodson for a 60-yard score. Another
interception positioned a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he'll find out about being an NFL quarterback now,''
Parcells said of Foley's resiliency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the special teams were burned for a 69-yard punt
return by Jermaine Lewis on the second kick by Brian Hansen, who
was playing golf in South Dakota on Friday when Parcells suddenly
summoned him to replace the rookie Nick Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a symbol of the Jets' frustration, it belonged
to the offense, which could not get Curtis Martin into the end zone
on three cracks from the 1-yard line. Over all, he had the ball
four straight times once the Jets got to the 3.
</P>
<P>
   His failed fourth-down effort from 24 inches out, with the score
tied at 7-7, spoiled a drive that had consumed more than half of
the second period. The Jets had tied the score on a 4-yard pass
from Foley to Keyshawn Johnson, who outmuscled the shorter DeRon
Jenkins, and another touchdown would have put the Ravens in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Eric Zeier came in to quarterback the Colts for the
sore-fingered Jim Harbaugh. The Ravens had 99 yards to go, but
Zeier's first pass was a 39-yard completion to Michael Jackson over
Otis Smith. It immediately lifted the Ravens out of trouble, and
they went on to score a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to be a long week for us,'' Foley said. ``This
is going to tell us a lot about this team.''
</P>
<P>
   If there was rampant fan optimism before this game, it was
understandable. The Jets were going into their home opener after
having taken the mighty 49ers to overtime last week. More than
70,000 fans were on hand, with thousands of them celebrating hours
before game time. Giants Stadium (the Jets simply call it the
Meadowlands) looked like the world's biggest outdoor barbecue.
Youngsters were throwing footballs, music blared from car radios,
the smell of hot dogs cooking filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   But the mood was quickly deflated. The offense never mounted
much of an attack, or certainly one with any consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Martin is one of football's finest runners. But in two games
with the Jets, he has been more dangerous as a receiver. Against
the 49ers, Martin was held to 58 yards on 22 carries. Sunday, the
Ravens, as expected, used similar tactics in launching what often
seemed to be nine men at the line when he had the ball. The result:
58 yards on 23 rushes. Martin was the club's only runner Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Martin caught six more passes for 60 yards, and the Ravens
seemed content to allow him his 10-yard receiving average. But they
were able to prevent was his cross-the-grain running, his darting
to the hole that appears for an instant, his commanding presence
that keeps drives alive with defense-tiring, wearing running.
</P>
<P>
   Why are the Jets having so much trouble getting Martin going?
</P>
<P>
   Parcells, who said last week that pass receptions have to be
counted to gauge Martin, backed off that somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in this league has a hard time running the ball
against that kind of defense,'' he said. ``They had a hard time
running the ball, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Say this for the Jets. They did not give up trying to run, even
while down by 17-10 midway through the final quarter. But after a
pair of failed Martin runs, Foley threw the ball toward fullback
Jerald Sowell. As if on cue, the 33-year-old Woodson appeared,
stepped in front of Sowell and produced the crushing score.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   That final touchdown punctuated a game of Jets mistakes. Yet, on
the game's opening score, it appeared the Jets were about to put
the Ravens in a hole.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen took the snap on a quick count from his own 23. It
surprised the Ravens' special teams, Ray Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the jump on the guy and I was the first one down
there,'' Lucas said. Indeed, he was at Lewis' heels virtually the
moment the dangerous returner hauled in the kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he shook me off,'' Lucas said. With that first fake, Lewis
suddenly had a clear road. No one got close enough to bother him in
his 69-yard romp to a touchdown. Only a few weeks ago, he generated
a 97-yard punt return for a touchdown in preseason play. So this
was no surprise to the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``No surprise at all,'' said Chris Hayes, one of the better
special-team players in the league. ``He's a good returner, and
we've just got to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Smith, beaten on the 39-yard pass to Jackson by Zeier, it
was this simple: ``I got beat. He got behind me. It was one of
those things that happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But nothing hurt worse than Martin's inability to score with
four cracks from 3 yards out. Martin said he had no explanation,
and Parcells defended his decision not to go for a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't make that play, you've got trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what the Jets had Sunday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
