<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2876 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-870(2T     09-13 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-REPUBS-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS' FALL STRATEGY IS BASED ON MORE THAN CLINTON'S WOES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Mo.)  (js) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Faced with a complex new set of political
calculations, Republicans say they want to appear focused on
substantive issues even as they debate how best to take advantage
of President Clinton's woes.
</P>
<P>
   As the pressure on Clinton mounted over the past week,
Republican leaders insisted they were concentrating on the issues
of most concern to their constituents, from tax cuts and the budget
to crime, drug use and national security.
</P>
<P>
   In part, they said, they were motivated by a desire to avoid
appearing overly partisan as the House considers impeachment
hearings. But they also said voters want them to have a positive
message heading into this fall's elections and not just to
capitalize on Clinton's problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to expand our majority is to do the business of
the people, not to expect the problems of the Democratic side to
carry us forward,'' said Sen. John Ashcroft of Missouri. ``Their
liabilities are not necessarily our assets.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said there is a division within the party about
how hard to push in coming weeks over tax cuts, spending levels for
next year and social issues like abortion. While some Republicans
in Congress want to press as hard as possible on those issues at a
time when the White House is struggling to stay politically
relevant, other Republicans are counseling restraint, saying the
party should not open up battles that would allow Clinton to change
the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the view that says that from a political standpoint
things seem to be breaking in the direction of the Republicans and
we should not engage in efforts to pursue our policy agenda that
are not consensual and should let the election be about the
president and his conduct,'' said Rep. David McIntosh of Indiana.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there's the argument that the American people want us to
do our job on the Starr report, but they really want us to do our
job on cutting taxes, balancing the budget and maintaining a strong
national defense,'' McIntosh said. ``People are evenly split
between those two views.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntosh said he came down on the side of pursuing an ambitious
agenda, although not to the point of shutting down the government
over differences with Clinton about spending priorities for the new
fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Republicans said, the trick for them will be to exploit
whatever legislative openings are created by the presumed sapping
of Clinton's political strength without handing the White House
issues that allow the president to cast himself as the defender of
middle-class values.
</P>
<P>
   A memo circulating among Republican members of Congress last
week from Frank Luntz, a consultant who is influential with many
conservatives, said Clinton is much weaker than he had been during
battles over changing the health care system in 1994 and balancing
the budget in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``By a healthy 14-point margin, Americans believe President
Clinton is likely to try to distract the nation from his ethical
problems by forcing a confrontation with Congress'' over policy
issues, Luntz's memo said.
</P>
<P>
   But Luntz said shutting down the government over spending bills
would be going too far, with voters saying they would blame
Republicans rather than Clinton, by a 42-32 percent margin, if such
a showdown occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Republicans said, Clinton's troubles have created new
opportunities for legislative victories. Republicans said they now
have a realistic hope of passing a substantial tax cut this year,
believing that Clinton has lost some of his ability to convince
voters that a tax cut, by dipping into projected federal budget
surpluses, will endanger the future of the ailing Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   Until Clinton's situation started deteriorating in the last
week, most Republicans viewed their tax-cutting effort this year
primarily as a way to force Democrats to cast votes that could be
used against them on the campaign trail this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Democrats see a president who's losing his voice,''
said a House Republican aide. ``For Democrats who are caught in a
squeeze about voting for a popular tax cut, they have to decide
whether to vote with their district or hope that the president can
scare people by demagoguing Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said the assumption that the president's
power and influence were in terminal decline vastly overstated his
loss of ability to shape the outcomes of many policy disputes. And
with the country still likely to face crises having nothing to do
with Clinton's sex life, they said Clinton will play as central a
role as ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still has the veto pen,'' said a senior administration
official. ``He still has the microphone.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said it would play to their strengths if
Republicans decide to push a conservative agenda, especially on
such issues as education and the environment, where the House has
often had to back down when confronted by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's win-win,'' said the White House official. ``If the
Republicans cave, it shows we're still winning our policy agenda.
And if they fight us on an issue like education it will only remind
the public why they like Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Along with taxes, the biggest policy fights in coming weeks will
be over the spending bills that Congress must pass to finance the
government's operation in the new fiscal year that starts Oct. 1.
Clinton issued veto threats against many of the bills during the
summer, objecting both to the spending levels for many programs and
to language dictating the way some programs are run.
</P>
<P>
   But although they said they ill almost certainly not allow the
government to be shut down _ Congress can pass temporary spending
measures if Clinton should veto any of the appropriations bills _
Republicans said they may prove less willing to compromise than if
the president was not fighting for his survival.
</P>
<P>
   While the need to pass the spending bills and the Republican
desire to push for a tax cut insures that policy debates will not
be completely drowned out by Clinton's battle to avoid impeachment,
Democrats said his limited ability to twist arms on Capitol Hill
and rally public support could thwart any chance of them getting
their legislative initiatives through this year.
</P>
<P>
   Without considerable help from the president, Democrats said,
the party's already difficult struggle to push new regulations on
health maintenance organizations through the Senate will become a
long shot at best.
</P>
<P>
   A hobbled and distracted president will also make it
considerably more difficult for Democrats to build pressure on
Republicans to go along with a proposed increase in the minimum
wage, a key goal of liberals in the final weeks of this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's problems also raise questions about a variety of other
issues, including how much time he will have to devote to foreign
policy. And his troubles have in some ways demoralized Republicans
as well as Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   After the campaign finance overhaul bill that he co-sponsored
suffered another procedural defeat last week, Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., was asked if he would continue bringing up the bill in the
hopes of creating more pressure for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not as long as the president has got the problems he has,''
McCain said. ``We don't talk about HMOs anymore, we don't talk
about taxes anymore, we don't talk about Social Security anymore.
There's only one thing on everybody's mind and everybody knows it.
That's the great tragedy of the whole thing we are going through.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
