</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-PERJURY-BOS </SLUG>
  
 IS PRESIDENT JUST BEING LEGALISTIC IN DENIAL OF PERJURY?
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ There was a point in President Clinton's Jan. 17
deposition in the Paula C. Jones sexual harassment suit when he
seemed to shed his occasional vagueness and uncertainty and became
uncommonly direct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never had sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky,'' he
told Jones's lawyer. ``I've never had an affair with her.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, eight months and so many revelations later, Clinton's team
of personal and White House lawyers argue that he was legally
correct in that declaration _ an assertion that has been ridiculed
by critics, disputed by many legal scholars, and has infuriated
lawmakers on both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<P>
   Digging himself further into potential trouble, on Aug. 17, in
his appearance before the federal grand jury, Clinton defended his
January declaration by saying, ``I did not have sexual relations,
as I understood that term to be defined.''
</P>
<P>
   The definition of sexual relations that had been explicitly read
to Clinton at the Jones deposition included any contact with the
genitalia or any fondling between the two partners. Lewinsky, the
former White House intern, told prosecutors that she engaged in
oral sex with Clinton 10 times and that each time, Clinton fondled
her breasts and occasionally touched her genitalia.
</P>
<P>
   Independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr, in his report to Congress
made public on Friday, accused Clinton of perjury in both the
January deposition and the August testimony, saying he knowingly
concealed his sexual relationship with Lewinsky, or at least the
nature and extent of the relationship, while under oath.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers seem to regard the perjury charges as the
clearest and most significant threat in the report. Asked Sunday if
lying under oath was a serious charge, White House counsel Charles
Ruff responded, ``Of course.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers and analysts now say Clinton and his lawyers are
engaged in a type of legal and semantic gymnastics transparent to
even the casual layman, an effort, they assert, that could doom the
president's attempts to garner forgiveness on Capitol Hill and
serve out the remainder of his term.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a stretch,'' said Susan Low Bloch, a professor at
the Georgetown University Law Center. ``He is taking the position
that having oral sex performed on him, she's engaged in sexual
relations but he is not. But it also requires him to dispute her
other allegations of physical contact, which is covered by the
deposition.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, White House lawyers Sunday did not directly dispute
Lewinsky's testimony that Clinton fondled and stimulated her during
their encounters near the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't necessarily mean because people recollect things
differently that either one of them is lying,'' said Clinton's
personal lawyer, David Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Invariably, as Clinton's lawyers journeyed across the talk show
circuit Sunday, they adamantly declared that Clinton had not
committed perjury, but they appeared unable to support their
assertion. Each time, they contended that the Jones deposition was
``a mess,'' they said Clinton had made a full admission in August,
and they changed the subject to friendlier terms.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president did not commit perjury,'' Kendall said on ABC's
``This Week.'' ``Our point is that the Starr report is full of
graphic and unnecessary salacious detail. It's not relevant to any
of the charges.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the Jones deposition, Clinton was repeatedly shown a
definition of sexual relations that included any contact with the
genitalia, breast, buttocks, or groin.
</P>
<P>
   In January and February, in the wake of Clinton's public
denials, his aides repeatedly said he was not involved in the type
of word play that had come to characterize some of his prior
controversies, such as drug use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex means sex, even in Washington, I've been assured,'' White
House communications director Ann Lewis said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Clinton's lawyers have repeatedly said that the
dictionary definition of sexual relations includes only
intercourse, and that was the definition Clinton was using when he
provided his answers in the Jones deposition.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; el.5l &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The White House is the only group of people who can see
ambiguity in the questions,'' said Jonathan Turley, a professor of
law at George Washington University. ``There is no question that
the president repeatedly and clearly lied under oath. Moreover,
there is little question that he repeated some of that false
testimony before the federal grand jury.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
