</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: yet heard.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ruff asserted on NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that perjury does not
warrant the initiation of impeachment hearings, nor does any of the
other presidential behavior so graphically described in Starr's
report
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States, whatever he did _ and he
has misled the American people and he has engaged in wrongful
sexual conduct with Ms. Lewinsky _ what he didn't do is do anything
that warrants the beginning of the impeachment process,'' Ruff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said that lying under oath is ``clearly not'' grounds for
impeachment, a view repeated by David Kendall, the president's
private attorney, in a separate television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's denial of a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky
originally came in the Jones lawsuit, in which Mrs. Jones alleged
that the president made a crude advance while he was governor of
Arkansas and she was a low-level state employee. Mrs. Jones'
lawyers asked Clinton a series of questions about his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky and the president repeatedly denied that he had
engaged in sexual relations with her under a detailed definition of
the term that includes touching of the breasts and genitals. Ms.
Lewinsky testified that their sexual encounters almost always
included such touching, as well as oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said that the president ``absolutely'' sought to mislead
Ms. Jones' attorneys during the Jan. 17 deposition, but excused his
action as justified by the context.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an arena in which his political enemies were out to
destroy him in a frivolous case that was then dismissed,'' Kendall
said. ``He did not perjure himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he had, Kendall declared, ``No prosecutor from the
United States on the basis of this interchange would bring a
perjury prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also preparing to announce as early as
Monday the hiring of several new lawyers and political advisers to
augment the president's defense team. Among those being considered
for a top post on the White House damage-control squad is Gregory
Craig, a former aide to Sen. Edward Kennedy and currently the
director of policy planning at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a former law partner of Kendall's and longtime friend of
Hillary Rodham Clinton, said in a brief telephone interview on
Sunday that he was still weighing the White House offer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the White House pursued its defense strategy, there were
signs from Democrats both of continued slippage and of steadying
support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., has been one of the president's most
reliable allies throughout his travails, but over the weekend he
expressed anger at Clinton's parsimony with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lies by being technically accurate. I wish he would stop
it,'' Frank said in an interview Saturday with a Fall River, Mass.,
radio station. ``He's not 14 anymore trying to outsmart the
principal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Sunday, Frank said that he believed
Clinton would survive the current crisis, but as a president who
had been ``diminished politically and discredited personally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a quandary,'' said Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., who is
retiring after this term. ``Based on first read of all this I'm not
yet convinced we're talking about proper grounds for impeachment.
Yet I'm afraid there's been pretty severe damage done to the
effectiveness of the president's presidency.'' There was evidence
from New York, however, that Mr. Clinton continues to be a strong
draw for Democratic fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, the chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, said on Sunday that the party had logged what he termed
a ``sort of late-surge of support'' from contributors for a
fund-raising event in New York on Monday night that will feature
Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and his
wife, Tipper. Grossman said the fund-raiser, which was originally
expected to raise around $3 million, now has commitments of over $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although some New York Democratic elected officials have said
they would not attend the event with Clinton _ citing prior
commitments, as opposed to wariness about being photographed with
him _ Grossman said that he had seen no signs of any of the party's
contributors backing off because of the president's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying over and over again that this defining
moment and we want to stand with the president,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   The public, naturally, sees things differently from the lawyers
and politicians who dominate the Sunday chat shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the street fair in Poolesville, Md., Pat Michaels, a travel
agency executive, expressed a widespread feeling of exhaustion with
the months of lurid revelations and the political gridlock the
scandal has brought to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Rep. Constance Morella, a Republican whose
congressional district includes Poolesville, working the fair
crowd, he rushed to her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to ask one thing,'' he said, frustration in his
voice. ``For God's sake, get us out of this mess.''
</P>
<P>
   As the nation debated the good, the bad and the tawdry in the
Clinton presidency, his top lawyer issued a categorical denial that
Clinton would ever leave office voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by NBC's Tim Russert on Sunday morning, Ruff was
asked if the president would consider resigning.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert: ``No way?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert: ``Ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
