<SLUG> BC-STARR-HILLARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON STANDS BY HER MAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Bill Clinton cheated on his wife when she was out
of town, when she was out of the country, when she was upstairs,
and when she had just come home from church on Easter Sunday.
Monica S. Lewinsky also said the president led his young girlfriend
to believe his marriage might end when his term was over.
</P>
<P>
   For most women, it would be reason enough to throw the guy out,
file for divorce, maybe even poison his coffee. But Hillary Rodham
Clinton hasn't said anything unkind about her caddish husband since
the scandalous Starr report of his sexual affair with the intern
came out, and her actions speak louder than words.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Mrs. Clinton stuck to the president's side, applauding
when he profusely apologized at a White House prayer breakfast.
Later, she shared a songsheet with him at a memorial service for US
embassy workers killed in Africa. At day's end, she was radiant and
animated as she introduced her husband at an Irish-American peace
awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is the matter with this woman?'' asked Claudia Barlow, a
spokeswoman for Independent Women's Forum, a conservative group.
``I think she allows him to be a bad boy because it elevates both
of them to greater heights of power. But it's confounding.''
</P>
<P>
   Friends of Mrs. Clinton say her stoicism and resilience are
exactly in character. It may look like an act, and indeed, it is
very important politically for the president that she be
supportive. But it's also obvious that throughout her marriage,
Mrs. Clinton has repeatedly forgiven her husband for infidelities
and humiliations that few wives would abide.
</P>
<P>
   Boastfully, the president allegedly told Lewinsky he ``had had
hundreds of affairs; but since turning 40, he had made a concerted
effort to be faithful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the rumors that she has not forgiven him are
hogwash,'' said Martha Burk, president of the Center for the
Advancement of Public Policy, a feminist group. ``She isn't trapped
in an abusive relationship; she is smarter and more competent than
he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is doing this because it is best for her, for the country,
and for her family,'' Burk said. ``That's what feminism is; women
making choices about what is best for them and their families.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Reich, the former Labor secretary, was a classmate of the
Clintons at Yale Law School, where Bill Clinton and Hillary Rodham
met. He said Mrs. Clinton knows her liberal social agenda would
lose its strongest advocate if the president resigned or was
impeached.
</P>
<P>
   ``At her core, Hillary is a crusader,'' Reich said. ``I can't
imagine her failing to continue to fight for him because that would
be the equivalent of giving up the fight herself.''
</P>
<P>
   Crises have brought other first ladies to the fore. Edith
Wilson, the strong-willed wife of Woodrow Wilson, essentially took
over the presidency after her husband had a stroke in 1919 and was
incapacitated for ths rest of his term. Eleanor Roosevelt bolstered
her husband, Franklin, during times of national trauma and was
greatly admired for her leadership and causes.
</P>
<P>
   Lady Bird Johnson was ``an anchor in her husband's life'' and an
``important force'' in Lyndon B. Johnson's political career,
according to Robert Dallek, a Boston University historian and
Johnson biographer. Nancy Reagan relentlessly defended and
protected her husband and, like Mrs. Clinton, was a woman to be
reckoned with inside the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though their ideologies were quite different, I see Mrs.
Reagan and Mrs. Clinton sharing the same energy, determination, and
approach,'' said Lewis Gould, an emeritus professor of history at
the University of Texas and the author of ``American First
Ladies.'' ``They are two gladiators who wouldn't give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to now, Mrs. Clinton's determination to stand by her husband
has paid off politically. Her popularity has soared in the last
eight months, public opinion polls show, particularly among older
women who once were put off by her aggressive and untraditional
copresidential style. It isn't unprecedented for Americans to
embrace &UR;  &LR; vulnerable first ladies; many admired Betty Ford, Nancy
Reagan, and Barbara Bush when they revealed bouts with addiction,
cancer, and depression.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the White House have lobbied for Mrs. Clinton to go live
and public with a statement of forgiveness in the wake of the
report by independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr. But in the fiercely
protective East Wing, known as ``Hillaryland,'' spokesmen for Mrs.
Clinton are keeping quotes terse and reporters guessing about just
how fragile the Clintons' relationship really is.
</P>
<P>
   Marsha Berry, the first lady's press secretary, said Mrs.
Clinton did all she needed to by saying on Aug. 18 she was
``committed to her marriage and loves her husband.'' Mrs. Clinton
made no public appearances over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Mandy Grunwald was a campaign aide in 1992 when allegations of
Clinton's extramarital affair with lounge singer Gennifer Flowers
nearly sank his presidential candidacy. Then, Mrs. Clinton appeared
on ``60 Minutes'' with her husband to confirm their marriage was
sound. Grunwald doesn't advise that this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is about her,'' Grunwald said. ``She has
demonstrated her public support for the president, and beyond that,
what happens between them is between them and private.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to gauge the role Mrs. Clinton is playing inside the
White House as a political strategist and lawyer as the president
fights for his survival. In other crises, aides say she has been in
full battle mode, managing the kind of aggressive damage control
the White House waged over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lewis, the White House communications director, will only
say that the Clintons, since law school, ``have talked about what
is important in their lives, and this will not be any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the first lady is maintaining a busy schedule of solo
engagements and joint appearances with her husband. Today she will
travel with the president to New York for a series of big
fund-raisers. Tomorrow she will be on her own when she opens the
new Peace Corps headquarters in Washington, gives a speech to a
Jewish organization, and attends a dinner honoring civil rights
leader Dorothy Height.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady also is in great demand among Democratic
candidates, and many expect her to campaign much more actively than
her husband this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Clinton has kind of a make-or-break role to play,
particularly with women voters who see the president's behavior as
gross and upsetting,'' said Patricia Ireland, president of the
National Organization for Women. ``Their relationship becomes sort
of a metaphor for his presidency: It's not without serious flaws,
but on the whole, the good outweighs the bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women go through this in their own marriages and identify
with it,'' Ireland said.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. J. Philip Wogaman, pastor to the first family at
Foundry United Methodist Church in Washington, said Mrs. Clinton is
``in good spirits in spite of everything.'' Her religious faith is
``at the root of her life and gives her resiliency, her commitment,
and her fortitude. I know she is deeply committed to her marriage
and to seeing this whole thing through.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the president? On July 4, 1997, Lewinsky said, Clinton
gave her reason to believe they could resume their relationship
after he left the White House. ``I don't know, I might be alone in
three years,'' Clinton told her, according to the Starr report.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was one of the goofiest and most gratuitous
things in Starr's report,'' Grunwald said. ``If the president did
say it, it's because people say a lot of things they don't mean
when they are in a relationship. It doesn't occur to me that the
Clintons won't be together four, 10 or 40 years from now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
