<HEADLINE>
FIVE YEARS AFTER ACCORD, MIDEAST PEACE SEEMS DISTANT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 1-888-603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) (th) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The fifth anniversary of the Oslo peace accords took
place here Sunday with a third day of violent unrest and Israel's
closing of the West Bank and Gaza Strip as an American envoy
continued to hammer at the impasse in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   As the envoy, Dennis Ross, visited Cairo, Egypt, as he shuttled
between Palestinians and Israelis, a palpable pessimism descended
over those who had initial hopes that his visit would produce a
breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the pessimism was fresh anxiety that a terrorist attack
could be imminent in retaliation for the Israeli Army's killing of
two Islamic militants last week on the day after Ross arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli officials said Sunday that they would bury the men, two
brothers who were key operatives in the Hamas movement, rather than
release the bodies to their family for a public funeral that could
escalate into a riot.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, an Israeli general altered the official
account of the killings.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier statements, the army said that it had raided a safe
house on Thursday afternoon and gunned down its occupants only to
discover after the fact that the dead were two long-wanted
fugitives, Imad and Adel Awadallah.
</P>
<P>
   But in a briefing for foreign journalists Sunday, Maj. Gen.
Joseph Ya'alon said that when he ordered troops to storm the
farmhouse outside Hebron on Thursday afternoon, he expected them to
find the brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Yaalon said that the house's owner, a Hebron merchant, had been
interrogated and told the Israelis the brothers were inside
sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   He said that troops had begun surveillance of the house after
hearing explosions in the surrounding fields, although, he added,
no evidence of explosions was later found.
</P>
<P>
   The general said Sunday that he had ordered the soldiers to try
to arrest the brothers so they could be interrogated. The soldiers
sent in dogs first, then followed, shooting before the brothers had
a chance to draw the weapons they wore on their hips, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the situation,'' he said, ``they found themselves forced to
fire and kill them.''
</P>
<P>
   While a spokesman said the army officially denied any assistance
by Palestinian security forces _ an active rumor here since one of
the brothers had escaped recently from a Palestinian jail _ Yaalon
said he would ``neither confirm or deny.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Palestinian commanders are blamed as collaborators by
Palestinian society'' when they cooperate, so any such cooperation
needs to remain secret, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The general's statement illuminated just how much the Israeli
action had thrown a wrench into the peace negotiations. Ross has
been trying to get the two sides to sign a memorandum elucidating
their cooperation on security issues. But both face pressures not
to capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   After the killings, Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
cannot appear to be cooperating too readily, according to an
Israeli expert close to the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   And the Israelis must underscore the very active threat posed by
Palestinian terrorism to justify not only their military action but
also the closures, which bar Palestinians from entering Israel and
are expected to remain through the Jewish High Holy Days next week.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the prime minister's press office chose to mark the
fifth anniversary of the signing of the Oslo accords by sending out
new statistics on Israelis killed by terrorists in the last five
years.
</P>
<P>
   Hamas, which has not carried out a suicide bombing in a year,
has vowed to do so in retaliation for the brothers' slaying.
</P>
<P>
   But Israeli intelligence experts said Sunday that they believe
Hamas has been planning another attack since February anyway.
Israelis thwarted what was meant to be a ``spectacular attack'' on
the Haifa bus station late last winter, they said.
</P>
</TEXT>
