<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Sept. 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Heavy showers and some thunderstorms will produce local flooding
Monday in parts of the eastern Plains and westerm Mississippi
Valley. The heaviest rain will fall near the track of a slow-moving
low pressure area as it moves north from Missouri to Iowa. More
than three inches will fall in some areas. Farther south, scattered
heavy showers and some flooding will linger over parts of eastern
Texas where the soil is saturated from recent rains.
</P>
<P>
   Gradual drying will develop over Mississippi and Louisiana as
high pressure strengthens over the interior Southeast. Elsewhere in
the southeast, very warm weather with abundant sunshine and
moderate humidity will prevail. A few afternoon thundershowers can
erupt in the sultry air over central and southern Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Another surge of unseasonably warm air accompanied by patchy
clouds will spead into the Northeast. Onshore breezes will keep
coastal New England several degrees cooler than the interior. Near
record heat is expected in parts of the Middle Atlantic States and
eastern Ohio valley where sunhine will be plentiful.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a band of potent thunderstorms will develop ahead of
a cold front in the northern and western Great Lakes States. In the
wake of the front, cooler and less humid air will spread from the
northern Rockies into the northern Plains.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the west will be sunny and warm. A few thundershowers
will develop along the east slopes of the Rockies where moist air
ascends the sloping terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Graveyard for Storms
</P>
<P>
   Alaska is a place where Pacific storms often go to die. During
the cold season, many storms are born along the Asian Coast, where
temperature contrasts between land and ocean provide energy for
developing lows. The storms are then typically steered toward the
Gulf of Alaska by prevailing high-altitude winds. Just before the
death-knell rings for the tempests, they reach peak intensity,
creating recurrent storminess over the Gulf. Early Sunday, six weak
low pressure centers, which were formerly potent Pacific storms,
were strewn across Alaska, causing patchy rain and snow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
