<HEADLINE>
PERJURY IS FOUNDATION OF GROUNDS FOR IMPEACHMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA;
CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(lb) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON and JEFF GERTH    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The independent counsel's contention that there is
``substantial and credible information'' supporting 11 possible
grounds for impeaching President Clinton boils down to four
charges: perjury, obstruction of justice, witness tampering and
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   It could take weeks to evaluate the effect of the case assembled
by the Whitewater independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, and his
office. But a close reading of Starr's submission to Congress and
the supporting documentation so far made public shows that some
charges rely more on direct evidence, while others turn on
interpretation of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Perjury is the cornerstone on which rest five of the 11 grounds
cited for impeachment in Starr's report. The report states that
Clinton lied under oath, when he denied having had sexual relations
with Monica Lewinsky, both in his deposition in the Paula Jones
sexual misconduct lawsuit and before Starr's federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   The report also charges Clinton with lying about being alone
with Ms. Lewinsky and about the many gifts they exchanged, which
included books and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lewinsky's efforts to find a job form the basis for two more
perjury accusations. Starr says that the president was untruthful
regarding his own discussions with Ms. Lewinsky about her job hunt
and that he also lied about his discussions with Vernon Jordan, the
prominent Washington lawyer and friend of Clinton who helped Ms.
Lewinsky seek a job in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In more than 100 pages of the report, Starr has amassed a large
body of evidence, based on the testimony of Ms. Lewinsky, her
friends, other witnesses, phone logs and physical evidence, to
challenge the veracity of Clinton's insistence that he did not have
sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The president has said his denials were based on a definition of
sexual relations in the Jones case that he understood to exclude
the kind of sexual contacts he had with Ms. Lewinsky. That is why
he called his answers ``legally accurate'' in his Aug. 17 address
to the nation, even while conceding that his answers were
incomplete and admitting to the grand jury that he had an
``inappropriate intimate'' relationship with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The report contains graphic descriptions, based mostly on Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony and the contemporaneous descriptions she
shared with friends, of 10 separate sexual encounters between her
and Clinton. Most of the encounters did involve the kind of
intimate touching and sexual contact that does appear to fall
within the Jones case definition of sexual relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president's denials _ semantic and factual _ do not
withstand scrutiny,'' Starr concludes, characterizing his lies as
``abundant.'' Starr rejects the basis of Clinton's sworn denials of
having had sexual relations with Ms. Lewinsky. ``The president's
linguistic parsing is unreasonable,'' the report concludes.
</P>
<P>
   The report also accuses Clinton of lying in his deposition in
the Jones case when he said he could not recall being alone with
Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The report cites evidence that Ms. Lewinsky and Clinton were
alone together on numerous occasions, drawing on testimony from Ms.
Lewinsky, the president's secretary, Betty Currie, Secret Service
agents and a White House steward.
</P>
<P>
   In his deposition, the president also said he was not sure
whether he discussed the Jones case with Ms. Lewinsky. Ms. Lewinsky
testified before the grand jury that she spoke three times to the
president about the prospect of testifying in the Jones case, and
that the president called Ms. Lewinsky at 2 a.m. on Dec. 17, 1997,
to tell her that her name had appeared on the witness list of the
Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   In these alleged instances of lying, among more than a dozen
cited in the report, Starr concludes that the president had a
motive to commit perjury. ``The president also had strong personal,
political, and legal motives to lie in the Jones deposition,'' the
report states. ``He did not want to admit that he had committed
extramarital sex acts with a young intern in the Oval Office area
of the White House. Such an admission could support Mrs. Jones'
theory of legal liability and would embarrass him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president's lawyers maintain that a ``disagreement about
the very specific details of certain encounters'' would be rejected
as the basis for a perjury prosecution and should be rejected for
impeachment because it rests on ``simple inconsistencies and memory
disparities between only two witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most serious charges do not revolve around
descriptions of sexual behavior. But Clinton's defense of the more
serious charges is more emphatic than his denials of lying about
sex, and the support for some of the most serious charges appears
to rely more on circumstantial evidence and logical inference than
direct testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Starr says that Clinton obstructed justice in four instances:
scheming with Ms. Lewinsky to hide their relationship mainly
through allowing her to submit a false affidavit, helping her seek
a job in New York, refusing to testify before the grand jury for
seven months, lying to senior aides knowing they would give false
testimony and helping Ms. Lewinsky conceal gifts he had given her
that had been subpoenaed.
</P>
<P>
   u wxxnt06 nt17 nt22 nt26 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
uwxx nypt &QL; 
 &UR; BC-CLINTON-CHARGES-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WASHINGTON: been subpoenaed. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie and Ms. Lewinsky figure in one of the more serious
of those charges _ the hiding of the gifts _ and there is
considerable conflicting testimony on some important points.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute that Clinton gave Ms. Lewinsky gifts that
she failed to turn over to lawyers for Mrs. Jones after they had
been subpoenaed. And both Ms. Lewinsky and Mrs. Currie agree that
Mrs. Currie picked up the gifts from Ms. Lewinsky and kept them at
her home during the court case. Mrs. Currie's lawyers turned them
over to Starr last January in response to a subpoena.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the president is not clear-cut. On the question
of what Clinton told Ms. Lewinsky to do with the gifts, the
president testified that he told her ``you have to give them
whatever you have.'' Ms. Lewinsky, however, said that when she
raised the possibility of hiding the gifts _ saying, ``Give them to
someone, maybe Betty'' _ the president offered a noncommittal or
somewhat ambiguous response _ either ``I don't know'' or ``Let me
think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie said that it was Ms. Lewinsky who initiated the call
that led her to go and pick up a box containing the gifts, and that
she had no recollection of the president's talking about it with
her. But Ms. Lewinsky says it was the president's secretary who
called her and said, ``I understand you have something for me.''
And according to Ms. Lewinsky, Mrs. Currie invoked the president's
name when picking up the gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors tried to reconcile the contrasting versions by
asking Mrs. Currie about Ms. Lewinsky's testimony. The president's
secretary said that Ms. Lewinsky ``may remember better than I.''
</P>
<P>
   Starr evaluated the conflicting and circumstantial evidence and
concluded that ``the president orchestrated this transfer'' of
gifts because it was ``unlikely'' Mrs. Currie would have been
involved without the president's assent.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie stands at the center of another serious charge by
Starr, that the president tried to corruptly influence Mrs.
Currie's possible testimony. The president's lawyers call the
charge ``the product of extraordinary, overreaching and pejorative
conjecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Mrs. Currie on Saturday night, Jan. 17, 1998,
shortly after testifying in the civil lawsuit brought by Mrs.
Jones. The president summoned his secretary to an unusual meeting
the next day. There, according to Mrs. Currie, the president went
over her understanding of his meetings with Ms. Lewinsky by asking
his secretary a ``series of questions that were more like
statements than questions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You were always there when she was there, right? We were never
really alone,'' Mrs. Currie quoted the president as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The president told the grand jury he did not try to get Mrs.
Currie to lie and was only trying to refresh his recollection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that this was part of a series of questions I asked
her to try to quickly refresh my memory. So, I wasn't trying to get
her to say something that wasn't so,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Currie's testimony to the grand jury about the meeting
varies at points and is different in some respects from what she
originally told Starr's investigators.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the question of whether Clinton and Ms. Lewinsky
were ever ``alone,'' Mrs. Currie presented different
interpretations to the grand jury. She testified that the president
and Ms. Lewinsky were either in the Oval Office or in the study
without anyone else present, but she did not consider them to be
``alone'' because she was at her desk outside the Oval Office.
</P>
<P>
   Another of the statements that Clinton made to Mrs. Currie was
that Ms. Lewinsky had wanted to have sex with him. Starr noted that
Mrs. Currie ``did alter a statement that she previously made to the
FBI,'' when she subsequently testified before the grand jury. Her
testimony was that Clinton's statement to her about Ms. Lewinsky
wanting to have sex with him ``appeared simply intended as a
statement, not a statement he wanted Mrs. Currie to agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   This goes to the heart of whether Clinton was trying to
influence what Mrs. Currie might say in her testimony. But Starr's
report sheds little light on what Mrs. Currie said about being
corruptly influenced.
</P>
<P>
   The submission to Congress said, ``Mrs. Currie testified that,
based on his demeanor and the way he made the statements, the
president wanted her to agree with them,'' but the supporting
footnote does not provide Mrs. Currie's actual words.
</P>
<P>
   Starr argues that Clinton's explanation that he was trying to
refresh his recollection with his secretary is ``not plausible''
and ``conflicts with common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the ``content of the president's statements and the
context in which those statements were made'' that ``provide
substantial and credible information that President Clinton sought
improperly to influence Mrs. Currie's testimony'' and was involved
in obstruction of justice, the report states.
</P>
<P>
   The last impeachment charge outlined by the report is that the
president has abused his power.
</P>
<P>
   According to Starr: ``President Clinton abused his
constitutional authority by (i)lying to the public and the Congress
in January 1998 about his relationship with Ms. Lewinsky;
(ii)promising at that time to cooperate fully with the grand jury
investigation; (iii)later refusing six invitations to testify
voluntarily to the grand jury; (iv)invoking executive privilege;
(v)lying to the grand jury in August 1998; and (vi)lying again to
the public and Congress on Aug. 17, 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of this charge rests on questions about motives, not facts.
Clinton and his lawyers do not deny, for example, that executive
privilege was invoked, but they say it was done at the request of
White House counsel ``to protect the constitutional interests of
the presidency'' and not to impede any investigation.
</P>
<P>
   And the last two parts of the abuse-of-power charge lead back to
where Starr's case begins in the first place: Did Clinton lie to
his aides, the country and the grand jury, about his sexual
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
