<HEADLINE>
MUCH OF CHIAPAS COAST ISOLATED AFTER FLOODS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico _ After a week of floods fed
by the heaviest rainfall in decades, much of the coastline of the
southern Mexican state of Chiapas continues to be immersed in
turbid brown water, and dozens of communities remain cut off from
food deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   As the flooding persists, President Ernesto Zedillo said its
damage has been surpassed in this century only by the 1985
earthquake that shattered the center of Mexico City, killing at
least 8,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In Chiapas, 78 bodies have been recovered and 157 people were
reported as missing. Zedillo said on Saturday that he expected the
totals to rise as emergency workers reached isolated lowland
villages that were completely under water.
</P>
<P>
   The waters gouged many holes in the highway along the 160-mile
coast and carried off dozens of railroad and highway bridges. An
airlift involving more than 70 helicopters started on Saturday,
when the skies cleared after 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   About 400,000 people live in inundated areas that are out of
communication and are facing starvation, Zedillo said, and 25,000
whose houses have washed away are in government shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the flooded areas, victims accused local officials,
especially those from the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party,
of favoring allies when handing out the meager aid.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
