<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARR-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-13 1585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEY TO SURVIVAL, CLINTON TOLD, IS TO STOP BEING LEGALISTIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Several key Republican and Democratic lawmakers
declared Sunday that President Clinton may survive his political
crisis if he abandons his technical defense against the impeachment
allegations. Their remarks provided the first sliver of hope for
the White House in a weekend of uneasy contemplation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the president has a chance of getting through it,''
said Senator Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee. ``But quit splitting legal hairs. If they'll quit
playing this legal game, and start being what he is, a basically
warm, winning person who the American people have liked from the
beginning, if he'll do that, and just acknowledge, `Yeah, I've done
some really bad things, I really screwed up here,' my gosh, I think
the president could get through this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's declaration came as Clinton's lawyers fanned out across
the television dial Sunday in a strident display of defense. They
argued that as unseemly as it was, Clinton had committed no
impeachable offenses in his illicit affair with Monica S. Lewinsky
and his subsequent denials.
</P>
<P>
   The remarks also came amid a growing sense that the House will
inevitably launch into impeachment proceedings in the next few
weeks, though Clinton could ultimately persevere or avoid the
process with a formal censure or reprimand on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton skipped Sunday church services and remained out of
the public eye for the second consecutive day, his lawyers advanced
the awkward argument that the president did not perjure himself in
a January deposition in Paula Jones's sexual-harassment suit when
he denied having a sexual affair with Lewinsky. Clinton has since
admitted an affair, leaving the conclusion that his denials _ even
under oath _ were a lie.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; if,,.1l &LR; Today, Clinton is scheduled to shed the stifling mood
of Washington and the White House for a trip to New York, where he
plans to deliver a speech on international economics before the
Council on Foreign Affairs, then attend a fund-raiser with
Democratic supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, meanwhile, stepped cautiously into the realm of
opinion Sunday. In a city and system of government driven naturally
to compromise, there is no middle ground in the question of whether
to remove Clinton, leaving senators and representatives tentatively
looking at their constituents before staking a position.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch's comments, made on CBS News's ``Face the Nation,'' marked
an end to what the White House perceived as a deafening silence
from Capitol Hill in the two days since the Starr report was
released. A conservative with a considerable following, the Utah
Republican is considered so crucial to Clinton's strategists that
the president pleaded his case by calling Hatch in his car minutes
before Hatch arrived at the CBS television studio.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hatch's opinion was not universally held, and even Hatch
expressed some ambivalence. The senator also said the House should
open impeachment proceedings and declared that if Clinton continues
to pursue a legalistic defense against Starr, he could lose his
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody should be impeached who's been elected by the American
people twice unless you have absolutely strong reasons for doing
so,'' Hatch said. ``Now, if you take any one of these accusations
against the president, standing alone they may not be enough. If
you accumulate them, and put them all together, there could be room
enough to do this in the House of Representatives. My own personal
view is that we ought to follow it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Even some closely watched Democrats _ notably Senator Bob Kerrey
of Nebraska _ urged Clinton to veer away from his legalistic
defense against the impeachment allegations, specifically the
charges of perjury.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come and say to the American people that `I'm legally
correct, I didn't have sexual relations with Monica Lewinsky,'
you're going to lose,'' Kerrey said. ``I think the president
understands that.''
</P>
<P>
   Other key lawmakers, notably House Minority Whip Tom DeLay of
Texas, said Sunday that Clinton would not finish out his term of
office but would end his tenure either by resignation or
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he will wake up one day, I hope, and put the American
people before himself and resign,'' DeLay said on NBC's ``Meet the
Press.'' ``But if he doesn't do that, I think unless the lawyers
are better than what they've been in the last two days, and can
prove to us that he hasn't committed perjury, that he hasn't
suborned perjury, that he hasn't obstructed justice, I think he's
in real trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if trouble meant impeachment, DeLay replied, ``It
certainly looks that way.''
</P>
<P>
   National public opinion polls provided a mixture of hope and
fear for Clinton. In an ABC poll, 53 percent of the respondents
said Congress should hold impeachment proceedings rather than drop
the matter. In a CNN poll, 56 percent of those asked said Congress
should censure the president. In that same poll, 64 percent of the
respondents said Clinton should not be impeached and removed from
office.
</P>
<P>
   In every network poll taken since the Starr report, Clinton's
job approval rating remained between 59 percent and 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars and analysts began floating the notion Sunday that
Clinton could be impeached by the House, but survive a Senate vote
and remain in office. The Senate, in effect, serves as the jury
after the House in effect indicts a president on charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way for a president to regain legal legitimacy is to
stand before the Senate and answer the allegations,'' said Jonathan
Turley, a professor of constitutional law at George Washington
University, in a telephone interview. ``By exposing himself to
removal, he can regain the legitimacy of his office through a
Senate vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Democratic Representative David Bonior of Michigan,
the minority whip, signaled that a congressional censure was
probably inevitable, and even palatable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a lot of options here,'' Bonior said on NBC
News's ``Meet the Press.'' ``One is to do nothing, which is
unacceptable. The other is some type of rebuke of the president, a
public rebuke by the body, and I think that becomes a very real
option. The other, of course, is proceeding ahead with impeachment
proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   In return, White House lawyers expressed no immediate reluctance
toward a formal censure, which would allow Clinton to complete his
term and avoid the ignominy of being only the second president in
the republic's history to resign or the first to lose his job from
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   The White House goal is ``to convince not only the House
Judiciary but, very candidly, the American people that whatever
they believe happened here, there is no grounds for beginning an
impeachment process,'' White House counsel Charles Ruff said on
``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Sunday, Clinton spokesman Joe Lockhart said in a telephone
interview that the president had called Hatch in the morning as
part of a ``continuation of the process of reaching out to people
on the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Hatch's plea to Clinton to abandon his narrow legal defense
on the issue of perjury, Lockhart said, ``The president has a lot
of respect for Senator Hatch and what he says. We certainly take on
board any counsel that he provides publicly and privately.''
</P>
<P>
   But such a technical defense continued full bore Sunday, with
adamant denials by a cadre of Clinton lawyers that the president
did not commit perjury in the Jones deposition in January or the
appearance before the federal grand jury Aug. 17.
</P>
<P>
   In his 445-page report to the House, Starr has accused Clinton
of committing perjury in both appearances, saying that the
president lied in January in his denial of a sexual affair, and
perjured himself in August over the extent and nature of the sexual
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Starr's report included 11 possible grounds for
impeachment, ranging from multiple perjury counts to obstruction of
justice to abuse of office and tampering with a potential witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jones deposition testimony is a mess,'' said David
Kendall, Clinton's personal attorney on the case. ``The president
did not perjure himself there. He had complicated definitions. The
questions were vague and ambiguous. There were objections. There
was no follow-up. He was giving responses to a very narrow and
technical definition of `sexual relations.' When he testified
before the grand jury on Aug. 17th, he acknowledged that he had had
an improper relationship with Miss Lewinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendall added: ``In the Jan. 17th deposition, the president did
not perjure himself. He did not volunteer information, he did not,
I'll agree, try to help the Jones lawyers. This was an arena in
which his political enemies were out to destroy him in a frivolous
case that was then dismissed.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside the White House, senior officials expressed confidence
over the weekend that Clinton's strategists had finally prevailed
over his lawyers in gaining more control over the president's
speeches and responses to Lewinsky allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, asked if Clinton would address the affair in his trip to
New York today, Lockhart said he didn't know. ``It's not like he's
coming to us asking what he should say anymore,'' Lockhart said.
``This is personal for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
