<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2902 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     09-13 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
NEW YORK _ Who's No. 1?
</P>
<P>
   Cripes, who knows?
</P>
<P>
   Today, perhaps it should be Patrick Rafter by default. He
conquered the U.S. Open again Sunday, defeating his unseeded and,
ultimately, unprepared countryman Mark Philippoussis in four
largely forgettable sets. The ATP's computer says Pete Sampras
retains the top spot, but there's no compelling reason to accept
the mathematical evidence as gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has had a mediocre year, save for the Wimbledon
fortnight. Unfortunately, nobody else excelled either, least of all
Marcelo Rios, perhaps the least deserving player ever to earn a No.
1 ranking, which he gained briefly twice.
</P>
<P>
   That's what I mean about the blasted computer. It's not to be
trusted.
</P>
<P>
   The four Grand Slams produced four different champions (among
the women also, by the way) as 14 players appeared in the various
semifinals. Never have we seen such balance, or shall we call it
blah-lance?
</P>
<P>
   Petr Korda, the stick figure from the Czech Republic, won the
Australian Open, then fell off the planet. Carlos Moya won the
French but was served into submission here by Philippoussis, who
answers to ``Scud'' yet proved a dud in his first final-round Slam
dance.
</P>
<P>
   Pete, as usual, smoked on grass, only to pull up lame against
Rafter on America's center court. His thigh injury Saturday
afforded Rafter a virtual free pass to his repeat and, in the
United States, where tennis seems to get lost in the sporting
shuffle, rendered the outcome almost irrelevant on what became a
Slammin' Sammy afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But in Australia, these are the good ol' days once more in
theory. All for one and one for all it would not be Sunday, with
Philippoussis complaining about what he considered favoritism on
Rafter's behalf from his hallowed elders, particularly John
Newcombe and Tony Roche. Roche, the runner-up to Ken Rosewall in
the last all-Aussie final (1970), was a conspicuous presence in
Rafter's box.
</P>
<P>
   ``Newk's and Roche's job is to work for our Davis Cup team,''
Rafter said, seeking a diplomatic middle ground. ``That's what
they're hired for. And Mark hasn't made himself available to our
Davis Cup team. It's unfortunate. He's the kind of player who could
help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Between 1951 and 1973, when tennis was about as Australian as
shrimp off the barbie washed down by a Fosters, nine Aussies won
the U.S. Open _ and six of them won it twice. On 10 occasions
during those years, two would meet in the final. From 1956 through
1962, only the Peruvian-born Alex Olmedo crashed their finals
parties at Forest Hills.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in a strictly historical context, Sunday's matchup was
fairly mundane, ranking right up there with a man hitting 62 home
runs in a single baseball season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, by winning, the soft-spoken, big-stick-carrying Rafter _
``a warrior for his country,'' the Sydney Herald hailed him _ did
something Rod Laver, Roy Emerson, Newcombe and Rosewall, the Fab
Four of the amazing Aussie dynasty, never could manage.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his title. And at 25, he stands a decent chance of
trumping them all _ in New York, anyway. Because none of the
legendary Aussies claimed a third U.S. championship, although let
it be said every one of them save for Newcombe was deprived of
multiple prime opportunities. Once they turned pro, they were, of
course, banned from participating in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, tennis' being screwed up isn't exactly a new
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian surname most glaringly absent from the U.S.
championship trophy is that of Lew Hoad. A four-set loser to his
contemporary Rosewall in his only final (1957), Hoad never
returned. He had bills to pay _ not that the play-for-a-pittance
circuit was lucrative relative to the staggering sums accumulated
by the jaded current stars _ and chronic back problems had ended
his career before the Open era began in 1968.
</P>
<P>
   Laver, with his two calendar-year Grand Slams and 11 titles
total _ the same as Sampras _ is rated the greatest of this
illustrious bloodline, but some who remember Hoad say he's the real
bloke against whom Sampras should be measured. Luis Ayala, who put
Chile on the world's tennis map more than a generation before the
churlish Rios scowled his first, considers the burly Hoad his most
formidable adversary.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Emerson's surviving record of 12 Slams must always be
asterisked by Laver's conspicuous absence from most of the
tournaments Emmo won, it's possible Rocket Rod also made
considerable hay with Hoad out of the way. Laver's '62 Slam, in
particular, is suspect in the eyes of Ayala, who prevented Ashley
Cooper, another Aussie, from perhaps pulling off a Slam in '58.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, 66 and living in Houston, where he helps out at the
Forest Club (his son, Juan, is the head pro), came from two sets
down to defeat Cooper in the '58 French Open semifinals. Cooper won
the other three majors that year. Hoad also had completed a
three-fourths Slam in '56 before falling to Rosewall at Forest
Hills in the latter's last Slam before being exiled for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I remember,'' Ayala said, ``Hoad beat Laver maybe 17 times
in a row after Laver joined our tour. Lew Hoad is the best player I
played against.''
</P>
<P>
   Affirming who's No. 1 for the ages then is roughly as
complicated as sorting out the proper pecking order for '98. Either
way, Sampras is at best a marginal choice for the top spot. He gets
votes but no mandate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
