</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-?-?-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Massachusetts voters are overwhelmingly forgiving of
President Clinton and by a more than 3-to-1 margin are against
impeachment, according to a new Boston Globe-WBZ poll taken after
the release of special prosecutor Kenneth W. Starr's report to
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Despite weeks of unrelenting public criticism of the president,
Clinton's favorability ratings remained high and steady from a
similar survey in late August. Fully 53 percent of Bay State voters
polled offered positive opinions of the president while 36 percent
were critical.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with that support, Massachusetts voters were harshly
critical of Starr and the $40 million-plus price tag of his
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Those polled also were vocal in their distaste for the level of
graphic sexual detail contained in Starr's report on Clinton's
relationship with former intern Monica S. Lewinsky. More than
three-quarters said it was not in the public interest to know the
specifics of their physical involvement.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of 400 registered voters was taken Saturday and
Sunday. It has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Though Bay State support for Clinton remained high, there was a
growing sense that his ability to do his job has been diminished by
Starr's allegations. Fifty-six percent of the voters said he had
been weakened, up from 45 percent in a Boston Globe-WBZ poll taken
in late August.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton's contrition campaign of the past few weeks appeared
to be succeeding with Massachusetts voters, who by a more than 2-1
margin said they forgive him for his actions. There was a split,
however, depending on marital status: While 61 percent of single
people forgave Clinton, only 52 percent of married people found him
sufficiently repentant.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how the question was asked, voters in Massachusetts _
where Clinton received just over 60 percent of votes in 1996 _
overwhelmingly wanted to see Clinton remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he should face impeachment, 68 percent of
Massachusetts voters considered that action unwarranted, while 21
percent said he should be placed on trial by Congress. Asked about
resignation, 65 percent were against while 27 percent were in
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions on most questions tracked fairly closely between men
and women, but a few showed signs of a gender gap.
</P>
<P>
   While men were more likely to blame Clinton for his current
predicament, women looked more to Starr. Overall, 26 percent of
those polled said Clinton was responsible, versus 24 percent for
Starr and the rest divided between the media, Congress, and some
combination of all those parties.
</P>
<P>
   But among men, 31 percent blamed Clinton while 17 percent blamed
Starr. Fully 29 percent of women, however, placed the blame with
Starr, while 21 percent of women said Clinton was responsible.
Married voters were also more likely to blame Clinton, while single
voters looked first to Starr, saying Clinton was even less
responsible than the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts is the state that has been the most supportive
of him, and this state stands behind him and forgives him and wants
him to be able to proceed with the business of the presidency,''
said Gerry Chervinsky, president of KRC Communications Research of
Newton, which conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massachusetts voters do recognize, however, that Clinton will
not be able to function at the same level as he could before this
occurred,'' Chervinsky added.
</P>
<P>
   Just as the president's favorability ratings remained high, so,
too, did Massachusetts' opinion of the first lady. Sixty-one
percent of Bay State voters expressed support for Hillary Rodham
Clinton, with that support crossing gender lines. Starr won
favorable notice from just 19 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Starr's motives were highly suspect among those polled.
Some 61 percent said they believed he was motivated by a desire to
hurt the president, while just 28 percent said he was seeking the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   Yet relatively few doubted there would be a price to be paid
internationally now that the report had been released. More than
two-thirds said the allegations would negatively affect the world's
image of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly, those surveyed found it impossible to escape the
Starr report. Eighty-eight percent of Massachusetts voters were
aware of the report and, of those, 27 percent said they had read
it.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts poll tracked closely with national surveys
taken this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   An ABC News poll found 53 percent of Americans favor impeachment
hearings, while 42 percent said Congress should drop the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But when a CNN/USA Today/Gallup poll took the next step _ asking
if impeachment hearings should lead to Clinton's removal from
office, only 30 percent said yes, while 64 percent said no.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion that a majority of Americans do not want Clinton
forcibly removed from office was echoed by his continued favorable
job performance ratings nationally. Four separate polls by national
media organizations found the president's job approval ratings
ranged from 59 percent to 67 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts cautioned that polls taken so soon after release
of the Starr report are premature, reflecting an American public
not fully focused on the allegations' content and implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The activists and the political elites haven't even absorbed
this report yet, much less the American people who have real
lives,'' said political scientist Larry Sabato, director of the
University of Virginia Center for Governmental Studies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a distracted public a long time to learn about
something as important and difficult as this,'' Sabato added. ``It
argues for the process to play out over weeks or months, even if
people are tired of it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
