u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GLOBAL-ECON-7     09-13 1266
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GLOBAL-ECON-710&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO TRY PUTTING FOCUS ON GLOBAL ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
  (See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA;
CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN, CLINTON-CHARGES) 
(lb) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton will spell out on Monday a
six-pronged approach for a coordinated international response to
the financial crisis spreading around the globe, in his first major
effort to turn the country's attention back to policy since the
publication of the Starr report on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's aides insisted Sunday that his speech at the Council
on Foreign Relations in New York was scheduled long before the
White House knew that Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel, was
to deliver a report to Congress making a case for the president's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton will endorse using the International
Monetary Fund's ``spare fuel tank'' _ an emergency cache that is
now down to $15 billion _ to choke off the crisis, probably
beginning with loans to Latin America. He will also call for all
leading economies to worry less about inflation and more about
restarting stalled economies around the globe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balance of risks has shifted,'' a draft of Clinton's
speech says. ``The industrial world's chief priority must be to
spur growth.'' That message seems to be aimed at Japan in
particular.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a central public role now in fighting the financial
crisis is a complex dance for Clinton. It is bound to raise
questions about why the president, who by all accounts has been
heavily involved in strategy sessions concerning Asia and Russia,
is only now talking publicly about major initiatives, 14 months
into the crisis and in the middle of the biggest threat his
presidency has faced.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, in recent days some of his own aides, along with
global investors and senior officials among the United States'
allies, have wondered aloud whether he still has the moral
authority to organize a global response to a complex contagion.
</P>
<P>
   Some say he should have taken a more public role in putting
together support for Russia last month, in the days before it
devalued its currency and announced a virtual default on its debts
_ though it is unclear that even action by the president of the
United States could have stopped the worldwide run on the Russian
ruble.
</P>
<P>
   ``His speech tomorrow will be useful,'' said David Hale, the
chief economist for the Zurich Group, a financial-services company,
``but because of the diminishment of his own standing it would have
been even better six months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The concern is that in the coming months Clinton will be so
distracted by the debate over possible impeachment that he will be
powerless to push through an increase in Washington's contribution
to the IMF, or to marshal initiatives by the Group of Seven, the
world's largest economies.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton's aides argue that the spread of the
crisis to Brazil last week, along with the imminent threat to all
of Latin America and, more distantly, the United States, gives
Clinton an opportunity to cast himself as the world leader
spearheading a battle against global recession, rather than a
hobbled president looking for a way to survive in office.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Secretary, Robert Rubin, urged Clinton to assume
that role more directly in an emotional session he held with his
cabinet on Thursday night. After agreeing that Clinton had made ``a
terrible mistake'' in his relationship with Monica Lewinsky, Rubin,
by his own account, urged the president to take a leading role in
quelling the financial crisis, saying that ``the most important
thing now is the world economy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a very, very scary time,'' said one leading foreign
official, who has been deeply involved in the succession of
bailouts in Asia and Russia and in the recent panic over Latin
America. ``Clearly, the prospect of a weak American leader only
adds to the impetus around the world to sell.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the United States has moved from a rock of stability
in the global crisis _ the world's strongest economy and the muscle
behind the International Monetary Fund _ to another potential
source of uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   That impression was fueled in markets around the world late last
week when, just as the Starr report was being released, a House
panel declined to approve $18 billion more for the fund. Other
countries will not increase their contributions until Washington
goes first.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The move by Republican leaders who have long been suspicious of
the IMF, even before its remedies for international crisis became
the subject of wide criticism, brought a harsh response from
Stanley Fischer, the No. 2 official at the fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are decisions of enormous importance being made now
about the role that the United States plans to take in the global
economic system it created in 1945,'' Fischer said. ``It's no small
thing to decide to abandon that system.''
</P>
<P>
   Curiously, while Clinton has often called for Congress to
support the IMF, he has made only a handful of telephone calls
about the issue to members of Congress. That is a sharp contrast to
his marathon effort last year, which ultimately proved
unsuccessful, to press every member on trade legislation that would
have given U.S. negotiators more authority to strike deals that
Congress would not reopen later.
</P>
<P>
   The administration says that the timing has not been right for
the president to get personally involved in such lobbying. But it
is difficult to see how he could ask members of Congress to cast a
politically unpopular vote now, while he desperately needs their
support either to quash an impeachment inquiry or to strike a deal
that would submit him to only a censure.
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, meanwhile, declared on Friday
that it is down to its last $5 billion to $9 billion in ordinary
funds to fight the economic turmoil _ a signal to the markets that
it is in no shape to be a lender of last resort for much longer. A
bailout of Brazil, if one is needed, would probably require tens of
billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   So in his speech on Monday, administration officials say,
Clinton will endorse dipping into a backup fund, the General
Agreement to Borrow. That fund has about $15 billion left after it
was used, unsuccessfully, to aid Russia in July.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was sent $4.8 billion at the time, but future payments
have been halted during the political turmoil that has brought to
power a new economic team that seems likely to shift away from the
unpopular market reforms that are a condition of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Clinton will also call for countries around the
world, especially Japan, to act decisively to write off hundreds of
billions of dollars of bad debts that are sinking their banking
systems, and leading to a credit crunch around the world. But it is
unclear if he will directly say that they should use taxpayer
dollars to do so.
</P>
<P>
   He will also call for a meeting of the finance ministers of the
Group of Seven and emerging markets, probably next month in
Washington, to take stock of broader efforts to improve the
international finance system in the midst of its greatest threat in
decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
