<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: JETS FAIL IN 3 MOMENTS OF TRUTH 1 YARD FROM END ZONE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ They're not the same ol' Jets, but
they're not last year's Jets either.
</P>
<P>
   With an 0-2 start after Sunday's 24-10 loss to the Baltimore
Ravens, these Jets displayed the defects that should have been
expected early in the second season of Bill Parcells' makeover _ a
virtual rookie quarterback, a new running back behind a retooled
offensive line, a somewhat revamped defense and special teams
weakened by the departure of some players to starting roles. And a
more difficult schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not to excuse the offense's failure to seize any of
Sunday's three moments of truth: three shots from the Ravens'
1-yard line for the touchdown that would have supplied a 14-7 lead
late in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Don't argue that Parcells should have taken a chip-shot field
goal there on fourth down. In that situation, any National Football
League coach worth his headset would go for the touchdown. To do
otherwise at that stage of a 7-7 game would be a shameful surrender
to his offense's not being capable of getting that 1 yard (actually
more like 2 feet).
</P>
<P>
   For Parcells, who goes for it on fourth down more than any other
NFL coach, it wasn't a gamble. It was a go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to be able to make that,'' he would say later.
``That's a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   Going for that 1 yard is why Parcells signed running back Curtis
Martin to a six-year, $36 million offer sheet. It's why Parcells
signed guard Todd Burger to a $3 million contract, to solidify the
left side of the offensive line alongside tackle John (Jumbo)
Elliott. On each of those three downs, Martin ran behind Elliott
and Burger.
</P>
<P>
   But each time, the Ravens _ especially middle linebacker Ray
Lewis _ stopped Martin for no gain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were trying to run behind who we think is supposed to be
able to block,'' Parcells said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Raven tacklers swarmed to stop Martin more effectively
than the Jets were able to block.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect to be stopped,'' Martin said. ``I just believe
there's no way to stop me. They hit the right hole at the right
time. There's no excuse. I take the blame. I had the ball in my
hands. They stopped me. It's just something we haven't got clicking
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin meant the running game, which means him. Against the
Ravens, he rushed for 58 yards on 23 carries, a poor 2.5-yard
average on an artificial surface that he professes to prefer.
Against the 49ers on grass in San Francisco a week ago, he rushed
for 58 yards on 22 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Other than fullback Jerald Sowell's two carries for 1 yard a
week ago, Martin has been the Jets' only ballcarrier. But he hasn't
had the blocking that even a $36 million breakaway back needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over all, we haven't produced much,'' said Kevin Mawae, the
center signed to a five-year, $17 million deal. ``We've protected
Foley pretty well, but we haven't gotten many yards on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Even being protected ``pretty well,'' Foley was sacked four
times while completing 22 of 32 passes for 247 yards and an early
4-yard touchdown to Keyshawn Johnson for a 7-7 tie. But he threw
three interceptions, two by Rod Woodson, who returned one 60 yards
for the Ravens' clinching touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're having trouble running the football, there's more
pressure on the passing game,'' Foley said. ``When you run the
football, you can do anything you want. The pressure's on us now.''
</P>
<P>
   Against the Indianapolis Colts next Sunday, the pressure will be
on the Jets' running game to excel and ease the pressure on Foley
to outperform Peyton Manning, the touted rookie quarterback. But in
Foley's seven starts as the Jets quarterback, he has yet to put
together a complete-game victory.
</P>
<P>
   Just because this is Foley's fifth season with the Jets, he's
hardly an experienced quarterback. He's going to make mistakes.
He's going to throw interceptions, two of which Woodson pounced on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when you throw at him all day he's going to get a
couple,'' Foley said of the cornerback who was a member of the
NFL's 75th anniversary team. ``He's unorthodox. He doesn't always
play textbook defense.''
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason why Foley should have known not to risk
throwing in Woodson's area so often. But it's all part of his
education as a quarterback. Throw and learn.
</P>
<P>
   And with the Jets playing a tougher schedule than they did in
producing last season's 9-7 turnaround from 1-15 the year before,
how soon the line can spring Curtis Martin and how soon Glenn Foley
earns a quarterback diploma will determine how soon the Jets start
winning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
