<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-RAIDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS GO IN REVERSE AND LOSE TO RAIDERS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ With a difficult 1998 schedule that includes
five playoff teams from a year ago, the Giants had hoped to
stockpile victories early in the season when they faced teams that
have met with less success recently.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had put the Oakland Raiders, who lost their
season-opening game last week and who won just four games a year
ago, in that category.
</P>
<P>
   Little wonder the Giants (1-1) found themselves frustrated and
disappointed in the wake of Sunday's 20-17 loss to Oakland (1-1).
They also said they had learned something about themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we aren't good enough to start thinking we can beat
anybody,'' fullback Charles Way said. ``We came here thinking we
were doing all right. Things aren't all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Teammate Michael Strahan said: ``This is a great example of
looking at the schedule and thinking about the games you think you
should win. All that is wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defeat in what was a topsy-turvy game also revealed
some of the Giants' consistent weaknesses this year, specifically
an inconsistent offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants gained just 233 yards, and just 71 rushing.
</P>
<P>
   That performance had Giants Coach Jim Fassel promising changes
when his team meets the Dallas Cowboys next Monday. Fassel said
running back Tyrone Wheatley, who has been inactive for the last
two weeks, might see action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't come here today ready to fight to win the game,''
Fassel said. ``We were not a mentally tough football team today.
I'm disappointed with how we played on both sides of the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants quarterback Danny Kanell, who led the team on a last,
futile drive that fell 30 yards short of field-goal position, said
the Giants couldn't sustain a rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never felt in sync,'' he said. ``I don't know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Kanell's last-minute attempts to rally the Giants followed a
26-yard field goal by Oakland's Greg Davis, a kick that proved to
be the game-winning score.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants had taken their only lead of the game early in the
third quarter when Kanell threw a 25-yard touchdown pass to Chris
Calloway.
</P>
<P>
   The touchdown came one play after the Giants had apparently tied
the score, 10-10, on a 42-yard field goal by Brad Daluiso. But
Oakland's James Folston was called for holding on the field-goal
attempt, a penalty the Giants accepted because it gave them a first
down.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell went for the touchdown on the next snap, throwing the
ball behind Calloway in the corner of the end zone. Calloway made a
brilliant adjustment on the ball, catching it before Oakland
cornerback Eric Allen even knew Kanell had released the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' lead was short-lived. Less than four minutes later,
the Raiders led by 17-14 when Oakland quarterback Jeff George
lofted a pass over Giants cornerback Conrad Hamilton and into the
hands of the All-Pro receiver Tim Brown.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-yard field goal by Daluiso with 59 seconds left in the
third quarter tied the score.
</P>
<P>
   With 12 minutes 28 seconds remaining in the fourth quarter and
the score still tied, Daluiso missed a 40-yard field goal. Daluiso
appeared to slip on the dirt infield portion of the field as he was
executing his kick, which knuckled to the right of the goal posts.
</P>
<P>
   The field-goal attempt was set up by a 39-yard punt return by
Amani Toomer and a 10-yard run from scrimmage by Tiki Barber.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants trailed 17 seconds into the game when Napoleon
Kaufman burst through the middle of the line on the first play from
scrimmage and raced 80 yards virtually untouched into the Giants
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants, however, responded with an 8-play, 77-yard touchdown
drive to tie the score at 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The developing rapport between Kanell and wide receiver Ike
Hilliard was on display in the drive as the duo connected on an
18-yard completion and a 10-yard touchdown pass. On the touchdown,
Hilliard caught the ball just inside the 5-yard line and fought his
way over the goal line, pushing past three Oakland defenders.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' running game continued to struggle. Way ran for 21
yards on the team's second play from scrimmage, but for the rest of
the game, the Giants rushed for just 50 yards on 22 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders were having trouble getting their passing game going
in part from good pressure applied by the Giants' defensive front,
which sacked George five times.
</P>
<P>
   But just before the end of the first half, the Raiders mounted a
drive against the Giants' defense, which was sorely weakened by the
absence of nickel linebacker Scott Galyon. Galyon, one of the
Giants' most valuable players in pass defense, left the game with a
strained Achilles' tendon.
</P>
<P>
   With linebacker Jessie Armstead already hampered by an ankle
sprain, the loss of Galyon meant the backup linebacker Ryan
Phillips saw significant time in pass defense. Phillips, a former
defensive end, is normally a strongside linebacker and is not
accustomed to covering receivers downfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders' final drive of the first half appeared to have
stalled at the Giants' 23-yard line when the game officials
signaled that Phillips had recovered a fumble by Kaufman. But after
a brief consultation on the field, the referee Dick Hantak ruled
that Kaufman had been down by contact and that the Raiders had
maintained possession.
</P>
<P>
   On the final play of the half, Davis kicked a 41-yard field goal
for a 10-7 Raiders lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
