<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-GORE-650&AMP;ADD-     09-13 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-GORE-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLEET GORE IS FAR FROM THE MADDING CROWD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash.)  (See also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-DAY; CLINTON-CENSURE;
CLINTON-JUDICIARY; CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS;
CLINTON-SERMONS; CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT;
CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT; CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT;
CLINTON-WASHINGTON; CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS;
CLINTON-MARYLAND; CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA;
CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN, CLINTON-CHARGES) 
(lb) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This is the quintessential road trip for Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In two days of travel through the Pacific Northwest, on Saturday
and Sunday, he talked to enthusiastic crowds about light rails,
planned growth, economic revitalization, Social Security, health
care, education, coastal salmon and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he shared the podium with Democratic candidates
and elected officials and starred at eight fund-raising events,
where aides said he had helped local party officials in Oregon and
Washington generate more than $350,000 for congressional and
statehouse candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of all this activity, he made about as much news
as the sun rising. His only mention of the report by the Whitewater
independent counsel, Kenneth Starr, was a hurried and predictable
statement on Saturday _ no questions, please _ that he did not
think the case outlined against President Clinton in the Monica
Lewinsky matter justified impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our story,'' a close aide to the vice president said as Gore
made a speech in Vancouver, Wash., ``is that there is no story.
Maybe after the election, we'll step out. But not now. The country
is stable. Why make things unstable?''
</P>
<P>
   This is the protective bubble surrounding the nation's
second-in-command, a haven of rarefied air that fairly floats above
the political craziness along Pennsylvania Avenue in Washington,
unconnected to any aspect of the boss's relationship with a young
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the bubble, Gore carries himself like a politician
without a worry, other than standard anxieties over close
congressional races in a year of midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   Scandal? What scandal? Gore never mentions it in speeches and is
fiercely insulated by his staff from reporters. Two months from the
midterms and two years from the presidential balloting of 2000, he
is but two things above all else, a Clinton loyalist and a
presidential candidate. As his aides say, what is the upside for
him to elaborate now?
</P>
<P>
   And so, they say, Gore's campaign season will proceed in the
same manner as the trip at hand, stuffed with frenzied days like
Sunday, in which he followed a five-kilometer race to raise money
for breast-cancer research with five events before an overnight
flight to New York, where he is to join Clinton at a state party
dinner on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, he is off to Boston for an event with
Clinton, then his third trip this year to New Hampshire, an early
battleground for the 2000 presidential campaign. Next week, more of
the same is planned for Michigan and Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore, the bubble is the ideal campaign vehicle. By
assiduously avoiding sensitive subjects, he has cleared a path to
discuss only his favorite issues, administration initiatives that
many Democrats claim have bolstered the economy and reflect voter
satisfaction with Clinton's stewardship of the country.
</P>
<P>
   As a strategy, it satisfies his main agenda, supporting Clinton
and reinforcing policies that would be extended into a Gore
administration.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, Gore's message and crazy-quilt of a
schedule are allowing him to fine-tune his presentations before
partisan audiences. Listeners are beginning to see a politician
wholly unlike the 1992 and 1996 version of Gore, a self-parodied
``stiff guy'' lacking many of the touchy-feely qualities that make
Clinton such a hit along the rope line and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has become more emotive in speeches, more animated and
funnier. One of his best laugh lines generally follows a comparison
of the administration's proposal for a patient's ``bill of rights''
and the Republicans' version, which he calls a ``bill of goods.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, the Republicans are in such discord and disarray,''
Gore says with a straight face, ``that the right hand doesn't know
what the far right hand is doing.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the most part, the reconstituted Gore plays well to the
crowd, especially in places like Seattle, which are geographically,
and to some degree psychologically, far removed from events in the
nation's capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doorbelling a lot, and I'll bet I haven't gotten
more than two comments about the president,'' said Maureen
Gallegos, a businesswoman who is running for a seat in the
Republican-controlled Washington statehouse. ``Clinton's sex life
is his business. This district has experienced 20 years of growth
in five years, and that is presenting us with a lot of problems to
talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   For some partisan Democrats, Gore _ at least for now _ may be
the premier headliner to address them as he stumps for candidates,
makes a case for Democratic ideals and raises money.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Richardson, the campaign manager for Brian Baird, a
professor of psychology who is running to fill the open seat in
Washington's 3rd Congressional District _ Linda Smith, a two-term
Republican, is running for the Senate _ appeared ecstatic that Gore
helped draw more than 400 people to a rally at the Pearson Air
Museum in Vancouver, Wash., on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The event raised $30,000 for Baird, whose Republican opponent in
what is expected to be a close race will be decided on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Richardson was asked whether the crowd would have been
as exuberant had Clinton been the featured speaker, she hesitated,
a clear sign she was happy to have Gore at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear that question,'' she said, smiling because she
did. ``I don't have an answer for that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
