<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONDS-SAFEHAVEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS USING BONDS AS SAFE HAVEN FROM MARKET TURMOIL 
</HEADLINE>
   By ARTHUR M. LOUIS  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
If the stock market's precipitous plunges and thrashing volatility
have you terrified, you might want to consider investing in bonds.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the long haul, stocks perform much better than bonds. But
that may be small consolation if you hold a portfolio of stocks _
or stock mutual funds _ that has shed close to 20 percent of its
value since the leading market averages reached their peaks two
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   If you are like most investors, you probably wonder whether your
stocks might plummet another 20 percent or so before they bottom
out.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, nobody knows for certain. And there are too many unknowns
_ notably, President Clinton's political problems and the potential
spillover effect of the Russian and Asian financial crises _ to
allow a confident guess.
</P>
<P>
   If you have nerves of steel and aren't close to retirement, stay
with stocks, which have produced average annual returns of 9 to 11
percent over a period of several decades.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; With U.S. Treasury bonds yielding around 5 percent and
high-grade corporate bonds less than 6 percent, it's no contest.
</P>
<P>
   But if you can't sleep for worrying, a dose of bonds might be
just what you need.
</P>
<P>
   Norm Boone, with the financial-planning firm of Boone and
Associates in San Francisco, says that in theory, long-term
investors probably shouldn't bother with bonds because of their
inferior long-term returns.
</P>
<P>
   But in practice, he includes them in client portfolios ``to
reduce volatility.'' That way, the clients won't be panicked into
``selling stocks at the wrong time.''
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, bonds look particularly unappetizing at the
moment to growth-hungry investors because their interest rates are
at their lowest levels in decades, thanks to low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But on closer inspection, bonds actually look pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index rose a meager 1.7 percent in the 12
months ended July 31 _ the latest for which figures are available.
</P>
<P>
   With the 10-year Treasury yielding 4.84 percent at the end of
last week, the ``real'' yield _ the difference between the bond
rate and inflation _ was a respectable 3.14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Real yields of 3 percent or more are historically on the high
side.
</P>
<P>
   During the past 45 years, real yields have remained above 3
percent only about one-third of the time. The median real yield
during the period was about 2.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Real yields measure actual increases in buying power _ which is
all that really matters.
</P>
<P>
   To take a simple example, suppose you invest $1,000 in a
Treasury bond with a 5 percent yield.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of a year, you will have received $50 in interest.
With inflation at 2 percent, the real value of your $1,000
investment would decline by $20, so your real gain would be $50
minus $20, or $30.
</P>
<P>
   That's a better outcome than you would get if your bond yielded
10 percent and the inflation rate also stood at 10 percent. In that
case, your buying power wouldn't increase at all.
</P>
<P>
   The calculation actually is more complicated than that because
the market value of the bond is likely to change during the year.
When bond prices go up, interest yields go down because the annual
interest payment remains fixed.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, interest rates still are trending downward.
</P>
<P>
   Jittery investors, agonizing over the financial crises in Russia
and Asia and fearing a spillover into the U.S. economy, have taken
many billions of dollars out of stocks. They have poured the money
into bonds _ mainly Treasuries, which generally are considered the
safest investments on Earth. That has pushed bond prices up and
rates down.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Two months ago, the 10-year Treasury bond was yielding about
5.5 percent annually _ well above last week's 4.84 percent.
</P>
<P>
   If you bought one for $1,000 at that time, you would have
accrued somewhat more than $9 in interest by now. Better still, you
would have enjoyed $136 in capital appreciation _ the amount by
which the price increased to bring the yield down to 4.84 percent.
</P>
<P>
   That's a combined return of 14.5 percent, which is spectacular
for any investment in a two-month period.
</P>
<P>
   During a speech on September 4 in Berkeley, Federal Reserve
Chairman Alan Greenspan suggested that the nation's central bank
might reduce rates in the near future to offset the potentially
dire effects of the global financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   That statement more or less ensures that rates won't go up
anytime soon, and it was one of the key factors pushing bond rates
lower last week.
</P>
<P>
   But many observers, such as retirement planner Richard DelMonte,
with DelMonte Group in Danville, think that a Fed loosening has
been discounted by the bond market. It may be too late to ``do the
bond thing,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ducote, senior managing director of fixed-income securities
with Sutter Securities in San Francisco, advises against locking
yourself into bonds that won't mature in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   A bond investor is guaranteed to get back the face value of a
bond when it matures. But if you buy, say, a Treasury maturing in
15 or 30 years and yielding only 5 percent, you expose yourself to
the danger that interest rates and inflation will rise again.
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, would cause the value of your bond to drop.
Unless you decide to sell at a loss, you would be forced to wait 15
or 30 years just to get your original investment back. And the 5
percent annual interest you get during that period could seem
piddling _ especially if stocks stage a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   While Treasury bonds undoubtedly are the safest kinds, corporate
bonds and municipal bonds may be better buys at this point, some
experts say.
</P>
<P>
   That stems from the fact that the bulk of the money from
frightened investors has gone into Treasuries, forcing their prices
up more sharply. Corporates and municipals have lagged because they
are perceived as being more risky because there is more chance of
default. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   High-grade corporate bonds with virtually no risk of default _
including those issued by NationsBank, J.P. Morgan and PepsiCo _
now typically yield 0.6 percentage points higher than equivalent
Treasuries _ those that mature the same number of years out.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, the spread between corporates and Treasuries has
been only about half that 0.6 spread or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been overdone to the extent that the spread has widened
on every corporate bond, regardless of fundamentals, regardless of
exposure to Asia or whatever,'' says Peter Van Dyke, head of the
taxable-bond department with the T. Rowe Price mutual-fund group.
</P>
<P>
   Municipal bonds also boast unusually favorable yields relative
to Treasuries, says Zane Mann, publisher of the California
Municipal Bond Advisor, in Palm Springs.
</P>
<P>
   If you compare issues with comparable maturities, municipal
yields now range above 90 percent of Treasury yields, compared with
less than 80 percent formerly.
</P>
<P>
   Although municipals have lower pretax yields, their after-tax
yields are considerably greater. Municipals are exempt from both
federal and state taxes, while Treasuries are exempt only from
state taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Mann figures that a California municipal bond yielding 5 percent
_ as many now do _ will produce the equivalent of a taxable yield
of 9.13 percent for a California resident in the top federal and
state tax brackets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no other bonds of similar quality or maturity that
yield that much,'' he remarks.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy newly issued Treasuries in increments of $1,000 by
opening an account with the Federal Reserve. You can apply
electronically on the Web at www.frbsf.org/, or by calling the
Federal Reserve Bank of San Francisco at (415) 974-2000.
</P>
<P>
   You also can buy Treasuries in the secondary market through your
broker.
</P>
<P>
   Corporates can be bought in the secondary market through your
broker, usually for around $1,000 per bond. Or you can buy new
issues through any broker that participates in an offering.
</P>
<P>
   However, if you have limited resources, you might want to invest
in corporates through a mutual fund. That way you get broad
diversification, insulating yourself against risk.
</P>
<P>
   Mutual funds also might be your best bet if you want to buy
municipals. Municipals are sold in minimum increments of $5,000,
which means you need a minimum of $25,000 to diversify among just
five issues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
