<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN YOUR FIRM KEEPS MESSING UP THE PAYCHECKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ILANA DEBARE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 Q:  I'm a recent college grad who just got a part-time sales job
with a well-known telecommunications firm that is launching a
wireless startup. I've now been with them 60 days, but the company
is still making errors on my paycheck. In the most recent instance,
I should have gotten a check for about $300 in salary and
commission but instead got just $18. The company eventually
corrects its errors, but needless to say, I am still insulted. Do I
have any recourse here?
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Drop your feelings of affront this instant! Sure, it's
awful to have your paychecks messed up. And you can't exactly tell
your landlord, ``Sorry, I'm not paying rent this month because my
company only paid me $18.''
</P>
<P>
   But you still shouldn't take it as a personal insult. This kind
of stuff happens all the time _ especially in startup ventures that
have to create policies and procedures from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The irony is that companies like this can find a way to bounce
our voices off a satellite, but they can't figure out how to pay
people correctly,'' said Richard Moran, a partner at Andersen
Consulting in San Francisco and author of a new book titled ``Fear
No Yellow Stickies,'' about how to navigate today's organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Your first step should be to double-check your firm's
sales-compensation rules. Companies sometimes have a policy of
delaying commissions for several weeks or months to be sure that
the sale goes through. If that's the case, this might not be a
mistake _ just the way business is done at your firm.
</P>
<P>
   If this truly was an error, you need to complain to the right
person _ someone in charge of issuing paychecks. That may be
someone in payroll or accounting. Or it may be someone outside the
company if your firm uses an outside contractor for payroll
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Ask your manager to help you find the right person, Moran
advises.
</P>
<P>
   And be persistent. It might take a while, but eventually, your
company will get it right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; My company has been hiring new employees and giving them
more money than I get, despite the fact our ranks are the same and
that I've even trained some of the newcomers. This seems unfair. Is
it legal? I've e-mailed a complaint about this to my managers, but
they haven't done anything.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; Not only is this legal, it's pretty common these days _
especially in tight labor markets like Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Companies are desperate to hire skilled workers. And they're
willing to offer big bucks to get them, which means that they
sometimes end up paying newcomers more than longtime insiders.
</P>
<P>
   You're right to seek more money, but e-mail isn't the best way
to handle this _ or any other complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't ever use e-mail for a negative communication,'' warns
Jack Chapman, the Wilmette, Ill., author of ``Negotiate Your
Salary: How to Make $1,000 a Minute.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time criticism is written down, it takes on a permanence
that you may not want. People's feelings can be hurt, or they may
feel backed into a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Do some homework: Find out how much money people with your
skills are getting at other companies. One good source is the
JobSmart Web site, which offers dozens of salary surveys at
www.jobsmart.com.
</P>
<P>
   Then ask your boss for a face-to-face performance evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   Remind the boss of your accomplishments. Ask for input about
your work. Then _ if your supervisor thinks you're doing a good job
_ you can make a pitch to ratchet your salary up to the same level
as the newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   What if the boss says your work is great but still won't pay you
as much as your newly arrived peers?
</P>
<P>
   It may be time to get a raise by doing the same thing the
newcomers did _ finding a new job.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; The corporation I work for recently adopted an electronic
time clock for all hourly workers. In order to guarantee that
everyone is taking a lunch break, the clock has been programmed to
subtract a half an hour at the six-hour point in the employee's
day. This happens whether or not the employee actually takes a
lunch. Is this legal?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; No, it's not legal: Companies may not subtract pay for meal
breaks unless workers actually take those breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Your company may be doing this with the best of intentions,
trying to comply with the law by making sure that workers take time
off for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   California law says most nonexempt employees who put in more
than six hours must take a meal break _ even if they'd rather work
straight through lunch in order to leave the office a half-hour
earlier at the end of the day.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those areas of the law that people violate all
the time without anyone being the worse. Who hasn't scarfed down
lunch at their desk in order to meet a deadline or leave early for
a 4:30 p.m. dental appointment?
</P>
<P>
   Still, the law is the law. And employers are legally responsible
for making sure their workers take meal breaks.
</P>
<P>
   But this is definitely not the right way to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right way is to tell people to take a meal break,'' said
Tom Grogan, assistant chief of the California Division of Labor
Standards Enforcement. ``If they don't take breaks, the company has
the option of starting a disciplinary process. But it can't just
withhold their pay.''
</P>
<P>
   Want to file a complaint? Call the Labor Commissioner at (415)
557-7878. But a better move, at least to start, would be to
politely notify your personnel department that this new meal-break
policy could get the company in some big legal trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways,
San Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, Calif.
94103. Or send e-mail to workways &LR; sfgate.com. Or call (415)
764-2815. We can't respond to each query, but we will answer as
many in print as we can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2239EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
