<HEADLINE>
ONLINE PAY-PER-VIEW OF STARR REPORT WOULD'VE MADE A BUNDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK VEVERKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
We hear a lot about the unleashed potential of the Internet, but
who knew it would play such a significant role in altering our
perception of the presidency?
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Starr report in all of its graphic detail was available to
the masses almost immediately via the U.S. House of
Representatives' official Web site. Unfortunately, the document
wasn't exactly the Federalist Papers.
</P>
<P>
   What do you suppose James Madison or other framers of the
Constitution would have said about our electronic democracy in
action, not to mention Monica Lewinsky's account of our nation's
commander in chief in action?
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad Congress couldn't bolster our federal coffers by
charging for access to the site. Talk about your budget-deficit
busters. Given that sports, sex and financial news are the few
things capable of making money on the Web, the Starr report
qualified on two counts (the latter evident by the financial press'
obsession with the president's woes). I think that the federal Web
site would have been a major ``revenue enhancer'' as they say
inside the Beltway.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the bellwether Net stocks stayed on the sidelines
Friday while the broader market rebounded in response to the
independent counsel finally having made his case against the
president. Conventional wisdom is that some degree of uncertainty
had been lifted, giving investors renewed confidence in the market.
(Don't you love these rationalizations of short-term swings in the
market?)
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Net fans were not persuaded. Yahoo was flat,
closing at $79.88, while America Online slipped 88 cents to close
at $95. Meanwhile, K-Tel _ the poster child for wannabe electronic
commerce stocks _ saw its shares rise 25.5 percent to $8. Go
figure.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weisel Watch '98:  &LR; The NationsBanc Montgomery Securities
Investment Conference, or ``28th Thom Weisel Memorial Investment
Conference,'' commences today at the Ritz Carlton in San Francisco
amid speculation about the future of the confab's chief steward,
Montgomery Securities founder Weisel.
</P>
<P>
   A week or so ago, Weisel was making noises about leaving the
firm after his contract agreement with NationsBank had been broken,
but Bloomberg News reported Friday that he was negotiating to stay
as long as severance payments were paid up front.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, the uncertainty surrounding Weisel and the
investment bank should make for inspired cocktail chatter. The
Montgomery chairman is scheduled to welcome investors today at
lunch along with former Secretary of Defense Dick Cheney. And no,
NationsBank Chairman Hugh McColl isn't slated to make an appearance
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate politics aside, NationsBanc Montgomery's research
director John Skeen is expecting an alert crowd of fund managers at
this year's conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, investors have demonstrated the ability to panic
for the first time since 1990,'' Skeen says. ``And the big concern
is banking exposure to emerging markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors fear that there will be more confessions from the
banks and brokerages in coming weeks regarding write-downs in
countries ranging from Russia to Brazil, he says.
</P>
<P>
   As far as tonics go for these uneasy times, Skeen is
recommending telephone company securities, of which several will
make presentations this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Data and video services are growing like weeds,'' Skeen says.
``(But) the big wild card for me is the banks.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka &LR; sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
