<HEADER>
A2947 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-DAY-1STLD-WRI     09-13 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-DAY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-1,300(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE BEGINS OVER FUTURE OF CLINTON'S PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 19th and 20th grafs for new information concerning possible
deal on censure and for re-editing) (EDS: Second take to follow within 20 minutes.) 
(See Also: CLINTON-RDP; CLINTON-CENSURE; CLINTON-JUDICIARY;
CLINTON-REPUBS; CLINTON-EDITORIALS; CLINTON-SERMONS;
CLINTON-FEDERALIST; CLINTON-PORTRAIT; CLINTON-RECONSTRUCT;
CLINTON-NJ-ATTITUDES; CLINTON-FOREIGN-REACT; CLINTON-WASHINGTON;
CLINTON-TEXAS; CLINTON-MASSACHUSETTS; CLINTON-MARYLAND;
CLINTON-CURRIE; CLINTON-MEDIA; CLINTON-SAFIRE-COLUMN) 
(sw) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the president's lawyers arguing on Sunday that
even possible perjury by Clinton is not sufficient grounds for
impeachment, the country began a painful debate over the future of
his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The 445-page report to Congress by the independent counsel,
Kenneth Starr, was the talk at county fairs, in church pews, on
editorial pages and on television talk shows. And congressmen back
home with their constituents for the weekend, with less than two
months to go before election day, were listening closely.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews around the country, citizens continued to express
revulsion at the president's behavior but also their reluctance to
put the nation through the trauma of presidential resignation or
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, Dennis Pappas, a 55-year-old inventory
planner for the Boeing Co., summarized the president's behavior as
``wrong but not impeachable.'' Added his wife, Janice, ``Yes, its
between him and Hillary. I think the rest of us should get on and
get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   But in Poolesville, Md., Alex Viessmann, a retired Navy captain,
declared, ``I want him out of there. Just can't stand the man.''
</P>
<P>
   That conflict was apparent in the early polling. While
two-thirds of Americans believe Clinton does not share their moral
values, an identical number does not think he should resign from
office, according to a CBS News Poll released on Sunday. And while
Clinton's favorability ratings have slipped over the past several
days, he is still considerably more popular than Starr.
</P>
<P>
   The White House, ever sensitive to popular opinion, appeared to
be relying on those public views in intensifying the vigorous
defense of Clinton's actions and continuing the attacks on Starr.
</P>
<P>
   At least 25 newspapers have called for the the president's
resignation, including seven that circulate 250,000 or more papers
on Sundays, while others pondered weightily the historic impact of
the scandal. The president is ``morally unfit to continue in
office,'' declared The Albuquerque Tribune. The Detroit Free Press
argued that by stepping down, Clinton would be surrendering to
Starr and setting a dangerous precedent for future presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In houses of worship of all denominations, the clergy used the
week's events to emphasize the power of redemption and the healing
grace of God.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbis were preparing their congregations for the High Holy
Days; the Roman Catholic liturgy this week highlights the tale of
the Prodigal Son. Clinton skipped church on Sunday morning after
learning that his pastor, the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman of the Foundry
United Methodist Church in Washington, had made forgiveness the
subject of his sermon. Wogaman said in his homily that the Lewinsky
affair might be a blessing ``because it forced him to face up to
things.''
</P>
<P>
   The president did not want to make the congregation
uncomfortable by attending, an aide said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the majority leader, said that
the evidence is ``overwhelming'' that Clinton lied to a grand jury.
He added that perjury could clearly be grounds to open an
impeachment inquiry. In an interview on the Fox network, Lott said
that Congress almost certainly would proceed with impeachment
hearings.
</P>
<P>
   He expressed hopes that the president ``will weigh very
carefully in his decisions from here on in the impact that all of
this has on his family, and on the presidency, and on the country,
the government, our image overseas. He needs to use judgment, which
he certainly didn't exercise when it comes to, when it came to the
sex matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether such considerations might lead Clinton to
voluntarily step down, Lott said, ``It could. I mean, I guess, you
know, that's a call only he can make.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott returned more forcefully to the theme later in the
interview, saying: ``I think he has got to come to terms with the
seriousness of this matter, and decide what he can do to help all
of us to get through it. That may mean that he needs to consider
the counsel of senior members of his party in the Congress about
whether or not he should resign or not.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House dispatched the top members of the president's
legal defense team to the airwaves on Sunday morning to rebut what
they called Starr's politically-motivated effort to humiliate the
president with a catalogue of titillating detail and a list of
spurious impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a significant shift in strategy, the president's lawyers said
that even if Clinton did commit perjury in a civil deposition in
January and again before a criminal grand jury in August, that
alone did not form sufficient grounds to begin impeachment
proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever the president did or whatever the president said,
whether it was in January or August, there simply is no basis for
removing the president from office,'' said Charles F.C. Ruff, the
White House counsel, in the broadest defense of the president yet
heard.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   White House officials privately encouraged speculation that the
president would accept censure or some other form of reprimand from
Congress as preferable to a protracted impeachment inquiry, even if
it eventually cleared him.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said that even if Clinton lied about his relationship with
Monica Lewinsky, a former White House intern, in his January
deposition in the Paula Jones lawsuit and in his August grand jury
testimony, he should not be impeached. In fact, Ruff asserted on
NBC's ``Meet the Press'' that perjury does not warrant the
initiation of impeachment hearings, nor does any of the other
presidential behavior so graphically described in Starr's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president of the United States, whatever he did _ and he
has misled the American people and he has engaged in wrongful
sexual conduct with Ms. Lewinsky _ what he didn't do is do anything
that warrants the beginning of the impeachment process,'' Ruff
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff said that lying under oath is ``clearly not'' grounds for
impeachment, a view repeated by David Kendall, the president's
private attorney, in a separate television interview.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's denial of a sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky
originally came in the Jones lawsuit, in which Mrs. Jones alleged
that the president made a crude advance while he was governor of
Arkansas and she was a low-level state employee. Mrs. Jones'
lawyers asked Clinton a series of questions about his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky and the president repeatedly denied that he had
engaged in sexual relations with her under a detailed definition of
the term that includes touching of the breasts and genitals. Ms.
Lewinsky testified that their sexual encounters almost always
included such touching, as well as oral sex.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall said that the president ``absolutely'' sought to mislead
Ms. Jones' attorneys during the Jan. 17 deposition, but excused his
action as justified by the context.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an arena in which his political enemies were out to
destroy him in a frivolous case that was then dismissed,'' Kendall
said. ``He did not perjure himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he had, Kendall declared, ``No prosecutor from the
United States on the basis of this interchange would bring a
perjury prosecution.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House was also preparing to announce as early as
Monday the hiring of several new lawyers and political advisers to
augment the president's defense team. Among those being considered
for a top post on the White House damage-control squad is Gregory
Craig, a former aide to Sen. Edward Kennedy and currently the
director of policy planning at the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a former law partner of Kendall's and longtime friend of
Hillary Rodham Clinton, said in a brief telephone interview on
Sunday that he was still weighing the White House offer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As the White House pursued its defense strategy, there were
signs from Democrats both of continued slippage and of steadying
support for the president.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., has been one of the president's most
reliable allies throughout his travails, but over the weekend he
expressed anger at Clinton's parsimony with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lies by being technically accurate. I wish he would stop
it,'' Frank said in an interview Saturday with a Fall River, Mass.,
radio station. ``He's not 14 anymore trying to outsmart the
principal.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview on Sunday, Frank said that he believed
Clinton would survive the current crisis, but as a president who
had been ``diminished politically and discredited personally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a quandary,'' said Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., who is
retiring after this term. ``Based on first read of all this I'm not
yet convinced we're talking about proper grounds for impeachment.
Yet I'm afraid there's been pretty severe damage done to the
effectiveness of the president's presidency.'' There was evidence
from New York, however, that Mr. Clinton continues to be a strong
draw for Democratic fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Grossman, the chairman of the Democratic National
Committee, said on Sunday that the party had logged what he termed
a ``sort of late-surge of support'' from contributors for a
fund-raising event in New York on Monday night that will feature
Clinton, Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and his
wife, Tipper. Grossman said the fund-raiser, which was originally
expected to raise around $3 million, now has commitments of over $4
million.
</P>
<P>
   Although some New York Democratic elected officials have said
they would not attend the event with Clinton _ citing prior
commitments, as opposed to wariness about being photographed with
him _ Grossman said that he had seen no signs of any of the party's
contributors backing off because of the president's difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are saying over and over again that this defining
moment and we want to stand with the president,'' Grossman said.
</P>
<P>
   The public, naturally, sees things differently from the lawyers
and politicians who dominate the Sunday chat shows.
</P>
<P>
   At the street fair in Poolesville, Md., Pat Michaels, a travel
agency executive, expressed a widespread feeling of exhaustion with
the months of lurid revelations and the political gridlock the
scandal has brought to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Spotting Rep. Constance Morella, a Republican whose
congressional district includes Poolesville, working the fair
crowd, he rushed to her side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to ask one thing,'' he said, frustration in his
voice. ``For God's sake, get us out of this mess.''
</P>
<P>
   As the nation debated the good, the bad and the tawdry in the
Clinton presidency, his top lawyer issued a categorical denial that
Clinton would ever leave office voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Interviewed by NBC's Tim Russert on Sunday morning, Ruff was
asked if the president would consider resigning.
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert: ``No way?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Absolutely not.''
</P>
<P>
   Russert: ``Ever?''
</P>
<P>
   Ruff: ``Never.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
