r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN     09-13 0728
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES INCREASES VALUE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Don't tell Ismael Valdes the final two weeks are
meaningless. With a new general manager in town and his contract
about to expire, Valdes knows the best way to get on Kevin Malone's
good side.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes needs to show Malone that he is the pitcher who went
eight strong innings in Sunday's 10-inning 5-4 victory over the San
Diego Padres in front of 37,390 at Qualcomm Stadium, not the often
timid right-hander who has slipped the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the situation,'' said Valdes, who has two starts
remaining. ``but I have the confidence to show everyone who I can
be.''
</P>
<P>
   You could say the effort should be discounted by the Padres'
second-string lineup, which played because of the hangover from
Saturday night's NL West-clinching victory. You could say he blew
two leads and allowed a two-run homer to light-hitting Andy Sheets
in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   But it's what Valdes did from there that could count most. He
showed a grit he rarely displays and something manager Glenn
Hoffman said has developed after returning from five weeks on the
disabled list (strained left side).
</P>
<P>
   That is the quality Valdes needs to show Malone now if he wants
to reap any benefits from salary arbitration this winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something I have worked on very hard this year,'' said
Valdes, who threw 130 pitches. ``I've watched a guy like Chan Ho
(Park), who got a win (Thursday) when he didn't have his best stuff
and the other guy (Kevin Brown) was pitching so great. I wasn't
always able to do that. But you watch and you learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Although minor-league call-up Eric Weaver recorded his first
major-league victory after Bobby Bonilla's sacrifice fly scored
Trenidad Hubbard in the 10th, the focus was on Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   He is in the final season of a three-year, $4.3 million
contract. If he approached the 28 victories of his first two full
seasons in the past two years, Valdes could easily have become a $5
million-a-year pitcher. The Dodgers would have been happy to tie
him up long term rather than face the spiraling possibilities of
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at the way he pitched when he fell behind 4-2,''
pitching coach Charlie Hough said. ``That's a spot where he could
have just given up. But he held the Padres right there and I look
at that as a very good sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes fell behind in the fourth inning with one of the few bad
pitches he threw Sunday. It was a 2-0 fastball that Sheets drilled
into the left-field stands for a two-run homer. Suddenly, Valdes
was trailing Padres rookie right-hander Matt Clement, who was
making his first major-league start. Suddenly, Valdes had a choice.
He could be the pitcher who wouldn't come inside, wouldn't trust
his 93-mph fastball, wouldn't challenge hitters for much of the
past two years. Or he could be the pitcher who showed up Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers had given him a 2-0 lead, but the Padres tied it in
the second on three hits and a sacrifice fly by Ruben Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Sheets made it 4-2, but Valdes stopped it there. He retired the
next nine batters. After a walk and an infield single, Valdes got a
double-play grounder to end the inning. He retired the first two
batters in the eighth, then allowed a single to former Angels
catcher Greg Myers. But Valdes hit 91 mph on his final pitch, a
fastball that caught George Arias for a called third strike.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes turned the game over to Weaver, called up Sept. 1 when
rosters were expanded. During the past two weeks, the Dodgers have
lost Antonio Osuna and Mark Guthrie to injuries. Hoffman couldn't
use rookie right-hander Mike Judd because tonight's scheduled
starter Carlos Perez injured his ankle before the game and might be
scratched.
</P>
<P>
   But Weaver got through the ninth and got a run when Hubbard
walked, Eric Karros doubled and Bonilla flied to left to score the
winning run. Jeff Shaw allowed a two-out single to John Vander Wal
in the 10th but held on to record his 43rd save.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our bullpen was in tough shape,'' said Hoffman, who could have
Guthrie (left elbow) back by the end of the week. ``That's why what
Rocket (Valdes) did was so big. It was the kind of game where he
might have come out after six. Instead, he gave us a big lift.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
