<SLUG> BC-TEN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENNIS COLUMN: A RINGING TELEPHONE HERALDS A CHAMPION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Mark McGwire (remember Mark McGwire?) hit his
62nd home run (it was only six days ago, but it seems longer),
somebody asked him if he ever went back to his room and looked at
himself in the mirror and shouted, ``Yessss!''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire is in touch with his feelings, as the saying goes, but
he was not admitting to that feeling of exultation. In fact, he
looked horrified at the suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Another famous American slugger, however, will freely admit that
she went back to her hotel room on Saturday evening, looked at the
flashing red light on her telephone, and began to realize she
really had won the U.S. Open a few hours earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first call I got, and I'll never forget it, was from a guy
that plays on the tour, his name is Brian McPhie,'' Lindsay
Davenport recalled Sunday. ``He called and said it was 3:27 and I
just won match point and he called and was screaming in the phone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the ones you remember, the people that you play
with,'' Davenport added. `` I went through the whole list. You just
know a lot of people, friends of mine are very happy for me; it was
a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 22 other messages on the machine, including one from
one Billie Jean King, who knows a thing or two about championships.
Davenport did not answer any of them, for which she was mildly
apologetic Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being by myself for half an hour was really nice,''
Davenport said, ``just sitting down and relaxing and thinking about
it for a little bit. Realizing that I accomplished a goal. It's
really tough in life to set out and achieve your goals and I really
felt that I did that.''
</P>
<P>
   How does a new tennis champion celebrate the greatest moment in
her career? She goes out for dinner with 15 relatives and friends
at the Palm Restaurant in Manhattan, where more than one glass was
raised.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody kept asking, `Who won the U.S. Open?' and I kept
saying, `I did,''' Davenport said.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport had no problem sharing her satisfaction on Sunday, the
next day, the first full day of her life as an American-born
champion, the first since Chris Evert in 1982, and in a California
lineage with Tracy Austin and King.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about myself in their company,'' Davenport
said. ``Maybe this sounds too modest, but I mean it. I'm not in
their company. If I win 10 or 11, maybe I'll feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   One Grand Slam championship is quite enough at the moment for a
player who transformed her game and her physique in relative middle
age. Davenport, 22, is quite likely to touch a nerve in her home
country, because she seems so normal. She actually graduated from
high school, which on the tennis circuit is the equivalent of a
doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   She has always rushed back to California in her spare time, and
now she and her mother share a large home. And tennis fans have
watched her play through her sadness as her parents divorced after
raising their children.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, her joy was right up front as she returned to the
U.S. Open to play in the doubles final, in which she and Natasha
Zvereva lost to Martina Hingis _ whom she had beaten for the
singles title _ and Jana Novotna, 6-3, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Then she was whisked off on a golf cart to a photo opportunity
in front of the Unisphere, the large globe in the center of
Flushing Meadows-Corona Park. The duties and the rewards of being
an American-born champion were just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   Davenport took the long road to the title. She came along in the
wake of Steffi Graf and Monica Seles, and when they faltered, she
saw Hingis and Anna Kournikova and a whole slew of people named
Williams come racing along in their early and middle teens.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, it didn't make me mad,'' Davenport said. ``I think it's
good for tennis. The more good players there are, the better. Jana
has played the best tennis of her life in the last year. Arantxa
has worked hard. It's good for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Novotna won Wimbledon this year, and Sanchez Vicario won the
French, and Hingis had already made her mark in the Grand Slams.
Davenport was usually seen as a diligent young woman who came up
through the American system but lacked the flair to break through.
She is also so nice that she would endure endless questions about
when she was going to get into shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a slow learner,'' she said on Sunday, riding the golf cart
out to the Unisphere. ``I would hear something in a press
conference or observe something on the court, and eventually I
would get it. But I'm not stupid, either. I mean, I read the
papers. I know what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, she spent more time with the jump rope, she watched
her diet, and she melted 25 pounds off her 6-foot-2-inch frame.
Then she won her national championship, and the bright lights
started flashing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
