</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODSON DEFLATES JETS AND REVIVES A CAREER
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Success can be a powerful enemy. Success
can deceive the confident, tempt the bold, lead the brave into
traps.
</P>
<P>
   Last week in San Francisco, Glenn Foley, the Jets' brash young
quarterback, threw 58 passes and completed 30 _ 3 for touchdowns _
in an overtime loss to the 49ers. Most of the passes were quick out
routes to his favorite receivers, Keyshawn Johnson and Wayne
Chrebet, and to running backs. So there was no reason to suspect
that Foley would not keep going to the well Sunday against
Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But there was one critical difference between the 49ers last
week and the Ravens on Sunday: Rod Woodson, Baltimore's left
cornerback. With two crushing interceptions, Woodson turned a game
around for his team and may have turned two seasons around as well.
His 60-yard touchdown run after intercepting Foley in the fourth
quarter clinched Baltimore's first victory and sent the Jets to a
second straight defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He baits you; he guesses,'' Foley said of Woodson after the
loss. People talk about the wily veteran. Sunday, Foley, Chrebet
and Johnson discovered how demoralizing ``wily'' can be.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was driving the Jets for a tying score with nine minutes
to play when he went to his well one too many times. On
third-and-3, Foley wanted to sneak a back out of the backfield for
a cutesy low-risk pass. The Jets had run the route a couple of
times before, and Woodson laid off Chrebet, who lined up in the
slot. ``This time I said, `I'm going to jam the guy,''' Woodson
recalled. ``I got a good jam, he went outside, I looked over my
shoulder and saw the back coming out like he did before and saw
Foley looking right at him. I just dropped Chrebet, and he threw
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, for the Jets, is demoralizing history. Woodson, who is
in his first season with Baltimore but his 12th in the league, went
in for the score, walking the last 10 yards backward. ``I wanted to
make sure there were no flags,'' he said. ``That's a long way to
run to have it called back.'' No flags. Just fallen Jets.
</P>
<P>
   Woodson had victimized Foley early in the third quarter _ again
with the Jets driving _ when he stepped in front of Johnson and
returned it 16 yards to the Jets' 49. Eight plays later, Baltimore
took a 17-7 lead on a field goal. Again, a case of going to the
well one too many times against the wrong defender.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ran that route a lot last week,'' Woodson said, although
they ran it a little differently this time. ``I knew what they were
going to run: they were going to run a China 7, have the tight end
block. I took about three steps and stopped. Foley threw it a
little inside; me and Keyshawn kind of fought over that one.
Luckily for me, I won that battle.''
</P>
<P>
   Before injuring a knee in 1995, Woodson was regarded as one of
the greatest defensive backs ever. He had made six Pro Bowl teams
and was elected to the National Football League's 75th anniversary
team. He came back at the end of the 1995 season _ the first NFL
player ever to tear an anterior cruciate ligament and return in the
same season. But the rapid return was the beginning of a two-year
slide, although he made the Pro Bowl team again in 1996. He left
Pittsburgh after that season, then spent 1997 in San Francisco. The
49ers released him after the season. Sunday's game may have been
the beginning of a resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last two years I haven't been playing that well,'' Woodson
said. ``I know that. I haven't been aggressive. My mind-set has
been kind of off the last two years for whatever reason. The year
after my surgery, I played OK, but not real well because I was
really beat up throughout the year. Last year, I was just never
comfortable, never had a feel for the defense in 'Frisco. I went
out there to get me a ring; it didn't work. So I came back to a
place where I'm comfortable, back in the AFC Central, back to a
defense I know, back to offenses I'm very familiar with. When
you're comfortable, you play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Jets lost a heartbreak game on the road. They
were competitive, though, and Jets fans, in typical underachieving
fashion, explained away the loss as a valiant effort against a good
team on the road. But Sunday's loss was a just a loss. Nothing
heroic. No valiant effort to crow about, nothing to build on. They
were stopped on the ground _ again _ and shut down in the air when
it mattered.
</P>
<P>
   They were defeated by a wily veteran. Woodson added what the
Jets already know. ``I'm back with the same intensity I had when I
was younger,'' he said. ``I'm more aggressive, anticipating, taking
chances. When you take chances, you make plays and get beat on
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are left to contemplate an 0-2 start and a ruined home
opener. Someone needs to energize the Jets the way Woodson has
energized Baltimore. No need for Jets fans to panic just yet,
though a bit of anxiety might be in order.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
