<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS BREAK AIKMAN'S COLLARBONE, DEFEAT COWBOYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ On a day when the Dallas Cowboys' defense couldn't stop
the defending Super Bowl champion Denver Broncos, an injury to
quarterback Troy Aikman may have put a stop to their season.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman sustained a broken left collarbone on a scramble in the
second quarter of Sunday's 42-23 loss to the Broncos before 75,013
fans at Mile High Stadium and is expected to be out four to six
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate use the word use the word `devastating','' first-year
Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said. ``But it hurts our football team.''
</P>
<P>
   And after the Broncos' dominating offensive show _ which was
highlighted by a 191-yard effort from all-pro running back Terrell
Davis, including first-quarter touchdowns jaunts of 59 and 63 yards
_ the same could said of the Cowboys' defense.
</P>
<P>
   Though he played the lead role, Davis was not alone in hurting
the Cowboys, who had no answer for the Broncos passing game as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Denver quarterback John Elway kept a Cowboys defense aimed to
stop the run off balance by completing 16 of 22 passes for 268
yards and two touchdowns to tight end Shannon Sharpe, who caught
six passes for 98 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Even Broncos ``possession'' receiver Ed McCaffrey joined in a
515-yard offensive output with five catches for 117 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defense tackle Chad Hennings compared the first-half
effort when the Broncos (2-0) scored touchdowns on five consecutive
drives and the Cowboys allowed 35 points, their most ever in one
half, to World War II's infamous invasion of Normandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like Omaha Beach,'' said Hennings, a former Air Force
pilot and Gulf War veteran, of the 35-17 halftime deficit. ``We
were shellshocked. We weren't able to answer soon enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Hennings acknowledged that the defense, which entered the season
with concerns about stopping the run and putting pressure on the
passer, had its confidence shaken Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are down on one knee,'' Hennings said. ``But we are not out
for the count.''
</P>
<P>
   A dejected Gailey, who now must prepare the Cowboys (1-1) for
next Monday's crucial NFC East battle with the ground-oriented
Giants, was particularly disappointed in the Cowboys' run defense.
</P>
<P>
   With a pre-game goal of stopping the run first, Gailey said he
was surprised the Broncos ran well and so easily on his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just overall, I was surprised they could move the ball like
that on our defense,'' Gailey said. ``I thought we'd stop the run
or stop the pass. I didn't think they could do both. But I thought
we'd stop the run, that's what we keyed on.''
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, it didn't look like the Cowboys keyed on
anything. The Broncos' first touchdown drive took advantage of the
Cowboys focusing on stopping Davis.
</P>
<P>
   On second down at the Cowboys 38, Elway set up in a shotgun
formation with five receivers spread wide against the Cowboys' base
defense. Sharpe ran undeterred down the middle and hauled in a
38-yard Elway touchdown pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had matchup problems, and they had a great game plan,''
Cowboys strong safety Darren Woodson said. ``I wasn't prepared to
see that. They spread us out. With our standard package in there,
we couldn't matchup.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys answered with a 36-yard touchdown strike from Aikman
to receiver Ernie Mills. But the defense never regained balance.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to stop the pass, the Cowboys were now at the mercy of
Davis and the Broncos' running game. Four plays into the ensuing
drive, Davis went around the left side and outran Cowboys
linebacker Dexter Coakley 59 yards to the end zone. Davis followed
with the 63-yard touchdown run on the Broncos' next play and
finished the first quarter with six carries and 138 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The final score and the loss of Aikman overshadowed a strong
performance by the Cowboys' offense, which appeared to be gaining
some continuity in Gailey's new system.
</P>
<P>
   Smith ran the ball well, gaining 93 yards on 20 carries and all
the receivers got into the act. Michael Irvin led the way with six
catches for 81 yards, but Billy Davis caught four balls and Mills
two, including the touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also accentuated the positive, which included moving
the ball in the second half behind Garrett, who completed 14 of 19
passes for 113 yards.
</P>
<P>
   However, they said other players will have to step up for the
Cowboys to get through Aikman's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got other great players,'' Smith said. ``We just got to
pick up the slack. We've all got to step up and believe we can win
games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
