<HEADER>
A3040 &Cx1f; ttf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-     09-13 0911
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-WEEKEND-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 9/13/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- TEN-USOPEN-MEN, 9-13 --
Patrick Rafter, flying high and on his way to putting his signature
on the U.S. Open's trophy for the second consecutive year on
Sunday. Rafter committed just five unforced errors during the 6-3,
3-6, 6-2, 6-0 pasting of his fellow Australian, Mark Philippoussis,
that secured him a second career Grand Slam crown. (Chang W.
Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- CLINTON-RDP, 9-13 --
President Clinton leaving the Old Executive Office Building on
Sunday after a meeting that commemorated the Arab-Israeli peace
accord. With him were his White House aides Lynn Cutler, Ann Lewis
and Minyon Moore. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MOSCOW -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- RUSSIA-CRISIS-ARTS, 9-13 -- A
cellist and a violist of the Seasons chamber orchestra in Moscow
going over a Tchaikovsky piece during a rehearsal break. The
group's concerts are often sold out, but low ticket prices mean
little income for members of the orchestra. Russia's artists have
never had it easy. With the ruble gyrating like a yo-yo, their
already difficult existence has become even more tenuous. (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DAHAISHE, West Bank -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- ISRAEL-UNREST,
9-13 -- Pessimism ruled on the fifth anniversary of the Oslo peace
accords. Palestinian protesters, carrying a coffin marked 'Oslo Is
Dead' in Hebrew, marching on Sunday at the refugee camp of Dahaishe
in the West Bank. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DUNDALK, Ireland -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- NIRELAND-CHANGE,
9-13 -- Brian O'Neill, a store owner and former head of the chamber
of commerce in Dundalk. Dundalk, a town 13 miles from the border
with Northern Ireland once harbored so many Irish Republican Army
safe houses, underground weapons networks and gunmen on the run
that police called it ``El Paso.'' ``We are saying that this is not
a part of us. People who do these things do not represent our
community,'' says O'Neill of the acts of violence in Northern
Ireland. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WORCESTER, Mass. -- Sept. 13, 1998 --
CLINTON-MASSACHUSSETTS, 9-13 -- Rep. Jim McGovern, Democrat of
Massachussetts, talking with Judy Ellis at the Wrentham Town Common
on Saturday. Most Democratic candidates can't do enough to distance
themselves from President Clinton. But not Jim McGovern.
``Notwithstanding the fact that you can't pick up a newspaper and
not read about scandals, there's a lot more to the government than
scandal,'' says McGovern. (Rick Friedman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) POOLESVILLE, Md. -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- CLINTON-MARYLAND,
9-13 -- Rep. Constance Morella, Republican of Maryland, seeking
votes for reelection to a seventh term, chatting with John Cooper,
a Cub Scout leader and a Democrat who voted for Clinton, at the
annual Poolesville street fair. Cooper opposes impeachment
proceedings. ``It's true that the country has been terribly hurt by
all this,'' says Cooper. ``What he's done is inexcusable, but it
isn't resignation or impeachable stuff. What I say is that, now
that it's all been aired, let's push on.'' (Justin Lane/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ROCHESTER, N.Y. -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- FRONTIER-PROSPECTS,
9-13 -- Joseph Clayton, 48, chief executive of the Frontier
Corporation, has continued to push Frontier's lofty goals. But high
expectations are a staple these days at Frontier Corp., as the
company tries to evolve beyond its roots as a local phone monopoly.
In many ways, Frontier's evolution from clumsy striver to
turnaround prospect reflects the difficulties faced by old midsize
companies in an industry dominated by national titans and lean
niche operators. (Phil Matt/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PROVO, Utah -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- NOVELL-MAJOR-PROFILE,
9-13 -- As chief scientist, Drew Major, 48, is the technological
soul of Novell Inc. One of the company's first three employees in
1982, Major, now the leader of the company's once-demoralized
engineering ranks, contends that Novell has found a way to once
again thrive in Microsoft's long shadow. ``We were a Microsoft
wannabe. But now, Novell understands that we have to be who we are,
and that is an independent maker of a specialized operating
system,'' says Major. (George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Sept. 13, 1998 -- JEKYLL-HYDE-MANIA, 9-13 --
Pat Costa, a nurse from West Islip, N.Y., has seen the musical
``Jekyll and Hyde'' 70 times. Most people in the Broadway audience
each night are first-timers, of course. But, as the Deadheads of
Broadway, hard-core ``Jekkies'' have helped build word of mouth
that has made the show a phenomenon. ``We're normal people usually.
Maybe it's a case of arrested development. What I didn't do at 16,
I'm doing at 47,'' says Ms. Costa. (Barbara Alper/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
