<HEADLINE>
CAN SOWARD ZIP INTO HEISMAN RACE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A Heisman Trophy campaign was expected to begin in
Los Angeles on Saturday, it just wasn't supposed to take place
inside the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   But USC wide receiver R. Jay Soward staked a claim to the
Heisman race when he tallied 256 total yards and scored three
touchdowns against San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   Soward had a 53-yard touchdown reception, a 74-yard punt return
for a touchdown, a 42-yard run and an 8-yard touchdown reception.
He averaged 28.4 yards every time he touched the ball. So is it
time to start the Heisman talk?
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't object, but don't expect a lot of talk out of me
because last year the talk got me in trouble,'' Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   This is the new Soward, a balance between natural exuberance and
political correctness.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. No Heisman. I'm not thinking about it. If you guys want to
write about me, put me in the Heisman race. That's you guys,''
Soward said.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to dismiss Soward's impact after one game, but the
spark he provided USC in its 35-6 victory over the Aztecs was
beyond dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just the talent. It's the energy he creates,'' USC
coach Paul Hackett said. ``I'm so proud of him, of the way he
handled himself after being (suspended for one game).''
</P>
<P>
   If Soward is a one-man scoring machine, his effect on others is
also significant. Just ask quarterback Mike Van Raaphorst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this. They know we'll throw it deep with R. Jay, but
they still can't stop it,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``He's just too
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst also experienced a bit of redemption against San
Diego State, after his opening effort against Purdue was so closely
scrutinized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I played a lot better and did what I expected of
myself,'' Van Raaphorst said.
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore quarterback admitted that he was distracted
against Purdue after experiencing food poisoning the night before
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was sick at 2 a.m.,'' Van Raaphorst said. ``It was something
I ate at the hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   The offense grabbed the headlines, but USC's defense has become
its trademark two games into the season. The Trojans have allowed
just six points in their past six quarters of football, and no
fourth quarter points in their past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker David Gibson continues to make plays, with eight
tackles, three forced fumbles and three sacks. Middle linebacker
Chris Claiborne was everywhere, with 11 tackles and two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   But before getting too excited, it's worth noting USC has not
yet played a top-notch opponent. And the penalties _ including four
false starts in the first half _ were not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   The offensive line remains suspect, and the defense has not yet
faced a physical, ball-control team. The kicking game will also be
under the microscope this week after Adam Abrams' 0-for-3
performance. Punter Mike MacGillivray also struggled, with a long
punt of 35 yards and averaged 32.8 yards per kick.
</P>
<P>
   Notes: Center Eric Denmon was wearing an ankle boot after
suffering a high sprain and could be out for this week's game
against Oregon State. Tight end Antoine Harris suffered a minor
ankle sprain but said he would practice this week. Linebacker Mark
Cusano tweaked his already sore left ankle during a brief
appearance and could sit miss some practices this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
