<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S DEFENSE HALFWAY TERRIFIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UCLA coach Bob Toledo admitted he was anxious. Defensive
coordinator Nick Aliotti said he was clueless. Each spent last week
wondering how UCLA's young defense would perform in the season
opener against Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was right in front of them all along.
</P>
<P>
   Each day for three weeks _ sometimes twice a day _ UCLA's
defense faced one of the nation's most potent offenses. What better
way to prepare a young unit than line it up against Cade McNown and
Co.?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really had no clue how we'd do,'' Aliotti said after the
Bruins defeated Texas 49-31 Saturday in the Rose Bowl. ``It's tough
(to get a feeling) when you're only going against yourself. But
it's been push-push against the offense and that's been
encouraging, because I think our offense is outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the concerns on defense, replacing tailback Skip
Hicks and receiver Jim McElroy were inconsequential.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have two senior starters, linebacker Brendan
Ayanbadejo and safety Larry Atkins. They had a new coordinator,
Aliotti, who replaced the popular and unconventional Rocky Long.
And they had a new system, as Aliotti tossed Long's unique 3-3-5 in
favor of a traditional 3-4-4.
</P>
<P>
   The most experienced lineman, Pete Holland, is a junior with
seven career starts.
</P>
<P>
   The inside linebackers, Ramogi Huma and Tony White, are
first-time starters.
</P>
<P>
   The reserve inside linebackers, Cheyane Caldwell and Ryan Nece,
weren't inside linebackers last year.
</P>
<P>
   The free safeties, Eric Whitfield and Jason Stephens, instilled
so little confidence in training camp that Aliotti considered
moving Atkins, his best player, from strong safety to free.
</P>
<P>
   But the youngsters were in good hands. Toledo and Aliotti worked
together at Oregon, where Aliotti masterminded the ``Gang Green''
defense that produced a Pac-10 title in 1994. He was well-liked by
his players and well-respected by his peers. In 1995, he followed
Ducks head coach Rich Brooks to the St. Louis Rams, where he spent
three seasons as an assistant.
</P>
<P>
   When Long departed in December, Toledo wasted no time hiring
Aliotti, whose first cousin, Al Borges, is the Bruins' offensive
coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   The players took to Aliotti immediately _ ``He's phenomenal,''
Whitfield said _ and they slowly absorbed his system. It retained
the blitzing, swarming principles Long preached for two seasons but
changed the alignments and assignments.
</P>
<P>
   Aliotti's strategy against Texas was textbook: Stack the line
with eight players to contain All-American tailback Ricky Williams,
while daring quarterback Richard Walton to win it through the air.
Weak-armed and slow-footed, he could not. If the blitzers didn't
get him, the cornerbacks did.
</P>
<P>
   For 30 minutes, UCLA's defense was as stingy as it needs to be,
executing the game plan and holding the Longhorns to three points
and 116 yards. In the second half, with a four-touchdown lead, the
young Bruins became complacent and Aliotti inserted seldom-used
reserves like Steve Sua, Ali Abdul Azziz and DuVal Hicks. The
Longhorns took advantage with 28 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was extremely pleased with the way we played in the first
half,'' Aliotti said. ``I was disappointed in the second, though.
We had guys going in and out and we didn't keep up the intensity.
We felt the game was over before it was.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Bruins' rookie coordinator, it was the best of both
worlds: an impressive first half to secure the win, a disappointing
second half to assure he'll have something to teach this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
