<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GOV-RACE-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN DEBATE, MCCAUGHEY ROSS CATCHES VALLONE OFF GUARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Betsy McCaughey Ross caught Peter Vallone off guard
Sunday in their final debate before Tuesday's Democratic primary
for governor, challenging his responses in a questionnaire on
abortion, answers that she said contradicted his public statements
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five days, Ms. McCaughey ross, the lieutenant
governor, has taken to attacking Vallone, who leads in the polls,
and questioning his commitment to abortion rights. Sunday's
exchange was the closest that any of his rivals have come in six
televised debates to truly rattling Vallone, the New York City
council speaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't this your signature?'' Ms. McCaughey Ross demanded
repeatedly, waving the questionnaire, in which Vallone opposed any
law requiring parental consent for a minor to have an abortion. The
form was sent to candidates by the National Abortion and
Reproductive Rights Action League, or NARAL.
</P>
<P>
   Flustered, Vallone at first did not respond, then said he did
not recognize the form, adding, ``And that's not my signature.''
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged after the debate, which was televised live
from the WNBC studios at Rockefeller Center in Manhattan, that the
questionnaire had been filled out by his campaign and said that it
reflected his views. He insisted there was no contradiction with
his other statements on the issue, but the exchange exposed some
inconsistencies in Vallone's position as expressed by both him and
his aides.
</P>
<P>
   In the debate, which was moderated by Gabe Pressman, a senior
political reporter for WNBC, Vallone recovered well enough to
explain one of his differences with Ms. McCaughey Ross and turn it
into a challenge to her. He said he supported a law requiring that
before a minor can have an abortion, an adult close to her must be
notified.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe you're saying that if a 12-year-old becomes
pregnant, she should have the right to make that decision without
any adult notification,'' he said to the lieutenant governor, who
did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, Ms. McCaughey Ross said, ``You signed a form to
NARAL that said you opposed any limitations on a woman's right to
choose, regardless of her age.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there was no such wording on the questionnaire, but
Vallone refused to take the paper and check its language. ``I did
not say that,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   But the strongest defense of Vallone came from the other
candidates, Charles Hynes, the Brooklyn district attorney, and
James Larocca, a former state transportation commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me it's very offensive of you to take on Peter
Vallone on an issue that he's made very, very clear he supports
totally,'' Hynes said.
</P>
<P>
   As in previous debates, he and Larocca noted that Ms. McCaughey
Ross switched from the Republican Party just a year ago, and
accused her of altering her positions for political convenience.
And they accused her of violating a promise that all the candidates
made earlier this year not to attack each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not going negative,'' Ms. McCaughey Ross said. ``I'm
here to seek the truth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vallone's aides said their aim for the debate was simply to have
their candidate avoid any embarrassing slips, and by that standard
he appeared to have succeeded. But the exchange on abortion exposed
some of the many fine, often semantic distinctions used by both
sides.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross has framed her candidacy as an appeal to
women, and has questioned whether Vallone can be called
``pro-choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the outcome of the primary on Tuesday, Ms. McCaughey
Ross is guaranteed to be a candidate in November's general election
because she has already been chosen as the Liberal Party nominee.
In the debate, Ms. McCaughey Ross reiterated her intention to
campaign on the Liberal line even if she loses the Democratic
primary. That drew attacks from the other contenders, who noted
that they had all promised Democratic Party leaders early this year
that they would not stand against the party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wins the Democratic nomination for governor, I will not
support her,'' Larocca said, citing the lieutenant governor's
refusal to pledge that she will back the winner if she loses the
primary.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone's position on abortion does not differ markedly from
that of Gov. George Pataki, who is unopposed for the Republican
gubernatorial nomination. Vallone says he supports unrestricted
abortion rights for adult women, except late in pregnancy, when he
would allow it only if the woman's life or health were threatened.
That view is already reflected in state law.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McCaughey Ross says she will put no restrictions on
abortion. Her opponents charged Sunday that she contradicted that
stance in a 1992 article she wrote, but she insisted they were
misinterpreting the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Pressman began the debate with questions about Kenneth Starr's
report on President Clinton, a topic that for days has overshadowed
the candidates' efforts to make their cases.
</P>
<P>
   All four contenders expressed disappointment in Clinton's
conduct, and, with varying vigor, defended his presidency and
criticized Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone was the most muted, declining to say whether Clinton
should resign or be impeached, and suggested that Congress consider
censuring the president.
</P>
<P>
   It was Ms. McCaughey Ross who made the strongest statement,
saying that Clinton's behavior ``offends my moral values,'' but
calling on Congress to ``spare the nation the tumult of an
impeachment process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These 11 charges do not constitute a threat to the welfare and
security of the nation,'' she said. ``Ken Starr's report is like an
edition of Playboy. It's time for the nation to move beyond this
crisis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
