<SLUG> BC-EDIT-BLACKFACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SICK TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Monday, Sept. 14:
</P>
<P>
   The scene evokes an ugly memory for many New Yorkers, harkening
back to a dozen years ago when a black man was killed by a car
after whites in Howard Beach chased him into a roadway. Now, from a
community only a few miles away, comes raw videotape of the Broad
Channel Labor Day parade, where one float was titled ``Black to the
Future: 2098.'' On the truck bed were several white men in
blackface. One participant held onto the back of the truck in a
sickening parody of the murder of James Byrd Jr., who was dragged
to his death last June by white racists in Jasper, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Such ``humor'' is not new to the parade in this insular
community of Queens. A few years ago, participants dressed like
Hasidic Jews in a jungle-like setting for a float called ``Hasidic
Park,'' a take-off on ``Jurassic Park.'' There were other years
with parade entries mocking Asians and gay people _ some of them
awarded parade prizes for humor.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie O'Hare, a trustee of the volunteer fire and ambulance
corps that has traditionally sponsored the parade, issued an
apology and promised to screen parades for such offensive material
in the future. Several participants in the event have also
apologized, and some in the community wisely tried to make amends
Saturday as the Rev. Al Sharpton led a peaceful protest through
Broad Channel.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani responded swiftly. It was
an appropriate opportunity to reassure black New Yorkers, who often
perceive the mayor as hostile. Calling the parade a ``disgusting
display of racism,'' Giuliani demanded dismissal of city employees
who were involved. So far a police officer and two firefighters
have been suspended. The mayor's outrage is justified and his
instinct to be as tough as legally possible is sound, even though
dismissals might run into constitutional problems on free-speech
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   As for the residents of Broad Channel, this embarrassment can
offer a harsh but necessary lesson. Watching the videotapes of this
float on the nightly news _ seen not by a few neighbors but by the
whole multicultural city _should remind them how easily ethnic
humor turns mean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-13-98 2343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19980913.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-13 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3130 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLUMN-NYT     09-13 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THERE IS NO THERE THERE FOR THE GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND , Calif. _ You trot to the grocery store and there are
12 items you must buy. Got to have them all. You have $50. And the
first thing you toss in the basket costs $47.50.
</P>
<P>
   Not much room left for easy pickings.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happened to the Giants against the Raiders Sunday
at the Oakland Coliseum. Giants call tails at the coin flip. It is
heads. Raiders get the ball first. Kickoff goes through the end
zone. Raiders at their own 20. First play, SWOOSH! Running back
Napoleon Kaufman rips through the middle of the Giants' defense for
an 80-yard touchdown gallop. The game is only 17 seconds old and
the Giants are fighting an uphill battle on the road and in the
heat, down by 7-0.
</P>
<P>
   There went $47.50 in one swipe.
</P>
<P>
   That set the table for the Giants' 20-17 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Try as hard as they might _ and the Giants showed resolve in a
game that featured two ties and one Giants lead _ the feeling was
evident in the first quarter that the Giants were not going to
completely overcome Kaufman's run. That it would haunt them
throughout this game. And it did.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but the Giants entered the game wanting to make sure that
the Raiders' Jeff George did not beat them with his arm by throwing
long balls all day to his fleet core of receivers. The Raiders'
longest passes of the day were 49, 27 and 26 yards. No gigantic
bombs. It was the legs of Kaufman. That was the early dagger.
</P>
<P>
   He caught the Giants in a defensive look called ``Bear.''
</P>
<P>
   For Kaufman, it proved sweeter than honey.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called a Bear defense, like everyone was coming, and then
we backed off and tried to fool them,'' Giants linebacker Jessie
Armstead said. ``He ran it and cut back. It was a good play and a
good call for them against that defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants defensive back Shaun Williams said: ``Any time a back
goes 80 yards on the opening play, that sets a bad tone. He put our
backs against the wall. I just saw him make a nice cut and a couple
of moves, and then he was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Giants linebacker Marcus Buckley added: ``We just opened a can
of worms. The way we played that and on some of our third-down
play, we set it up where teams are going to come after us and
challenge us in the same ways until we stop it. Everyone knows he
is the type of runner that if he hits daylight at full speed that
you are not going to catch him. And on the first play? It wasn't
good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raiders absolutely loved it. The Giants got tangled in their
own web on the play and fell over each other. Tim Brown, the
Raiders' big-play receiver who had a 22-yard touchdown grab and
made big third-down catches the rest of the day, said that the
Raiders felt tremendous confidence after Kaufman's run. That the
day, regardless of ups and downs, simply might the theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for the Giants,'' Brown said, ``we saw where coach Fassel
said that the one thing he didn't want to happen was give up big
plays. So, we start the game with the biggest of plays, 80 yards
for a touchdown. That does not bode too well for their team on the
scoreboard or in their minds. They had to be thinking, `We've
already done the one thing coach didn't want us to do.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants made 15 penalties. The Raiders made 16. Some of it
was comical _ jumping offside, late hits, simply a pure lack of
discipline. The Giants were concerned about not giving up big
plays, but they certainly did not make any, either. The Giants
averaged a measly 4.5 yards gained per pass play. Their longest
completion was for 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   They got a fumble recovery at the Raiders' 15 with 2 minutes 24
seconds left in the third quarter and did not take one shot into
the end zone. Short stuff that went backward. They settled for a
field goal and a 17-17 tie. That, too, would haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   What kept the game from being brutal to watch was hard hitting
on defense and big third-down conversions by the Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   They made eight of 18, and one of them was a fourth-quarter,
third-and-26 pass of 26 yards to tight end Rickey Dudley. That
changed the game of field position, because the Giants stopped
them, got a punt to their own 6, punted themselves to their own 49,
and then the Raiders took over from there and scored the winning
field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah. During that game-winning drive, the Raiders made a
third-and-10 pass to Desmond Howard at the Giants' 13. It was
Howard's only reception of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in our defense wasn't exactly on the same page
today,'' Buckley said. ``I don't know why. We let this game slip
out of our hands in certain spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
